</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMAN-FILM-BUZZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUMAN SHOW' LATEST TINSELTOWN EPIC, BUZZ INDICATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The studio hype may be real this time.
</P>
<P>
   A rapidly escalating crescendo of buzz -- an indefinable sense
that a movie is about to become a blockbuster -- has overtaken Jim
Carrey's ``The Truman Show,'' which opens today in 2,350 theaters
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity has become white-hot and largely fawning, the kind
that a certain giant lizard couldn't buy with millions of dollars
of advertising earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers have been ecstatic about the tale of Truman Burbank,
and Carrey's elastic mug has been on the covers of Time and
Entertainment Weekly magazines just in time to generate even more
interest.
</P>
<P>
   If America agrees, ``The Truman Show'' may be that
once-in-awhile movie that, against appearances, somehow becomes a
cultural event in tune with its time like ``Easy Rider,''
``Network'' and ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a real steamroller on this film,'' said Chandler
Wood, head film buyer for the Pacific Theatres chain. ``The buzz
has been getting stronger every day. It's going to attract the
whole spectrum of people over 18.''
</P>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, ``The Truman Show'' looked like little
more than a quirky, $60 million film. It had been delayed twice,
presumably because of Paramount's concern that Carrey's fans
wouldn't be interested in anything other than his typical goofball
persona.
</P>
<P>
   But Paramount's recent good fortune appears to have continued
with ``Truman.'' First, Paramount invested $65 million in the
way-over-budget disaster movie, only to see ``Titanic'' break the
record for biggest-domestic-grossing film of all time and earn a
boatload of Oscars this spring, including Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Paramount's ``Deep Impact'' performed far better than
expected when it opened last month -- so well, in fact, that it's
partially credited with bringing ``Godzilla'' to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   When they open the doors today, multiplex operators will be
giving screens to ``The Truman Show'' they previously planned to
use for ``Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paramount has a lot of clout with exhibitors right now,'' said
analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake Capital Management. ``This film
had been a question mark, but now the feeling is that it's so good
that you've got to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Fay, president of films for the AMC chain, believes
``The Truman Show'' can pull in an impressive $30 million to $35
million this weekend, then remain at or near the top of the box
office for the rest of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think even Paramount is a little surprised at how the buzz
has kicked in just as the film opened,'' Fay said. ``I would see it
a second time, but the trick will be getting the younger audiences
to see something that doesn't have the usual Jim Carrey in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of Reel Source, forecasts an opening
weekend of $24 million and believes a $200 million final gross
won't be out of the question if ``Truman'' catches on with
teen-agers. ``It's an excellent film that will receive a lot of
support from older audiences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Carrey squandered some of his good will in
Hollywood by stepping outside his usual manic characters (``Ace
Ventura,'' ``The Mask,'' ``Dumb and Dumber'') to play the lead in
``The Cable Guy,'' a dark-humored film mostly ignored by fans. But
others have already forecast that Carrey will be picking up an
Academy Award next year, much like Tom Hanks did for ``Forrest
Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
