<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LEADERS ACT TO AVERT SLPLIT AS BUDGET IS DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders scrambled on Thursday to
avert a crippling split in their ranks over their budget plan for
next year, seeking to mollify both conservatives who are demanding
big tax cuts and moderates wary of a bitterly partisan
election-year fight over deep spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   With their chances of passing their tax and spending outline
hanging on a handful of votes, Republican leaders opened debate on
the House floor, saying that they were intent on giving taxpayers
back more of their money as the nation entered an era of budget
surpluses and that they would head off Democratic efforts to expand
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Republican plan is to address the
provision in the tax code that forces many two-income couples to
pay more in taxes than they would if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would ``make the government budget smaller
and the family budget larger,'' said Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon,
R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., said the Republican budget ``picks on
those most vulnerable in our society'' by cutting spending on
assistance to low-income families, schoolchildren, veterans and
other groups.
</P>
<P>
   A final vote on the plan is expected on Friday. But in its first
procedural test on Thursday night, the Republican plan passed, 216
to 197, with four Republicans voting against it.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan, drafted by Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, the
chairman of the House Budget Committee, calls for $101 billion in
tax cuts over the next five years and spending cuts of a similar
magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   The party's most conservative members want tax cuts of $150
billion and hope to resurrect the drive for a smaller government
that led to bitter political clashes with President Clinton and a
partial shutdown of some federal agencies in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican moderates have little stomach for the deep
spending cuts in domestic programs called for by Kasich's plan. And
although relatively few of them are likely to defy their
leadership, the defections of as few as 10 Republicans would leave
the party short of the votes needed for final passage.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders were sufficiently concerned about the
potential defections that they used a parliamentary maneuver late
on Wednesday night to block consideration on the floor of a
substitute budget, offered by a group of conservative Democrats,
that closely mirrored the plan passed by the Republican-controlled
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan provided for $30 billion in tax cuts and largely
stuck to the spending path agreed to by both parties in Congress
and Clinton in last year's balanced-budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Some Senate Republicans, including Pete Domenici of New Mexico,
the chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, have made it clear
they think the House version goes too far in tax and spending cuts.
But conservatives in the Senate want at least $60 billion in tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the House version passes when it comes to a final vote,
House and Senate negotiators would then have to work out a
compromise between their versions
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Republican leaders were telling wavering moderates on
Thursday that voting for the budget plan was only an interim step
toward a final package, and that the version that emerged from
House-Senate negotiations would be more palatable to them,
Republican aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership in the Senate used the same tactic to
win support from conservatives when the Senate voted on its budget
outline earlier this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders in the House were almost gleeful, both at the
divisions among Republicans and at the prospect of going into this
fall's midterm congressional elections with the Republicans on
record as favoring deep spending cuts in popular programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unacceptable, not only to Democrats but also to many
Republicans,'' Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority
leader, said of the Republican plan. ``They want to withdraw from
our commitments to education, health care and the environment, key
areas critical to the future of our country and the security of our
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win more votes, Kasich changed his plan late on
Wednesday. In a nod to conservatives, he added a provision saying
that would make it easier to use some of any future budget
surpluses for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to deal with the concerns of some moderates,
Kasich shifted proposed cuts in Medicare, the health insurance
program for the elderly that has often been a political
battleground, to a broader spending category that finances welfare
payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
