<HEADLINE>
TMS FASTER DESPITE RAINSTORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The reconfigured Texas Motor Speedway is
fast, according to the speeds run by Indy Racing League and NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series drivers during practice sessions yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   However, not even a state-of-the-art drainage system can make it
dry any faster after a thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Truck qualifying for tonight's Pronto Auto Parts 400K was
delayed 31/2 hours when a storm front dumped half an inch of rain
on the track in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Sprague won the truck pole with a lap of 178.642 mph, and
Jay Sauter was second 177.480.
</P>
<P>
   IRL officials decided at 10:25 p.m. to postpone qualifying until
today.
</P>
<P>
   The revised schedule has the IRL cars practicing in two groups
from 1 to 1:30 p.m and 1:30 to 2 p.m. Qualifying under a
best-of-two-laps format is scheduled for 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a dampness out there,'' said Leo Mehl, the IRL's
executive director. ``We think we're getting into an area where
we're in a safety situation. For the speeds we're going, it's got
so late that we thought it was wise not to squeeze it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a guy running an Indy car at 1 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehl said there was no problem with the track or its new
drainage system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no puddles,'' Mehl said. ``On the inside (of the
corners) there is a dampness. But the track is as good a racing
surface as I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reigning Indy 500 champion Eddie Cheever Jr. said he welcomed
the delay, because it gave his team an extra practice session.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very slow on the straightaway today, so we put in a
fresh engine to see if that's the problem,'' said Cheever, whose
top lap was 213.152 mph. ``We're flat with the throttle and not
going fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Indy 500 pole sitter Billy Boat, who was second-fastest overall
at 221.067 mph, said the delay was not a huge problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have run quicker (last night), but I'm used
to these late nights,'' Boat said. ``We have a car capable of
winning the pole. We always got a little bit left. But it's hard to
have much left here driverwise, because you're always flat.''
</P>
<P>
   It began to rain at TMS about 7:10 p.m., and rained for about a
half-hour. Drying crews got on the track about 8 p.m., and it took
more than two hours to get the track dry.
</P>
<P>
   Truck qualifying finally got under way at 10:15 p.m., 31/2 hours
later than the 6:45 p.m. scheduled start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be dry instantly, but it's normal stuff,'' said
Eddie Gossage, TMS executive vice president and general manager.
``We're at the mercy of the weather. You've got a real humid night,
so it takes longer to dry.''
</P>
<P>
   It also took longer because the track had to be dry for two
series with distinct handling characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We not only had to dry the track for us, but also for the IRL
guys,'' said Owen Kearns Jr., news media coordinator for the truck
series. ``They run a different line than we do. That took a little
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least the track was finally dry enough for the trucks to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rains came, there seemed to be plenty of evidence
that the track is faster since it was revamped.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart turned a hot lap of 223.224 in his Indy car, the
fastest ever at the speedway. The fast lap during the True Value
500k last year was 218.094 by Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Truck driver Bob Keselowski turned a hot lap of 177.597 in his
Dodge during the second practice session. Mike Bliss won the pole
last year with a lap of 175.667. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Sturbin contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
