<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TMS-RENOVATION-TE     06-05 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-RENOVATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONFIGURED TMS IS `SMOOTH'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway fostered high speeds
and even higher praise from NASCAR Craftsman Truck and Indy Racing
League drivers yesterday in its first test since a $2 million
renovation that included a newly paved track and a reconstruction
of troubling Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   The only blemish on yesterday's events may have been the rain
that moved through the area about 7:30 p.m. and delayed qualifying
for tonight's NASCAR Craftsman Truck Pronto Auto Parts 400K race
for more than three hours and postponed the qualifying round for
tomorrow's Indy Racing League True Value 500K competition until
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so smooth out there, you lose perspective on how fast
you're going,'' said Tony Stewart, IRL series defending champion,
who turned a practice lap at 223.224 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations began less than three weeks after the NASCAR Winston
Cup Texas 500 on April 5, which was marked by a major crash in Turn
1 and drivers' complaints about the transition at the exit of Turn
4 and entrance into Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Huth, NASCAR vice president for administration, said
officials at the speedway will continue to listen as drivers come
off the track and give reviews throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers complained of a bump in the racing line between
Turn 1 and Turn 2, but IRL driver Kenny Brack said those bumps
``are no problem for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis 500 champion Eddie Cheever Jr. said the bumps ``are
there, but they are small and negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   Huth said: ``As the weekend goes on, we'll continue to keep the
lines of communication open and see if anything changes. But
everything we've heard about Turn 4 and the situation on Turn 1 is
that the problems have been solved.''
</P>
<P>
   The first endorsement for Texas Motor Speedway's newly
resurfaced Turn 4 and ``special-mixture'' asphalt came from driver
Ron Barfield, who was standing beside his crumpled pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half-hour into yesterday's NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series opening practice, Barfield and his No. 35 Ortho Chevrolet
spun going into Turn 2. But he put all the blame for the crash on
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the track's fault, Barfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track was holding so well in my first few laps that I
thought it was time to open it up and go a little faster,'' he
said. ``I probably should have waited. I was a little too anxious
because the asphalt is smooth, and it's really gripping in the
banks.''
</P>
<P>
   But after their first practice session for tonight's Pronto Auto
Parts 400K, truck drivers followed Barfield in extolling the
track's new surface. Later yesterday afternoon, drivers of the
faster Indy Racing League cars, which race in tomorrow's True Value
500, also praised the track.
</P>
<P>
   It was the vote of confidence Texas Motor Speedway officials
hoped for after they completed what Vice President and General
Manager Eddie Gossage called a ``major reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavement was torn out and replaced in those turns and the
8-degree banking _ part of the ``dual-banking'' concept _ was
eliminated in favor of a full 24-degree bank in each turn.
</P>
<P>
   A new drainage system was installed after water seeped through
the pavement in Turn 1 during Texas 500 qualifying on April 3,
forcing postponement of the session until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The problems appear to be solved. It cost the speedway a
two-year headache and more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely wider, a whole other lane wider,'' IRL driver
Billy Boat said. ``I think we're going to be able to race side by
side. With the exception of a small bump in Turn 4, it is
glass-smooth. I wouldn't be surprised if we're racing three wide
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever said: ``We didn't have a problem with this place last
year. It's almost too easy now. The track is so smooth and so
clean, and it's got so much grip. ... They did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Pronto Auto Parts 400, Mike Bliss took the pole
at 175.667 mph. Yesterday in practice, Bob Keselowski and Jay
Sauter ran faster than 177 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``New asphalt is always going to stick better, but I'm excited
about how the track felt,'' Sauter said. ``It's smooth, wide, and
the transition out of Turn 4 is great. I can't wait to race. I'd
like to go out there and go right now.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Craftsman Truck series defending champion Jack Sprague,
who pushed his truck to 176.062 mph by the second practice session,
said Texas Motor Speedway stands up to some of the more popular
tracks on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' he said. ``They did a great job. They did it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said he is pleased about the positive response and is
hoping for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we want the drivers all to be pleased,'' he said.
``That's why we spent 2-3 million here. We are tickled the drivers
are complimentary across the board. We still want to hear what
Rusty ( Wallace) and Mark (Martin) and Dale (Earnhardt) and Jeff (
Gordon) have to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
