<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SPRAGUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRAGUE WANTS REDEMPTION IN A BIG WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jack's back, and he has an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it bad,'' he said. ``We want it real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A scene from The Shining? No, not that Jack.
</P>
<P>
   This little drama could be called ``The Redemption,'' and the
star is NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series driver Jack Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   The ``it'' in question is the Pronto Auto Parts 400-kilometer
race scheduled for tonight at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing personal. It's just that the 1997 event at TMS is
the scene of Sprague's worst weekend in his four seasons racing the
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague seemingly won the pole for last year's race, but was
caught with an illegal part in his engine during NASCAR's
post-qualifying inspection. He had to start from the back of the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do about it, so we just accepted it
and went on,'' Sprague said. ``I don't build the motors, and I'm
not sure what was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He put on an incredible charge during the race, working his way
back to third, but the backup engine blew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put on a cool show, but the second one didn't last,'' he
said. ``I had to race hard to get back to the front, where I felt I
belonged. But that had nothing to do with (the engine). It was just
one of those deals.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an extremely rare deal. It is the only time in 77 starts
that Sprague failed to finish a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we had it last year, and lost the motor,'' said
the defending NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series champion and current
points leader. ``We were on a mission there, and it was looking
good; it just didn't last long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jack is back, and he's still on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to win this race,'' said the 33-year-old driver of
the No. 24 Team Hendrick Chevrolet. ``We felt like we had it won
last year. The track doesn't owe us anything. It's more along the
lines of we owe ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague looks like a pretty good bet to cancel the debt.
</P>
<P>
   He has seven victories on tracks of one mile or longer, the most
in series history.
</P>
<P>
   His average finish on superspeedways _ tracks of 1.5 miles or
longer _ is third if the 31st at TMS last year is disregarded
</P>
<P>
   He has finished in the top five in all seven truck races this
year, including a victory at the NAPACARD 200 in Monroe, Wash., on
May 9. His average finish this year is 3.14.
</P>
<P>
   He has nine consecutive top-five finishes going back to the
final two races last year.
</P>
<P>
   He has 19 consecutive top-10 finishes, one shy of the series
record by Ron Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   And he is coming off one of the best rides of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics show that Sprague finished fifth at the Parts
America 150 last week at Watkins Glen. What the stats don't show is
a charge reminiscent of what he did at TMS last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague started fifth, but had a flat tire on the 15th lap. By
the time he got into the pits and got out again he was back in 32nd
place.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't stay there long. He immediately began to pass trucks,
a feat that can be difficult on a road course, and eventually kept
alive the string of top-five finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive hard every lap,'' he said. ``Last week I was more
proud of the team for digging deep and giving me as many spots as
they could on pit road. We just never gave up and that's what this
team is all about. We don't ever give up. We didn't give up last
week, and we didn't give up last year when we started from the
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, was that the engine didn't blow last
week. It did last year. That's why Jack is back with something to
prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Texas Motor Speedway bad,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
