<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTIONLAW-CHALLENGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ABORTION-RESTRICTION LAW IN KANSAS IS CHALLENGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN PETTERSON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Even before its contentious provisions could be
implemented, Kansas' new abortion-restriction law was challenged
Wednesday in the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   George Tiller, a Wichita abortion provider, and his Women's
Health Care Services filed the lawsuit. Tiller wants the new law,
which becomes effective July 1, to be put on hold to give the
justices time to decide its fate.
</P>
<P>
   Those on both sides of the abortion issue have raised questions
about the wording of the hastily written bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Graves signed the measure but later said it might take
a court challenge to clarify it.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who ran for office four years ago as a supporter of
existing law, drew fire from abortion-rights activists after he
signed the bill into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hopeful the court will give us what the Kansas
Legislature and the governor could not: clarity for physicians
providing abortion services and justice for women seeking
services,'' said Peggy Bowman, a spokeswoman for Tiller and an
official in the Kansas ProChoice Action League.
</P>
<P>
   Tiller's lawsuit contends that the new law is vague, has
unconstitutional reporting requirements providing for sanctions
against physicians and medical care facilities, ``and places
unconstitutional limits on a woman's right to an abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Gittrich, a spokesman for Kansans for Life, said the
organization would file briefs in support of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill hurts his business, and now he's challenging it,''
Gittrich said of Tiller. ``It goes to show that he has been
aborting babies that can live outside the womb, and that comprises
a considerable amount of his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiller, in urging the court to hear the case, said it should
take the action now because if the case is filed in a lower court,
appeals eventually will bring it before the justices anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to decide before the end of the month
whether to hear the case, dismiss it or send it to a district
court.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the filing came as no surprise to Planned Parenthood of
Mid-Missouri and Eastern Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was coming,'' said Erika Fox, vice president for
public policy. ``We fully support this challenge and the effort to
clarify what we consider to be an ill-conceived law.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the lawsuit appeared to address the questions of
vagueness and constitutionality ``that have concerned many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits abortions of viable fetuses after 22 weeks'
gestation, including those with severe, life-threatening
abnormalities and deformities.
</P>
<P>
   The provision of the act that has generated the most public
debate allows a post-viability abortion to be performed if
``continuation of the pregnancy will cause a substantial and
irreversible impairment of a major bodily function of the pregnant
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether ``mental health'' should be included as a
major bodily function, as Graves said he believed the law intended.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the law includes the mental-health exception, while
another is silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petitioners face the problem of `guessing' which
interpretation will be applied,'' Tiller said in his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The new law also requires detailed reporting of abortions to the
Kansas Department of Health and Environment. Tiller argued that
such a requirement could violate the self-incrimination provisions
of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   That could occur, the lawsuit said, if he performed abortions he
believed to be legal and completed reports on them, and then they
were ruled illegal and he was prosecuted. The records could be used
against him.
</P>
<P>
   In another area, Tiller said the law was so restrictive in cases
of medical emergency that a doctor could not act quickly to perform
an abortion when the fetus was viable if the woman's life was in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit does not challenge a portion of the law that bans a
procedure often referred to as partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Gittrich argued that the bill took steps toward reducing the
number of late-term abortions performed on Kansas women as well as
those who traveled to the state specifically for the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas may be known all over the world as great agriculture
and airplane centers, but it shouldn't be known as an abortion
center,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
