<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH MAY BE OUT FOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just when it appeared Todd Hollandsworth had
regained the form that helped him be the 1996 National League
Rookie of the Year, he learned Thursday he could miss the rest of
the season with torn cartilage in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, who batted .410 (16 for 39) during a recent
nine-game hitting streak, underwent an MRI Thursday at Centinela
Hospital Medical Center that revealed a cartilage tear in the front
of the shoulder. He was placed on the 60-day disabled list and will
have surgery next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Hollandsworth's place on the roster is Triple-A infielder
Alex Cora, brother of Seattle second baseman Joey Cora. The Los
Angeles Dodgers will use a platoon of Jim Eisenreich and rookie
Paul Konerko in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is discouraging; this is the hardest thing I've ever had to
deal with in my professional career,'' said Hollandsworth, who was
batting .269 (47 for 175) with three homers and 20 RBI. ``It is
something I just have to push through.''
</P>
<P>
   He first injured the shoulder diving back into first base two
weeks ago when the Dodgers were in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, 24, has been plagued by injuries his entire
career. In 1995, he was limited to 41 games because of a broken
left hand that required surgery and a fractured right thumb. He
recovered to hit .291 with 12 homers and 21 stolen bases in 1996
when the Dodgers won the NL West and he became the fifth straight
Dodgers player to be named Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Hollandsworth went on the disabled list twice and
never recovered his stoke. He batted .247 with just 31 RBI in 106
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd was playing very well and had really gotten back in a
groove,'' Dodgers executive vice president Fred Claire said. ``He
thought he could play through this, but it is serious. He could
miss the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Radinsky gets the win: Closer Scott Radinsky, who blew two saves
over the weekend, pitched the ninth inning to earn the victory. He
got a save Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are seeing that his confidence has been
restored,'' said pitching coach Goose Gregson, who sat with
Radinsky in the Dodgers dugout for more than an hour after Sunday's
loss. ``This is a quality pitcher. Everyone goes through slumps.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire misses series: Mark McGwire, the major-league home run
leader (27) who did not play against the Dodgers, is hopeful he
will be ready tonight when the Cardinals face the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who strained his lower back Monday in San Diego,
jogged, stretched and played catch before the game but did not take
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why everybody is concerned about it,'' McGwire
said after Thursday's game. ``There isn't an athlete in America
that hasn't been injured.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
