<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELWAY-STADIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL STAR ELWAY'S HIGH SCHOOL RENAMES STADIUM AFTER HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC MOSES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- When John Elway walked the halls of Granada Hills
High School in the late 1970s, he was a big man on campus --
leading the baseball team to back-to-back city championships and
the football team to the city playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he was the biggest man on campus.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Denver Broncos quarterback and Super Bowl
champion returned to suburban Granada Hills to join 3,500 fans for
the renaming of the football field as John Elway Stadium. It had
been named after founding Principal Bryce Schurr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has dreams,'' Elway told the crowd. ``But you know
when I was playing back here in '77, '78, '79, this was something I
never even thought of. Even last year this is something I never
thought of.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a treat for me to be here and to have the
stadium named after me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Elway, who traveled from his home in Engelwood, Colo., with
his 8-year-old son, Jack, this marked a rare appearance at his alma
mater.
</P>
<P>
   He was greeted by more than four dozen former teammates,
teachers and coaches, and of course, his fans.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, the quarterback was mobbed by students and
fans in orange-and-blue Bronco jerseys. He was given flowers, and
after he kissed a woman's cheek, she wandered through the throng
with her hands on her cheeks, screaming: ``Oh, my God! Oh, my God!
He kissed me! Oh, my God!''
</P>
<P>
   Granada Hills students were impressed but not obsessed with the
1979 graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty cool,'' said Jen Dallis, an 18-year-old
senior who was assigned to work with the media. ``I think it's a
bigger deal than everybody's making it out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, Elway announced that he would play one more
season in the National Football League before calling it quits. On
Thursday, his return to the stadium where it all began elicited
memories of his high school victories -- one in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was against San Fernando, and I threw a touchdown pass to
Chris Sutton to go ahead with 20 seconds left or something like
that,'' Elway recalled. ``But it got called back because of
holding, and we called a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the sidelines and Coach (Jack) Neumeier said, `Same
play.' And we went back and Chris made a great catch again, and
that was really kind of the first comeback I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The renaming of the stadium was engineered by Elway's high
school teammate Chris Sutton, coach Darryl Stroh and Principal
Kathleen Rattay. And it did not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of keeping Schurr's name argued that giving the honor
to Elway emphasizes athletics over academics.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise, Schurr's name was placed on the athletic
complex, including all sports fields. A dedication ceremony is
scheduled for Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Irwin, the school's principal from 1976-86, who signed
Elway's diploma, acknowledged there was a lot of controversy over
the name change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's recognition of one graduate that's symbolic of the many
students that have come out of here and gone on to other things,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former teammates and current coaches also say Elway deserves the
honor. His name on the new $8,000 scoreboard, donated by an
anonymous former high school teammate of Elway's, will help
motivate future Highlander players, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it reinforces the idea of having goals for the
future,'' said current Highlander co-coach Tom Harp. ``He went to
the Super Bowl and won it. He kept trying after losing it a few
times.''
</P>
<P>
   In talking to the students, Elway espoused those ideals, telling
them to set goals just above their reach and get an education so
they will be prepared for future opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got different talents,'' he said, ``and somebody
is going to be better at something than somebody else. But what
you're good at, be the best at.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Elway's accomplishments: four trips to the Super Bowl, 33
last-minute, game-winning drives, the 1993 American Football
Conference's Most Valuable Player award and seven Pro Bowl
selections.
</P>
<P>
   That and more have earned him cult status among his fans, but
that was nowhere more apparent than in Denver, where two TV
stations carried the 50-minute ceremony live.
</P>
<P>
   Others hope playing on the newly named field will help the team
improve its record: three wins in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pumps us up,'' said Robert Baca, a freshman quarterback and
wide receiver. ``I can't wait to play next year. We're the first
players to play on it.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
