<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-OROSCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OROSCO HAS SEEN IT ALL, BUT HAS FRESH OUTLOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He is the fourth-oldest Oriole ever, behind Rick
Dempsey, Dizzy Trout, and Dave Philley. He stands seventh all-time
with 979 games pitched and is taking a run at the No. 6 man, Lindy
McDaniel, at 987.
</P>
<P>
   Add the two World Series rings with the New York Mets and Los
Angeles Dodgers and you'd think Baltimore reliever Jesse Orosco,
who turned 41 April 21 and is in his 21st professional season _ 18
in the majors _ would look back on his career and point to the
championships and the personal statistics as his crowning
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   But Orosco, who saved Game 7 of the 1986 World Series against
the Red Sox for the Mets, figures he's probably set a different
kind of rec-ord.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my professional seasons,'' he said before Thursday
night's game at Fenway Park, ``I've never been on the disabled
list. Knock on wood, I've been fortunate. I try real hard in the
offseason to stay in shape and I run every day to keep my body
going and my arm in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've also got to have good work habits, good mechanics to
keep your arm sound. When I first broke into the majors, I had
hoped to play a long time, but I never imagined this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco, who had a career-high 71 appearances with the Orioles
last season and whose 975 relief appearances for five teams rank
fourth in major league history, is still going strong, physically
and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still love coming out of the bullpen,'' he said. ``I love
the competition. It's not every day you can wake up and say, `Well,
I might be facing Ken Griffey or Mark McGwire today.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, I've learned how to mix my pitches. Watching a
lot of baseball also helps, and I've watched a lot of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   For nine National League seasons, Orosco, despite his mechanics,
his ``book'' on hitters, and his natural skills, had a terrible
time facing slugger Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed that he got hit after hit after hit on me,'' Orosco
said. ``We were pretty good friends, and I used to ask him, `Chili,
what are you doing to me?' And he'd say, `I don't know, Jess, it's
just one of those things.'''
</P>
<P>
   A California native, Orosco lives in San Diego with his wife,
Leticia, and three children. ``That's the tough part, missing the
heck out of my family,'' he said, ``and that's the hard-est part of
playing 21 years. It makes me think about how much longer I want to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco said that when he retires as a player, ``I'll definitely
take a year off before deciding what to do. If I stay in baseball,
I'd like to stay around the San Diego area and perhaps do something
with baseball camps or at the college level. But I just want to cut
out the traveling.''
</P>
<P>
   But that day hasn't quite come, and there's a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe that I'm throwing harder now than 20 years
ago,'' said Orosco. ``And not having serious arm problems has
helped. I'm also glad I took the advice of George Bamberger years
ago when he told me to develop strong wrists that would enable me
to throw a good breaking ball. Developing the breaking ball did a
lot for my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he's witnessed many changes over 21 seasons, said Orosco,
one thing remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American League games take forever,'' he sighed. ``The
National League games don't take very long at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
