A5350 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS-BOS &LR;      06-05 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS TAKING IT FROM THE TOP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was a career .247 hitter who signed on last December
with his fifth major league team since the 1995 season. But Red Sox
outfielder Darren Lewis, who went 3 for 5 with a home run in
Thursday night's 9-1 thrashing of the Orioles at Fenway Park, is
not only batting .300, he's rediscovered his old San Francisco
Giants niche as a leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed into service at the top of the order by Jimy Williams
when Nomar Garciaparra went down with a shoulder injury in early
May, Lewis has batted leadoff in 23 of Boston's last 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my struggles the last couple of years,'' said Lewis,
whose third home run of 1998 was the second this season that he's
wrapped with an inside-out swing around Pesky's Pole in right
field. ``But the key for me has been to work through that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been nice being on this team is that there's no
pressure for me to be an offensive force because we have such a
great offensive club. But at the same time,'' added the 30-year-old
former Gold Glove winner who holds the major league record for
consecutive errorless games (392) by a non-pitcher, ``I'm a little
older and a little smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to do my little part. I was a leadoff hitter
my first 3 1/2 years in the big leagues. You have to learn when to
take pitches, but also when to be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Williams and Lewis were part of the dramatic 1993 pennant
race in the National League West when the Braves, for whom Williams
was a coach, won their 104th game on the last day of the regular
season. The Giants, who won 103 games that season, the last before
the wild card, were beaten by the Dodgers in their final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren's allowed us to spread that lineup,'' said Williams,
``and it's helped a lot. He understands his job as a leadoff
hitter, to see how many runs he can score in the course of the
season. I saw him when he first came up (with the Giants) when he
and Royce Clayton were at the top of that order.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1993, those two guys set the table for the (Barry) Bondses
and the (Matt) Williamses and those other guys. He's acclimated to
hitting at the top of the order, so it's not unusual for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who set a personal season high Thursday night with six
total bases and tied his season highs with three hits and three
RBIs, would like nothing better than to get another taste of
postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   He came heartbreakingly close as a key man with the Giants in
'93 and was a backup outfielder with the Reds in 1995 when they
were eliminated in the National League Championship Series by the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1993 season was the year the wild card was made for, and I
can't really describe that disappointment of losing out by one
game,'' he said. ``That's in the back of my mind every day. We had
the best all-around team I've ever played on, and to go home after
that kind of season was very hard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who said his opposite-field stroke is ``tailor-made'' for
Fenway, may be on track for consideration for Comeback Player of
the Year honors, but he quickly dismissed that subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' he said. ``The way I've always approached the game
is that individual awards are secondary. What I would love is an
opportunity to get back in a playoff setting.''
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, Lewis has certainly helped the Red Sox make
a run at the postseason with his well-documented outfield defense
and his offensive presence. But, he said, ``even though we're
playing good baseball, I'm not too excited yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long year. Guys have to stay healthy and things have to
continue to go right. There are so many different ingredients that
go into a successful season.''
</P>
<P>
   Like an experienced leadoff hitter with some newfound pop in his
bat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
