<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-JAZZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ HOPES MALONE, HORNACEK GET IN TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ While the Chicago Bulls snipe at each other,
the Utah Jazz has remained all quiet on the Wasatch Front.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Despite getting subpar performances from two of its
top three players _ Karl Malone and Jeff Hornacek _ in Game 1, Utah
leads the best-of-seven NBA Finals series, 1-0, going into Game 2
tonight at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   The rust is off after a 10-day layoff, and the Jazz figures it
can only play better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we might come out flat in the first game,''
center Greg Foster said. ``We missed some shots, did some other
things well. We can take some confidence from it knowing that we
didn't play our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from it, according to Utah Coach Jerry Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to jump up and down about,'' said Sloan,
who probably wouldn't have been satisfied with a 20-point victory
any more the one that came in overtime. ``Hopefully, we can execute
a little better. And hopefully, we can try and defend them a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Jazz also knows that, to beat the Bulls, it's going to
need a lot more from Malone and Hornacek. John Stockton carried the
team, especially down the stretch, in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who had a similarly poor performance in Game 1 of the
1997 Finals, made only 9 of 25 shots this year. He said he'll make
a few minor adjustments but expects his shots to start falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots I took were within our offense,'' Malone said.
``There's one thing I might do differently, and I'll adapt. I'm not
going to say what it is. But I'm not going to stop shooting. I
didn't do some things I'm capable of doing. I'll adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hornacek, who made only 2 10 shots, it's not so simple.
First, he has to expend a lot of energy trying to guard Bulls star
Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realizes he's not going to stop him,'' Malone said. ``It's
up to us big guys to help him a lot more. I don't think we did that
as well as we could have in Game 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Hornacek is not healthy, even if he insists that he is.
Hornacek has had a chronically bad left knee, admitting that it has
been swelling off and on for the past seven seasons. This season,
he also has sore Achilles' tendons during the playoffs that have
limited his mobility and made it difficult for him to shoot his
jump shot with normal lift and rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   And Hornacek really started wondering whether he's star-crossed
last week. With that 10-day respite, Hornacek not only had a rare
opportunity to let his body rest, he also had a chance to get some
work done around the house. It turned out to be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you have to realize my garage is a disaster,'' Hornacek
said. ``I was carrying an extension ladder, trying to go between
the cars and stepping over some junk. I tripped over some stuff and
hit my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek took a dive, and and the ladder whacked him in the
head. He needed a half-dozen stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rough year,'' Hornacek said.
</P>
<P>
   Not as rough as the Bulls' start in this series, though. Jordan
scored 33 points and Scottie Pippen had 21, but neither shot the
ball well, and Pippen had five turnovers. And the rest of the Bulls
were mostly ineffective. Forward Toni Kukoc made only 4 of 12
shots. Guard Ron Harper scored four points and had only one assist
in 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago bench was worse. But Chicago reserve Steve Kerr said
too much was made of Utah's advantage in bench scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play more minutes, so we don't pay a lot of attention to
the stats off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is for us to be effective while we're out
there. The biggest thing in Game 1 is that Utah didn't play well
and we passed up a great opportunity to win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
