<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-CWS-ARIZ-ONASTATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DISASTER TO TITLE SHOT  
 ATTITUDE ADJUST MENT ENDED ASU SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ It was March 18. It was dreary. It was Fresno. And
Pat Murphy was miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we ever going to win another game?'' he wondered out loud.
</P>
<P>
   True story. This team on the brink of a College World Series
championship was once on the brink of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State had just lost its sixth game in a row to drop to
16-12. The offense was struggling. Some tension existed among these
typically close-knit players.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few guys had major attitude problems,'' one player said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Murphy handled it well,'' outfielder Mikel Moreno said.
``He confronted the problems, the players backed him, and the
attitudes changed.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened after that 6-5 loss to Fresno State on March 18,
the midpoint of the season, is why the Sun Devils will play for the
national title Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ASU went 18-9 in the second half primarily because its offense
kicked in gear. The Sun Devils scored 199 runs in the first half,
262 in the second. They had 281 hits in the first, 330 in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you've got to get knocked down before you rise to
the top,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted the turnaround? Murphy and several players point
to three things:
</P>
<P>
   _A straight-shooting team meeting before the start of the next
series, against California.
</P>
<P>
   _An inspiring performance by pitcher Phill Lowery in the first
game against the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   _Murphy's handling of several attitude problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we got sick and tired of underachieving,'' third
baseman Andrew Beinbrink said. ``We were not playing as well as we
could. Each player finally took responsibility for themselves and
their performances and turned it up a level.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players, in particular, seemed to step it up
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Michael Collins' batting average leaped from .206 at
the midway point to .287 at the end of the regular season. Catcher
Jeremy Jones improved from .250 to .342; Moreno from .317 to .343;
and Casey Myers from .328 to .389.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came just before California visited on March 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept it real simple,'' Murphy said. ``We didn't try to
philosophize with them. We didn't try to analyze. We just said,
`Hey, take some responsibility, button your chin straps and go
after it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Several players said Murphy's conviction in that meeting was a
wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing I did,'' Murphy said. ``The players took charge
and did what they needed to do. (Pitcher Ryan) Mills was willing to
make some adjustments, and that helped. And then Lowery came out
and gave us a great performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the series opener against California, Lowery allowed just two
hits and struck out 12 in seven innings as ASU won, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the Sun Devils rallied with six runs in the
ninth to beat the Bears, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of sparked us offensively,'' Moreno said. ``It gave
us momentum for the rest of season. Until then, we weren't scoring
any runs. We couldn't swing with confidence. Once we got on a roll,
we saw what our capabilities were.''
</P>
<P>
   And players whose goals were singular changed their tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of attitude adjustments that needed to be made,''
Murphy said. ``We had a lot of guys that didn't want to take that
next step up. You've got to take responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until then I was very concerned. It didn't seem like we had
a lot of fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy and several players said Moreno was a key to the
second-half turnaround, more by example than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been at the crux of a lot of it,'' Murphy said. ``He's a
great leader. He doesn't give a hoot what anyone thinks about him.
He speaks his mind to the coaches, the players. He's a respectful
young man, but a great leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just his focus. He made everybody recognize we're all
on the same page here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Beinbrink, ``We finally learned from our mistakes and had a
better attitude. We got more confidence within ourselves. We let go
of any fears. That's what turned us around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were finally willing, as a team, to do anything necessary
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players never doubted that they would turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set a goal not to just make it to Omaha, but to win in
Omaha,'' Willie Bloomquist said. ``And we weren't going to back
down from anybody.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 0320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
