<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEUTRINO-DISCOVERY-SF     06-05 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEUTRINO-DISCOVERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTICLE OFFERS CLUE TO COMPOSITION OF COSMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    In a discovery climaxing decades of research into the past and
future of the universe, a team of physicists reported Thursday that
they have determined that the quirky subnuclear particles called
neutrinos carry at least as much mass as all the stars and galaxies
created since the Big Bang.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ghostly particles may also account for a significant portion
of the universe's mysterious ``missing mass,'' the researchers
said. The phenomenon has puzzled cosmologists for years because all
the stars, the galaxies and every bit of ordinary matter we know
cannot possibly weigh enough to account for the over all mass of
the universe.
</P>
<P>
   No recent cosmic discovery has generated as much excitement in
the scientific community as Thursday's confirmation that neutrinos
do indeed have mass and that they oscillate from one state to
another as they stream by the trillions from cosmic rays, from the
sun, from exploding stars known as supernovas, and from the decay
of other particles that make up every nucleus of every atom that
exists.
</P>
<P>
   The eagerly awaited neutrino discoveries were announced Thursday
from Japan, where scientists from all over the world were gathered
to hear the news and to describe their own experiments hunting down
the elusive particles.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been trying to study the neutrinos that zip
unscathed through Earth by capturing them in deep mines or creating
them though violent nuclear collisions at some of the world's
biggest atom-smashers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They are so fantastically small, so nearly weightless and so
electrically neutral that trillions of them can zip through every
human body every day without being felt. Even more of them
constantly stream unchanged through Earth without altering anything
_ except, of course, when a few are trapped inside detection
devices like the one in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120 scientists from Japanese, American and European
research institutions had collaborated for two years on the
``Super-Kamiokande'' experiments that were conducted in a vast
detection chamber located a mile deep inside the Kamioka zinc mine
about 150 miles northwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with 121/2 tons of highly purified water and surrounded
by 13,000 photomultiplier tubes and electronic data recorders, the
chamber _ insulated from any possible interference by other nuclear
particles _ captured a few elusive neutrinos that had been created
by the interaction between cosmic rays and Earth's atmosphere. The
experiment then detected their oscillation rate from one state to
another as the changes yielded tiny flashes of radiant energy.
</P>
<P>
   To John G. Learned, a University of Hawaii physicist and member
of the research team, the results are virtually unprecedented and
an extraordinary contribution to science's fundamental insights
into the past and present of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business you only get great data like this once in a
lifetime _ if ever,'' Learned said in a telephone interview
Thursday. ``This is as good as it gets. It could prove to be the
key to the Holy Grail of physics, a unified theory of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   That theory, a concept first proposed by Albert Einstein and
often reiterated by British astrophysicist Stephen Hawking, seeks
to find a single set of equations that can explain all the
fundamental forces in the universe: gravity, electromagnetism, and
the strong and weak interactive forces among subnuclear particles.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery announced Thursday does not provide that ultimate
explanation, but it seems bound to change significantly the current
``standard model'' of physics.
</P>
<P>
   And to Learned, altering the standard model could well mean a
new understanding of the origin of all matter, and a clue to the
fate of the universe _ whether it will continue expanding forever
or whether it contains so much mass that in billions upon billions
of years it will collapse on itself in a final ``Big Crunch.''
</P>
<P>
   To Princeton astrophysicist John Bahcall of the Institute for
Advanced Study, another experimenter, the discovery ``is something
that physicists had hoped for and eagerly sought for decades. It's
a huge step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current ``standard model'' of the universe, all matter is
fundamentally made up of six particles called quarks (whimsically
so named by the late Nobel laureate Murray Gell-Mann for James
Joyce's cryptic quotation ``Three Quarks for Muster Mark'' in
Finnegan's Wake) plus three electrons, tau particles, and muons,
plus three kinds of neutrinos.
</P>
<P>
   In that standard model, all those particles except the neutrinos
have mass, but now the model will have to be revised if the new
discovery is validated.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese experiment did not actually measure the mass of the
neutrinos it detected, but instead it enabled the experimenters to
calculate the tiny difference between the mass of neutrinos in each
state just as they oscillated to another state.
</P>
<P>
   As Learned explained it, those oscillations altered each
neutrino &UR;  &LR; known as a muon neutrino into a new and different state
called a tau neutrino. At most the actual mass of each of those
neutrino states was an almost infinitely small fraction of the
total mass of an entire electron, the lightest of the traditional
fundamental particles.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much of the ``missing mass'' of the universe is
accounted for by the neutrinos remains a question that has long
vexed astronomers and physicists alike. And according to physicists
like Joel Primack of the University of California at Santa Cruz and
Joseph Silk of the Center for Particle Astrophysicists at UC
Berkeley, the mystery is by no means solved by the Super-Kamiokande
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever the mass of the neutrino may be, it makes up only
the part of the missing mass known as ``hot dark matter.'' And to
Primack and Silk, there remains an even larger quantity of massive
stuff in the universe that they call ``cold dark matter''_ and no
one even knows what that stuff might be.
</P>
<P>
   To Silk, who is working in Paris right now, the news from Japan
was ``very exciting, exciting indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   But at best, he said in an interview, only about 20 percent of
the entire mass of the universe is made up of neutrinos, while
barely 5 percent is the mass of ordinary matter we can see or touch
or feel or observe through telescopes. All the rest _ about 75
percent of the mass of the universe _ must be cold and dark and
wholly unknown so far, Silk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early universe,'' he said, ``neutrinos must have been
very hot, and because of that they tended to suppress the formation
of galaxies after the Big Bang. So the implication is that because
of this mixture of hot and cold, dark matter the galaxies we know
must have formed much later than we've supposed. And there's a
statement we're wrestling with right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The neutrino experiment announced Thursday surely will result in
one or more Nobel prizes for the experiment's leaders, according to
Primack. ``This has been a wonderful experiment,'' he said, ``and a
real triumph for Japanese science. It's now truly a golden age for
neutrino physics and astrophysics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 0323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
