A5422 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIFAITH-CONFERENCE-S     06-05 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIFAITH-CONFERENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE, RELIGION INTERSECT AT UC BERKELEY CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON LATTIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH BERKELEY, Calif. _ From his study here, the Rev. W. Mark
Richardson sits amid the ivy-covered seminaries of the Graduate
Theological Union, enjoying an inspiring view of the Campanile, the
symbolic center of the University of California.
</P>
<P>
   It is the perfect setting for this philosopher and cognitive
scientist, whose mission is to promote dialogue between the secular
scientists working inside UC's numerous research laboratories and
the doctors of divinity in the adjacent seminaries atop ``Holy
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson directs the Center for Theology and the Natural
Sciences, which Sunday convenes a four-day conference where
physicists, biologists, cosmologists and computer scientists from
around the world will talk about finding the hand of God in
everything from the genetic code to the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost unprecedented for scientists to be able to sit
down with their colleagues and talk about spirituality,'' said
Richardson, who is an Episcopal priest.
</P>
<P>
   Many universities and research laboratories, he said, oppose
``any perspective with an element of transcendence,'' refusing to
question ``the claim that the physical universe is all there is,
all there ever was, and all there ever will be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this idea that the universe was created wearing a lab
coat,'' he added. ``Scientists make ontological claims that surpass
the evidence and scope of their science.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which runs through Wednesday at UC Berkeley's
Wheeler Auditorium, was designed for scientists who are also
believers in one of the three Abrahamic faiths _ Judaism,
Christianity and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the big questions the scientists will ponder include:
</P>
<P>
   --Does science offer evidence of a transcendent reality and
purpose?
</P>
<P>
   --Is there a bridge between science and morality?
</P>
<P>
   --Is there something distinctive about being human?
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from England, the Rev. Arthur Peacocke,
an Anglican priest and a biochemist, said it is hard to talk about
scientific ``evidence'' of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``In religion, you don't get evidence. It's not a court of
law,'' he said. ``But the modern scientific vista is so
comprehensive, it raises more sharply the question, `What's the
meaning of it all?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Peacocke, a theologian at the University of Oxford and a former
genetics researcher at UC Berkeley, has witnessed almost
unimaginable advances in that field during the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 150 years, science has painted a great canvas of
connectedness,'' he said. ``It's not `evidence' of God, but if you
believe in a God who has a purpose, faith fits together with our
universe now more than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, scientific breakthroughs like the mapping of
the entire human genome pose new challenges for moral theologians.
For example, what are the implications for church teachings on
homosexuality if scientists establish a genetic basis for sexual
orientation?
</P>
<P>
   ``That may require revisions within Christianity,'' Richardson
said. ``You might say you now believe in the goodness of creation,
and no longer see homosexuality as the result of something called
`the fall.' Maybe now you see it as part of the pre-moral condition
of the mammal even before human beings came along.''
</P>
<P>
   Another conference speaker, Dr. Carl Feit, worked as a research
scientist at the Sloan-Kettering Institute for Cancer Research
before accepting an appointment as a professor of health sciences
at Yeshiva University in New York, where Feit is free to mingle his
scientific research and Jewish faith.
</P>
<P>
   Feit cited a growing body of research showing that religious
faith may strengthen the immune system and help the body fight
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith is an important factor,'' he said. ``I don't believe in
the mind-body split. There is an interplay of all these systems. A
positive attitude, an attitude of hope, can have physical effects
on the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Feit agreed that science cannot prove God's existence, but he
said his faith allows him to see ``the hand of God in creation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My specific scientific knowledge about the tens of thousands
of chemical reactions taking place in our cells at any moment
enhances my appreciation of the maker of the universe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez Hewlett, an associate professor of molecular and
cellular biology at the University of Arizona, said he is starting
to see more openness to ``God-talk'' on secular campuses. His
school, for example, just offered a course on science and theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, that course would have met with much more
resistance. People would say that is outside our interest, or not
even a proper thing to think about,'' said Hewlett, a Roman
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Not invited to the conference are proponents of ``creation
science,'' Christian fundamentalists who question the validity of
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the biologists we invited believe in evolution,''
Richardson said. ``They are practicing scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson did not invite Phillip Johnson, a law professor at UC
Berkeley and an outspoken critic of evolutionary theory. In an
interview, Johnson said the fuzzy mix of science and spirituality
at conferences like the upcoming Berkeley gathering produce neither
good science nor good theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tolerate religion and science as long as science is in
the driver's seat,'' Johnson said, author of ``Defeating Darwinism
by Opening Minds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I find it easier to dialogue with atheists than these
theistic evolutionists.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will have many more opportunities for debating these
folks. Last week, the John Templeton Foundation, which funded the
conference, announced that it was giving another $12.6 million to
the Center for the Theology and the Natural Sciences to develop
programs in science and religion at universities worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
