Carrey, but it isn't a Jim Carrey movie. It contains no
butt-talking, no bizarro rubber-face behavior (not much, anyway),
no scatological fixation or creepy, overarching mania. Instead, it
is the most sophisticated, artfully disquieting commentary on
identity and the evils of television since Sidney Lumet's
``Network.'' By AMY BIANCOLLI.
