</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL-TV06-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Cedar Park could become gospel music's TV home
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin Wishard
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   CEDAR PARK _ A Baptist preacher and a rock-singer-turned-promot
er say that the Southern gospel music performance at Hilltop
Baptist Temple could lead to a Williamson County version of the
television program ``Austin City Limits.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely partners have hired a production crew to hang
lights, run wires and operate cameras. Many crew members have
worked on ``Austin City Limits,'' a nationally syndicated Public
Broadcasting Service show that features taped performances by an
eclectic array of musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Pastor Jack Humbert and Rob Brandon, owner of BNI
Enterprises, have prepared a script and overseen rehearsals. With
showtime approaching, the duo is dreaming of how their venture
could shape this community's image for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do to Cedar Park with gospel what country and
western did for Nashville,'' said Humbert, who described ``Hill
County Gospel Music'' as a cross between a Statler Brothers
performance and a ``Hee Haw'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert expects to sell all 650 tickets available at $12.50
each, and he is confident one of four cable networks that have
shown interest in a 13-episode package will pick up the gospel
music show. He won't reveal the names of the networks for fear of
jeopardizing negotiations but said they are based in Texas,
California, Florida and Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is strongly courting us, and another is saying don't sign
with anyone before you talk to us. We've approached the other
two,'' Humbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gates, a gospel music promoter who lives in Austin, said
the program could succeed here if done correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demographic that they would be broadcasting to is people
who are going to be at home _ older people, mostly,'' said Gates,
who helped promote a recent Amy Grant concert. ``There's definitely
a market for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon, a music promoter, shares Humbert's vision and energy
for the project, even though he has a limited religious background.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob had never heard a gospel song, seen a Bible or been to
church,'' Humbert said. ``But the more he was exposed to this, the
more he liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon said he was originally skeptical but changed his opinion
after hearing that another gospel music enterprise netted sales of
$30 million last year. ``I thought, God, if there's that much money
in gospel, let me sign up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon, a native of Canada, wears his curly hair long, to his
shoulders. The earrings and black felt boots fit the persona he
built while singing with rock bands Damian, the Fury, the LA Sharks
and Bad Boys. He talks about an extensive network of contacts he
has expanded since he gave up his singing career four years ago and
began managing musicians. Brandon said he hopes to persuade
high-profile performers to appear on future ``Hill Country Gospel
Music'' shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe how many big people love gospel or have a
background in gospel,'' Brandon said. ``We've got Larry Gatlin, and
Wayne Newton is calling us.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon said ``Hill Country Gospel Music'' will look and sound
different from any current gospel music production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gospel music has been so poorly produced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Brandon's flashy style, Humbert is a grandfather
who drives a minivan and knows prominent gospel music figures such
as Blackwood and Lister on a first-name basis. He's a savvy
promoter himself, and recently removed the word ``fundamental''
from the sign in front of his church. ``It has negative
connotations,'' Humbert said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes the television production will help raise money
to complete an 1,100-seat football stadium for the private school
next door. A lighted baseball and softball complex also are
envisioned for Hilltop Christian Academy, and Humbert said he wants
eventually to build assisted-living homes on the 40-acre campus.
It's all part of a master plan that began 20 years ago when he left
his executive office in a Chicago skyscraper to build a church on
the hill along U.S. 183 overlooking Cedar Park.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert and Brandon have agreed to split any profits 50-50.
Humbert's share will benefit Hilltop Christian Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert estimates the school and Brandon's company will spend
$35,000 to produce Saturday's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect to make any money from our ticket sales, but
when we tie in with a TV network, that's when we'll make our
money,'' Humbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
