<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL KIDS MAROONED ON TREASURE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Treasure Island School has 460 kids in
kindergarten through seventh grade, with an eighth grade and 140
more kids to come next year. All students are bused from San
Francisco's Tenderloin, Chinatown and Mission neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say the concrete jungle,'' principal Janet Dong
said.
</P>
<P>
   I just adopted this school. It's on an island paradise, except
it's called Willigan's Island (as in Mayor Willie Brown, who has
kept the island off-limits to the general public). That means these
kids need help. It's either me or Quentin Kopp.
</P>
<P>
   You see, the kids are fenced in on an acre of asphalt a
softball's throw from palms and playing fields. But they can't play
there without clearance from the island administration.
</P>
<P>
   They plant little gardens in boxes inside the fence, keep tabs
on the robin in its nest, and the kindergartners play in a patch of
weeds they find glorious.
</P>
<P>
   The only playground equipment on the school's asphalt is a
volleyball net and some balls bought by teachers, and hula hoops
donated by the San Francisco Sheriff's Department, which also has
adopted the school.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet beyond the fence are slides and jungle gyms in the
unused former Navy housing area on Treasure Island, a former naval
base.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of equipment the school needs, but needs help
getting from the island bureaucracy. The principal still hasn't
gotten a response from her request last August for a piece of
playground equipment she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I immediately called island administrator Annemarie Conroy, who
said: ``It's certainly possible to get the equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   I love being an adoptive columnist. Unfortunately, the school
also needs a $10,000 mat to put on the asphalt under the playground
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are Quentin and I going to wrestle on it?'' asked Conroy,
referring to state Sen. Quentin Kopp, whose Proposition K took the
wind out of Willigan's sails.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows where the money for that mat comes from, when
teachers choked on the $70 insurance fee Conroy's office was going
to charge for two class picnics on an island field Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fee was eventually waived, but only after Sheriff's
Department Capt. Rich Cairns heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich Cairns did say, `I want to pay for it myself,''' Conroy
said. ``I said I would go to the city attorney to get a waiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy said the kids now can go beyond the school fence without
paying for insurance, as long as they tell her office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say this spot or that spot,'' Dong said. ``It's so
limited. There's no running room.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy says she's watching out for the kids' safety. She said
recently a class took a walk to an island cove, and some kids went
into the water. ``That was irresponsible of the teachers to let
them in the water,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't in the water,'' Dong said.
</P>
<P>
   Dong is a first-year principal learning how to deal with island
bureaucracy. One thing this experienced educator doesn't have to
learn is how to run a school.
</P>
<P>
   The school sparkles. The walls are covered with projects done on
computers and paintings of scenes from ``Nutcracker,'' which kids
saw with their energetic, cultured 67-year-old part-time gym
teacher, Manuel Tchakalian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school is very good,'' said Francie Estandarte, a
seventh-grader who has been at the Treasure Island School since
kindergarten, and says he plans to become a gourmet chef. ``They
have no trouble. It's very safe. It's very peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``See, there is a positive thing about our gate policy,'' Conroy
said. ``They can come here and go to school and be children.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's the fence policy I'm concerned with now.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday I was on this island-within-an-island while
kindergartners commemorated the end of their ``first year toward
college,'' as Dong put it.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and kids in the finest clothes stood in a circle
cheering and chanting as blindfolded children took whacks at a
pinata.
</P>
<P>
   Three generations of the Aucar family came over the Bay Bridge
to see 6-year-old Wilda Faride Aucar graduate from kindergarten in
her gown. When I asked her 81-year-old grandmother, Zoila P.
Torres, how she liked the island, she gestured expansively and
said, ``Linda!''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty. It is very pretty, beyond the fence.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the first year the school's enrollment has been
all city kids. When the Navy left, taking its dependents, city
parents were afraid the school would close, and 600 of them signed
a petition to keep it open.
</P>
<P>
   The school brings life to a corner of the island, joy to the
kids and pride to the teachers. One hundred percent of the
seventh-graders, all of whom learned English as a second language,
passed the writing test given by the school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, they live with rats and roaches,'' said Carolyn
Froeberg, who has taught for 12 years at the school. ``Here they
don't have to deal with gangs and drugs. One thing the parents say
when they see the school is the kids can't slip out. It's on an
island.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids didn't seem to want to escape. They watched attentively
on Thursday as middle school boys played soccer against teachers
and parents.
</P>
<P>
   It was fearless soccer. Parents crashed into sixth-grade backs.
Seventh-grade forwards dribbled past puffing teachers and booted
goals between goal posts made of traffic cones.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks away were real soccer fields with real nets. Unused.
Off-limits. Behind a fence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
