<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5765 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     06-05 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTISTS TO CONSIDER THORNY ISSUE OF `SUBMISSION OF
WOMEN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although overshadowed by all the hyperbole about Baptists going
to Salt Lake City to convert Mormons, one of the biggest issues
facing Southern Baptists at their convention next week is
``submission of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptists meeting Tuesday through Thursday at the Salt Dome are
expected to add a passage to their statement of faith declaring
that the wife should ``submit graciously to the servant leadership
of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement on ``submission'' is part of a larger
pronouncement supporting only heterosexual marriage and declaring
that children should obey their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting the statement on submission of women would be another
example of the extreme rightward swing of the 15.9 million-member
Southern Baptist Convention _ the nation's largest Protestant
group.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it would show the dramatic differences between moderates
and conservatives in the denomination. Not that the two factions
aren't already irrevocably split.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates, following their ouster from power in the 1980s,
have formed their own organization, called the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship, which, in effect, already is a separate denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates _ who claim they are the ``real'' Southern Baptists _
are becoming more open to having women in major leadership roles,
including deacon and senior pastor. But not all moderates agree on
that, either.
</P>
<P>
   Whether one is a conservative or a moderate, though, statements
about women submitting to their husbands likely will be a
controversial subject.
</P>
<P>
   One Bible verse cited by those drawing up the ``submission''
statement is Ephesians 5:22-25.
</P>
<P>
   It states: ``Wives be subject to your husbands, as to the Lord.
For the husband is head of the wife, as Christ is also head of the
church. ... Husbands love your wives just as Christ also loved the
Church.''
</P>
<P>
   The submission pronouncement is anti-feminist but not
``anti-woman,'' says conservative Baptist leader Paige Patterson,
who is a shoo-in to be elected president of the Southern Baptist
Convention next week.
</P>
<P>
   His election would also be an emphatic indication of how
conservative the Southern Baptist denomination has become.
Patterson spearheaded the conservative revolution of the 1980s and
now is president of Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in
Wake Forest, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Patterson's wife, Dorothy Patterson, is one of the
most powerful women in the denomination. She is an author, editor
of a popular Woman's Study Bible published by Thomas Nelson, and a
popular teacher and speaker throughout the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, she submits to her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for modern women to understand that,'' she said.
``And it's not always easy for me. But the final decisions in our
home are made by Paige.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all biblical, Dorothy Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the headship of the man even in Genesis,'' she said.
``Even before Eve was created, you have Adam, who is to provide for
the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Baptists, such as the Rev. Buckner Fanning of San
Antonio, said the statement on submission is another example of
``fundamentalists'' taking the Bible out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Dilday of Fort Worth, a leading moderate and president
of the Baptist General Convention of Texas, which is separately
governed from the national convention, said the desire to add a
statement supporting families is commendable.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the view of submission of women to men and limiting their
places of service is not consistent with all the Scripture,'' said
Dilday, who is a professor at Baylor University's Truett
Theological Seminary. ``The Bible speaks of equal submission of
husbands and wives to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptist conservatives who insist on male leadership can take
some lessons from the Mormon leaders they will be visiting in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, like the most
conservative of Baptists, does not allow women to be pastors or
priests. None of the ruling hierarchy of Mormons is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it was in the Savior's church,'' said Stephen
Posey, president of the Mormon mission governing young missionaries
in the Fort Worth area and West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons, conservative Baptists, and some Episcopalians and Roman
Catholics, for that matter, use the argument that because Jesus' 12
apostles were all males, priestly leaders of the church should all
be males.
</P>
<P>
   So conservative Baptists and Mormons, although at odds over many
theological matters, will be in agreement this week about keeping
women in their submissive places.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
