<SLUG> BC-COMFORT-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KOREAN ``COMFORT WOMAN'' TELLS HER STORY IN WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ She cannot wake up from a nightmare that started
almost 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She was only 14 when she was forced to leave her home in Korea
and become a ``comfort woman,'' a sex slave to Japanese soldiers
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Bok Dong, now 72, wants the world to know about the
suffering that she and an estimated 200,000 other comfort women
endured. She also wants Japan's government to apologize and provide
financial reparation.
</P>
<P>
   Kim told her story through an interpreter Thursday at a luncheon
sponsored by the Washington Coalition on Comfort Women Issues,
which earlier issued a plea for help from the United States to get
reparation from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition said 63 House members support a resolution that
says Congress believes Japan should apologize for the war crimes
committed by the Japanese military during World War II and pay
reparations.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government has refused to compensate the women with
public funds, saying such claims were settled by postwar treaties.
Instead, Japan created a private fund that has offered to pay
$18,600 each to the former comfort women.
</P>
<P>
   However, the women insist that reparations should come directly
from the Japanese treasury.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibit illustrating the women's experiences, sponsored by
the coalition, the Human Rights Caucus, and the Women's Rights
Caucus, is on display through June 12 at the Cannon House Office
Building.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, wearing a pale green, silk han-bok, a traditional Korean
dress, described how the Japanese soldiers took her from her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese generals told our parents that we had to go work
for a military factory,'' she said. ``They said that we would make
uniforms and be able to save money, go home, and get married.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead she was taken to a comfort station, where the soldiers
raped her every day, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a young girl. I didn't even know what sex was,'' Kim
said. ``I was just captured, and these boys approached me like
wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Although telling her story is painful, she said she and other
former comfort women must get the word out to bring justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our days are limited, but we have to do this for the second
and next generation,'' said Kim, who lives in a communal home
called the House of Sharing with seven other former comfort women.
``We have been liberated long ago, but we have yet to receive
reparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Losita Nacino, 70, a former comfort woman originally from the
Philippines, said that she, like Kim, was 14 when Japanese soldiers
robbed her of her childhood and her dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The comfort women resisted, she said, but were powerless to
escape. ``We had nothing that we could do,'' she said. ``We were
only women. They were men, and they had guns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
