A5833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARSHBARGER'S RACE TO LOSE _ AND HE WON'T
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Saturday is payback time for all those who love to hate Scott
Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   The earnest prosecutor with 16 years of playing cop under his
belt tries to make the leap to governor. And the Democratic State
Convention in Worcester offers the last best chance for those he's
crossed to get even.
</P>
<P>
   As a prosecutor, a plodder, and a Protestant, the former
Middlesex County DA (eight years) and attorney general (eight more)
has stood outside the State House zeitgeist and rubbed a lot of
Beacon Hill insiders the wrong way. The party regulars, the
in-crowd, the party lifers who never warmed to Harshbarger's
call-'em-by-the-book style in political prosecutions, can try
tomorrow to gang up on the Democratic front-runner in the
gubernatorial nomination roll call.
</P>
<P>
   From the day US Representative Joe Kennedy bailed out, this has
been Harshbarger's race to lose. And he won't. In polls, money,
delegates, endorsements by sitting legislators, he has a big
advantage over Patricia McGovern and Brian Donnelly.
</P>
<P>
   And in terms of profile, Harshbarger's claim on the nomination
dwarfs that of either the former state senator or the onetime
congressman. As AG, Harshbarger can make news any day he wishes. As
the only candidate in the diminished Democratic field who's run
statewide (twice for AG), Harshbarger is deeper in breadth, depth,
reach, and field organization.
</P>
<P>
   His policies place him squarely in the center of the Democrats'
urban-suburban matrix: pro-women, pro-education, pro-labor;
antigun, antitobacco, anticasino. Personality, not policy, is his
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Once he clears the convention tomorrow, Harshbarger can look
forward to clear blue water and easier sailing. The package he
offers primary voters, plus his advantages in money and name
recognition, should make him the nominee in September unless he
totally blows it.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern should easily clear the 15-percent hurdle for delegates
to make the primary, but Donnelly will probably need some help from
his friends. If any established Democrat thinks Donnelly is likely
to be the nominee, I have not met that person. And if the most
serious charge leveled against Harshbarger is that he hasn't
``taken off ... nailed it down ... taken this thing to the bank,''
then that goes double or triple for McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to see why some important Democratic insiders are
cool to Harshbarger. The AG's longstanding indifference to small
political courtesies and the backscratching to which insiders are
accustomed has cost him.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Tom Menino's bloc of Boston delegates will likely go to
McGovern. The mayor is still peeved that Harshbarger dug his
pitchfork into the City Hall Plaza tiff, and Hizzonor likes Acting
Governor Cellucci, the overall favorite still.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Tom Finneran's leadership team is all over the
map, some with McGovern, some with Harshbarger, and the speaker
himself, a friend expects, will vote for fellow Dorchester boyo
Donnelly.
</P>
<P>
   The hard fact for the Harshbarger operation is that both Menino
and Finneran would prefer to deal with a re-elected Republican
governor they already know and like than an off-putting fellow
Democrat with an independent streak wider than Beacon Street. So
they'll be busting no rocks, and no heads either, in the mayor's or
the speaker's office to make life easier, or vote tallies higher,
for Harshbarger. The curious lack of Democratic unity extends to
some in the congressional delegation, who seek revenge for
Harshbarger's probe of this pol or that one or who, like US
Representative Marty Meehan, seem to view Harshbarger as a threat
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a poor Protestant prosecutor with a long, spiffy
record to do in September to try to unify a party whose barons,
earls, and satraps see no need to help him win against a
make-no-waves incumbent flush with cash?
</P>
<P>
   One option is for Harshbarger to nationalize the governor's
race: Assume Cellucci will top Treasurer Joe Malone in the GOP
primary, begin now to link Cellucci to national GOP icons who are
unpopular hereabouts, and raise cain, hob, and holy hell with
Kenneth Starr, Newt Gingrich, Trent Lott, Jesse Helms, et al.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a stretch. Yes, it's a long shot. Yes, Cellucci is
ditching almost any position (save perhaps the death penalty?) that
smacks of the Bible Belt. But Cellucci has so much money he won't
be able to duck the congressional leadership's antipathy to reform.
The pieces can fit.
</P>
<P>
   And Gingrich and Lott are _ how to put it? _ enormously
unpopular here. Some of the national controversies you can count on
for debate are tobacco, campaign reform, and Starr's jihad against
Clinton. Harshbarger already has strong positions on the first two,
and after a bungled effort to get on both sides of the independent
counsel probe, Harshbarger is presumably cognizant that Democratic
voters don't want him lining up with Starr.
</P>
<P>
   By casting Cellucci as a stand-in for unpopular GOP figures and
policies, by running ads morphing the Acting Guv into Gingrich's
beady-eyed image, Harshbarger can run hard for November beginning
now. Democrats don't want to see him pounding either McGovern or
Donnelly; better he beats up on the GOP's Newt-niks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1333EDT &QL; 
