<HEADER>
A5839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MARIUS-BOS &LR;      06-05 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MARIUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPLIFTING FRENCH HIT STRIKES A UNIVERSAL CHORD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIUS AND JEANNETTE &QC; 
Directed by: Robert Guediguian &QC; 
Screenplay by: Guediguian, Jean-Louis Milesi &QC; 
Starring: Ariane Ascaride, Gerard Meylan, Pascale Roberts, Jacques
Boudet, Frederique Bonnal, Jean-Pierre Darroussin, Laetitia
Pesenti, Miloud Nacer, Pierre Benderet &QC; 
Playing at: Coolidge Corner (in French with subtitles) &QC; 
Running time: 102 minutes &QC; 
Unrated &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Marius and Jeannette'' is a sunny and endearing throwback to
the physically cramped but spiritually expansive cinema of Marcel
Pagnol. Like Pagnol, filmmaker Robert Guediguian grew up in
Marseilles and says he wouldn't dream of making films anywhere
else. But the fact that ``Marius and Jeannette'' has become a huge
hit in its native France reminds us that it fills deeper needs than
those afforded by regional filmmaking. Although it's very specific
in its depiction and celebration of hardy working-class characters
leading a mutually nourishing communal existence in the shared
courtyard of their old tenement dwellings, it offers an embracing
vision of proletarian solidarity underpinning a modest but luminous
love story between a security guard and a single mother fired from
her supermarket checkout clerk job for complaining about working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   It's the easiest thing to sentimentalize everyday types, but
``Marius and Jeannette'' avoids the trap, partly by daring to
embrace a frankly retro belief in the dignity of workers struggling
to keep food on the table, partly by never allowing its highly
politicized passions to get in the way of its joie de vivre. Ariane
Ascaride's Jeannette meets Gerard Meylan's Marius when he discovers
her about to make off with two cans of paint salvaged from the
about-to-be-dismantled cement factory he's guarding in Day-Glo
coveralls as he brandishes a rifle with a telescopic sight.
Scarcely has Ascaride's scrappy Jeannette bawled him out for being
a class traitor by refusing to let her take the paint than he shows
up at her exfoliating quarters with paint and roller, ready to
pitch in and help.
</P>
<P>
   Ascaride, who won a French Cesar for this role and who is
Guediguian's wife and muse, is a firebrand when it comes to
sticking up for her rights, and a tender, concerned mother raising
two kids alone ever since the father of the younger one was killed
by a falling scaffold eight years ago. It helps that the children _
Laetitia Pesenti's Magali, who can't wait to be an investigative
journalist, and Milou Nacir's Malek, a precocious Koran scholar _
are not only nice kids, but star pupils who shine at school and
never add to their caring and hard-working mother's load. Meylan, a
friend of Guediguian's since childhood who has acted in all his
films but makes his living as a night nurse in a Marseilles
hospital, balances Ascaride's spontaneity with a sensitivity tinged
with gravity and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In the virtually plotless film, which Guediguian freely admits
is resolutely rose-colored when it comes to the embattled working
class, the conflict that moves the romance forward does not escape
contrivance. But of more importance is the allure of the
characters' little patch of turf in L'Estaque, the northern port
district of Marseilles, immortalized by Cezanne and Gauguin in
paintings that now ironically hang in millionaires' homes. Marius
(whose name echoes that of one of the films in Pagnol's famous
Marseilles trilogy) finds himself bonding with Jeannette's extended
family of neighbors as well as with her and the children. It's been
a long time since any film has been so animated by benevolent and
passionate energies _ the reason, no doubt, for the film's surprise
success in an otherwise pervasive Western social and cultural
vacuum. ``Marius and Jeannette'' harks back to the
solidarity-driven films of the great Jean Renoir, reminding us that
art says more than speeches ever can when it speaks from the heart
and not from theory.
</P>
<P>
   The film's benevolent spirits include Pascale Roberts's
concentration camp survivor who places a high value on life,
Jacques Boudet's retired teacher who patiently enlightens the
neighborhood kids while romancing Roberts in his halting way,
Jean-Pierre Darroussin's laborer whose wife won't let him live down
the fact that he once voted for the right-wing National Front, and
Frederique Bonnai, as the activist wife who reminds him that
everything becomes a political act, right down to choosing which
brand of beer to order. The film opens with a wonderful image _ an
inflated plastic globe, turned upside down, bobbing along a
waterway until it gently bumps to a stop at the cement steps of the
cracking, weed-ridden neighborhood at which we're about to
disembark. As the characters mix their aioli communally in a stone
bowl, ``Marius and Jeannette'' offers a simple human alternative of
neighborliness to the alienation that keeps workers (and would-be
workers) fragmented. Charmingly, it asserts that finding the
courage to love, and in doing so reclaiming your life, is a
political act, too. ``Marius and Jeannette'' is a radiant little
proletarian fairy tale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
