<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5861 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCREEN-SIREN-COMEBACK     06-05 1813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCREEN-SIREN-COMEBACK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENA ROWLANDS: THE REAL BLONDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine _
the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH
STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package
composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from
numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: Two color slides are available FREE OF CHARGE!)  
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``It's a phase!'' Gena Rowlands snaps at the notion that she may
be at height of her 50-year acting career. She's lived through
enough ups and downs to know better than to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's a phase,'' she adds, smiling drolly. ``I see most
things happening in 10- to 12-year increments. And when you've been
around as long as I have, you begin to see things more clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in her mid-60s, Rowlands is a legend in the film world. But
as a woman she's not so easy to classify.
</P>
<P>
   Well-bred, worldly and streetwise at the same time, she manages
to be both a lady and a real broad _ an American Jeanne Moreau. In
fact, Rowlands has long been a popular icon in Europe, while she's
had more of a cult following at home.
</P>
<P>
   But even if her current renaissance is just a phase, it looks
like it will be a long one. She filmed three movies this year, a
thick pile of scripts arrives at her home every day _ and Sharon
Stone pays the questionable tribute of remaking ``Gloria,'' one of
the best films Rowlands made with her late husband, writer-director
John Cassavetes.
</P>
<P>
   Cassavetes (who died of liver cancer in 1989) had a bit of a
revival of his own last fall, when his last unproduced script,
``She's So Lovely,'' was directed by the couple's son, Nick
Cassavetes.
</P>
<P>
   Nick also directed his mother two years ago in ``Unhook The
Stars,'' a movie he wrote for her.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing an orange and claret Todd Oldham velvet robe and tightly
clutching her first coffee of the morning, Rowlands pads out of her
bedroom in the same Hollywood Hills home where Cassavetes shot the
movies ``Faces'' (1968), ``Opening Night'' (1977) and ``Love
Streams'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   In the living room, her longtime makeup artist sits ready to
transform her for a photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' she says, reiterating one of her oft-quoted lines, ``I
do look like a goldfish without my makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   With her live-in boyfriend, Bob Forrest, standing close by,
Rowlands immediately begins reminiscing about Cassavetes, the man
whom she credits for her success as an actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My late husband made a lot of great pictures,'' she says. ``It
was a very creative time we were working in. That was followed by a
not-so-creative time, which I think we're still in. So people look
back with nostalgia. I think some of the magic of that time rubbed
off on me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the makeup artist works, Rowlands' thin red mouth becomes
more pronounced, her platinum bob gains a healthy pouf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glamour was never my game,'' says the actress, who still
possesses her famously cool looks. ``I just hate that thing about
beauty. There's always someone out there better looking or worse
looking. Beauty and glamour are not real things. To depend on them
is very hard for anyone, but particularly hard for attractive
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing the photo session, Rowlands brings out pictures
that were taken on the set of ``Paulie,'' the film in which she
plays a woman who forms a bond with a talking parrot.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen different birds were used to play Paulie, as well as
several animatronic copies created by special-effects wizard Stan
Winston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The animated bird was very dear,'' Rowlands says. ``You forget
he's animated. But there was one live bird they used primarily _
and, well, I fell in love. It was unrequited, of course, but that
doesn't make it any less passionate!''
</P>
<P>
   In her most recent film ``Hope Floats,'' Rowlands plays a
taxidermist who's a constant source of embarrassment to her young
daughter, Sandra Bullock. Harry Connick Jr. plays Bullock's
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a studio picture, but it reads like an independent
picture because it's an examination of love,'' Rowlands says.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls dancing with Connick between takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we had tornadoes in Austin and some terrible
weather,'' she says, ``it might have been the happiest set I've
ever been on.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is not something one generally associates with Gena
Rowlands _ at least not onscreen. In most of her movies, she has
specialized in melancholy or madness, or something in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I've had terrifying times of unhappiness,'' she
says. ``After John died, there were years of crippling insanity. I
couldn't work. But I've finally reconciled by realizing I had him
through all the good years. Nobody has everything all the time.
Yes, it's nine years ago this week that he died. And I have to say
I'm very happy. I adore my three children _ Nick, 39, and daughters
Alexandra and Zoe, both in their 20s. I have a lot of friends and a
lot of work.'' (Her third upcoming film is ``The Mighty,'' which
costars Sharon Stone.)
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands grew up in a small Wisconsin town, where her father was
a liberal politician. Her childhood wasn't entirely idyllic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a grandmother who didn't like me much,'' she says. ``I
only stopped blaming that on myself when I figured out she didn't
like my mother much, either. Nothing I did pleased her. And I was a
sickly kid, so that compounded things.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided early in her teens that she wanted to be an actress.
But after high school, she tried to put that goal aside and had a
brief, dispiriting stint at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little breakdown, actually,'' she says. ``Now they'd
call it a `depression.' But we didn't have that word then. My
parents immediately understood _ they knew I was just in the wrong
place. So my mother took me to New York when I was 20 so I could
try to become an actress.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young adult, Rowlands says, she was ``terribly, terribly
serious _ as you can only be at that age. That's the nice thing
about getting older; you get somewhat lighter. We should all be
born old and finally return to our mother's wombs.''
</P>
<P>
   When she enrolled at the American Academy of Dramatic Arts in
Manhattan, Rowland immediately noticed the brooding, intensely
handsome John Cassavetes _ but she did her best to avoid him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left Wisconsin, all I knew was that I didn't want to
get married or have children,'' she remembers. ``I assumed it
ruined your career. So I was desperate not to fall in love. I said
all the things people say _ only I meant them! Then one day I saw
John talking to someone and I thought _ `Oh, no!' And whenever I
saw him, I'd head the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   But when she performed in a production of Archibald MacLeish's
``Dangerous Corners,'' Cassavetes came backstage to seek her out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have a very beautiful red dress on,'' Rowlands recalls
wistfully. ``I resisted him as long as I could.'' Which wasn't very
long: They married several months later.
</P>
<P>
   While Rowlands worked in the theater in the evenings, Cassavetes
formed an improvisational group with some fellow actors and began
working on what became his first film, ``Shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   While his films are considered classics now, Cassavetes and his
troupe were vilified at the time for dealing so directly with such
subjects as alcoholism, infidelity and mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People attacked us wildly,'' Rowlands says. ``They were not
used to having their emotions so engaged or seeing anything so
intimate on screen. John's films weren't particularly sexual _ they
were all about love. People felt exposed. But years later, women
started coming up to me crying about ``A Woman Under the
Influence.'' They said it was a catharsis for them. And men
admitted it was something they'd never understood.
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands is still close with many of the actors who appeared in
Cassavetes' films, including Peter Falk, Ben Gazzara and Seymour
Cassell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real sociable,'' she says. ``I never have been. But we
revealed ourselves through acting, and we often made fools of
ourselves. That created bonds. Acting is endlessly fascinating _ if
you expose yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Rowlands admits that she can still wake up profoundly
depressed _ ``I have great variations in moods,'' is how she puts
it _ but she tries to channel it all into her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, `What'll it be today? Let's do something with this.'
For me, acting heals. To put one foot in front of another when
you're in an awful mood _ that kind of pressure is so good. I never
found acting scary. I found it an immense relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she has now worked with many other directors _ Woody
Allen on ``Another Woman,'' Lasse Halstrom on ``Once Around'' and
``Something to Talk About'' _ it's clear that she'll always
consider her partnership with Cassavetes to be her most precious
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she's not the type to retreat into a nostalgic haze. In
fact, the older she gets, the more she feels the need to reinvent
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you new energy and keeps life exciting _ and most of
all, bearable,'' she says. ``I realized that after John died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a chance to change your baggage and your opinion
of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain age,'' she adds, ``you realize that you must be
reincarnated throughout your life. You certainly don't have to wait
until you die.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
