</P>
<P>
   When she enrolled at the American Academy of Dramatic Arts in
Manhattan, Rowland immediately noticed the brooding, intensely
handsome John Cassavetes _ but she did her best to avoid him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left Wisconsin, all I knew was that I didn't want to
get married or have children,'' she remembers. ``I assumed it
ruined your career. So I was desperate not to fall in love. I said
all the things people say _ only I meant them! Then one day I saw
John talking to someone and I thought _ `Oh, no!' And whenever I
saw him, I'd head the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   But when she performed in a production of Archibald MacLeish's
``Dangerous Corners,'' Cassavetes came backstage to seek her out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have a very beautiful red dress on,'' Rowlands recalls
wistfully. ``I resisted him as long as I could.'' Which wasn't very
long: They married several months later.
</P>
<P>
   While Rowlands worked in the theater in the evenings, Cassavetes
formed an improvisational group with some fellow actors and began
working on what became his first film, ``Shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   While his films are considered classics now, Cassavetes and his
troupe were vilified at the time for dealing so directly with such
subjects as alcoholism, infidelity and mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People attacked us wildly,'' Rowlands says. ``They were not
used to having their emotions so engaged or seeing anything so
intimate on screen. John's films weren't particularly sexual _ they
were all about love. People felt exposed. But years later, women
started coming up to me crying about ``A Woman Under the
Influence.'' They said it was a catharsis for them. And men
admitted it was something they'd never understood.
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands is still close with many of the actors who appeared in
Cassavetes' films, including Peter Falk, Ben Gazzara and Seymour
Cassell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real sociable,'' she says. ``I never have been. But we
revealed ourselves through acting, and we often made fools of
ourselves. That created bonds. Acting is endlessly fascinating _ if
you expose yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Rowlands admits that she can still wake up profoundly
depressed _ ``I have great variations in moods,'' is how she puts
it _ but she tries to channel it all into her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, `What'll it be today? Let's do something with this.'
For me, acting heals. To put one foot in front of another when
you're in an awful mood _ that kind of pressure is so good. I never
found acting scary. I found it an immense relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she has now worked with many other directors _ Woody
Allen on ``Another Woman,'' Lasse Halstrom on ``Once Around'' and
``Something to Talk About'' _ it's clear that she'll always
consider her partnership with Cassavetes to be her most precious
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she's not the type to retreat into a nostalgic haze. In
fact, the older she gets, the more she feels the need to reinvent
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you new energy and keeps life exciting _ and most of
all, bearable,'' she says. ``I realized that after John died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a chance to change your baggage and your opinion
of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain age,'' she adds, ``you realize that you must be
reincarnated throughout your life. You certainly don't have to wait
until you die.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
