<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CAPSULE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST MOVIES ON VIDEOTAPE AND TELEVISION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are capsule reviews of the latest video releases and
weekend movies scheduled for the three major premium cable
services.
</P>
<P>
   In video stores this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar and Lucinda'' As few period films do, this Gillian
Armstrong production comes to life magically, powered by Ralph
Fiennes and Cate Blanchett. They play eccentric gamblers who meet
on a ship from London to Australia and enkindle in each other a
wildly romantic dream _ building a glass church held together with
steel struts and floating it on a barge from Sydney to a remote
corner of New South Wales. His shame-drenched missionary and her
strong-willed glass-factory owner are memorable. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' Clint Eastwood's
film of John Berendt's bestseller doesn't come together as a whole,
but still has juicy stuff to savor. Savannah eccentrics buzz around
the murder trial of an antiques dealer (Kevin Spacey, purring
indolently) who shot his bisexual lover. John Cusack is a
bright-eyed outsider; Alison Eastwood (Clint's daughter) needs no
nepotism to convince as a warm, sexy love interest; and the film is
stolen by the sassy, cross-dressing Lady Chablis, playing herself
as only she can. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Locusts'' Period piece about a sensitive, virile drifter
and a man-eating widow who runs the symbolic feedlot in her corner
of Kansas. Nicely textured, with Vince Vaughn's maverick and Kate
Capshaw's boss lady holding the screen easily until the film
collapses under the weight of all the killings and castrations that
pile up at the end. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On premium cable Friday and Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ``Father Hood'' Patrick Swayze, as the wayward father of two
kids, snatches them and hits the road, one step ahead of the law.
He and the juves are appealing, but they're sunk by prefab writing
that confines them to the level of TV sitcom, never letting them
really break out. (PG-13) On HBO Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turbulence'' Silly thriller about a serial killer (Ray Liotta)
loose on a jumbo jet bound from New York to Los Angeles in a storm.
He toys sadistically with Lauren Holly's flight attendant, who'd
rather take over the plane's controls and land it since everybody
else on board seems to be dead. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Independence Day''  &LR; It plays like an entire movie studio
dropped on your head. Aliens in massive flying saucers aim to
clobber us, and President Bill Pullman must lead the resistance,
which includes scientist Jeff Goldblum and fighter pilot Will
Smith. Imagine Cecil B. DeMille directing ``War of the Worlds,''
and you've got the picture. (PG-13) On HBO Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Men in Black'' &LR;  Hugely funny, deadpan spoof in which Tommy
Lee Jones and Will Smith don Blues Brothers garb and keep the world
safe from aliens who obviously landed long ago. Director Barry
Sonnenfeld gave it enough wit and self-confidence to make
sophisticated mass entertainment with some moments of real
pop-culture brilliance. (PG-13) On HBO Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Friday &UR; ``Fools Rush In''  &LR; Matthew Perry's Manhattan WASP and
Salma Hayek's Las Vegas Latina are attractive in this would-be
romantic comedy of cultural collision, but there's not much impulse
or antic spark to be found in its sitcom moves. (PG-13) On Cinemax
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   (CT)(CT) &UR; ``The Devil's Own''  &LR; Intelligent but murky and
slow-moving attempt to put character into the thriller. Idealistic
New York cop Harrison Ford unwittingly shelters fugitive Irish
terrorist Brad Pitt, whose attempt to get his hands on a shipment
of missiles is downplayed as he's transformed into a romantic hero.
(R) On Cinemax Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Protocol'' The US State Department wants to swap Goldie Hawn
to an oil emir for a military base, but she gives them a lesson in
patriotism. (PG) On Cinemax Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Against All Odds'' Remake of a film noir about an unemployed
football player who's sent down to Mexico to retrieve a gangster's
girlfriend, finds her, and falls for her, with dire consequences.
But there's no real heat between Jeff Bridges and Rachel Ward, so
their love among the ruins goes limp. The film's depiction of Los
Angeles as a barren game board of corruption isn't bad, but the
only thing worth seeing is Jane Greer, who played the femme fatale
in the original and is riveting as a pillar of the evil,
land-grabbing rich. (R) On Cinemax Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   FridaySaturday ``Race the Sun'' After being inspired overnight
by their new teacher, a class of underachieving students in Hawaii
enters an international competition for solar-powered cars. The
cars are cool, but the go-team story is deeply cliche-ridden. Halle
Berry is on cruise control as the idealistic teacher. (PG) (Matthew
Gilbert) On Showtime Saturday night. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Housesitter'' Not the most original of screwball comedies, but
a sweet, user-friendly one, with ingratiating performances by
Goldie Hawn as a one-night stand who moves in on architect Steve
Martin, who can't keep up with her whoppers _ especially the one
that they're married. (PG) On Showtime Saturday night.
</P>
