<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WILDE-BOS &LR;      06-05 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WILDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PORTRAYAL RICHER THAN OSCAR WILDE'S STATUS AS GAY ICON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILDE &QC; 
Directed by: Brian Gilbert &QC; 
Screenplay by: Julian Mitchell, based on Richard Ellman's
biography &QC; 
Starring: Stephen Fry, Jude Law, Vanessa Redgrave, Jennifer Ehle,
Gemma Jones, Judy Parfitt, Michael Sheen, Zoe Wanamaker, Tom
Wilkinsen &QC; 
Playing at: Kendall Square Cinema; Embassy Cinema, Waltham &QC; 
Running time: 116 minutes &QC; 
Rated: R (strong sexuality and language) &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Wilde is back in a big way. His plays are being staged
with increasing frequency, and plays about him are thriving too.
``Wilde,'' directed by Brian Gilbert and starring Stephen Fry, not
only adds to the growing list of films on the brilliant Irish
author whose life and career crashed and burned and who died broken
at 46 in 1900 after his homosexuality _ then illegal in England _
landed him in prison. It is quite the best film about Wilde,
rescuing him not only from gay-icon status, but from portrayals
that emphasized his epigrammatic wit and fey style at the expense
of his other qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Like Richard Ellmann's biography, from which this biofilm is
drawn, ``Wilde'' achieves a balance almost unheard of in depictions
of the elegant maverick who disconcerted and entertained fin de
siecle London. Apart from being the closest thing to a dead ringer
in the several films about Wilde, Fry convinces us he enjoys
inhabiting Wilde, even when the writer's melancholy side takes
over. Moreover, Fry compels us to share his obviously heartfelt
admiration not only for Wilde's talent, but for his sensitivity,
generosity, and bravery.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about Fry's Wilde is his way of making us realize
that Wilde spent more time feeling than talking. He may have
exhibited a self-destructive streak in stubbornly chasing after the
wild, petulant, and emotionally and intellectually pinched Lord
Alfred Douglas, but Fry's reaction shots make a good case for the
fact that he was a steadfast and caring friend. That caring also
extended to his loyal and loving wife, even if he subordinated her
happiness and well-being, and that of his two children, to his
pursuit of young Douglas, nicknamed Bosie.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the film flinch from depicting, although not unendingly
or leeringly, a few convincing homosexual sex scenes. It was the
testimony of several so-called rent boys, after all, that sank
Wilde in his ill-advised suit against Bosie's vicious and
vindictive father, the marquess of Queensberry (the same man who,
ironically, invented the rules said to have civilized boxing). As
no other Wilde before him has done, Fry conveys with his eyes a
certainty that his arrogant and capricious young lover is going to
be bad news, and an equal certainty that he will pursue Bosie all
the same, even though it cost him everything.
</P>
<P>
   Fry and director Brian Gilbert's biggest accomplishment is to
portray Wilde with dignity, even as he seems more than a little
ridiculous playing the fop. Jude Law moves a promising career yet
another step forward as the unscrupulous Bosie, utterly convincing
as a shallow but dangerous brat. Jennifer Ehle is another plus as
Wilde's wife, the aptly named Constance, who stood by her errant
husband. Michael Sheen is sympathetic as Wilde's first male lover,
the Canadian Robbie Ross, who returned Wilde's love. For a worldly
man, Fry's Wilde proceeds with prodigious blindness to the
consequences of thumbing his nose at the establishment, which stood
for it in his plays, but drew the line when in real life he
challenged its hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Wilde's loyalty and bravery were misplaced, at great
cost to himself and those who loved him. As both Irishman and
homosexual, Wilde was doubly an outsider, and Fry subtly but
tellingly projects Wilde's sense of growing isolation. He may be a
foolish iconoclast, but he's never an unfeeling one. Fry captures
him sympathetically, and in all his contradictions, in a film that
brings the period to life with vivid immediacy. His refined
sensibility and quick wit are released with an amusingly studied
carelessness from his tall, pudgy body by Fry's empathetic and, we
are convinced, fully inhabited and sensitively faceted Wilde.
Stylish, sad, opulent, brilliant, and clear-eyed, ``Wilde'' does
justice to its complex subject. It should stand as the definitive
biofilm for years to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
