<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK WHAT HAPPENS WHEN HARVARD NAMES THE WRONG MAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Local bicycle historian David Herlihy was a bit surprised to
receive a letter from Jack Reardon, executive director of the
Harvard Alumni Association, inviting him to join the HAA board.
It's not that Herlihy wasn't worthy. He's active in local bicycle
causes and has spent a decade researching a definitive history of
the invention of the ``bipedaliferous wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Herlihy just doesn't fit the profile of the usual HAA
glad-hander. He can't remember making a donation since he graduated
from the World's Greatest University in 1980, and he thinks he may
be the first board member to have spent his Harvard years in the
once-radical Dudley Co-ops, off-campus cooperative housing in North
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Herlihy was to begin his two-year term, HAA boss
Reardon phoned him in a tizzy. You're the wrong David Herlihy,
Reardon gasped. We meant to appoint David Herlihy of Hyannis, a
retired executive who spent 37 years at IBM. Ooops. Our David
Herlihy went to the first meeting anyway, met the real David
Herlihy, and _ surprise, surprise _ got the feeling that he wasn't
really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   After the first meeting, Herlihy realized he wasn't receiving
briefing materials for the next gathering. After initially blowing
him off, Reardon agreed to a lunch. Thenceforward, this story has a
(relatively) happy ending. Reardon suggested that Herlihy work with
Professional Connections, an HAA-based career counseling service
that had been languishing from inattention. ``Today,'' reports our
David Herlihy, ``thanks in large part to my subcommittee, the
service has been completely reorganized and is showing strong signs
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Special message for David Herlihy, former singer-guitarist for
the rock band O Positive: The next David Herlihy item is yours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I can dig it
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Boston historian Susan Wilson promises plenty of ``good dirt''
in her just-published history of Forest Hills cemetery, called
``Garden of Memories.'' And indeed, she delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Hills, possibly the most beautiful open area in Boston,
was consecrated in 1848 to complement existing ``garden
cemeteries,'' like Cambridge's Mt. Auburn. The latter was and is
private. Forest Hills was a public cemetery, with large tracts
reserved for veterans and Boston firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Hollowed cheek by withered jowl with hoi polloi, however, one
also finds no shortage of Welds, Minots, Plimptons, and Shaws at
Forest Hills. ``The most migratory corpse'' of Joseph Warren, hero
of Bunker Hill, ended up at Forest Hills, after two previous
interments (a fitting end for a man who robbed many a grave in
dubious ``medical'' pursuits). Former Boston mayor Andrew Peters is
there, though his mistress of 11 years _ I don't mean for 11 years,
I mean 11 years old _ is not.
</P>
<P>
   Lit'ry dust abounds. Playwright Eugene O'Neill, late of the
Hotel Shelton (famous last words: ``Born in a hotel room and died
in a hotel room, dammit!''), lies there, not far from e.e.
cummings, whose headstone is engraved in capital letters, EDWARD
ESTLIN CUMMINGS. Also sited: The poet Anne Sexton and historian
Frederick Lewis Allen. Restaurateur Jacob Wirth sleeps in Forest
Hills, as does Boston Celtic star Reggie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson reports that Lewis's funeral procession was topped only
once at Forest Hills, by the 200,000-person ``Walk of Sorrow'' that
accompanied the bodies of Sacco and Vanzetti to the Forest Hills
crematorium (``Nobody else would touch them,'' Wilson explains) in
1928. Elizabeth Glendower Evans, the Beacon Hill socialite who
tried to rally world opinion to save the two Italian immigrants, is
also in Forest Hills. The two men's ashes now repose partly in
Italy, and partly in the special collections room of the Boston
Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's book is available from Forest Hills (617-524-0703), or
you could pick it up at the cemetery's 150th-anniversary
celebration and sculpture exhibition during the afternoon of
Sunday, June 14. Read a good book, stroll among examples of
contemporary art ... ``You go there and it's a real picnic,'' as
Kahlil Gibran once said of Forest Hills. No, not Kahlil Gibran, the
mystical poet! I mean his nephew, the artist, who lived on Harrison
Avenue in Chinatown. These names are so confusing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(AT)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
