</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF GAY LIFE IN SAN FRANCISCO IN THE YEARS BEFORE AIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALES OF THE CITY &QC; 
Starring: Laura Linney, Paul Hopkins, Colin Ferguson, Bill
Campbell, Olympia Dukakis, Swoosie Kurtz, Jackie Burroughs, Thomas
Gibson, Barbara Garick &QC; 
Directed by: Pierre Gang &QC; 
On: Showtime &QC; 
Time: Sunday and Monday nights, 9 p.m. &QC; 
Rated: TVMA (nudity, drug use) &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that it aired on the generally high-minded PBS
in 1994, and that it was quickly elevated into an arts cause when
right-wing groups began whining about the gay content and drug use,
``Tales of the City'' was just a lot of good fun. It was a wry,
sentimental, and heavily plotted soap opera, and it was dressed up
in Day-Glo 1970s kitsch and the wonderfully sunny surfaces of San
Francisco. While themes of identity and personal liberation managed
to keep the rare goings-on at 28 Barbary Lane from sheer
weightlessness, still the miniseries was six hours of light
amusement and mystery. ``Brideshead Revisited'' it was not.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday nights on Showtime, ``More Tales of the
City'' arrives with its own arts-world stigma, since PBS is said to
have bowed to right-wing censorship when it bowed out of this
sequel. But like its highly rated predecessor, ``More Tales of the
City'' is nothing more or less than six hours of fully outrageous
coincidence, 1970s visual wit, and nostalgia for the years before
AIDS put a hole in the world. It's an addictive stretch of
television that picks up six weeks after ``Tales'' left off,
successfully bringing back the same characters and plot lines and
apartments, and adding a few newer ones such as Mother Mucca, the
elderly madam of a brothel in the Nevada desert. Many of the
original actors also return, with the notable exceptions of Chloe
Webb as Mona, Marcus D'Amico as Michael, and Paul Gross as Brian,
who have been replaced without much disruption by Nina Siemaszko,
Paul Hopkins, and Whip Hubley, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``More Tales'' is primarily divided between the plot turns of
two sets of characters _ turns that I will not spoil here.
Basically, Mona Ramsey learns that her magical landlady, Mrs.
Madrigal, is actually her father (after a sex-change operation),
and she receives even more family information at Mother Mucca's
whorehouse, where she has become the receptionist. Meanwhile, the
less innocent Mary Ann Singleton and the romantic Michael Tolliver
take a cruise ship to Mexico, where Mary Ann falls for a handsome
new character named Burke Andrews. Burke isn't gay, as Mary Ann
fears, but he does come with some pretty bizarre baggage. And
Michael runs into his former lover, Jon Fielding, with whom he
attempts a more mature relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Because Armistead Maupin's fiction, on which ``Tales'' and
``More Tales'' are based, is both episodic and intricately
designed, it continues to lend itself beautifully to the extended
time afforded by television. (The books began in serial form in the
San Francisco Chronicle.) As with Dickens, ``More Tales'' has the
right balance of minor characters and subplots mixed into the
sprawl to provide a welcome detour from the major doings. The less
visible include Beauchamp and DeDe Day, whose marriage takes a
disastrous turn, and DeDe's recently widowed mother, Frannie, who
is inducted into a sex club for women over 60 called Pinus. Also on
the periphery is Brian Hawkins, who begins a strangely anonymous
sexual relationship, and Swoosie Kurtz as Mona's vengeful mother.
</P>
<P>
   It's all engaging and charming, although ``More Tales'' does
lack some of the giddy and revelatory energy of ``Tales.'' The
problem is not sequel-itis, that dashed-off cashing-in quality that
infects many returns to the well; it's just that the sexual and
personal liberations of Maupin's world are more familiar and less
mind-bending the second time around. And much of the plot activity
involves the dusting up of fallout from the ``Tales'' narrative,
making it feel less inventive and fresh. Also, the 1970s have been
mined so relentlessly in recent years that it's not as much of a
tickle in 1998 to find clips from ``The Sonny &AMP; Cher Comedy Hour''
or references to Patty Hearst and Angie Dickinson as it was in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are uniformly good, with Laura Linney once
again delightful as Mary Ann, the Cleveland naif. Hopkins manages
to make Michael's moodiness and heroism appealing, and Siemaszko is
fine as Mona, though not as dynamic as Webb was. It's fun to see
Thomas Gibson, most visible these days for his mild-mannered comedy
on ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' playing an out-and-out villain, and Bill
Campbell is natural and gentle as Jon. Olympia Dukakis is in the
most difficult role of all, of course, as the transgendered Mrs.
Madrigal. She's a strong mother to her tenant ``children,'' but
she's a fountain of melancholy, too, noting about her love for pot
that ``some people drink to forget; I smoke to remember.'' To make
such an unusual character so sympathetic, to present her entirely
without judgment or preachiness, may be the biggest achievement of
the ``Tales'' series, both for Dukakis and for Maupin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
