<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PERFECT-BOS &LR;      06-05 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PERFECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUDE, MONEYED HEARTLESSNESS SPLASHED ACROSS THE SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A PERFECT MURDER &QC; 
Directed by: Andrew Davis &QC; 
Screenplay by: Patrick Smith Kelly, based on Frederick Knott's
play, ``Dial M for Murder'' &QC; 
Starring: Michael Douglas, Gwyneth Paltrow, Viggo Mortensen, David
Suchet, Sarita Choudhury, Michael P. Moran, Novella Nelson,
Constance Towers &QC; 
Playing at: Cheri, suburbs &QC; 
Running time: 107 minutes &QC; 
Rated: R (violence, sexuality and language) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Alfred Hitchcock filmed ``Dial M for Murder,'' its
perversity and malevolence _ the qualities that attracted Hitchcock
_ were couched in what seemed a cerebral puzzle. It very much
seemed stagebound, a filmed play. ``A Perfect Murder,'' Andrew
Davis's remake, predictably takes the story outside and even hurls
it tempestuously through the streets of New York. Yet it's much
darker and twistier than the original, not only more physically
violent, but more psychically violent. Unlike the original, where
at least Grace Kelly's intended victim was adulterous but
sympathetic, this new version spares nobody. Its inner world is one
of brutal lovelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Lies and greed are its twin motors, and it sweeps you along in
its steady descent like a Jacobean revenge tragedy. As soon as
Michael Douglas's predatory millionaire looks at his trophy wife,
Gwyneth Paltrow, raises a flute of champagne, and says, in what
she's sure is a sadistic double entendre, ``Here's to stolen
moments,'' the nonstop dread begins. Paltrow's Silk Stocking
District trust-fund princess, who wears an air of entitlement with
the same swanlike poise as she wears a ball gown, has been having
an affair with a rough-edged painter in his Brooklyn loft, and
she's sure her powerful, if hitherto inattentive, husband knows. A
lot of white starts showing beneath the pupils of her eyes. They
suggest poached eggs.
</P>
<P>
   What we've got here is a triangle, and the underrated Viggo
Mortensen, as the artist who's romancing the married woman, is more
than adequate to the task of holding up his quota of the venality
and danger hemming Paltrow's anxious woman in. The screenplay is
smart enough to make sure Paltrow is handed more than a victim
role. Still, it amounts to a square-off between Douglas's raging
but outwardly controlled husband and Mortensen's smooth barbarian
at the gates. The trouble at home is exacerbated by the
wheeler-dealer's business troubles. His wife's trust fund, in fact,
would help him cover some reckless financial overextensions.
</P>
<P>
   So the plot is hatched. Douglas, using moral outrage like a
baton, suggests Gordon Gekko under pressure, who has perhaps lost a
little off his fastball. In this film where everybody has at least
one guilty secret and nobody's hands are clean, Douglas projects
instincts as basic as any. Getting the edge on the painter by
looking into the latter's past, he blackmails him into murdering
his wife, sets up the killing, and retreats into an airtight alibi
at his club. Naturally, the murder doesn't go as planned. That's
when the improvisation _ and the guignol-based entertainment _
begins, enlivened by glimpses of a multi-culti New York,
personified by Sarita Choudhury's pal to Paltrow at the United
Nations, where both work as translators, and by David Suchet's
Arabic-American cop, as unnervingly competent-seeming as the sleuth
Suchet plays on TV, Hercule Poirot.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving anything away, it can be said that the film ends
with a death, and involves a couple more along the way. They're
staged for shock value, and achieve it. The film works as a series
of skilled and cynical hammerstrokes executed in a pervasive
darkness that makes the route between Wall Street and the Upper
East Side seem a tunnel to hell.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is, as usual, all fire and ice, clenched and furious.
Paltrow becomes interesting when she abandons her usual air of cool
self-possession and allows her features to blur with the stress
she's feeling as she simmers in her bad choice of men. Mortensen
holds the screen against them both as the far from romantic
psychopath, whose role is expanded most beyond the original, and
who takes it to career-propelling realms of silken creepiness.
</P>
<P>
   While successfully steeping the story in its fast-paced,
soulless, art-saturated, money-soaked world, ``A Perfect Murder''
denies audiences the usual moral certainties, even if it proffers
the usual soothing masscult consolations of beauty and power being
equated with moral corruption. Nobody is entirely sympathetic in
this successful updating to a jangly contemporaneity. You won't
necessarily develop a rooting interest in any of them, or
necessarily even like them. So enthusiastically, and with such
Hogarthian vigor, is the film's world of sleek, crude,
steamrolling, moneyed heartlessness splashed across the screen that
you half expect Donald Trump to be revealed as the murderer. You
may not like where ``A Perfect Murder'' is going, but once aboard,
you won't want to leave until you get there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
