<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TRUMAN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRUMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN A SPOOF, A RICH PORTRAYAL OF OUR TELEVISION AGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE TRUMAN SHOW &QC; 
Directed by: Peter Weir &QC; 
Screenplay by: Andrew Niccol &QC; 
Starring: Jim Carrey, Laura Linney, Noah Emmerich, Natascha
McElhone, Holland Taylor, Ed Harris &QC; 
Playing at: Cheri, suburbs &QC; 
Running time: 104 minutes &QC; 
Rated: PG (thematic elements and mild language) &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey did a better job than he was given credit for when he
linked TV and dysfunction in ``The Cable Guy.'' But nothing in that
film, or in any of his previous films, prepares us for the
mind-bending dazzle of ``The Truman Show.'' It's not enough to say
that there's nothing dumb or dumber in it. It's more than comedy,
more than satire. It's the kind of huge instant pop culture myth
that comes into being when Hollywood gets the big bang theory right
by throwing together a popular star ready to push the envelope and
a bold, powerful, reverberant fantasy that nails the Zeitgeist with
enough thematic richness to carry us into and beyond the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' pushes off from the fact that TV is
voracious, swallowing material endlessly, seldom chewing it. Once
it served us. Now we serve it. TV's synthetic reality has become
our model for ``real life.'' Carrey's Truman Burbank is the only
real thing in ``The Truman Show.'' It's the world's longest-running
documentary soap opera, watched by millions. Truman has no idea he
has been its unwitting star for 30 years, never once dreaming he
was acquired as a baby by the network and plunked into the world's
biggest set under a massive man-made dome. He thinks he's living in
an oceanside community called Seahaven. Everyone in his life _ his
wife, his mother, his beer-drinking best buddy _ is an actor. The
show's creator, Ed Harris's Christof, watches from above: godlike,
remote, bringing sinister new meaning to the terms ``planned
community'' and ``control room.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Christof control the weather; he also controls the
aggressive cheer level in this film that neatly turns the tables on
so-called reality-based TV as it follows the logic of turning lives
into programming. What does reality become when all it wants to do
is copy TV? Truman is the only thing that's unscripted, or rather
the innocence of his reactions is. His innocence and his privacy
are the real subjects of the show-within-the-movie, not the daily
banalities he has been conditioned to believe constitute reality in
his blindingly sunny world of greeting-card platitudes, shimmering
so surrealistically. The brave new world of Shakespeare and Aldous
Huxley has been supplanted by a ratings-driven world. Cannon fodder
has been replaced by camera fodder. Five thousand hidden cameras
are ever ready to capture Truman's every move and flicker through
Seahaven's beachfront world of Victorian replicas and white picket
fences.
</P>
<P>
   He's the postmodern equivalent of 18th-century castrati,
mutilated in order to ensure ongoing entertainment value. Truman,
an adventurer at heart, is functionally lobotomized, made afraid to
attempt the voyage that would bring him bumping up against the
outer wall of the set he thinks is the horizon, because his
make-believe mother convinced him his father died in a boating
accident. ``You belong here with me,'' Christof's voice tells him
from above; ``in my world you have nothing to fear.'' But when an
actress playing a girl he meets feels sorry for him, breaks
character, and tells him what's really going on before she's
discovered and banished by the network Nazis, Carrey slips into his
postmodern Jimmy Stewart mode, sputtering with anger, gathering
steam slowly, like a locomotive.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey's screen persona has until now been an extension of his
wacky unguided-missile characters from TV's ``In Living Color'' _
brighter-than-bright, heightened, stylized. But here he tones down
the physical comedy, abandons the Astaire-on-acid shtick for
vulnerability. He moves from anesthetized to desperate to indignant
as he confronts the truth of his situation and resolves literally
to break through the fourth wall and reclaim his life. ``The Truman
Show'' becomes a rebellion against the synthetic, the prefab, the
inauthentic. Truman's enemy is TV's falsifying of experience, its
stifling of any urges it thinks it can't control.
</P>
<P>
   Truman's appeal is rooted in Carrey's ability to project a
childlike acceptance of everything at _ what better for TV? _ face
value. He only dimly suspects that everybody around him is
different. He isn't paranoiac, but should be. Yet director Peter
Weir and screenwriter Andrew Niccol shrewdly allow Truman to feel
the cocoonlike comfort of his squeaky-clean box, the life he only
now realizes has been the centerpiece in a massive falsifying of
experience. Truman's anger, revved into action as he realizes his
theme-park world is a cage he must escape, must blast through the
passive urge to let TV keep doling out cues.
</P>
<P>
   Doing less than usual physically, Carrey accomplishes more than
he ever has. ``The Truman Show'' is not without glitches and even
shortfall. In addition to starting slowly, it ends too abruptly,
without a feeling of closure, of arriving at a sense of emotional
destination. But Carrey's muted yet feelingful clowning is
brilliant and touching, and Weir's direction plugs us seductively
and then disquietingly into the virtual unreality of Truman's
Playskool jungle, where the only thing weirder than the blurring of
the line between life and TV is the audience's need to watch it.
``The Truman Show'' shows us more than Truman. Not since the
flip-flopping of high and low culture in ``Quiz Show'' has an
ambitious take on our culture _ in this case TV's bludgeoning of
America into the stupidity that feeds conformity _ been so vividly
folded into a film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
