A6103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-TRUMAN-HN     06-05 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TRUMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MORE SERIOUS JIM CARREY, TRAPPED IN THE THEATER OF TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' may star Jim Carrey, but it isn't a Jim
Carrey movie. It contains no butt-talking, no bizarro rubber-face
behavior (not much, anyway), no scatological fixation or creepy,
overarching mania.
</P>
<P>
   It boasts, instead, plentiful reason to marvel at director Peter
Weir's subversive masterpiece, the most sophisticated, artfully
disquieting commentary on identity and the evils of television
since Sidney Lumet's ``Network.''
</P>
<P>
   That landmark 1976 film, an eerily prescient satire, starred
William Holden and Faye Dunaway as Machiavellian network executives
who exploit the insanity of a news anchor (Peter Finch) in their
quest for higher ratings. Finch's character is an unwitting tool in
the network's plan, a human pawn whose individuality is abused, and
subsumed, by the media that bore him. He's trapped in the theater
of television.
</P>
<P>
   So is Truman Burbank. Truman (Carrey) is the star of a show he
doesn't even know about ``The Truman Show,'' a live, globally
popular broadcast that has tracked every motion and moment of his
life (except sex; it's a family show) since the day he was born.
Every aspect of his world is artificial, every conversation false:
His island hometown is a soundstage, his wife (Laura Linney) and
best friend (Noah Emmerich) are actors, and his kitchen is stocked
with brand-name products placed for commercial sponsors (check out
that Chef's Pal).
</P>
<P>
   The stars in the sky are stagelights in the film's first scene,
one of them crashes at Truman's foot.
</P>
<P>
   The genius of the film, the reason it intoxicates and horrifies,
is the audience's own culpability in the hoax. The onus is on us.
Like another film about television and celebrity, Hal Ashby's
``Being There,'' ``The Truman Show'' is all about watching who
watches whom, and why.
</P>
<P>
   Truman's escapades are intercut with shots of Joe Sixpacks
nesting in front of the tube: zaftig ladies on a couch, night
watchmen, tipsy bar patrons, a guy bobbing in a bathtub. They watch
Truman; we watch Truman; we watch them watching Truman.
</P>
<P>
   They watch because they're lured by the mundane dramas of his
life, and by television's seductive powers to hold them. We watch
because we're seduced as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the film becomes most unnerving when Truman starts watching
us, when he finally realizes he's the object of unseen, cunning
eyes. It's not a sudden epiphany Weir's movie unspools gradually,
establishing the artifice of Truman's world before breaking it down
entirely. He, and we, see clues to the trickery around him: a tear
in the sky, a cloudburst that rains on him alone, a wedding
photograph in which his wife is crossing her fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm being set up for something,'' Truman tells best pal,
Marlon, during a heart-to-heart on the beach. Marlon calms his
friend by gesturing to the horizon. ``Look at that sunset,
Truman,'' he says. ``It's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is. It's too perfect, too radiant with gold and
magenta shafts of light. Everything in ``The Truman Show'' is
exaggerated to the point of spookiness. Smiles are wide, voices are
syrupy and colors throb with the false light of a postcard. When
Truman climbs past painted clouds along the wall of a bright blue
sky, the image has the surrealist artistry of a figure by Magritte.
It awes.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey is an ideal match for Truman, because his raging comic
sensibility has always carried with it a hint of innocence there's
a childlike purity to his talent, a foolish abandon that recalls
Charlie Chaplin's Little Tramp. And although he never meets his
maker, a cool media magnate played by Ed Harris, Truman is very
much a son in the biblical mold. He's Adam, maybe Isaac, possibly
Jesus. He is the created in a dance with his creator.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Weir's earlier films (``Dead Poets Society,''
``Witness,'' ``Green Card'') have illumined the outsider in a
foreign or confusing environment, but this time it's the insider
who has to force his way out of maze; Truman isn't so much a
stranger in his own home as the terrified inhabitant of a strange
home. He's the one authentic presence in a universe built on lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' asks whether a human life can be scripted,
start to finish. It asks whether television drains us of privacy
and numbs us to reality. It asks us, in the end, to look at the
looker to stare Truman in the eye, and see ourselves reflected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
