<HEADLINE>
HAS KAY GRANGER STEPPED ON PRO-CHOICE FORCES' TOES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some pro-choice groups want to make Rep. Kay Granger of Texas
face the music, claiming she ain't dancing with them what brung her
to the big party in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters for her challenger in November, Democrat Tom Hall,
are trying to use the Republican congresswoman's voting record to
paint her as anti-choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A surprising and disappointing fact about Congresswoman Kay
Granger has become evident,'' begins a May mailing by Women for
Choice, Women for Tom Hall. ``Kay Granger is anti-choice. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Granger has become another cog in the Right-Wing Republican
plan to eliminate a woman's right to choose,'' says the letter.
</P>
<P>
   The communique goes on to cite Granger's legislative scorecard
as rated by National Right to Life and the National Abortion Rights
Action League. According to the letter, Granger voted ``100 percent
in favor of the Republican Anti-Choice Agenda'' and ``scored a
paltry 3 percent,'' according to NARAL.
</P>
<P>
   Her detractors, including Hall, the Fort Worth attorney who
faces her in the general election, point to that record as evidence
of her kowtowing to Republican bigwigs inside the Texas delegation
and out, rather than doing right by her moderately conservative
district.
</P>
<P>
   Balderdash, says Granger.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is always going to be one that doesn't satisfy
some people,'' Granger said this week in a phone interview from her
Washington office. ``I am a pro-choice person with exceptions. And
those exceptions occur when the issue is taxpayer-funded abortions
or abortion lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it clear in the campaign, and that has been the way I
have voted.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the former Fort Worth mayor has learned some
fancy footwork that usually takes new members of Congress longer to
master. She sashayed up to House Speaker Newt Gingrich quicker than
you can say Cotton-Eyed Joe, and it paid off in powerful
appointments and opportunities normally not bestowed on lowly
freshmen. The House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee was
a coup for a rookie, as was her appointment to the House Budget
Committee, where she fought hard to limit defense spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Her voting record can't be argued. According to Congressional
Quarterly, Granger voted 95 percent of the time with her GOP
colleagues on party-line issues. That should put to rest the
concerns by GOP leaders prior to her 1996 election that she might
not be loyal to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Granger contends she has a realistic grasp on the moderate
leanings of the 12th Congressional District _ a district that
faithfully supported Pete Geren, a Democrat who on some issues
could out-conservative the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my position is reflective of the people in my
district,'' Granger said. ``This issue is between a woman, her
physician and God. The decision should be made there. But it is one
thing to hold personal feelings about choice, and another to vote
on how taxpayer dollars are spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Granger points to two votes that are exceptions to her overall
pro-choice leanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted to ban the partial-birth abortion procedure unless it
is needed to save the life of the mother,'' Granger said. ``Prior
to that vote, I talked with doctors; even the American Medical
Association endorsed the ban. There are options to that really
gruesome procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   The other exception was voting in favor of requiring parental
notification before prescribing contraceptives for minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hard time with that vote,'' Granger admitted. ``There
is always a situation in which parental notification could be a
problem _ what if the minor is the victim of incest? But look at
the situation we have with schools. We say that you have to have
parental consent to give an aspirin in school. I think it's fair to
require parental notification on contraceptives.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall has some complicated footwork ahead of him if he thinks he
can bump the immensely popular Granger from the floor. His
supporters are obviously hoping to woo pro-choice Republicans away
from her dance card.
</P>
<P>
   ``If folks are disappointed or surprised, I'm sorry, but they
shouldn't have been,'' Granger said. ``I'm exactly where I said I
would be. It would be legitimate to be upset if I had promised one
thing, then voted differently, but that is not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Granger's ready to dance with them what brung her, all right, as
long as they remember there are some steps she won't do.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is a columnist and senior editorial writer
for the Fot Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
