<HEADER>
A6177 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-SYNDROME-2NDTAKE     06-05 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-SYNDROME-2NDTAKE-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
  
 HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif.: focused on mycoplasma.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We just went through the medical literature saying, `What
could it be (to cause) a chronic, kind of smoldering disease, a
multi-organ process that is manifested in different ways in
different patients, that is in part immunosuppressive?''' Garth
Nicolson said. ``All of these things start to point in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Their research connected them with Baseman, who had been
studying mycoplasma for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We first met in 1994,'' Baseman said. ``They submitted a
contract with the Army to do this study. They're not mycoplasma
experts, they're tumor cancer experts. They asked if I would
provide the expertise and strains and DNA for them to do the
study.''
</P>
<P>
   They also connected with the network of other Gulf War veterans
who had become ill. In a study of 170 patients with Gulf War
illness, they found 76 with signs of mycoplasmal infections. They
published their findings in occupational medicine journals and
described it in testimony before Congress and investigative panels.
</P>
<P>
   The fact their work had not been published in more recognized,
peer-reviewed scientific journals has been criticized by some
medical experts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the veterans who sought them out was Dannie Wolf of
Lawton, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just ate up my insides, whatever it was,'' Wolf said. ``The
chronic fatigue was overwhelming. I had an accounting degree in
business. Now I can't even add.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, who served with the Army Reserve's 920th transportation
unit in Saudi Arabia, tested positive for mycoplasma infection, as
did his 12-year-old daughter. He has undergone several cycles of
antibiotic treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps while I'm on the treatment. I've been on it for a
year now, with antibiotics 45 days at a time, then I'm off for a
couple of weeks. I start relapsing and I have to go back on it.''
</P>
<P>
   While their work attracted supporters, it was often obscured by
plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   When a mysterious cluster of illnesses was reported by residents
of Huntsville, Texas, the Nicolsons charged that DOD researchers
had tested biologic agents containing mycoplasmas on Texas
prisoners _ experiments that also sickened guards and local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nicolson was quoted in articles charging that U.S.
operatives had broken into their lab and had tried to kill them on
multiple occasions. They left Houston after Nicolson was stripped
of his chairmanship at M.D. Anderson, and set up their private
laboratory in California.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the government prepared to take a serious look at
their claims, the couple steers the conversation away from
conspiracy theories.
</P>
<P>
   The experiments in Huntsville are ``no longer a burning issue
for me. When I was in Texas, it was a burning issue because they
were trying to use that issue to fire me, so they could stop the
research that we were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will serve no useful purpose at this point for anyone to
point fingers,'' Nancy Nicolson said. ``We've put aside
professional and political differences because it's a kind of war
that nobody wins unless you team up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are satisfied by the cooperation they're getting from
the military, particularly since Army Gen. Hugh Shelton became
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. Shelton, a Green Beret who
was an assistant division commander during the Gulf War, has been
supportive of their work, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicolsons say that 75 percent of Gulf War veterans who test
positive for mycoplasma infection recover on long-term antibiotic
treatment. They also recommend nutrition therapy and other methods
to boost the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Kilpatrick, an infectious disease specialist who is the DOD's
point man for Gulf War illness, remains doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Garth Nicolson) said that with six weeks of treatment he
had a lot of people who became well and got sick again. Then he
said, well, they need six more weeks. Now he's talking about a year
of treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Although dioxicycline, the antibiotic used by the Nicolsons, is
a relatively benign one, such treatments can cause problems over
time, including gastrointestinal illness, painful mouth sores and
vaginitis, Kilpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done any kind of standardized control (studies)
looking at non-symptomatic Gulf War veterans, non-deployed
veterans, civilians who were never in the military,'' Kilpatrick
said. ``He is saying, well, DOD isn't interested in doing that. We
are very interested in doing that. And we contracted with him to
teach his technique to two different DOD labs, and two civilian
labs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicolson, who first submitted grant proposals to the DOD four
years ago, says he hasn't had the funds to conduct that kind of
research. The couple took out a second mortgage on their home and
are $450,000 in debt. They have more than 600 frozen samples from
Gulf vets they say they haven't been able to test because they
can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   With some 20,000 U.S. troops assigned to the Persian Gulf today,
Nicolson said the question of Gulf War illness is more important
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've been trying to do recently is prepare ourselves for
a lot of new patients we're going to see if these things get
released again,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
