<SLUG> BC-EMPLOYMENT-QUESTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COMPANY SETTLES LAWSUIT OVER INTERVIEW PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A security company that asked its applicants a
series of questions about their political beliefs settled a
class-action lawsuit for up to $2.1 million, a case that could
change the way corporations around the country screen job
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, filed Thursday in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco, will pay up to 8,000 job applicants as much as $1,250 as
part of an agreement reached between the American Civil Liberties
Union and Burns International Security Services, a subsidiary of
Borg-Warner Protective Services Corporation, the nation's largest
security company.
</P>
<P>
   Questions to which applicants were to reply ``yes'' or ``no''
included: ``The drinking age should be lowered,'' ``The government
has no right to interfere with a person who chooses drugs if it
doesn't hurt anyone'' and ``Illegal use of marijuana is worse than
drinking liquor.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on their answers, applicants were ranked as high-, medium-
or low-risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pre-employment honesty tests are very common but this one went
over the line,'' said lead attorney Brad Seligman, a Berkeley civil
rights attorney associated with the ACLU. ``The (grading) manual
made it clear that one of the purposes of the test was to identify
people with anti-establishment or free-enterprise ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Borg-Warner said the company denied all
liability in the lawsuit and follows all state and federal
employment laws.
</P>
<P>
   Lead plaintiff Mel Thompson, 38, said he took the test at the
company's San Francisco office in 1993 and was offended by the
questions and refused to answer many of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were questioning me on my political beliefs,'' said
Thompson, who works for another security company in San Francisco.
``When I realized that, I felt terribly invaded and afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he voiced objections to the supervisor who gave
him the test when he realized he would be disqualified because of
his answers.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the settlement, Thompson and other applicants who
were disqualified based on their test answers will receive up to
$1,250 while those applicants who were hired can receive up to
$500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6207 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLOMON-ASSESS-2TAKES     06-05 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLOMON-ASSESS-2TAKES-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLOMON ASSESSES HIS RECORD AS CHAIRMAN OF HOUSE RULES PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon took over three years
ago as the first Republican chairman of the House Rules Committee
since 1954, he said his goal was to be a ``fair'' chairman of the
powerful behind-the-scenes panel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he contemplates his record in the job _ and his
retirement at year-end _ Solomon says he believes he has attained
his ``private and public goal to be more fair to (the Democrats)
then they were to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That self-assessment was sharply disputed by Democrats on the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, R-N.Y., an ex-Marine with a hurried but genial manner,
said he set his fairness target because ``I had suffered in the
minority for 16 years and was persecuted'' by the majority
Democrats. They were ``high handed and arrogant'' when they
controlled the House Rules panel, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   The Rules Committee is the management apparatus that the
majority party uses to run the business of the unruly 435-member
House. The 13-member committee can quickly doom a bill by
determining how it will be treated when it reaches the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   One fairness goal that Solomon set was to increase the number of
bills that the Rules Committee sent to the floor with an ``open
rule'' _ one that would allow members of either party to amend or
alter the legislation. Otherwise, bills head to the floor under
``closed'' or ``structured'' rules that limit or ban floor
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged that 70 percent of the legislation the panel sent to
the House floor would go there under an open rule.
</P>
<P>
   His record to date: 58 percent of House bills in his first two
years had open rules and 53 percent of bill so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging this shortcoming, Solomon insists that he is
being more fair than the Democrats were.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon also says he has made other changes in the name of
fairness, such as:
</P>
<P>
   __ Allowing members of the minority party to have the last
chance before a vote to offer their own version of a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means they always have the last bite of the apple,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   __ Eliminating the ``King of the Hill'' rule that allowed the
last standing version of a bill to prevail, rather than the one
with the most votes, which allowed the majority to put their
version in last and win.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ending proxy voting in House committees, thereby forcing
members to attend. He also worked to allow TV cameras to cover all
committee testimony and cut the number of committee staffers in the
House by almost one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon's stint as chairman gets a less-glowing report card from
his predecessor, Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., committee chairman from
1989 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman has been ``far from fair,'' Moakley said in an
interview. ``The truth of the matter is, the Republicans are
tougher than we were. These people froze us out most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   By Moakley's count, Solomon sent legislation to the floor with
open rules just 43 percent of the time in his first two years and
just 33 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Moakley argues that this isn't much better than his own record
of 30 percent in his last two years as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solomon came in on this big white horse saying we're going to
be fair,'' Moakley said. ``Jerry Solomon is my friend. But if he
wants to be known for fairness, he needs to take someone else's
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon ``did the job he was supposed to do _ he carried out the
will of (House Speaker) Newt Gingrich... What I am saying is, as
chairman of the Rules Committee, you have to do your party's
bidding,'' said Moakley.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans never join the Democrats on a vote
``because they are in lockstep with the leader... Gingrich is a
very dictatorial-type person and he demands loyalty. You don't mess
with Newt,'' Moakley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat knows from experience that the chairman of the
Rules Committee takes orders from the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   When Moakley chaired the panel, he also ``had to act like a
soldier'' to carry out the agenda of his leader, then-Speaker
Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., according to Steven S. Smith, a
University of Minnesota political scientist who has written books
on House floor procedure.
</P>
<P>
   However, Foley was ``more laid back'' and allowed Moakley ``to
take the initiative'' and define the floor agenda much of the time.
Gingrich, on the other hand, attempts to direct the course of every
piece of legislation, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the prime qualifications for membership on the
Rules Committee is fierce loyalty to the party leader, either
Speaker Gingrich or Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House Democratic
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Both Solomon and the man who will succeed him next year if the
Republicans remain in control, Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., are
known as Gingrich disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier, 45, a smooth, dapper Southern Californian with a
penchant for pinball, says the speaker calls the shots in the final
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   That's why all 13 members of the rules panel come from ``safe
seats,'' making them politically secure in their home districts so
they can freely pursue their leadership's agenda in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, a conservative who worships Ronald Reagan, was
appointed to the post by Gingrich, who named all nine Republicans
to the committee. The four Democrats, picked by Gephardt, are
outnumbered more than 2-to-1, assuring that the speaker's desires
will be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   When Solomon announced his retirement plans in April, Gingrich
praised his loyal lieutenant as ``a conservative's conservative and
a legislator's legislator. The wisdom of Solomon will be sorely
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What endows the Rules Committee with its huge clout is the fact
that every House member pushing legislation has to win the panel's
approval before the bill can go to the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, virtually every House committee chairman and
subcommittee chairman attends a Rules Committee meeting in the
course of a session to ask the panel's blessing on particular
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee meets three or four times a week in an intimate
Capitol hearing room under three chandeliers. The beseeching member
sits at a small table, peering up at Solomon who looks down at the
witness from his perch atop a tall semi-circular dais.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, in an interview, gave this an example of his power: ``I
can put a bill in my back pocket and go to the Adirondack mountains
and no one can go ahead with it. That's the kind of power I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Solomon has carried out the speaker's will by using
House rules to assure that the House won't approve campaign finance
legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Louise McIntosh Slaughter, D-N.Y., says Solomon effectively
killed the legislation by sending the bill to the House floor under
a rule that allows 12 different versions of the bill to be debated
and amended. This will require so much debate that there won't be
enough time to finish action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be debating this until Labor Day,'' fumes Slaughter.
``It's a colossal time waster.''
</P>
<P>
   While the strategy Solomon used is considered fair play under
House rules, Slaughter says ``it's stupid,'' and it takes away from
the seriousness of the legislation. Gingrich and Solomon ``are
playing games,'' she said. ``They can do anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have also shown mastery at manipulating House rules
when they are in the majority.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s and 1960s, then-rules chairman Howard Smith, D-Va.,
would block civil rights legislation by simply disappearing or
arranging for other committee members to be absent so that a quorum
wouldn't be present. Absent a quorum, the panel would adjourn.
</P>
<P>
   The committee applies 51 standing House rules that are found in
a 4-inch-thick black book with gold letters, which includes a
manual by Thomas Jefferson with his anecdotes and thoughts on how
the House should be run.
</P>
<P>
   The rules book gets fatter every two years when members of every
new Congress update it, usually with footnotes. One rule,
stipulating that all amendments to a bill must be germane, is just
25 words long, but 26 pages of footnotes have been added to explain
how the rule is applied.
</P>
<P>
   When he leaves Congress at the end of the year, Solomon, 67,
will have finished just four years in his six year-term as rules
chairman, after serving 16 years in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   That's why his late April retirement announcement left many of
his friends and colleagues baffled. Dreier, 45, says he was one who
wasn't surprised. He said that when he was pondering leaving the
House to run for the Senate two years ago, Solomon discouraged him,
saying the chairmanship of rules would open up soon.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said he realized that after taking just five vacation
days in 20 years, he owed it to his wife, Freda, to spend more time
with her, his children and grandchildren. He also said he wanted to
make more money. He's paid $136,700.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two guilty feelings,'' Solomon said. ``One is guilt
about not having enough time with family, another is guilt about
giving up this kind of power.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solomon said bouts of prostate and bladder cancer a couple
years ago, which he says he is now clear of, gave him ``a wake up
call that you might not be around forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said he ``would like to be chairman of the Rules
Committee forever'' because it enables him to influence every major
piece of legislation moving through Congress. He said he especially
enjoys melding together bills from different panels into one
version for the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very philosophical person,'' Solomon said. ``My heart
and soul is in this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon insists his exit was not prompted by the fact that he
has only two years remaining in his chairmanship under a 1994
Republican caucus rule limiting committee chairmen to six years.
</P>
<P>
   While some Republican chairmen have questioned the wisdom of
term limits, Solomon stands by them, saying they prevent House
members from developing ``little fiefdoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said he is confident that he could have become chairman
of another panel if he had finished his term as chairman of the
rules panel. For example, he might have taken over the helm of the
Veterans' Affairs Committee, Solomon says.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he adds: ``I might have become the majority leader, I might
have been the speaker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
