<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6238 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSONS-FASHION-860&AMP;     06-05 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSONS-FASHION-860&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BETSEY JOHNSON AND DAUGHTER, A ROLE REVERSAL ON THE RUNWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (For release Sunday, June 7.)  
 (js)  
 By PHOEBE HOBAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's Betsey, her hair in gravity-defying Raggedy
Ann orange pigtails, dressed for success in a bra-revealing
bustier, tightly laced over a teeny flowered minidress worn over
black leggings and, for comic relief, striped socks and sparkly
blue platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Lulu in a simple black cardigan, her blond hair
hanging down her back, her long, slim legs encased in black
boot-cut pants. The only thing they seem to have in common is
matching tattoos _ a lightning bolt over the left breast.
</P>
<P>
   These careful studies in fashion-victim contrast could be the
stars of a sitcom along the lines of ``Absolutely Fabulous,'' but
the wacky mother-daughter team are the real-life stars of the
Betsey Johnson company, which recently doubled its showroom space
at 498 Seventh Ave. (37th Street), opened a store on Wooster Street
in SoHo and opened its first overseas outlet, in London.
</P>
<P>
   If Betsey Johnson, 55, isn't exactly growing up _ she ended her
latest Bryant Park fashion show with a trademark cartwheel _ her
daughter, Lulu, 23, who is in charge of the designer's Ultra line,
has definitely brought a new level of sophistication to her
mother's fashion carnival.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do when you're a baby-boomer fashion designer
creating clothes for people half your age? Get a muse _ or turn to
the one you've borne and raised. Donna Karan has her daughter Gaby,
Diane Von Furstenberg has her daughter-in-law Alexandra. And Betsey
Johnson has the daughter she calls ``my Donatella,'' in reference
to Gianni Versace's designer sister. ``I really feel that Donatella
was Versace's everything in a way, and I have the same sort of
thing with Lulu,'' Betsey Johnson said. ``I can call her up at 3 in
the morning, and bore her with design stuff over dinner. It's
abusive sometimes, but there's nobody else you can do that with.
It's just so perfect that in this chunk of older years between your
40s and 50s, you do have your kids in this teen-age, young-20s,
perfect-customer period.''
</P>
<P>
   Lulu Johnson added, ``If anything, Betsey's vision is even
younger than mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Johnson picks her daughter up every morning for work.
They share an office space with desks that face each other. They
giggle, constantly interrupt each other, complete each other's
sentences and generally act like joined-at-the-hip best friends _
without ever losing sight of the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The Betsey Johnson company, which was founded in 1978 by Ms.
Johnson and a partner, Chantal Bacon, now has 23 outlets and had
revenues of $38 million last year, Ms. Bacon said. In 1995, the
company introduced the pricier Ultra line, which is aimed at the
designer-label buyer and Ms. Johnson's celebrity clients, including
Jenn
</P>
<P>
   Lulu earned her fashion stripes working as a runway model in her
mother's shows, and as a salesgirl in the company's stores during
summer vacations. After high school, she went to work full time for
the company. Her biggest contribution may be that she represents
the company's target demographic. She keeps her mother abreast of
the club scene, the latest videos, the hottest new models.
</P>
<P>
   But Lulu's fashion sense is at the other end of the spectrum
from her mother's punk, sex-kitten style. The clothes Lulu designs
for the Ultra line include slinky, hand-beaded slip dresses, tiny
cardigans, fake fur-trimmed embroidered satin coats and cashmere
separates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lulu's real design strength and what she made all of us see
was severely great business was her formula of the slip dress and
the cardigan and the boot-cut pants,'' Betsey Johnson said. ``It's
a known fact in the industry that those three items are all you
need in life right now. ''
</P>
<P>
   The Ultra line, whose prices range from $300 to $2,500 _ more
expensive than the original Betsey Johnson line _ is the most
obvious effort to give the company legs. It tends to appeal to a
more sophisticated customer than the typical buyer of Betsey
Johnson's signature clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultra was established to upgrade my designer image,'' Betsey
Johnson said. ``That's very important for the company now as we
grow. I hate to say it, but the truth is that the upscale line is
where I get respect as a designer. The higher the price range, the
higher the respect level from the industry, even though it's much
easier to make a great $500 dress than a great $100 dress. Lulu is
very Prada-Gucci.''
</P>
<P>
   The line has proved popular at upscale department stores. ``The
Ultra line has done extremely well for us,'' said Ed Burstell, the
general merchandise manager at Henri Bendel. ``It is feminine,
slightly vintage, definitely luxe. There's a cashmere cardigan and
camisole which sold extremely well. I would call it conservative
for Betsey Johnson, but it is for someone who really likes the
finer things in life.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days before Fashion Week, everybody t the Betsey Johnson
showroom was engaged in the same activity _ frantically nailing
rhinestones to skimpy garments for the designer's show. Manning
their stud guns, dozens of assistants looked like Santa's elves, if
Santa were based in Las Vegas. Paper-doll thin Irene Wright, the
company's fitting model, sidled in in a gold lame dress.
</P>
<P>
   Betsey and Lulu set to work adjusting the dress, which fastened
up the front with hooks and eyes that reveal a gold-lace bra.
Betsey pinned the garment until it was skin-tight, then decided it
should be shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, make it longer,'' Lulu suggested, in a role reversal of
the usual mother-daughter hem discussion. They went back and forth
on the length until ultimately Lulu prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in my old age, the place for me in the company is a
more frivolous, carefree, inspired place,'' Betsey Johnson said,
her mouth bristling with pins. ``A good use for me is to let me go
away with my sewing machine and come back with some really new
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   She let Lulu have the last word. ``And when you come back with
these really out-there things, we'll work on minimalizing it, and
cleaning it up, and making it strong,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
