<HEADLINE>
SURROUNDED BY DEATH, DOCTOR REVELS IN HIS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The thousands of pale, lifeless faces he has
gazed upon over four decades don't haunt him. Most of the names are
a blur. It's the images of the organs _ abnormal or lacerated,
poisoned or punctured _ that remain with Dr. Michael Baden.
</P>
<P>
   Baden's career by the numbers is vast: 20,000 autopsies
conducted. One hundred thousand case files reviewed. Hundreds, if
not thousands, of walks to the court witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   The corpses Baden has examined through the years _ the heroin
overdoses and motor vehicle fatalities and victims of drug deals
gone bad among them _ never made the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But Baden is best known for being a key figure in examining some
of the most spectacular deaths of this and other generations, from
the assassinations of John F. Kennedy and civil rights leaders Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. and Medgar Evers, to the deaths of comedian
John Belushi and Czar Nicholas of Russia, to the autopsies of
victims of Trans World Airlines Flight 800.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight on this coroner-cum-celebrity pathologist reached
its zenith during the O.J. Simpson trial, when he testified on
behalf of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   While Baden isn't shy about talking about his accomplishments,
he explains away some of the high-profile cases as a result of a
shortage of board-certified forensic pathologists in the country _
less than 300 by his count, with none found in 12 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting called in a case like Medgar Evers and knowing I'm
part of history makes my job very worthwhile,'' Baden said. ``I
like doing something that I think if I weren't there to do it, it's
unlikely it would have been done as well by somebody else. But
that's because there are so few people who have my kind of training
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigeonholing Baden is elusive. He is not a cop, although he
works for the New York State Police. He is not just a forensic
pathologist, even though he is probably the nation's foremost
medical examiner. ``Expert-for-hire'' works, but only to a point.
</P>
<P>
   Baden, 63, said the word that best encapsulates him in both his
job and his life is more descriptive than defining: interloper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a cop,'' said the co-director of the State Police
Medicolegal Investigation Unit (formerly the Forensic Sciences
Unit). ``We don't have a commonality in background and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt like an outsider,'' he said. ``I always felt
like an outsider because I was Jewish ... because I had very few
friends ... because I went to reform school.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Baden is often called by the defense, some police
officers and prosecutors have tagged another label on him: Whore.
If you have Baden's fee of $2,500 a day plus expenses, you have
yourself a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``State Police have gotten calls from prosecutors in many other
states saying, `How can you let Baden testify against us?''' Baden
acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   Baden, who testifies primarily for the prosecution in New York
state, said people don't know of the many cases in which he is
retained _ but not called to testify _ by the defense because his
conclusions don't help a client. But that doesn't stop the enmity
of police who view him as undermining their brethren elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's not there, it is the appearance of a conflict,''
said State Police Lt. Kevin Costello, who works with, and has a
general affection for, the pathologist. ``That's what people are
concerned about here.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Bronx in 1934, Baden was what was then commonly
called a hellion _ one wild child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a juvenile delinquent,'' he said. ``Apparently I was a
sufficient a problem that around age 6 I was sent to reform
school.'' He is sketchy on the details.
</P>
<P>
   There is a wildness to Baden that lingers today, from his
longish, hair to his shirttail that struggles to free itself to a
fondness for sloppy-but-casual attire. A hulking figure, he first
appears to be a younger man worn down too quickly, until you learn
his age. Then his dominant feature emerges _ a boundless energy
that has co-workers scrambling to ensure Baden is not scheduling
himself to be three places at once.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Baden was released from reform school at age 9, the
family had moved to the Fort Green housing projects in Brooklyn,
where his dad worked at the Brooklyn Navy Yard. Baden said he and
his brother were the only Jews in the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by a mother who, reform school or not, envisioned her
son a doctor, Baden went on to City College, and then New York
University School of Medicine, before serving as an intern, then
resident at Bellevue Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked very much the patient contact, explaining things to a
patient,'' Baden recalled. ``My initial goal was to be the world's
best internist and diagnostician.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in Bellevue was the New York City Medical Examiner's
Office. Baden was drawn there not just because of its proximity,
but also out of a desire to learn the human body from the inside
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a detective aspect to it and the ability to get an
answer right away,'' Baden said. ``There is an aspect of instant
gratification. You go right to the organs.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1961-86, Baden worked in the New York City Medical
Examiner's Office, serving as chief medical examiner from 1978 to
1979 before a rift resulted in his demotion by Mayor Ed Koch.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a team player,'' Baden said sarcastically of himself. In
1986, when the State Police opened its own forensic unit, Baden
took the job _ with the provision he could retain his outside
consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Baden took a lot of heat from the State Police and elsewhere for
his testimony for the defense in the Simpson case. Baden's theory
is there was more than one assailant and the attack took more than
10 minutes, damaging prosecution claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been asked by the prosecutor if there was evidence
that excludes O.J., I would have said no,'' Baden said. ``They
never asked the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Baden said the O.J. juries reached the correct, if
different, verdicts. ``It is the job of the prosecution to prove
someone is guilty. Clearly, the prosecution did not prove he was
guilty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man who embraces death is against the death penalty. Baden
said his opposition to capital punishment is not rooted in
philosophical or theological reasoning, but rather the fact that
authorities sometimes arrest the wrong person.
</P>
<P>
   Baden, who has courted the news media throughout his career, is
colorful and upfront with his responses (too upfront for some
colleagues).
</P>
<P>
   He pops up in many high-profile cases, and makes a lucrative
side living in addition to his ``part-time'' State Police job,
which pays about $40,000 per year and takes him from his New York
City home to Albany at least twice a week. This omnipresence has
resulted in resentment in some quarters, with Baden being called a
shameless self-promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that anytime a person who is well known as an expert
becomes a celebrity, there is going to be criticism,'' said Dr.
John Pless, president of the National Association of Medical
Examiners. ``That happens with all of us who function as medical
examiners, because we get our names in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Pless, who is also a professor at the Indiana University School
of Medicine, said that despite concerns of some, he doesn't buy the
notion that Baden is a hired gun willing to testify to anything to
suit a client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard any substantial arguments about his opinion
being subject to major question,'' he said. ``My observations are
he gives an opinion, the same opinion, no matter what side.''
</P>
<P>
   Baden confronted death more starkly than he ever has before two
years ago when his 32-year-old son, Jud, was killed in a motorcycle
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Baden said only the deaths of children, ``true innocents,''
affect him deeply.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, death has treated Baden well. He is famous
and paid handsomely, an outsider who has been on the inside of
high-profile cases coast to coast. To him, death and demise are not
synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at death as being bad,'' he said. ``Death is part
of life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
