UNDATED: writers and directors. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Similarly, Walker, who oversees ``Seed,'' was making a
comfortable living producing videos for Tina Turner, Babyface and
Vanessa L. Williams before taking a shot at filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed between the films and Marshall's quickie interviews are
brief insights from more-established filmmakers like Amy Heckerling
``(Clueless)'' and Jocelyn Moorhouse ``(How to Make an American
Quilt)'' who says, ``Being tough does not mean mouthing off to your
crew ... it means putting up with things when other people laugh at
you when they don't understand what you're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasi Lemmons, who wrote and directed the fine ``Eve's Bayou,''
tells aspiring filmmakers to take stock in the positives of the
work, to not look at difficulties of getting a film made but the
miracles of getting the film made.
</P>
<P>
   She knows. Just last year, Lemmons' film was considered one of
the up-and-comers as part of ``Lifetime's Women's Film Festival.''
``Look at her now,'' beams Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere this week:
</P>
<P>
   CBS has a film festival of its own. Trying to lure viewers to
reruns by repackaging them, CBS on Monday will show four
consecutive episodes of ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' the funny
comedy that deserves a much wider audience. ``Ray Day'' (this is
CBS' promotional title, not mine) begins at 7 p.m. CDT and includes
some pretty hilarious episodes, including the Christmas show where
Ray (Ray Romano) is in full lust after his wife, Debra, played by
Patricia Heaton. (This episode peeved some TV advocacy groups who
felt married characters shouldn't talk about having sex.)...
</P>
<P>
   Expect a slew of programming on Robert Kennedy, who was
assassinated 30 years ago. So far, the best comes from the
Discovery Channel. ``Robert F. Kennedy: A Memoir'' (7 p.m. CDT
Sunday) is part historical biography, part memoir, all engaging.
Based on journalist Jack Newfield's book of the same name, the
program traces Kennedy's journey in fine detail and, perhaps, with
the least amount of hero worship...
</P>
<P>
   HBO returns ``Arli$$'' for a third season with Richard Wuhl as
the scruple-less sports agent. The season's first new batch of
half-hour episodes debuts at 8:30 p.m. CDT Sunday, followed by 12
more episodes on subsequent Sundays. Sunday night's episode has a
little more substance and wit than the previous ``Arli$$'' season,
which routinely floundered in its attempts to do a weekly ``Jerry
McGuire'' with teeth. Let's hope this is the start of something
good...
</P>
<P>
   Preceding ``Arli$$'' at 8 p.m. CDT Sunday is HBO's ``Sex and the
City,'' billed as a candid, comic view of sex and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Jessica Parker is Carrie Bradshaw, the thirtysomething sex
columnist navigating and writing about relationships in New York.
Darren Star, who created ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and ``Melrose
Place,'' has made a half-hour comedic romp based on what Bradshaw
has seen and done.
</P>
<P>
   The initial thought after watching the first three episodes is:
Who cares about yet another batch of whiny New Yorkers? I've had
enough. Besides, I think Star has merely brought a ``Melrose
Place'' with nudity to the place where he could get away with it _
cable...
</P>
<P>
   For anyone wondering what happened to Sean Young, she's on the
Family Channel. Young turns up at 7 p.m. CDT Sunday in ``The Cowboy
and the Movie Star,'' a weak, dreary love story. Young is the
pampered movie star ready for a change, Perry King the cowboy
looking for love. You're the viewer yawning over the film's
predictability.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
