<HEADER>
A6295 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV08     06-05 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV08-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 Advance for editions of Monday June 8  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DON QUIXOTE AND MONICA LEWINSKY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't stand on the sidelines criticizing as a cold, timid soul
who has never understood the thrill of victory or the agony of
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ William Ginsburg in a farewell to Lewinsky oration last week
to the members of the Los Angeles County Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRISTO WANTS TO DRAPE CENTRAL PARK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bulgarian-born artist  &UR; Christo &LR;  and his wife,
 &UR; Jeanne-Claude &LR; , showed ``fabric swatches and plans'' for a series
of structures they hope to build in Central Park this autumn, says
the New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   If the project is approved by the New York Parks Department, the
artists will drape fabric around a series of 15-foot steel
``gates.'' A proposal says that pedestrians in the park will walk
under ``a golden ceiling creating warm shadows,'' and people in the
buildings surrounding the park will see ``a golden river appearing
and disappearing through the foliage.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Christo's projects were a fabric fence that rolled through
Marin and Sonoma counties, and hundreds of yellow umbrellas he
placed on a Southern California hillside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sebastian Junger &LR; , author of the best-selling ``The Perfect
Storm,'' revealed last week that he was born in 1962 in Belmont,
Mass., and the Boston Strangler was his baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Academic note: &UR; Wavy Gravy &LR; 's Camp Winnarainbow for Adults _
which starts in Laytonville, Calif., on Saturday and runs through
the next Sunday _ has added whip-cracking to the curriculum, which
already includes unicycling, trapeze, improvisation and sleeping on
mats in tepees.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Randy Alfred  &LR; suggests naming the replacement part on the Bay
Bridge, which links San Francisco and Oakland, the ``Mayor Brown
Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Some years ago, cartoonist  &UR; Dan O'Neill &LR;  incurred the wrath of
Disney with a drawing of  &UR; Mickey Mouse &LR;  in an un-family-rated
position. The cartoonist lost a legal battle that was fought all
the way to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, posters heralding  &UR; Janet Jackson &LR; 's
performances in Sweden featured a photograph showing her personal
homage to Mickey: an X-rated tattoo on her inner thigh, based on
O'Neill's drawing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE U.K. EPICUREAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Linda McCartney &LR;  was working on vegetarian fish cakes when
she died, and a spokesman has announced that her vegetarian food
line will soon be expanded to include this delicacy. Sales of
vegetarian food in England are said to have soared in response to
her death.
</P>
<P>
   _ After attending a flower show in London last week,  &UR; Prince &LR; 
 &UR; Charles &LR;  told Harpers and Queen magazine that he thinks purple
carrots have ``much more of an interesting taste than ordinary
carrots, ditto purple Brussels sprouts. I also like the striped
beetroot, which don't taste much different from ordinary beetroot,
but it's rather wonderful to see the stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The BBC has received a reprimand from the British Broadcasting
Standards Commission for a program in the series ``TV Dinners''
that showed the mother of a newborn preparing and eating the
placenta (sauteed with shallots and garlic, flambeed, pureed and
spread on focaccia). Labour MP  &UR; Kevin McNamara  &LR; said the program
reached ``a new low in sheer grossness,'' and the BSC said it
``breached convention in a way which would have been disagreeable
to many.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The story of the Castro district is one of the great
immigrant stories of our country. However, these immigrants weren't
coming from Italy, Ireland or Germany, but from within their own
country. And like other immigrant neighborhoods, the residents
staked a claim to their turf. They made it a place where they could
own businesses, buy property, elect their own officials, and where
they could be themselves 24 hours a day. ... (Nowadays) the Castro,
or at least parts of it, has become a sort of gay Disneyland. And
as gay men and women realize they can live in lots of different
places without fear, the need for a `gay neighborhood' may in fact
be obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peabody award-winning Peter Stein of KQED, whose ``The
Castro'' will be shown nationwide on PBS on Friday. Stein was
quoted in Total TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
