<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDELINED JACK RUSSELLS, ARTFUL MINGLING, BIKES AND BINOCULARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 7.)   (js)  
 By KIMBERLY STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedigreed Paws
</P>
<P>
   Every dog may have its day, but if you're a short-legged Jack
Russell terrier you'll have to wait. The American Kennel Club, the
arbiter of who's in in canine society, ruled in January that only
Jack Russells with legs 12 to 14 inches long are standard for the
breed. This leaves many shorter-legged Jack Russells out in the
cold. Owners of the trendy breed include Prince Charles, Dr.
Frasier Crane and the mother of David Cone, the Yankee pitcher
sidelined with a nipped hand.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of long-legged Jack Russells are gloating, while fans of
the short-legged cousins, known as Puds, are feeling snubbed. ``If
they want to start their own club, they can,'' said Pat Wilcox, the
vice president of the Jack Russell Terrier Association, in Old
Lyme, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of owners were unhappy about the long-sought
acceptance, fearing it will lead to over-breeding. So, some owners
of short-legged Jack Russells are happy to be blackballed. They
include Christopher Walling , a jewelry designer who takes his
short-legged Jack Russell, Jack, everywhere. ``Because I live in
the city, I have a small dog,'' he said. ``Anyone that knows Jack
Russells knows they are little dogs that don't think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Up on the Roof
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even the impending thunderstorms a couple of Fridays
ago couldn't keep the droves away from the Roof Garden at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, a spot where youthful culture seekers
go to meet and mingle. Laura Marino, a 37-year-old broadcast
producer for Bravo, dropped by and was surprised at how easy it was
to meet people. ``I haven't done the singles scene in a while and
this was unintimidating,'' she said. The museum's rooftop has
turned into a happy hour of sorts on Fridays and Saturdays, with
drinks served to as many as 1,600 until 8:45, when the museum
closes.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the line for the bar snakes around the sculptures.
``The people there have an interest in art or museums,'' Ms. Marino
said. ``It takes it up a notch from the bar scene.'' When the first
few raindrops hit, guards ushered everyone off the premises _ but
not before many had hurriedly exchanged business cards. Down below,
as guests were turned away at the elevator because of the rain, a
young woman vowed to return. ``We have the entire summer ahead of
us to check out the new installation,'' she said. ``And the men.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedaling Back
</P>
<P>
   The reintroduction of Schwinn's 1968 Orange Krate is good news
for nostalgic grown-ups like Andrew Mer. The 35-year-old Manhattan
lawyer remembers receiving a Grey Ghost (part of the Krate family)
for his 8th birthday. ``The one day I lent it to my younger
brother, the bike was stolen and stripped,'' he said ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Orange Krate, retooled from the original, which flew
out of stores as sales peaked in the early 1970s, will roll out in
July. The redesign celebrates Schwinn's improved fortunes: the
company entered Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1992, but is back on its
feet. (One trade group lists it as No. 1 for the $200-to-$400
bicycle market.)
</P>
<P>
   Greg Bagney, Schwinn's vice president for marketing, said,
``Younger kids will want the bike because of their love for
anything retro, and the older group will be interested because they
owned one the first time around and they're going to want another
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The bikes will sell for $350 to $500 at bicycle stores
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts to Match
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ People are literally ordering the clothes off Paige
Novick's back. ``I had a friend stitch up a skirt to go with one of
my bags for the Seventh on Sixth party, and that night I had people
ordering it off my body,'' said Ms. Novick, 31, explaining how her
company, Frou by Paige Novick, expanded to women's wear last
November. It started as a hair-accessory business four years ago
and grew to include handbags two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really design around my handbags,'' Ms. Novick said. ``I
look at the skirts as accessories and the handbags as the focal
point.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress Julianne Moore wears the black satin skirt with the
pink embroidered flowers, as have the hostesses and waitresses at
Moomba since the designer was spotted wearing one in the
restaurant. The skirts cost between $235 and $250, and the bags are
about $200. Among the stores that carry them are Barneys and
Calypso in New York and Fred Siegal in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A Wide View
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're a sports fan stuck in the nose-bleed seats or a
summer concertgoer without the energy to push to the front,
Bushnell's Xtra-Wide binoculars may be the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you the amount of people that ask about them at
games,'' said Luther Jones, an engineer, who regularly takes his
three children to Yankee Stadium. ``I can't afford the primo seats,
and the binoculars make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   At $100 they are cheaper than most models designed for bird
watching, and they offer a wider view _ up to three times wider
than regular binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   George Egon, Bushnell's vice president for marketing, says it's
like having a wide-screen television set at the game.
</P>
<P>
   For stores that sell the binoculars: (800) 423-3537.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
