<HEADER>
A6350 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAKDANCING-$ADV07-A     06-05 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAKDANCING-$ADV07-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROOVING AGAIN TO BREAKDANCING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: PHoto is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
(ja) 
 By LOLA OGUNNAIKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's midnight on a Saturday and a battle is on in the
Bronx. Tammy Keo, 12, is squared against Marcos Oquendo, 19.
Despite the David-and-Goliath mismatch _ Tammy, known as Lady Love
Bug, stands 4 foot 10, and Oquendo, known as 2 Sweet, is 6 foot 2 _
there's no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   The young challenger stuffs her ponytails under a knitted cap
and reties the fat shoelaces of her Adidas sneakers. Her opponent
tucks his sleeveless jersey into his boxers. Both are ready for the
three-minute round before 300 spectators at the Hunt's Point
Community Center. In this arena, skill isn't determined by one's
left hook or right jab. The rules are as they've always been: May
the fanciest footwork win.
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes were common 15 years ago, when no street corner or
subway platform was safe from bandanna-wearing breakdancers and
their behemoth boom boxes. The pulsating street theater indigenous
to New York and its spoken accompaniment _ rap _ were at the
forefront of the cultural flowering called hip-hop. Hollywood made
movies about breakdancing, dancers performed at the White House and
the sky seemed the limit.
</P>
<P>
   But as rap grew into a major influence on pop culture,
breakdancing was left in the dust. Until now, when breakdancers are
once again performing head spins and other gyrations in music
videos, clubs and arenas, often to the beat of ``old school'' rap
by the likes of Erik B and Rakim and cheered on by audiences in
retro styles like track suits. The return seems an inner-city
counterpart to the 1980s nostalgia on view in recent hit films like
``The Wedding Singer.''
</P>
<P>
   Breakdancers have popped up recently in videos for Mariah
Carey's ``The Roof,'' Madonna's ``Ray of Light'' and Jason Nevin's
remake of Run-DMC's 1983 classic ``It's Like That.'' Under the
slogan ``Khakis Groove,'' the Gap has a commercial featuring
multiracial breakdancing couples. B-boys _ or breakdance boys _
have been spotted in Coca-Cola and Sprite advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are definitely waking back up to it,'' said
Rocafella, 26, a B-girl who tours with ``Jam on the Groove,'' a
musical production sponsored by Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   When Bam, a well-known dancer, and Fred Berry, who played the
portly Rerun on the 1970s sitcom ``What's Happening!,'' recently
offered classes at a dance studio in Manhattan, they had a waiting
list before the class started.
</P>
<P>
   The art form has its roots in African dance and capoeira, an
Afro-Brazilian martial art, but it originated in the black and
Hispanic communities of the Bronx during the mid-'70s. DJ's would
spin soul and funk hits and extend the ``break'' (the percussion
section of the song). A spectator might grab the microphone and
improvise a rhyme, while others danced. Over time, dance partners
evolved into alliances or ``crews,'' and competitions or
``battles'' became the highlight of barbecues and block parties.
</P>
<P>
   Breakdancing, along with tagging (graffiti writing), emceeing
and deejaying _ the pillars of hip-hop culture _ grew into a way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``B-boying, that was my way of being loud, that was my voice,''
said Crazy Legs, 32, president of the Rock Steady Crew, an elite
group of about 60 dancers. He has been dancing for 21 years and
claims to have invented the back spin, the windmill and the 1990.
``We weren't in it for the money, it was all about being a ghetto
celebrity,'' he said. ``We didn't have the means for sports so we
created our own ghetto games.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1987 the ghetto game that had turned into an
international fad had been milked for every backspin it was worth.
``The media really exploited breakdancing and made people sick of
it,'' Rocafella said.
</P>
<P>
   It never disappeared entirely _ ``it just went back
underground,'' she said. Now, around the city at clubs like Vinyl
and Soundlab, B-boys and B-girls with street names like Crazy Boy
and Kid Flex are diving onto hardwood floors and twisting
themselves into complex contortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing is like a drug,'' said 2 Sweet, a student from the
Lower East Side. ``When I'm out there in the middle of the floor I
zone out and feel like I'm the only one in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   One source of the comeback is Britain's rave scene. At the huge
parties, young people started breakdancing to the low-on-lyrics,
heavy-on-the-bass beats of techno, drum-'n'-bass and house music.
``A lot of people dance to house because it sounds like old break
beats,'' explained K-Mel, 18, a dancer from the Bronx. Raves
crossed the Atlantic in the early '90s and landed in American
suburbs, introducing many white youth to breakdancing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike inner-city breakdancers _ who tend to wear the
traditional uniform of ``swooshies'' (Adidas warm-up suits),
shell-top sneakers and Kangol hats, and to affiliate themselves
with crews _ ravers are more likely to be found with body piercings
and wide-leg jeans. Because dancing at raves is fueled by drugs
like Ecstasy instead of the inner-city incentive of gaining street
fame, it lacks the competitive spirit that dominates its urban
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   The retro-'80s vibe that is behind breakdancing's return in the
inner city can be traced back in part to a nostalgia for a more
innocent period of hip-hop. There is a backlash against the
excessive violence and materialism that has been extolled by
gangsta rap for the last decade, culminating in the murders of
Tupak Shakur and Notorious B.I.G. B-boys and B-girls say that their
dance style represents a return to times when people could compete
and live to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the day we had our Kangol hats, Lee jeans and
two-finger rings, it was different,'' said Fever, 27, a B-boy from
Seattle. ``Nobody was following the next man. It was all about
originality in your clothes, style and moves. We've got to get back
to that before it's gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
