<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCENA-OPERA-REVIEW-NY     06-05 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCENA-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAN SCENA OPERA COMPANY: A GALA OF OPERA TRANSFORMED INTO
COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (js)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing in the classical music world offers as much
room for parody as opera. The repertory itself, packed as it is
with implausible plots and peculiar characters, offers ample
material, and there is even more to skewer in the practical side of
the business, where the grandiose egos of divas, directors and
conductors _ to say nothing of the fervent partisanship of their
fans _ can be mistaken for parody by dispassionate outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Turning these quirks into true comedy demands a deep knowledge
and a sincere love of the form as well as a high level of
musicianship and vocal agility. One can only parody great
performers, after all, if one can approximate their strengths while
exaggerating their weaknesses. The Gran Scena Opera Company _ a
troupe of male singers who dress and act as divas, sing in falsetto
and perform under comic stage names (Gabriella
Tonnoziti-Casseruola, for example) _ has made a specialty of this
specialized brand of comedy since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The group performed at Alice Tully Hall on Thursday evening for
an audience that was enthusiastic enough to make an actual diva
jealous.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Scena's preferred format is that of the opera gala, the
regularly televised affairs in which starry singers trot out for
arias and scenes from diverse operas. Joe Simmons, as Sylvia Bills
(``America's most beloved retired diva,'' with mannerisms uncannily
like those of Beverly Sills), provided introductions and commentary
between selections, in a show written by the group's founder and
artistic director, Ira Siff.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about Those Three Tenors,'' Ms. Bills began, stifling a
yawn. ``Or I should say Four Tenors _ we musn't forget Aretha,''
she added, referring to Aretha Franklin's substitution for Luciano
Pavarotti at the Grammy Awards. From there, she and the other
performers took few prisoners. Barbs were aimed with extraordinary
precision at the Met, operatic crossover recordings, the Alagnas,
Franco Zeffirelli's stagings, Cecilia Bartoli (``last year she was
arrested on stage for mugging,'' Ms. Bills said) and Montserrat
Caballe, as well as Wagner and Verdi.
</P>
<P>
   The musical performances often relied on slapstick, which wore
thin by the end of the three-hour show. But when it worked, it was
brilliant. In a version of the ``Ride of the Valkyries,'' the
singers ambled and posed and pointed their spears enigmatically, in
the style of the Met's current production, eventually abandoning
their forced sobriety to upstage one another and exchange Nazi
salutes. Keith Jurosko's impersonation of an aging diva in a duet
from ``La Boheme'' was stunning, and there were some wonderful
moments in Siff's centerpiece as the Russian diva Vera
Galupe-Borszkh, a send-up of the second act of ``Tosca.''
</P>
<P>
   Much sport was made of the vocal weaknesses one hears on the
opera stage, but now and then there was some fine singing as well.
Most notably Kyle Church Cheseborough, as Kavatina Turner, produced
a beautifully rounded soprano timbre in a duet from ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Sisley, as Maestro Lorenzo Costalotta-Denaro, provided
suitably dramatic accompaniments at the piano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
