<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING 1898, A TURNING POINT IN AMERICAN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain, Philippines)  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Centennials usually call for a lot of clanking celebration, a
period souvenir or two and perhaps some minor historical
revisionism. The 1898 observation, now under way in Spain, Cuba,
the Philippines and the United States, is a tough one. So much was
set in motion that it is difficult to contemplate how we got from
there to here.
</P>
<P>
   Four months of fighting dispatched the remnants of a Spanish
empire dating to the landing of Columbus and gave rise to an
American empire and century, with entanglements, entitlements and
expectations yet to be fully sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of books, parades, symposiums and museum shows are
trying to push 1898 from the fringes of public awareness. New York
has eight exhibitions and programs this year, the biggest of which
is probably ``A War in Perspective, 1898-1998: Public Appeals,
Memory, and the Spanish-American Conflict,'' running through Aug.
29 at the New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of historians, whether second-guessers or those in
the academic mainstream, is that 1898 marked the death of one age
and the start of another.
</P>
<P>
   ``During 12 months of rich confusion, wild contradiction and
violent change, the United States of 1898 advanced from being
viewed as a country of sharp-dealing businessmen with a second-rate
military and little international influence to acknowledgment as a
respected member of the imperialists' club,'' David Traxel writes
in ``1898: The Birth of the American Century,'' just published by
Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the United States at the start of that year. Geronimo
had surrendered, but his haunts of New Mexico and Arizona were
still territories and considered foreign land to many on the East
Coast. Americans commuted to work by bicycle. Though the shift from
rural to urban was well under way, the United States still thought
of itself as a nation of farmers and of Anglo-Saxons. Foreign wars
were for Europeans, the detested monarchs of the Old World.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, the United States would have an empire
that reached 6,000 miles across the Pacific and would be accepting
lessons from the British in how to live with a ``white man's
burden,'' in Rudyard Kipling's words. In less than 20 years the
nation would be deeply involved in a horrific global war in the
name of making the world safe for American-style democracy.
</P>
<P>
   A ``deluge of wonders,'' as one observer put it, many from the
brain of Thomas Alva Edison, were about to transform society. A
deluge of immigrants was already at hand. The Irish had come in
waves since the famine of the early 1850s, followed by Italians,
Scandinavians, Germans, Greeks and Russians. The Chinese were first
drawn by California gold, then banned under various exclusion acts.
By 1898, half a million Jews, almost one-third of the Jewish
population of Europe, had moved to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The city strutted its new muscle. In 1898, by incorporating the
outer boroughs, New York City grew from 39 square miles to 320,
becoming the second biggest metropolis in the world, with a
population of 3.4 million. Only London was bigger.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the United States had learned to shop, passing
Britain as the world's leading consumer society. With wealth,
unparalleled population growth, physical space and technology, all
it lacked was a place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That would be taken care of in part by the mysterious explosion
of the battleship Maine in Havana harbor on the evening of Feb. 15,
1898, which killed 266 American servicemen. The ship was in Cuba
ostensibly to protect American interests while rebels tried to
remove the hand of Spain from the island. These rebels had been
depicted at first as modern-day Jeffersons and Washingtons.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish helped rescue nearly a hundred Americans from the
burning ship, but they were portrayed from the start as the
instigators. ``The Warship Maine Split in Two by an Enemy's Secret
Infernal Machine'' was one of the headlines in Hearst's Journal.
Pulitzer, now associated with the highest awards in journalism, was
not to be outdone. ``The whole country thrills with war fever,''
wrote Pulitzer's World, even providing a slogan in headline form:
``Remember the Maine! To Hell With Spain!''
</P>
<P>
   The daily journals, using cartoons and color to broad effect,
had gone from being ``beggar and blackmailer and became one of the
major industries of every little town,'' Traxel notes. New York had
15 dailies, the loudest of which were Joseph Pulitzer's World and
William Randolph Hearst's Journal. Yellow was the color of their
comics, but it became the pejorative term for bad journalism.
</P>
<P>
   It did not matter that there was little proof of Spanish
complicity in the explosion. Hearst, in perhaps his most famous
statement, told one of the illustrators he sent to Cuba, ``You
provide the pictures and I'll provide the war.'' One of the more
exhaustive studies of the explosion, the 1976 investigation by Adm.
Hyman Rickover, concluded that the sinking of the Maine was most
likely an accident, a fire in the ship's hold where gunpowder was
stored.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming serial propagandists for the Spanish-American War misses
a larger point, some scholars now believe. ``This was the age of
National Geographic, of the first film footage, of world fairs, and
so it was a time when the United States started to see the world as
being available for expansion,'' said Amy Kaplan, a professor of
literature and American studies at Mount Holyoke College who has
been writing and lecturing on the centennial. ``Expansion was
portrayed as an extension of American values, not as conquering
other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1875 to 1905, Britain added 5 million square miles to its
empire; France added 3 million. The United States stretched from
one ocean to the other, but it was for the first time without a
frontier. European expansion, long condemned, provided an excuse
for emulation. How the United States could go from condemning
European colonialism to trying to rule the 7,100 islands of the
distant Philippines is one of the driving questions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
