<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Friday, the winds at 35,000 feet over Long Island were
blowing from the west at nearly 225 mph. This extraordinary wind
was a reflection of an unusually large temperature contrast that is
only slowly dissipating across the nation. Earlier in the week,
surface temperatures varied by 60 degrees across a front in the
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, a cold front will sink southward to the Gulf of
Mexico, ending the heat wave in most of the South. Thunderstorms
will accompany both ends of the front from the Carolinas to the Rio
Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Record heat is still expected in Florida, though afternoon
thundershowers will bring temporary relief. Low pressure near the
Carolina coast will strengthen during the next 24 hours, directing
cooler, less humid air into the Southeast on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A pool of cold air at 15,000 feet over the Great Lakes and
Northeast will combine with mild air near the ground to cause a
rapid overturning of the lower atmosphere. The result will be
widespread afternoon clouds from the Appalachians to the northern
Plains. A few showers will develop in the higher terrain of New
England, near the Great Lakes and in the western Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure stretching from North Dakota to Oklahoma will
promote dry, but cool weather for much of the Plains. Winds
ascending the Rockies will keep plenty of clouds along the eastern
slopes of the mountains in New Mexico. A disturbance moving into
the West Coast will trigger afternoon thundershowers from the
northern Sierra and Cascades to the Bitterroots and Wasatch.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TOO WARM FOR THUNDER
</P>
<P>
   A blistering heat wave this past week sent the mercury over 110
degrees on a few days in central Texas. Despite the scorching heat
and sultry air mass, there were very few clouds and no
thunderstorms in the area. The reason for the lack of clouds could
be traced to reports from weather balloons launched over Texas.
Many indicated readings near freezing at 18,000 feet. Such warmth
is usually only found near hurricanes, which produce a great amount
of heat due to condensation. The hot air above Texas prevented
rising air currents from reaching a level where a cloud could
form. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
