u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDERAL-DEBTS-COX &UR;  &UR; CO     06-05 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-DEBTS-COX </SLUG>
     COLLECTIONS LAG AS FEDERAL DEBT BACKLOG
HITS $52 BILLION
 &HT;     By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;     c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite reforms of its debt-collection methods, the
federal government has a backlog of $52 billion in delinquent debts
that spurred bipartisan complaints Friday from members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two years of shilly-shallying,'' Rep. Steve Horn,
R-Calif., chairman of a House government oversight committee, told
a hearing where Treasury Department officials conceded that they
were lagging in implementing the Debt Collection Improvement Act of
1996.
</P>
<P>
   One of the act's key programs has cost $40 million and brought
in only $4 million in repayments.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new measure, Treasury has extended powers and
government-wide responsibility for collecting debts that are more
than 180 days tardy, including student loans, farm and business
loans, and federally backed home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   However, federal agencies have been slow to refer their debts to
Treasury until they have become so old as to be deemed
uncollectible.
</P>
<P>
   The law also authorizes automatic deductions from federal
salaries or federal benefits for anyone who has a delinquent debt.
But little of this has taken effect, since it depends on developing
a new computer program. Treasury spent $5 million on such a
program, which proved defective and has now been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Undersecretary John D. Hawke Jr. acknowledged that
``there is still much work to be done,'' although he said that the
effort is now moving on track. Still, he tried to lower
expectations that his department will ever collect much of the huge
portfolio of delinquent debt. He cited a study by the accounting
firm of Price Waterhouse predicting that the best possible result
would be $1 billion in receipts a year.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's current slow pace brought expressions of
frustration from Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are just not coming in,'' she said. ``The older
the debt gets, the harder it is to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like some common sense,'' she said. She called on the
administration to stop waiting around for computer programs and
said they should begin taking immediate steps, such as sending out
notices under U.S. Treasury letterhead to debtors as soon as they
are 60 days late in making a payment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Corp. sent an analysis to the
congressional oversight panel warning that unless the government
takes more care in granting loans, it will continue to make bad
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cases it cited was a company that defaulted on one
federal loan and then was given a second loan from the same agency,
which it also failed to pay. Later, a second federal agency awarded
the same company $200,000 in contracts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
