<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6489 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-A&AMP;M-WINTRACK06-COX     06-05 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A&AMP;M-WINTRACK06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCAA outdoor championships: Texas A&AMP;M hurdler battles the wind
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Winning his heat in the 110-meter hurdles evoked
an odd reaction from Larry Wade.
</P>
<P>
   Wade, a Texas A&AMP;M senior from Elgin, rolled his eyes and took a
deep sigh after crossing first at the NCAA outdoor track and field
championships.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Part if it was surviving the gusting, swirling winds inside the
University of Buffalo stadium. Part of it was his time of 13.96
seconds _ ``I haven't run that slow since I was a freshman,'' Wade
said _ and the two were related.
</P>
<P>
   The chilly winds played havoc on Thursday (6/4), especially for
the hurdlers. Nobody fell, but nobody felt comfortable, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was blowing in my face, at my back, sideways, everywhere,''
said the University of Texas' Angie Vaughn, the national leader in
the high hurdles whose preliminary time of 13.21 seconds in lane
eight was the fastest of the qualifiers. ``It was tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a lot of hurdles,'' Vaughn said. ``It wasn't like I was
clobbering them. More like clipping them. But I can't be clipping
anything in the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Also qualifying in the hurdles was Brigitte Foster of Southwest
Texas State with a time of 13.78.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to control your technique both over the hurdles
and between them. You couldn't get any drive,'' Foster said. ``But
at least I advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas women had another good day of qualifying, advancing
Vaughn in the high hurdles, LaKeisha Backus and Kim McGruder in the
100, Suziann Reid and Toya Brown in the 400 and their 1,600 relay.
Elizabeth Diaz failed to advance in the 1,500 when her time of 4
minutes, 22.18 seconds missed the cutoff by one spot.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES _ SWT's Foster also advanced in the 100 with a
seventh-place heat time of 11.75. ... The Baylor men's
national-leading 1,600 relay barely advanced to the finals. Bayano
Kamani, running the second leg, suffered a hamstring cramp and
limped the final 150 meters of his split to hand off to Stephan
Bragner. Bragner's 44.7 split and the 44.5 by anchor Brandon Couts
pulled the Bears from last to fourth in their heat and gave them
the seventh of eight qualifying times. ``I could have lost both
legs and I still would have gotten them the stick (baton),'' said
Kamani, a freshman from Houston. ``They would have done the same
for me because we're a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas sophomore Jessica Koch, a Round Rock product who
transferred from UT after her freshman year, led qualifying in the
3,000 meters with a time of 9:28.94. ... Nebraska's Tressa Thompson
broke her own meet record in the shot put with a toss of 61 feet, 2
1/4 inches. Second went to Southern Methodist's Teri Tunks, whose
throw of 60-10 3/4 also broke Thompson's previous mark of 60-8 1/2.
... Arkansas' Robert Howard won the long jump with a leap of 27-5
1/2 on his final attempt. ``No negative thoughts,'' Howard said of
his mind-set before the last jump. ``All I think of is running. I
see fire under my feet, like I'm running on coals.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
