<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6497 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-TONY06-COX     06-05 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-TONY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broadway hits a high note
 &HT;    Has sidebars: BROADWAY-MUSICALS, BROADWAY-NONMUSICALS
 &HT;    By HAP ERSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Construction jackhammers are pounding. Computerized
ticket sales are whirring. Satisfied audiences are jumping to their
feet and cheering. Theater producers, toasting their good fortune,
are popping champagne corks all over town.
</P>
<P>
   These are the sounds of Broadway, which is on a roll after years
of hand-wringing. Tonight, with the annual Tony Awards celebration,
Broadway officially closes the book on its most successful season
in history.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary data from the League of American Theatres and
Producers indicate that more than 11.3 million people saw a
Broadway show this season, breaking the previous attendance high
notched in 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   Box office income reached an estimated record high of $545
million, a 9.2 percent increase over last season. In December, 23
musicals were running on Broadway _ the most at any time in modern
history. And the top ticket price for musicals spiraled to $75, a
$5 increase.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, some ticket prices rose even higher. Livent Inc.,
which produces Ragtime, added a $1 surcharge _ making its tickets
$76 _ to defray the construction costs of its new Ford Center for
the Performing Arts. Then it established a $125 ticket that
includes entry to a VIP lounge at intermission, refreshments and
free coat check. Who says elitism is dead on Broadway?
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the attendance and sales records is the way
the theater district is cleaning up its act. Two renovated and
restored, state-of-the-art theatrical palaces have opened along the
formerly tacky, now tourist-friendly, neon-bright 42nd Street
corridor.
</P>
<P>
   But what's on stage? Some genuine quality.
</P>
<P>
   Those two ``new'' theaters, the New Amsterdam and Ford Center,
opened with a pair of blockbuster productions _ Disney's puppet
spectacle ``The Lion King'' and the musical juggernaut ``Ragtime.''
Each will continue overwhelming theatergoers for years to come,
regardless of who wins Best Musical tonight at the Tonys. Yes, for
the first season in a long time, there will be some nail-biting as
both musicals vie for the bragging rights and marketing punch that
comes with the Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Not that either show is hurting. ``Ragtime'' and ``The Lion
King'' are two of four shows (along with ``Chicago'' and ``Rent'')
doing sold-out business. A further measure of Broadway's health is
that by late May, another seven productions were doing above 90
percent attendance. In one week, ``Ragtime'' brought in an
impressive $888,006 and ``The Lion King'' $805,954. Together, the
two shows have accounted for $44 million in ticket sales, according
to Variety, equal to 77 percent of the season's increase in sales.
Without these two shows, the Broadway ledger books would look very
different.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that both shows, while containing moments of stylized
violence, could be described as ``family-oriented.'' Contrast that
with the third hot-ticket musical, a raunchy revival of ``Cabaret''
that emphasizes the seamy side of life in Weimar Berlin. It also is
housed in a recently re-opened theater, the gone-to-seed Henry
Miller, converted into the time-warp Kit Kat Klub for this show.
Any Broadway season that can produce three hit shows in three
previously inactive theaters cannot be all bad.
</P>
<P>
   For the downside, this was supposed to be the year that composer
Paul Simon and his long-promised ``The Capeman'' inched the sounds
of Broadway closer to pop-rock. Well, it never caught on, in part
because of theater novice Simon's abrasive remarks about
revolutionizing the musical theater. While that was surely a factor
in its reception, there was a convincing consensus among critics
that the show was an inert mess.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in records should note that ``The Capeman'' set
a new mark as the most expensive flop on Broadway, going through
more than $11 million before giving up after two months of
performances. Such is Simon's box office draw that there has been
talk of a concert tour of ``The Capeman,'' but don't hold your
breath.
</P>
<P>
   Good, bad or in between, nearly every new musical this season
originated in America, in contrast to the days when the British
dominated with ``Cats,'' ``Les Miserables'' and ``Phantom of the
Opera.'' But the most praised and popular dramas this season are
London imports _ ``Art'' and ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of America's best playwrights fared less well. David
Mamet's trio of short plays, ``The Old Neighborhood,'' folded the
week it received no Tony nominations. A revival of Neil Simon's
``The Sunshine Boys'' (that began at the Coconut Grove Playhouse)
found an audience, but his new, more personal play, ``Proposals,''
died quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Arthur Miller's 1960 family drama ``A View From the
Bridge'' has earned awards and a following, but his newest work,
``Mr. Peters' Connections,'' failed to connect with most critics.
And time and money ran out on David Henry Hwang's ``Golden Child,''
a delicate meditation on Western ways and their effect on Asian
values. It folded a week ago, even though it is up for the Best
Play Tony.
</P>
<P>
   And not all British plays were well received. ``The Herbal
Bed,'' about a court case involving William Shakespeare's daughter,
was acclaimed in London but met a wall of indifference here and
closed quickly. ``The Judas Kiss,'' David Hare's look at the trials
of Oscar Wilde starring Liam Neeson, also had favorable advance
word, but was totally shut out on Tony nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a bullish year on Broadway. But will this brisk
business spill over into upcoming seasons, or is it a mere fluke?
</P>
<P>
   It seems aggressive marketing from the League of American
Theatres and Producers is working, with Broadway trumpeted through
syndicated television specials and upbeat Web sites. (To see how
they crow about the season, click on http://www.broadway.org.)
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the league claims that theatergoers under 18
have doubled in the past seven years. Some of that must be due to
the increasing presence of Disney. Some must come from shows like
``Rent,'' ``Bring in 'da Noise'' and ``The Capeman,'' which aim to
attract untraditional Broadway audiences. The emphasis is off the
hypothetical ``tired businessman'' and toward the younger, hipper
audience.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the reasoning goes, theater-going habits may take root,
and Broadway could have new patrons for life. So not only is
Broadway not dying, it is sprucing itself up, preparing to sprint
into the 21st century. HAP'S PICKS
</P>
<P>
   Here are my predicted winners of this season's Tony Awards. Tune
in Sunday night to see instantaneously how far off I was.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Play: The Beauty Queen of Leenane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Musical: Ragtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Book of a Musical: Terrence McNally, Ragtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Original Score: Stephen Flaherty &AMP; Lynn Ahrens, Ragtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Revival, Play: A View _ Best Revival, Musical: Cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Leading Actor, Play: Anthony La Paglia, A View _ Best
Leading Actress, Play: Marie Mullen, The Beauty Queen of Leenane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Leading Actor, Musical: Alan Cumming, Cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Leading Actress, Musical: Natasha Richardson, Cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Featured Actor, Play: Tom Murphy, The Beauty Queen of
Leenane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Featured Actress, Play: Linda Lavin, The Diary of Anne
Frank.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Featured Actor, Musical: Ron Rifkin, Cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Featured Actress, Musical: Audra McDonald, Ragtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Direction, Play: Garry Hynes, The Beauty Queen of
Leenane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Direction, Musical: Julie Taymor, The Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Choreography: Graciela Daniele, Ragtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Orchestrations: Robert Elhai, David Metzger and Bruce
Fowler, The Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Scenic Design: Richard Hudson, The Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Costume Design: Julie Taymor, The Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Lighting Design: Donald Holder, The Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
