</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-MINIREVIEW06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POWERHOUSE MUSICALS COMPETE FOR AWARDS
 &HT;    Sidebar for BROADWAY-TONYS
 &HT;    By HAP ERSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mini-reviews of three of Broadway's biggest musicals, all up for
Tonys Sunday night:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Ragtime'' _ The Livent musical mill (``Kiss of the Spider
Woman,'' the revival of ``Show Boat'') hits its apex with this
emotion-laden adaptation of E.L. Doctorow's turn-of-the-century
novel about the multicultural American melting pot.
</P>
<P>
   With a lush, anthem-rich score by Stephen Flaherty and Lynn
Ahrens (``Once on This Island'') and a tight, yet intricate script
by Terrence McNally (``Master Class''), it interweaves the fates of
three diverse groups. There's the WASPy New Rochelle crowd headed
by a muddled global explorer, Harlem blacks led by a ragtime
piano-player who grows militant from injustice, and Eastern
European Jews exemplified by a silhouette artist who becomes a
silent filmmaker and self-styled baron.
</P>
<P>
   The canvas is vast and the results are epic, as director Frank
Galati deftly balances so many story lines, and Graciela Daniele's
nimble, musical staging shows the clash of cultures in movement. In
the huge cast are such Tony-worthy performers as Brian Stokes
Mitchell, powerfully towering above the fray as firebrand Coalhouse
Walker, and the ethereal Audra McDonald as his washerwoman lover
reaching out to grab the American Dream. Peter Friedman is fiercely
protective of his daughter and later amusingly aristocratic as
upwardly mobile Tateh. And the delicate Marin Mazzie strikes a
personal chord with her soaring soprano, turning Mother's journey
of self-discovery into the spine of the show.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great musical, one that will continue to move
audiences for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime,'' Ford Center for the Performing Arts, 213 W. 42nd
St., New York, $31-$76, (212) 307-4550.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Lion King'' _ Give the Disney gang credit for not giving
us another ``Beauty and the Beast,'' a slapped together stage
version of an animated cartoon minus the charm. Instead, they went
into uncharted terrain, hiring cutting edge director-puppeteer
Julie Taymor, who transformed this story of a lion cub's ascension
to jungle royalty into her own celebration of the imagination and
potential of live theater.
</P>
<P>
   The opening number, ``Circle of Life,'' is a stunning display of
oversized puppet art, as the beasts of the veldt parade through the
aisles to the stage, visibly motored by human power. Youngsters
will see a new take on the video they cherish. Parents will see
something more ingenious and original.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Taymor's staging of the wildebeest stampede, a
fanciful flight of birds throughout the theater and a magical
assembly of puppet creatures that forms into a stage-high image of
former lion king Mufasa's face. The Elton John-Tim Rice film score
has been bolstered with songs featuring African rhythms and
orchestrations. The design elements are wondrous. Still, the
production feels like it hops from effect to effect, only
occasionally touching the heart as the film did. Taymor's spectacle
inspires awe, but she doesn't have a story that can fully support
her stage wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion King,'' New Amsterdam Theatre, 214 W. 42nd St., New
York. $25-$75. (800) 755-4000.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cabaret'' _ In 1966, when Harold Prince first staged this
dark, cautionary musical about the rise of Nazism, he admits he
compromised on some of the darker elements of Christopher
Isherwood's Berlin stories. Now comes British director Sam Mendes
to emphasize the seamy side of this John Kander-Fred Ebb show about
a mad moment in history mirrored inside a tacky, tawdry nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Masteroff retooled his script to make the homosexuality more
explicit, and Mendes tossed out some of the conventional musical
comedy numbers. But the revelation is how the Kit Kat Klub's Emcee
insinuates himself throughout the production as a wry observer, and
how lasciviously Alan Cumming redefines the creepy character.
</P>
<P>
   The evening is his, though Natasha Richardson also brings new
dramatic qualities to naive songbird Sally Bowles, wallowing in
decadence and political denial. Her convulsive breakdown during the
title song is a nightmarish stunner. The ensemble, which sings,
dances, plays band instruments and fills various supporting roles,
is a show unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is set in a theater converted into a Weimar cabaret,
but this environmental approach is the least important part of this
in-your-face production. It could easily be sacrificed if the show
tours, as road presenter and investor PACE Theatrical Group
intends. Meanwhile, life is likely to be a cabaret, old chum, for
the foreseeable future on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret,'' Kit Kat Klub, 124 W. 43rd St., New York. $55-$80.
(212) 239-6200.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
