<SLUG> BC-INDIANS-INOHIO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indians draw old-time fans to Ohio game
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ Rev. John Long has conducted hundreds of
wedding rehearsals in his 30-plus years in the ministry, but he
hopes none will go smoother than the one scheduled for today at Oak
Creek United Church of Christ in Kettering, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the bride and groom it had to be early and they
understood,'' said Long, who will need plenty of lead time to get
his family of eight to Cincinnati for tonight's game between the
Reds and Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Long will be among thousands of transplanted or traveling
Indians fans at Cinergy Field this weekend as the Reds host the
Indians in night games today (Friday June 5) and Saturday and a day
game Sunday. It will be the first time the Indians visit Cincinnati
for regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday game is sold out, but 2,000 standing-room tickets
will go on sale at 5:05 p.m. Saturday at Cinergy. The Reds expect
total attendance for the series to surpass 140,000. The record for
a three-game series is 152,565, set against the Los Angeles Dodgers
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing my Indians in person is something I've been looking
forward to for a long time,'' Long said. ``I made three trips to
Jacobs Field (in Cleveland) the first two years it was open
(1994-95), but then it became impossible for regular people to get
tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Long grew up in Cleveland and quickly formed an
attachment for the Indians. ``The way I see it, I still owe them,''
he said. ``In 1948, I was in the sixth grade and school got
canceled for the World Series. In 1954, I was a senior in high
school and school got canceled again for the World Series. Any kid
who gets to miss that much school because of a baseball team has to
have loyalty to that team no matter what, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Long, who has served the Oak Creek church for 13 years, said his
parishioners, mostly Reds fans, accepted his loyalty to the Indians
with benign benevolence until interleague play began last year.
``Until that happened, I'm not sure anybody around here knew or
cared too much about Cleveland and vice versa,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``pro football was always different. I was a
big Browns fan, too, so I heard from Bengals fans all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Long for tonight's pilgrimage will be his wife Shirley,
also a Cleveland native, and daughters Mary and Beth. Also going
are Dave Higgins, Beth's husband, their two children, Hannah and
Andrew, and Barbara Cassady, Shirley's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining ties to the Indians hasn't been easy for Dayton-area
residents, including Jim Dennis, an Oakwood attorney who moved here
from Cleveland in 1976, when the Big Red Machine was at its peak
and the Indians were in the midst of a decline that produced only
five winning seasons from 1967 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``My loyalty has always been to the Indians and always will
be,'' said Dennis, who will take in Saturday's game, ``but I took a
lot of ribbing in those days. I longed for the time when my Indians
would have that kind of record. And now the roles are reversed.
It's only a matter of time before the Indians win a World Series
and it's the Reds who are building.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Owens, another former Clevelander who lives in Oakwood,
said her allegiance has also remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy that the Reds were doing so well and even went to
a few of their games,'' she said, ``but if you're an Indians fan,
it doesn't matter how they're doing. No matter what happens,
they're still my Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   e-mail marty_williamscoxohio.co
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
