the Goodwill Games. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   LONGHORNS-LOSETRACK _ BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Wagner, the University of
Texas' defending NCAA outdoor high jump champion, concluded an
injury-plagued junior season by failing to clear the opening height
at this year's meet. For Wagner, it was a fitting end. Ditto for
the Longhorns, who have run smack into Murphy's Law at the
University of Buffalo's stadium. ``Tough meet,'' understated UT
men's coach Bubba Thornton, who saw his sophomore Jacob Davis, the
favorite in the pole vault, finish sixth. (Riggs, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M-WINTRACK _ BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Larry Wade, a Texas A&AMP;M senior
from Elgin, rolled his eyes and took a deep sigh after crossing
first at the NCAA outdoor track and field championships. It was a
sigh of relief. Part if it was surviving the gusting, swirling
winds inside the University of Buffalo stadium. Part of it was his
time of 13.96 seconds _ ``I haven't run that slow since I was a
freshman,'' Wade said _ and the two were related. (Riggs, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-INOHIO _ KETTERING, Ohio _ Rev. John Long will be among
thousands of transplanted or traveling Indians fans at Cinergy
Field this weekend as the Reds host the Indians in night games
today (Friday June 5) and Saturday and a day game Sunday. It will
be the first time the Indians visit Cincinnati for regular-season
games. (Williams, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MARLINS-KOTSAY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If he watches the
College World Series, he must do so with greater interest than
most, knowing that he once owned it. Mark Kotsay, the Marlins'
right fielder, was a sophomore center fielder/relief pitcher on the
Cal State-Fullerton baseball team when they went to Omaha for the
1995 World Series. By the time he left Rosenblatt Stadium, he had
led Fullerton to the title, broken or tied six offensive records,
and been called ``the Messiah'' by an opposing coach. Not a bad
week. (Graziano, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
