<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION EMERGES EARLY AS AN ISSUE IN CALIFORNIA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In his primary campaign, ``experience money
can't buy'' was how Lt. Gov. Gray Davis distinguished himself from
his Democratic opponents.
</P>
<P>
   For the general election race, the newly minted nominee running
against Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren has found a new
mantra: ``pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days into the campaign for the November 3 election, Davis
has already seized on his opponent's opposition to abortion to try
to paint him as an extremist.
</P>
<P>
   The former two-term controller pounded the theme home at a
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League rally in
San Francisco Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision for California is much closer to the mainstream than
Dan Lungren's: I am strongly pro-choice. He's not,'' Davis told 30
mostly women supporters at the event led by NARAL president Kate
Michelman.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is hoping a pro-abortion rights message will resonate with
uncommitted women voters _ especially independents and moderate
Republicans _ whose support he needs in what is expected to be a
close race.
</P>
<P>
   State politics watchers say the message plays well with voters
who view support for abortion rights as a litmus test, but may have
little effect on the electorate at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems less likely that it will swing the women's vote, if
such a thing exists,'' said Mary Hughes, a San Francisco-based
political consultant. Hughes said most women are more interested in
issues like education, public safety and health care _ the
``benchmark issues that women pay a lot of attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the public is divided on abortion: while 60 percent
of Americans identify themselves as ``pro-choice,'' many dislike
late-term abortions and would support parental consent for minors
seeking abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't favor a constitutional amendment prohibiting
abortion, but they don't like abortion either,'' said John Pitney
Jr., political scientist and former Republican party official. ``So
an emphasis on this issue could backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion was never much of an issue in the primary. The three
major Democratic candidates all backed abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   As a congressman, Lungren co-sponsored the ``human life
amendment,'' a failed measure to overturn Roe vs. Wade. A devout
Catholic, he also voted to cut federal funding for abortions and
for family planning services.
</P>
<P>
   Staking his own claim to the center, Lungren has sought to
moderate his abortion stance. As governor, he says he would seek
only three changes: ending taxpayer-funded abortions and late-term
procedures, and reinstating a state law requiring parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's strategists maintain that abortion is a minor issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would defy Gray Davis or any of those he was standing with
to show me any poll that shows this is the issue voters care most
about,'' said Dave Puglia, Lungren's campaign manager. ``It is
education, crime and taxes, in that order.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
