u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-REUNION-HNS     06-05 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-REUNION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS MARK 60TH ANNIVERSARY OF ESCAPE FROM NAZIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Holocaust survivors from around the world are
holding a reunion here this weekend to mark the 60th anniversary of
the first ``Kindertransport,'' an effort to help Jewish children
escape the Nazis just before and during World War II by fleeing to
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 of the 10,000 Jewish children who left Germany,
Austria, Czechoslovakia and Poland on trains and then ships for
Britain between 1938 and 1940 are attending the reunion, some of
them meeting one another for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one part of the Holocaust where the end result was
life, not death,'' said Tamara Meyer, a spokeswoman for the
Washington-based Kindertransport Association. ``It's the story of
love _ the story of one country that opened its doors and allowed
children to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the reunion, which started Friday and goes
through Sunday in the Washington suburb of Arlington, Va., are
taking part in workshops, hearing speeches and sharing stories of
their lives after their escape. They will visit the United States
Holocaust Museum in Washington on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the survivors now live in the United States. Some have
come from Europe, some from Israel and some from as far away as
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1938, Jewish leaders in Europe and in the United
States appealed to major western nations to take in the Jewish
children under Nazi Germany's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jews knew the horror firsthand,'' said Melissa Hacker, a
filmmaker who recently finished a documentary about the
Kindertransports. ``They wrote to newspapers, they wrote to the
governments of different countries _ anyone that could help them.''
</P>
<P>
   But only Britain responded.
</P>
<P>
   The United States _ then plagued by the Great Depression,
various outbreaks of antisemitism and a strict immigration quota _
denied their appeal, Hacker said.
</P>
<P>
   Children left their parents behind as they fled to England. They
lived with foster families or in orphanages in England, Ireland,
Scotland and Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their parents died in Nazi death camps, Meyer said.
``But these survivors say they are the lucky ones,'' she added.
``They are grateful that they never worked in the camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Eva Burger, a Kindertransport survivor now living in Silver
Spring, Md., was 13 when she and her two sisters were rushed out of
their home town, Vienna, Austria, and shipped to London in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very sad and traumatic,'' Burger recalled. ``I didn't
know what was happening. I just wanted to take care of my little
sisters and not be apart from them.''
</P>
<P>
   But when they arrived in England, the three sisters were sent to
different foster families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tragic time for us, but looking back, I think
all of the people who took care us did the best they could,''
Burger said.
</P>
<P>
   Burger, who only spoke German at the time, said language and
cultural barriers made her new life in England more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   She was eventually reunited nine years later with her sisters
and their mother, who had survived the death camps. Her mother told
them their father had died in one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living because people made sacrifices,'' Burger said.
``Our parents, our foster families, the British government,
everyone. We need to remind each other of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
