<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET TRIES TO MAKE HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBBIE ARRINGTON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. -- Bob Baffert figures he's done all he can do to
prepare Real Quiet for today's rendevous with history. Now, he just
has to hang loose and wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hardest part _ the waiting,'' said the white-haired
trainer Friday morning after watching his Kentucky Derby and
Preakness champion lope around Belmont's sweeping curves. ``I know
I won't sleep tonight. I just want this thing to be over.''
</P>
<P>
   That wait will end late this afternoon when Real Quiet enters
the starting gate for the 130th Belmont Stakes, the 1{-mile test of
the champion.
</P>
<P>
   If the skinny bay colt with a crooked leg manages to win, Real
Quiet will become only the 12th horse ever to wear the Triple Crown
and the first in two decades. Affirmed was the last to accomplish
this Herculean task, 20 years ago to the day.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would be worth $5.6 million to a horse that cost only
$17,000, a bargain Cinderella that Baffert nicknamed the Fish
because of his long and narrow build. Now, the Fish has turned into
a shark, ready to devour his 12 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, a former Long Beach resident, found himself in this
same position at last year's Belmont with ``Double Crown'' hero
Silver Charm. But the big gray came an arm's length short of
winning the grueling Belmont, finishing second to Touch Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is luck and coincidence,'' said Baffert about his
back-to-back Triple Crown tries, the first in a century of racing
tradition. ``But I do believe in the Derby gods and the Triple
Crown gods, too. My owners are generous, wonderful people. When you
live a good life, you'll be rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Those gods have been smiling a lot on Team Baffert. After early
forecasts for thunderstorms, today's weather is expected to be
breezy and warm under sunny skies. A crowd of 70,000 is expected to
come out to root for Real Quiet, Baffert and owner Mike Pegram.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of the Fish has astounded many longtime race watchers,
but Baffert has a ready explanation. ``The sport of kings can be
very intimidating to people. But you can get lucky; we've shown
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several critics have blasted Real Quiet, winner of only four of
14 starts, as unworthy of the Triple Crown. But Baffert ignores
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep knocking our horse and us because we came from
humble beginnings,'' continued the 45-year-old trainer. ``It's just
like President Clinton. He's doing a great job, but people keep
knocking him. We're from the same generation. So is Mike (Pegram).
We're all regular guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram agreed. ``President Clinton doesn't act any differently
now than before he became president. Success didn't change us. We
didn't have to go through the Depression or fight World War II, but
we've had our own social crises to deal with. We look at the world
a helluva lot differently than someone in their 60s. We're more
kicked back, not as serious. We've done a good job, but some folks
still won't give us any credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, a self-made millionaire who went from flipping burgers
to owning 22 McDonalds franchises, added another similarity between
himself, Baffert and Clinton. ``We all eat at McDonalds.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Real Quiet, Pegram sees him as the people's pony. ``This
horse belongs to the fans. They're the ones who really make racing.
We want people to feel like they're part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's still one mammoth hurdle for Real Quiet to overcome.
Baffert regards Victory Gallop, who finished second behind Real
Quiet in both prior classics, as the main rival again. ``But I
don't really pay attention to who else is in the race. I can only
worry about my own horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that can get him beat is bad racing luck,'' he
added. ``His only vulnerability is having a guy like me train
him.''
</P>
<P>
   His instructions to jockey Kent Desormeaux will be simple.
``It's a huge field and I'll tell Kent to get him around that first
turn clean, then I guarantee he'll be fine the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   After only three days, Real Quiet has acclimated beautifully to
this Long Island race track. Exercise rider Larry Damore beamed
after Friday's morning jog, reporting that Real Quiet handled
Belmont's sandy surface better than Pimlico, home of the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hitting on all cylinders,'' said Baffert. ``He used to
gawk around, but now he's intensely focused and very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   No Baffert fans will be rooting harder for Real Quiet than Bob
and Beverly Lewis, the owners of Silver Charm. The Newport Beach
couple flew to New York to watch another of their horses, Baquero,
compete on Belmont Day's stakes-heavy undercard. But they say
they'd like nothing better than to see Real Quiet do what Silver
Charm couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stablemates,'' said Bob Lewis. ``Silver Charm has been
stabled right next to Real Quiet at Churchill Downs and, if I know
my horse, he's been whispering to him, giving him instructions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises sympathize with the Real Quiet camp. ``Last year at
this time, I was thinking, `God, I wish this thing would get over
with!' '' he added. ``The longest three weeks of our 51 years of
marriage was that time between the Preakness and the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Those three weeks are almost over again. Baffert planned to
spend Friday night at Yankee Stadium with his sons, he said.
``Then, I'll do what I did last year: Go back to the hotel room,
have a couple of brewskis and try to relax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
