</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQI FOREIGN MINISTER ATTACKS U.N. INSPECTOR'S PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq's foreign minister on Friday dismissed as
a ``nonstarter'' the agenda that the United Nations' chief arms
inspector for Iraq plans to take to Baghdad next week.
</P>
<P>
   The arms inspector, Richard Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission, is due to meet Iraqi officials to discuss what has been
called a ``road map'' of requirements to lead Iraq toward the
lifting of an 8-year-old oil embargo. He will ask for documents and
materials still unaccounted for by the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister, Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, at a news
conference at the United Nations, angrily rejected Butler's
conclusions, presented to the Security Council this week, that Iraq
was still withholding critical material and information on
biological, chemical and missile systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in UNSCOM are politically motivated,'' al-Sahhaf
said of the Special Commission. He left the impression that Butler
could not look forward to a warm reception in Baghdad next week.
</P>
<P>
   Amir al-Saadi, a former general and now an adviser to President
Saddam Hussein, said at the news conference that Butler's road map
was ``just an excuse to ask for a new slogan: access to
documents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All documents relevant to disarmament have been presented,''
al-Saadi said, confirming the suspicion of some Western officials
that there are some areas of information in Iraq touching the
political leadership where U.N. inspectors will never be permitted
to go.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sahhaf reiterated Iraq's claims that it had met all the
requirements of the disarmament process and that nothing now stood
in the way of lifting sanctions. He also repeated complaints that
the embargo, imposed in August 1990 after Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait, had produced ``the severest suffering in human history''
among the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed as temporary and insufficient the oil-for-food
program, under which Iraq can now sell up to $5 billion in oil
every six months to pay for civilian goods. He said conditions were
continuing to worsen and more children were dying.
</P>
<P>
   But in Baghdad on Thursday, a spokesman for the program, Eric
Falt, said a recent World Health Organization survey of Iraq had
found attendance at health clinics rising across the country, with
50 percent of patients interviewed saying they were getting the
full treatments prescribed, after suffering shortages of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``On average, 74 percent of the patients felt there had been an
increase in the availability of drugs over the last three months,''
Falt said. Doctors in government health centers gave a lower
figure, saying they received only about a third of the medicines
they needed to treat the 10 most common diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The oil-for-food administrator in Iraq, Denis Halliday,
announced recently that he would be allocating money to improve
Iraq's run-down schools. Electricity systems and agriculture are
also getting larger shares of equipment and money with an increase
in the amount of oil allowed to be sold. The program was expanded
early this year by the Security Council, under pressure to do more
to relieve the hardships of Iraqis. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
