<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COMPUTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES TECHNOLOGICAL LITERACY FOR STUDENTS ENTERING HIGH
SCHOOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Warning of a ``digital divide,'' President
Clinton called Friday for technological literacy to become a
requirement for middle school students and pledged $180 million to
help train teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In a commencement address at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, Clinton also defended a law now under attack by the
telecommunications industry that would provide reduced costs to
poor schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
visited the opening of the Thoreau Institute at Walden Woods and
participate in a ``video conversation'' between students at
Concord, Mass., and St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In his address to MIT's 2,400 graduates, Clinton challenged
states to make technology literacy a requirement for students to
graduate from middle school. He pledged to provide $180 million
over three years, starting in 2000, to train a team of teachers who
in turn would help train other teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child in America deserves the chance to participate in
the information revolution,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten states, including Texas, currently require technology
literacy of high school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happily, the digital divide has begun to narrow, but it will
not disappear of its own accord. History teaches us that even as
new technologies create growth and new opportunity, they can
heighten economic inequalities and sharpen social divisions,''
Clinton said, citing the Industrial Revolution as an example.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted the high-technology industries already
employ more people than the auto industry did at its height in the
1950s. Yet, Clinton said rich schools are three times more likely
to have Internet access than poor schools, and white students are
more than twice as likely as black students to have a computer in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But until every child has a computer in the classroom and a
teacher well-trained to help, until every student has the skills to
tap the enormous resources of the Internet, until every high-tech
company can find skilled workers to fill its high-wage jobs,
America will miss the full promise of the Information Age,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged the graduates to join his effort to preserve
the so-called ``E-Rate'' that requires telecommunication companies
to provide discounts of up to 90 percent to schools and libraries
connecting to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now some businesses have called on Congress to repeal the
initiative. They say our nation cannot afford to provide discounts
to these institutions,'' Clinton said. ``I say we cannot afford not
to have an E-rate.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that the FCC is considering suspending the
E-rate program, but an administration official said the White House
had no knowledge of any such move.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications companies agreed in 1996 to provide the
low-cost service in return for the Federal Communications
Commission lowering the local access fees long-distance companies
pay to local telephone companies. The lowered access fees were to
save long-distance companies $2.6 billion over 11 months while the
discount to schools and libraries was to cost $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, the industry is now pressing for repeal of the
initiative, saying it has imposed a 5 percent surcharge on business
customers and will add the surcharge to residential customers in
July. Critics call the surcharge the ``Gore tax'' after Vice
President Al Gore who championed the provision.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, a White House spokesman, said the industry
previously agreed to provide the service. He maintained there was
no reason to pass along the surcharge costs to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of poor schools and libraries and rural health
centers are in desperate need of discounts. If we really believed
that we all belong in the Information Age, then, at this sunlit
moment of prosperity, we can't leave anyone behind in the dark,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for large increases in the budgets of the
National Science Foundation and the National Institutes of Health
for long-term information and communications research. He cited the
discovery this week in Japan that subatomic particles called
neutrinos have mass, a key to the workings of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discovery calls into question the decision made in
Washington a couple of years ago to disband the superconducting
super collider, and it reaffirms the importance of the work now
being done at the Fermi National Acceleration Facility in
Illinois,'' Clinton said. Congress canceled the supercollider,
which was to be built in Waxahachie, Texas, in 1993 because of
escalating costs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton shared commencement duties with Dr. David Ho, who
discovered the drug combination treatment to control AIDS. Ho
accepted MIT's invitation to speak at its commencement last
February but the White House, searching for a venue for Clinton to
speak on the Information revolution, called last month asking to be
included.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ho, born in Taiwan, lamented the anti-immigrant sentiments
brewing in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``One prevailing view that immigrants constitute a constant
drain on our society is simply baseless, wrong and shameful,
especially for this nation of immigrants,'' Ho said.
</P>
<P>
   After his address, the president had lunch with Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., and then joined the first lady to mark the
opening of the Thoreau Institute. Don Henley, former drummer for
the band The Eagles, created the institute and the Walden Woods
Project to preserve the legacy of Henry David Thoreau. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
