<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-BIBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    According to the Word: Biblical texts most often cited by
opponents of homosexuality
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verses from New Revised Standard Version of the Bible
</P>
<P>
   -- Genesis 19:1-11
</P>
<P>
   The story of two angels who visit Lot, the nephew of Abraham, in
Sodom. While the angels are in Lot's house, the ``men of Sodom''
ask him to bring out the ``men who came to you tonight'' so that
``we may know them.'' Lot offers his two virgin daughters in place
of his guests. The men of Sodom are struck blind when they insist
on attempting to go into Lot's house to take the men.
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: Many ministers and scholars say the great sin of
this passage is that the men of Sodom wanted to have sexual
relations with Lot's male visitors. In fact, the word ``sodomite''
is sometimes used to refer to homosexuals. Others argue that the
transgression of the men of Sodom was that they were abusive and
inhospitable.
</P>
<P>
   -- Leviticus 18:22
</P>
<P>
   ``You shall not lie with a male as with a woman; it is an
abomination.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Leviticus 20:13
</P>
<P>
   ``If a man lies with a male as with a woman, both of them have
committed an abomination; they shall be put to death; their blood
is upon them.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: Perhaps the strongest passages in the Bible
referring to homosexuality. However, advocates of a more lenient
view of homosexuality in the church say the condemnation of
male-male sexual relations must be taken in the context of
Leviticus' emphasis on keeping certain practices to preserve Jewish
identity. Other laws in Leviticus forbid eating shellfish and
wearing mixed fabric.
</P>
<P>
   -- Romans 1:18-32
</P>
<P>
   According to the apostle Paul in this book, when people who knew
God failed to honor God, ``God gave them up to degrading passions.
Their women exchanged natural intercourse for unnatural, and in the
same way also the men, giving up natural intercourse with women,
were consumed with passion for one another. Men committed shameless
acts with men and received in their own persons the due penalty for
their error.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: The only passage in the Bible that refers to
lesbian sexual relations. This text cites homosexuality as a symbol
of how far humankind has fallen from God's ideal, according to
traditional interpretations. Some have even seen AIDS as the ``due
penalty'' of homosexual sex. Those who disagree say that in the
context of Paul's time, the apostle was saying only that homosexual
acts were unusual or not the norm, and that heterosexuals should
not go against their innate nature and have homosexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   -- I Corinthians 6:9-10
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you not know that wrongdoers will not inherit the kingdom
of God? Do not be deceived! Fornicators, idolaters, adulterers,
male prostitutes, sodomites, thieves, the greedy, drunkards,
revilers, robbers _ none of these will inherit the kingdom of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   -- I Timothy 1:9-11
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is laid down not for the innocent but for the lawless
and disobedient, for the godless and sinful, for the unholy and
profane, for those who kill their father or mother, for murderers,
fornicators, sodomites, slave traders, liars, perjurers, and
whatever else is contrary to the sound teaching that conforms to
the glorious gospel of the blessed God.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: These New Testament texts include apparent
references to homosexual practices in lists of bad deeds, while
offering no further discussion about the specific acts or
prohibitions. Certain words in the passage have been translated
over the years as ``homosexuals,'' ``sexual perverts,''
``sodomites'' and ``male prostitutes,'' fostering arguments about
exactly what acts or practices they address.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-CHANGE-COX     06-05 1722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-CHANGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is change possible?: The `ex-gay movement' sets off intense
debate
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Jack Vaiden and his wife had just finished making love
when he made an agonizing confession.
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden was holding his wife, Diane, when she turned to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack, I'm afraid I'm losing you,'' his wife of six years said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never leave you for another woman,'' Vaiden responded.
``If you lose me, it'll be to either two things: death ... or to
another man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you trying to tell me, Jack?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith may move mountains, but can it change a person's sexual
desires? That's the brutal question Vaiden and other Christians
face when they discover they have homosexual desires. Many pray for
years, participate in dramatic healing ceremonies or even marry,
hoping they will become free of homosexuality. They may become part
of the ``ex-gay movement,'' an organized effort by Christians who
proclaim Jesus can release people from homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of Christians views religious-based efforts to
make gay people straight as not only impossible, but cruel. They
insist there is no such thing as an ex-gay person.
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden has lived on both sides of the issue. He tried celibacy.
He tried marriage. He tried God. But his homosexual desires
persisted. He eventually divorced his wife and for the past 15
years has been living with a man in Stone Mountain. His partner,
Lowrey Fleming, whom he met in a Bible study class, helped Vaiden
raise his two sons, now adults in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubts about my salvation,'' Vaiden, 51, said. ``I
tried to tell the Lord for years what he says. I thought he was
saying, `You can't be gay. You can't be Christian.' But I was
telling him what he had to say. When I finally trusted enough to
allow him to speak for himself, I learned that, `Lord, your grace
is sufficient.'''
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden says he is comfortable with his sexual orientation today.
But many Christians remain certain that practicing homosexuality is
a sin. The issue has split the Christian community into two camps.
</P>
<P>
   One group believes homosexuality is a sin that can be ``healed''
by belief in Jesus. Exodus International, based in Seattle, is the
flagship for this group, whose primary mission is to free
Christians from homosexuality through rigorous Bible study, prayer
and support group principles.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1976, Exodus has 88 chapters in the United States and
nine international chapters in places as far apart as Singapore and
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Christians who embrace their gayness also cite Scripture. And
their contention that homosexuality isn't something that can be
changed has in recent years been reinforced by many in the
scientific and psychological communities.
</P>
<P>
   Gays and ex-gays differ on basic assumptions about
homosexuality. Most Christians who believe God can change a
person's sexual orientation think that homosexuality is not inborn,
but caused by a person's environment. They often cite an inadequate
relationship between children and parents as the spark for
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   George Morales said he was healed of his homosexuality during a
demonic deliverance session at Landmark Church, a charismatic
church in Norcross. Morales, 32, said a troubled relationship with
his father caused him to look for affection from other men. He said
his father routinely called him stupid and told him he ran ``like a
faggot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was subconsciously, `If you can't give me that love, I'm
going to go to a man to get that love,''' Morales said.
</P>
<P>
   Many gay Christians who laim they have been healed are
unwilling to say they no longer are attracted to members of the
same sex. They describe healing as a process, not an overnight
change. Temptation remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at a man, if I'm attracted to him, I'll turn my
head the other way,'' Morales said. ``I just don't feed on it.
That's what the devil wants me to do, to go back into that
</P>
<P>
   lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Morton is a member of Living Stones, an Atlanta-based
ministry affiliated with Exodus International. Morton, 40, a
minister's son from Indiana, joined Living Stones after his
marriage failed because of his homosexuality. He lost his wife and
male lover in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Morton said Living Stones uses a tough-love approach. Members
are required to meet each week, stay in constant touch with a
sponsor, and are forbidden to buy pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Morton said his struggle to overcome his gay tendencies was
fierce. Lonely, he would call Living Stones' members late at night.
``I'm dying,'' he remembers telling his friends. ``I can't stand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morton said leaders of the group did not condemn him for his
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would talk to me on the phone, talk me through it and
share their experiences,'' said Morton, now chairman of the Living
Stones support group in metro Atlanta, which has 12 active members.
``Sometimes they would tell me to get in the car, bring my clothes
over and spend the night with them and their families. We'd make
plans for (the next day) so I would have something to look forward
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Morton said, he still has homosexual desires, but they
have ``tremendously subsided.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the ex-gay movement believe Morton's quest will
ultimately fail. They scoff at the idea that homosexuality can be
explained by a deficient relationship between a child and a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden, for example, said he got along great with his father and
mother. Both supported him when he left his wife, although they
didn't understand his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with straight parents, straight brothers and I was
as gay as they come,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden and others believe homosexuality is inborn. Scientists
are starting to agree with such thinking. Several recent studies
suggest sexual orientation is predetermined at birth.
</P>
<P>
   The American Psychological Association adopted a resolution last
year that said it was dangerous to try to alter a person's sexual
orientation. Doug Haldeman, who conducted the APA study, said he
found ``absolutely no evidence'' that ex-gay ministries or
traditional psychological counseling can change a person from gay
to straight.
</P>
<P>
   What Haldeman said he found instead were homosexuals who live in
``inner martyrdom.'' They kill their sexual desires to live a
straight lifestyle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically think that sexual orientation is very strongly
rooted and impossible to change,'' Haldeman said. ``Those inner
impulses are very strong. Imagine for a moment if you were
forbidden the rest of your life of having sex with the gender of
your choice and had to try to have a loving relationship with
another gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Sneed, a 27-year-old Emory University graduate student,
drew the same conclusion as Haldeman after he tried to go straight.
Sneed said he thought he was twice ``healed'' of his homosexuality
_ once by a Pentecostal preacher during a revival service and
another time during an exorcism where church members assured him
that they had driven out the ``demon of homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither healing lasted. Sneed said he continued being sexual
with men, even while he assured people that he was ``free from the
devil'' and condemned other homosexuals. He said he finally
accepted his homosexuality because he believed God created him gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe a person who is gay or lesbian can be
converted,'' Sneed said. ``I tried. I think it's damnable. They're
forcing people to live in a way that's not honest to them or the
God that created them. You have people who want to live right
buying into this crap because you've taught them to hate
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Christians who believe that God can deliver people from
homosexuality think the argument that people are born gay is
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the position of Joe Dallas, author of several books that
are critical of what he calls ``pro-gay theology.'' He also
describes himself as an ex-gay. He was once a member of the
Metropolitan Community Church, the world's largest gay-affirming
Christian denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas points out that studies suggesting biological roots for
homosexuality are small in sample size and far from proven, a point
Haldeman concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Of much greater importance, Dallas adds, is the fact that
Christians who grapple with homosexual desires must still obey
Scripture, which forbids homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we assuming that even if something is proven to be inborn
that that will legitimize the behavior?'' Dallas said. ``We seem to
be innately created with the ability to lie. Children do it so
well. But none of us have adopted that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, who said he left the MCC church because his gay
</P>
<P>
   lifestyle had caused a ``crisis in confidence'' in his faith,
said critics of the ex-gay movement base their beliefs on their own
personal failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They conclude, `I didn't change so no one can change,'''
Dallas said. ``And because they didn't change, they think it must
not be bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden has long since given up trying to change his sexual
orientation. That's not to say he didn't struggle to remain with
his wife and attempt to be straight.
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden thought he could cure his homosexuality through prayer
and Scripture. But such efforts proved futile. He tried to balance
his sexual desires with his need to take care of his wife and
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all the blessings and that wasn't enough,'' Vaiden said.
``I felt like a horrible spider who was pulling these people into
my web, destroying my parents, my children, my wife and the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   It all became too much. Vaiden divorced. A year later he and
Fleming began living together, a partnership that has lasted for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Vaiden's public ministry ended. The church he helped to start,
First Moravian in Stone Mountain, asked him to step down because he
had become too ``controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   Today he trains hotel managers and is a member of the
Metropolitan Community Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ask anyone to agree or accept,'' Vaiden says of his
lifestyle and choices. ``At best, just leave me alone. I've already
put in too much time, too much prayer, too many tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
