<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-THEOLOGY-COX     06-05 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-THEOLOGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate within the church
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For United Methodists, the verdict in the church trial of the
Rev. Jimmy Creech was almost as divisive as the O.J. Simpson
verdict was for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Across Methodism, the Creech trial brought to a head simmering
debates about homosexuality. Creech, a pastor in the country's
second-largest Protestant denomination, was acquitted in March of
violating church law by blessing the union of two lesbians at his
Omaha, Neb., church. Eight of the 13-member, all-clergy jury found
him guilty, one short of the nine required for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout continues.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 ministers who supported Creech signed a statement
vowing to continue to bless same-sex unions, while those outraged
at the verdict called for a special session of the denomination's
General Conference to deal with the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   And the issue may find its way into the North and South Georgia
conferences this month.
</P>
<P>
   After his bishop did not reappoint him to his Omaha church,
Creech announced that he will take a leave of absence from the
ministry and move to North Carolina. His last sermon in the Omaha
pulpit will be today.
</P>
<P>
   The Methodists are just one group of many in Christendom
struggling with questions of same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterians, Lutherans, Episcopalians, Catholics, Baptists and
members of the United Church of Christ have their own skirmishes.
The votes and charges at the national level have filtered down into
metro Atlanta's pews and pulpits, in some cases causing division
within churches and defection from denominations.
</P>
<P>
   On a practical level, the great church debates center on two
questions: Should there be a rite for same-sex unions? And, should
sexually active gay men and lesbian women be ordained to church
office?
</P>
<P>
   But on a theological level, what is at stake may be much greater
than a ceremony or a clerical position. Some leaders on both sides
of the line see themselves in a battle for the soul of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Driving beliefs about homosexuality are views about other,
larger matters:
</P>
<P>
   The Scriptures
</P>
<P>
   Those who oppose recognizing homosexuality as a legitimate
sexual practice take a literalist approach to Bible verses that
refer to same-sex relationships as an ``abomination.'' To accept
such relationships, to them, would undermine the teachings of the
Bible. Those who advocate a more liberal attitude in the churches
say the Bible must be examined through the lenses of experience,
science and later revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people on both sides who take the Bible seriously,''
said the Rev. Michael Wilson, associate pastor of Clairmont
Presbyterian Church in DeKalb County. ``This discussion has a lot
to do with whether we're going to interpret Scripture according to
Scripture or according to the culture in which we live.'' He
believes Scripture is clear that homosexual practice is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Rex Kaney, pastor of Trinity United Methodist Church in
downtown Atlanta, says that Scripture has to be examined in the
light of contemporary understanding. ``Scripture has always had the
primary place, but we have always felt like we needed to do
scholarly and serious search to discern what the Scriptures mean.
As I read the Bible, all those texts about homosexuality are about
several things. They are about violence. They are about lust. They
are about inhospitality. They are not ever, it seems to me at this
point in history, dealing with the subject of homosexuality as
possibly being an orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   The nature of God
</P>
<P>
   Most Christians agree that God balances mercy and judgment.
Opponents of homosexual ordination and same-sex unions regard
homosexual activity as sinful and emphasize the need to ask God's
forgiveness and determine to sin no more. Those who say gays and
lesbians are entitled to greater recognition point to God's
inclusivity and the admonition to ``judge not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's an issue of repentance,'' said Joe Whittemore, a
United Methodist layman from Hartwell. ``When we join the Methodist
Church, we're asked if we repent of our sins and reject sin and
intend to lead a new life. We answer `I do' in order to join the
church. So this brings us to the main issue of whether homosexual
acts are sin. I believe the answer is very clearly yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a justice issue,'' said the Rev. Tim Shirley,
pastor of Virginia-Highland Baptist Church. ``It is an issue of the
gospel. Never do I see where Jesus delegates anyone to second-class
status. Never do I see where Jesus excludes anyone. It just isn't
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of the church
</P>
<P>
   The names of two movements within United Methodism describe the
attitudes of the two factions toward the church. Reconciling
Congregations are those who intentionally include gays and
lesbians, focusing on the need to bring in and nurture everyone as
a member of God's family. Transforming Congregations are those who
believe homosexuals can be changed in their orientation through
God's healing powers, or can find the courage to live a life of
celibacy in order to conform to the church's teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing black, white, gay, straight, old and young together
around the Communion table at Grant Park-Aldersgate United
Methodist Church is a foretaste of the kingdom of God, said the
church's pastor, the Rev. Pat York. The church's affiliation with
the Reconciling group is more than a political statement, she said.
``We're willing to be open and welcoming and affirming, and we're
willing to say that. When all churches become in reality
reconciling, we'll all be Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Pat Looper, pastor of Faith United Methodist Church in
Riverdale, said she supports the mission of the Transforming
Congregations ``wholeheartedly'' because ``they are the ones giving
the truth to people. How terrible to say to the wife abuser, the
alcoholic or the adulterer that nothing's going to change! You can
be transformed through Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of sexual expression
</P>
<P>
   While both sides say they see sexual expression ideally as an
expression of commitment and love, in general those who would
prohibit the blessing of same-sex unions or the ordination of
sexually active homosexuals see sex as tied to procreation and
God's plan of creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans are to see their sex as a part of the ongoing flow of
life, as a blessed link in the generations, becoming fathers and
mothers to the generations of tomorrow in a way that can be
honored, and then honoring the fathers and mothers who went
before,'' said Max Stackhouse, professor of Christian ethics at
Princeton Theological Seminary, in a recent discussion sponsored by
a ``centrist'' group in the United Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sharon Taylor, pastor of Atlanta's Ormewood Park
Presbyterian Church, counters that God created humans to live in
families. ``I'm thinking when we say to gay and lesbian people that
they cannot create relationships, that we're telling them they
cannot live in families. You must do life all by yourself,'' she
said. ``That is so far removed from everything we talk about with
God and making communities and loving that it feels sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements run deep, but most mainline Christians do agree on
some statements about sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   A statement by the Alliance of Baptists, a moderate group of
Southern and American Baptists, is echoed in reports by other
denominations, including the United Methodist Church and the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.). The statement says:
</P>
<P>
   -- Human sexuality is a gift of God and should be ``accepted
with gratitude and expressed responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Genital sex ``is most responsibly expressed when it occurs in
the context of caring, loving, committed, covenant relationships
between monogamous adults.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Sexual abuse and exploitation are contrary to God's will.
</P>
<P>
   -- Human sexual behavior is imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   Several mainline denominations have also adopted resolutions
calling for civil rights for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond these basic statements, consensus is hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 United Methodist report concluded with an admission that
it was left with ``unresolvable questions and disagreements,'' and
acknowledged the possibility that ``no study process will be able
to answer the important questions conclusively or bridge all the
differences soon.''
</P>
<P>
   With more bishops, priests and ministers willing to defy their
denominations by blessing same-sex unions and ordaining
homosexuals, and more legislative action pending before several
bodies, there is no end in view.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the country's historic Christian bodies
can hold together while the grappling goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
