<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Saturday, June 6. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOPE (Washington) _ The testimonials to Bob Hope on the U.S. House
floor were so heartfelt that one could almost imagine the
95-year-old entertainer were still alive. In fact, he was. A
thoroughly embarrassing string of events, even by congressional
standards, started when House Majority Leader Dick Armey introduced
Rep. Bob Stump, R-Ariz., for an ``announcement I think will be of
great interest to this body.'' Stump stepped to the microphone and
said, ``Mr. Speaker, I have the sad responsibility to tell you this
afternoon that Bob Hope passed away.'' At that moment, Hope was
finishing breakfast in California. The culprit was an Associated
Press article being prepared in the event of Hope's death. The
article somehow was inadvertently displayed on the news service's
Web site. Stump, who has known Hope since 1943, called Hope to
apologize and was told by Hope's daughter that he ``was alive and
well.'' Said Stump: ``I said we were sorry and that I hoped Mr.
Hope got a kick out of it.'' By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNCOVERED (Phoenix) - Thousands of Arizona's former welfare
families are walking away from free state health care benefits, and
no one is sure why. While bureaucrats debate what to do, these
former welfare families are increasingly dependent on costly
emergency room care at taxpayers' expense _ even though most remain
eligible for state insurance coverage. Arizona is not alone.
Arizona's welfare reform began a year earlier than most states, but
researchers already are tracking this unexpected impact nationwide.
By PAT KOSSAN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RELIGION (Phoenix) - The line between church and state shrinks to a
pinstripe at a Higley, Arizona, charter school. While the school
runs on taxpayer dollars, its big red-white-and-blue sign proudly
proclaims: ``In God We Trust.'' At a Phoenix charter school, a
picture of the Virgin Mary hung for a time in the school office.
And in Mesa, Aria., a charter school placed an advertisement
encouraging students to attend Mormon seminary. When it comes to
separating religion and government, there are charter schools that
walk that fine line and others that have clearly crossed it. KELLY
PEARCE. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEYOTE (Phoenix) - Leo Mercado claims that his use of the
hallucinogenic drug peyote is part of his religion, a ``sacrament''
that helps him to spiritually purge his soul and cleanse his life.
But a Pinal County Superior Court judge saw it differently, ruling
this week that Mercado was essentially hiding behind the cloak of
religious immunity to veil illegal activities and that he should
forfeit a quantity of the drug. By JUDI VILLA. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEACE (Phoenix) - As if students at Arizona State University East
don't already go to school in the hinterlands, they'll soon go even
farther in pursuit of college degrees. Beginning this fall, ASU
East will offer master's level credit for agribusiness students who
join a special Peace Corps program. By MELISSA L. JONES. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
