<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-SCARE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 `BOMB' AT AIR TRAFFIC CONTROL CENTER turns out to be inside joke  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ An object found at the regional air traffic
control center in Olathe on Wednesday was a personal joke between a
contractor's employees and was not meant to resemble a bomb,
authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a personal matter between two people,'' said FBI
spokesman Jeff Lanza. ``They just left it behind in the rest
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanza said there was no evidence that the two intended to make
the quart-sized water bottle filled with a brownish-yellow fluid
resemble a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no laws violated, at least not at the federal
level,'' Lanza said. No charges will be filed and the case has been
closed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The object sent a scare through the Kansas City Air Route
Traffic Control Center at 9:35 a.m. Wednesday _ one of the center's
busiest times.
</P>
<P>
   Its discovery forced controllers to reroute about 200 airplanes
and temporarily ground 41 flights at more than 600 airports in the
area, including Kansas City International and Lambert-St. Louis
International.
</P>
<P>
   The Olathe Fire Department took the object _ a clear plastic
water bottle with a disposable cup on the top and a cigarette
sticking out like a fuse _ to its explosives range and drew a
sample of the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a nonflammable, sugary, water-based,
noncarbonated liquid.
</P>
<P>
   By 11:30 a.m, employees had returned to their jobs and the
Olathe Center returned to normal operation.
</P>
<P>
   Lanza declined to release the name of the contractor or the
employees involved. He also would not discuss the nature of the
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a personal thing unrelated to the center,'' he said.
``It was only a coincidence it looked like a bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanza said the contractor's employees contacted the FBI late
Wednesday after they saw news reports about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   He said the individuals told the FBI that they inadvertently
left the object in the men's room. It was discovered within a few
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Lanza said the FBI interviewed those involved Wednesday evening
and Thursday morning for several hours before taking the
information to the U.S. attorney's office, which determined no
charges would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Federal Aviation Administration reacted
appropriately even though the object ended up not being a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA did everything it should have done, given the fact
they didn't know what it was and the level of security they must
maintain,'' he said. ``They took the proper steps....It looked like
a bomb, and they are trained in what to do. They took the proper
steps to protect human life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
