<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAYER-AMENDMENT-2TAK     06-05 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-AMENDMENT-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYER AMENDMENT GETS MAJORITY OF VOTES, IS DEFEATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House toils beneath the inscription ``In God We
Trust,'' yet the debate Thursday over the school prayer amendment
revealed just how divisive the issue of praying to the deity can
be.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment _ which for the first time in a generation would
have permitted school-sponsored organized prayer and religious
displays on public property _ received a majority with 224 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it fell short of the two-thirds necessary for a
constitutional change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant that a majority of the House agreed that the
Supreme Court has gone too far in distorting the First Amendment
and religious freedom rights,'' Rep. Ernest Istook Jr., an Oklahoma
Republican and sponsor of the amendment, said afterward, putting a
positive spin on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   His leading opponent, Rep. Chet Edwards, a Texas Democrat, said,
``We won a tough vote against sound bite politics and for the Bill
of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the amendment passed, it would have required a similar
majority in the Senate and then ratification by three-fourths of
the state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure was a victory in any case for religious
conservatives and their supporters in Congress, who had made it a
legislative priority. It was the first time in 27 years that
Congress recorded a vote on a school prayer amendment and
Thursday's vote will become a political marker for the fall
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The more than six-hour debate turned on politics, on individual
interpretations of the 1963 Supreme Court decision that outlawed
school prayer, on what the founding fathers intended, and on the
meaning of the word ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   An effort to remove the word from the measure was defeated, as
was an attempt to send the entire amendment back to committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the level of debate occurring already,'' said Rep.
Louise Slaughter, a New York Democrat and an opponent. She then
quoted Rep. Jack Kingston, a Georgia Republican and supporter, as
saying recently of the amendment's opponents:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that there is a special place in
hell for a number of federal court judges, as I am sure there will
be for members of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate also produced some sharp exchanges across the
philosophical divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have religious convictions and have the right to
express them,'' said Republican Rep. Dana Rohrabacher of
California. ``There's nothing wrong with shouting out for the glory
of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they have that right,'' replied Rep. Gene Green, a Texas
opponent. ``But that's not the right to stand up in algebra class
and say it.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the issue was certain to evoke strong passions, the
debate took on an even greater urgency among supporters. Against a
backdrop of recent killings in several of the nation's schools,
many speakers equated the attacks with the absence of a religious
presence in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine,'' said Istook, ``that in an era when drugs, guns and
knives are common in public schools, we are told the Ten
Commandments is not welcome, not permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards said of the Religious Freedom Amendment: ``Anyone
can pray in school and no one, not Ernest Istook, not the Supreme
Court, is going to stop me and my child from praying in school.
What is prohibited is allowing government organized prayer. Parents
do not send their children to school to be proselytized by
religious groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argued that children ought to be able to initiate
voluntary prayers in classrooms, at graduations, at sporting events
and other school activities. The amendment, they said, does not
require that everyone must join in, nor does it prescribe what
prayer should be said, nor establish an official religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all there is to it,'' said Rep. Sue Myrick, a North
Carolina Republican and supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents countered that laws already allow students to pray:
before class, during lunch, after school and during moments of
silence. They can also form religious clubs. Opponents worried
about the ``perilous path'' the amendment opened by tampering with
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But since the last vote on school prayer in 1971 _ when the
supporters actually gained more votes with 240 in favor and 163
against but still failed to reach a two-thirds majority _ faith and
family issues have moved center stage, especially in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month ago, Republican congressional leaders, faced
with angry Christian activists, assured them that religious issues
would become legislative priorities.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a full-court press for school prayer by religious
conservatives. The Christian Coalition financed a $500,000 radio
advertising campaign in support of the amendment that aired in many
swing congressional districts. The coalition also sent letters to
voters in Edwards' Texas district that accused him of ``bigotry
directed at Christians,'' and stated: ``His attitudes have no place
in Texas or anywhere in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition leaders have said they intend to send out 45
million voter guides next fall and the school prayer vote is likely
to be one of its leading political indicators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put all the king's men and all the king's horses on this,''
said the Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the Traditional Values
Coalition. ``This is a defining moment for many congressmen and
elected officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents saw it that way, too. But for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Several complained that the rules governing the debate of the
amendment were patched together at the last minute and didn't
reflect the importance of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we were still slapping this together,'' said Rep.
Robert Scott, a Virginia Democrat and leading opponent. ``This will
be the first amendment to the Bill of Rights. Every word is
important. We need to know exactly what the amendment will do.''
MORE
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ amendment will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas agreed, noting that
James Madison and Thomas Jefferson debated the issue of religious
freedom in the Virginia legislature over a period of 10 years. ``We
want to change this in two-three hours,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. James Traficant Jr. of Ohio replied, ``I submit
the founding fathers are rolling over in their graves. They never
intended to separate God and the American people and this legal
mumbo jumbo is absolutely ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Each side boasted its own lists of interdenominational backing.
But as symbolic as the debate promised to be, it was largely made
in a near-empty chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries were half-full with tourists, scout groups and
others, while below, on the blue, red and gold carpeted floor, only
a few members were present at any one time, except during a vote,
when the hall was full.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was almost strictly on party lines. One who did break
ranks, Rep. Amo Houghton Jr., a New York Republican, captured the
flavor of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to sort out the issue,'' Houghton said, ``because
both sides claim they're on the side of the righteous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
