<HEADLINE>
RAINY SEASON'S FIRST SHOWERS FAIL TO QUENCH MEXICO WILDFIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The first showers of the rainy season have fallen
across parts of Mexico and Central America but have failed to
quench many wildfires that are destroying virgin forests and
feeding a smoke cloud that is drifting across the southern United
States, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and American officials predicted that some fires, which
have consumed millions of acres of forest and grassland across the
region, may continue to rage for several weeks. About 150 fires, 23
of them large, very destructive blazes, were burning this week.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural Secretary Dan Glickman, who led an American
delegation that flew over vast blazes roaring through one cloud
forest in southern Mexico on Thursday, described them Friday as ``a
catastrophe.'' Another senior American official said they were the
worst he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disaster in Mexico has to be the most serious of its kind
in the world, including Indonesia,'' said Brian Atwood, director of
the Agency for International Development. ``The duration of these
fires, the complexity of fighting them and the danger to the
firefighters, it's the most serious that we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation visited Mexico to coordinate a $5 million
assistance program, which includes a heavy-lift helicopter and
radios, as well as boots and other safety equipment for 3,000
Mexican forest rangers. Many Mexican firefighters have been wearing
straw hats and sandals while battling flames with buckets of water.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new equipment, Glickman said that because many fires
were raging across virtually impenetrable mountain ravines and
ridges, ``rainfall will have as much to do with extinguishing the
fires as anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, seasonal rains that began this week have not been heavy
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light rains have begun in some areas but they're not
sufficient to extinguish these fires,'' Atwood said. A spokesman
for Mexico's Environment Ministry agreed Friday with that
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The American officials praised Mexico's battle to control the
fires, in which more than 60 firefighters have died this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing an outstanding job fighting this thing,''
Glickman said. Those comments and praise by other American
officials contrasted with statements by Mexican conservationists,
who have argued that the Mexican and American governments have been
slow to react.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, for instance, Homero Aridjis, a
prominent Mexican environmentalist, called the Mexican government's
response to the wildfires ``really exasperating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first the policy was to minimize the fires,'' Aridjis said.
``And now that much of our ecological patrimony has been destroyed,
the government is still waiting for rains to put them out. This is
like waiting for Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   Environment Secretary Julia Carabias defended herself and other
officials Friday against a barrage of similar recent criticisms,
saying her government ``took precautions, sounded the alert, acted
vigorously and continues to act.''
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo, standing at Ms. Carabias' side on a
visit to a mountain park burned by recent wildfires that roared
through a Mexico City suburb, said, ``Our country has suffered what
I would characterize as a true ecological tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said many, perhaps most, of the blazes have started as
out-of-control agricultural fires, set by peasant farmers who
prepare their fields for planting by burning the previous year's
stubble. In other cases, forests have been set afire to clear plots
for growing marijuana or opium, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been fires caused by narcotics traffickers,''
Zedillo said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 1952EDT &QL; 
