<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6716 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-DEAD-SFCHRON &LR;      06-05 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DEAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLY GRATEFUL: OTHER ONES MAKE PROMISING DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometimes tough decisions call for waffling.
</P>
<P>
   In the Grateful Dead camp, there's been plenty of agonizing
lately about naming a guitarist for the new, post-Jerry Garcia
group the Other Ones. For Thursday night's debut at the Warfield,
the indecisive band invited not one but two replacements for the
irreplaceable Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the set _ three hours' worth of signature songs that
at times reached giddy peaks _ the core band members may be obliged
to keep both.
</P>
<P>
   It was no secret that the specter of the late Garcia would loom
large over the Other Ones' unveiling, a pricey benefit for the
Rainforest Action Network that served as a public warm-up for a
monthlong summer tour with the Furthur Festival. Until recently,
Dead mainstays Bob Weir, Phil Lesh and Mickey Hart were considering
guitarist Stan Franks, whose jazz background was expected to
discourage the inevitable Garcia comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   But Franks' tentative approach during a few side-project trials
led to an uproar among the Dead cognoscenti. Many clamored for
Steve Kimock of the Bay Area jam band Zero; word has it his
Garcia-like inclinations ran counter to some members' wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the blue comes Mark Karan, a burly local native with a
curiously un-Deadlike resume that includes stints with Dave Mason,
Huey Lewis and the Rembrandts. At the Warfield, Karan and Kimock
shared stage left, deftly clearing room for each other and
creating, with Weir, an exhilarating web of guitar tones.
</P>
<P>
   Opening with ``Jack Straw,'' the band took a few minutes to find
its footing, but after Karan took an effective, economical lead on
his Gibson Les Paul, Hart and second drummer John Molo began
pounding. As the song fell together, the expectant crowd burst into
enthusiastic hooting.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from last summer's Furthur Festival was Berkeley
saxophonist Dave Ellis, whose presence _ despite early technical
troubles _ went a long way toward distinguishing the Other Ones'
sound from that of the Dead. Longtime associate Bruce Hornsby added
his trademark feathery, upper-register runs on grand piano, sharing
most of the vocal duties with Weir.
</P>
<P>
   On the second song, ``Sugaree,'' Hornsby sang Garcia's lead
while Kimock, perched on a stool and wearing headphones, took his
own first lead on a huge hollow-body guitar. The song's easy gait
left lots of room for surges of ensemble interplay; by its finish,
there were plenty of relieved grins onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Weir flexed a little musical muscle with ``New Minglewood
Blues'' and ``Goin' Down the Road Feeling Bad.'' Playing six-string
bass, Lesh took a vocal turn on the latter song and then made way
for a canny Bakersfield guitar lead by Karan.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything worked perfectly. Hornsby's vocal on ``Scarlet
Begonias,'' for instance, was characteristically wan, and Lesh
sounded a little like Grandpa Simpson on ``Box of Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   During the second set of the three-hour show, the band played a
half-hour-plus medley that included ``Playing in the Band'' and the
free-form ``Space.'' Stepping to the sidelines as the two
percussionists cranked up the drum-battle portion of ``Space,''
Weir made a comic gesture befitting the night's heady atmosphere,
circling his ears with his fists like bike pedals.
</P>
<P>
   As the lengthy medley pieced itself back together from
purposeful deconstruction _ with Hornsby alluding to Miles Davis'
``So What'' on piano, Ellis switching between baritone and soprano
sax, and Hart coaxing skeleton music from a xylophone _ the show
rose to a zenith it would maintain till closing time.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the group found its way back to ``Playing in the Band,''
setting off a delirious finale that included ``St. Stephen,'' ``The
Eleven'' _ out of the repertoire since 1970 _ and the Dead version
of Bobby ``Blue'' Bland's ``Turn On Your Love Light.'' The latter,
the night's last song, was perfectly chosen, featuring
around-the-horn showcases for each musician and the effervescence
of a Holy Rollers congregation.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many, this show bode well for life after
Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
