<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASE-JAZZ-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M BASE: COLD AND DEFINITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the M Base movement in jazz came into being in
the mid-1980s, it organized several strains of jazz rhetoric into a
point of view that wasn't always backed up musically. But the early
members _ saxophonists Steve Coleman and Greg Osby, pianist Geri
Allen, trombonist Robin Eubanks, cornetist Graham Haynes and singer
Cassandra Wilson _ worked on a communal sound that was easily
identifiable, mixing textures and jazz improvisation. And often
idiosyncratic improvisation: Coleman and Osby came up with a
distinct school of soloing, jagged and abstract and virtuosic, that
hadn't been heard before.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade some members have fallen away, others have
become stars, and Coleman and Osby have slipped into a bit of
popular neglect. But recently they have been recording powerful
albums and working on the conception, and at the Knitting Factory
on Thursday night, as part of the Texaco New York Jazz Festival,
they and Haynes put on mature shows that filled the Main Space with
enthusiastic fans.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman started the show with his trumpeter, Ralph Alessi,
playing against the bass of Anthony Tidd. The rest of the group,
with Jason Moran on piano and Sean Rickman on drums, joined in, and
for much of the set the music maintained a motoric, repeating
velocity that was harmonically vague. One can deal with the music's
coldness, its sameness, its emphasis on a textural hardness that
sometimes seems like a retreat from emotionalism, or one can't; it
still sounds like nothing else in music.
</P>
<P>
   And that coldness and lack of variety is its attraction:
Coleman's lines, with their lack of dynamic change, force a
listener to follow the music's contours, and by the end of the show
he had presented his case for a music of real complexity and
imagination. Osby, who followed, uses all sorts of groups and with
this one he backed himself with an acoustic trio.
</P>
<P>
   Osby's abilities are still surging forward, and he dipped
immediately into a stunning jazz seriousness with a set of tunes
that had his saxophone, liquid and sleek, making even the most
intricate lines swing. Where Coleman's music was rigid in its
industrial order, Osby's band made its material flexible, with
drummer Rodney Green changing volume and attack. Moran, a young,
promising pianist, improvised solos brimming with acidic ideas that
the group followed.
</P>
<P>
   The next set, by Graham Haynes, brought together DJs, videos and
Haynes' electronically reworked cornet. It ventured into the
freneticism of drum and bass, then went into funk and ambient dance
music, with ominous bass lines overlaid with noise and sound.
Haynes' cornet slit holes in the music, and with waves of echoing
sound he appeared in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   The night ended in the main space with an all-star group of M
Base musicians, including Coleman and Osby on saxophones, Haynes on
cornet and a rhythm section that included Moran, David Gilmore on
guitar, Tidd on bass and Rickman on drums. It was hard music,
positioned somewhere between pop and jazz, and its accommodations
sounded just fine, as if the movement no longer had to worry about
whether it had arrived. It was complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
