<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SCHEDULES ARGUMENTS ON PRIVILEGE IN LEWINSKY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following a suggestion from the Supreme Court, a
federal appeals court Friday set a quick schedule to consider the
privileges asserted by the Clinton administration to limit the
testimony of four government employees in the Monica Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
instructed the White House and the independent counsel to prepare
for oral arguments to be held during the week of June 29 over the
legal privilege that has been asserted to limit testimony of White
House deputy counsel Bruce Lindsey and June 26 for the privilege
claimed to block the testimony of three employees of the Secret
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has asserted that the questions asked of
Lindsey about conversations that he had with President Clinton and
other officials are protected by the attorney-client privilege. The
Secret Service has claimed that its employees should not be
questioned because any breach in White House confidences would make
it harder for agents to protect the president.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Supreme Court turned down a request by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr to quickly decide the issues
posed by the administration's appeal. In brushing aside Starr's
request, the court said that it expected the appeals court would
``proceed expeditiously.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district judge last month ruled that the attorney-client
privilege was outweighed by Starr's need for Lindsey's testimony.
The judge also ruled that there was no privilege that could be
invoked by the Secret Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
