<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSST, IT'S OK TO DUCK OUT OF THE OFFICE EARLY ON FRIDAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For the last couple of years, it's gotten pretty quiet
around here on Friday afternoons. After about 2 p.m., the phones in
the business news department stop ringing, the faxes stop coming
and there's a general sense of peace that invades what is typically
a fairly busy place during the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Glancing out the windows, you can see people fleeing work early
to get a start on the weekend. One banker was spotted practically
running from his office about 2 p.m. one Friday, carrying a duffel
bag for a weekend at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard week, said the banker, who, like many in this
column, wishes to remain anonymous. It's OK to duck out early, but
it's still not a good idea to advertise it.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more people seem to be working harder during the
rest of the week, leaving early on Friday has become the latest
perk for the management and professional classes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a way to prevent burnout, said Stephen Morel, general
manager of Pro Staff, a staffing company in Houston. Like many
staffing companies, Pro Staff is swamped with orders from clients
to find workers. Morel, who works long hours Monday through
Thursday overseeing the company's 22 offices, said he tries to
leave at midafternoon on Fridays to get in a game of golf or simply
go home to relax, and encourages the employees who report to him to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can work 10 hours every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stampede starts about 3 p.m., said Joe Ahmad, a Houston
lawyer who has watched the trend develop as the parking lot in his
downtown office building quickly empties on Friday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad speculates that the lawyers who populate his building are
leaving early because they're doing so well financially. They want
some time to enjoy themselves, he said, and ducking out early is a
way to take a breather.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving early _ especially if the boss is still at the office _
still feels a bit clandestine. It's like a freebie but it really
isn't, said a consultant who works for one of the big accounting
firms in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of shortened Fridays became institutionalized at
many oil companies when they began moving to a compressed work
schedule a few years ago. Many employees either get every other
Friday off or they work a half-day every Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As that practice becomes more common, it's getting harder for
people to find anyone connected to the energy industry at their
desks on a Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get so frustrated because I can't get hold of anyone,'' said
Shirley Barr, who owns a public relations firm. ``I figure, `What
the heck, I might as well take off, too,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By 3 p.m., Barr said, she is off running errands or at the
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll check my phone mail messages but seldom any clients
call,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Rivera said she finds she has to make a specific
appointment if she wants to schedule a Friday afternoon phone call.
Otherwise, forget it _ there is no chance Rivera, who teaches
people how to make presentations, will track someone down at 4 p.m.
on a Friday.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber stockbroker Tom Edwards stops making phone calls at
noon, and instead spends the afternoons getting paperwork done and
designing client portfolios. It seems to be worse in the summer
than the winter, said Edwards, who claims he rarely leaves early on
Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving work early is a practice largely confined to the
white-collar professional world such as finance. At industrial
plants, Fridays are like any other day.
</P>
<P>
   Leave early? asked Kirk Norris, the brewmaster at the
Anheuser-Busch plant in Houston, who seemed startled by the
question. It's a seven-day-a-week, 24-hour operation, he said.
There's no leaving early on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity in some circles of leaving early, many
managers still hate to be seen running to the parking lot with
briefcase in hand before the lunch crowd has dissipated for fear of
looking like a slacker. It's like the company that built a gym for
its managers but no one would be caught dead using it, said Bob
Dipboye, professor of psychology and administrative science at Rice
University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And there's always those who, as hard as they try, can't seem to
clear their desks early. At the advertising agency Bates Southwest,
most folks clear out by 1:30 p.m. on Friday during the summer. But
Chief Executive Jerry Kerr isn't one of the lucky ones. He said he
left early only three times last summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
