   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Prodded by the Supreme
Court, an appeals court panel agrees to consider whether President
Clinton's closest confidant and three Secret Service employees must
testify before a federal grand jury investigating an alleged
presidential affair and cover up. By JOHN C. HENRY. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-LIMITS (Washington) _ Republican leaders muster enough
support to pass a five-year $101 billion tax cut plan, but it is
hardly a victory for some GOP moderates concerned that making
deeper reductions in social programs to pay for the plan could hurt
lawmakers in an election year. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTING (Washington) _ Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, says
the House immigration subcommittee may hold a hearing next month
into the death of a young Texas man who was herding goats near the
Rio Grande. The man was shot dead by a Marine counter-narcotics
patrol a year ago. By GARY MARTIN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-MONEY (Washington) _ When she first ran for the Senate,
Kay Bailey Hutchison was heavily dependent on contributions from
Big Tobacco. But she has since kicked the habit, joining a number
of lawmakers trying to distance themselves from the industry. By
BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SUICIDE-RENO (Washington) _ Despite the Clinton Administration's
opposition to physician-assisted suicide, Attorney General Janet
Reno decides not to go after doctors in Oregon who aid in suicides
allowed by state law. She says there is no federal prohibition that
would block the Oregon law. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-REUNION (Washington) _ Survivors of the Holocaust hold
a reunion here this weekend to mark the 60th anniversary of the
transportation of nearly 10,000 Jewish children from Germany,
Austria, Czechoslovakia and Poland to Britain. The journey saved
the children, many of whom never saw their parents again, from the
Nazi death camps. By EUN LEE KOH. (Already filed)
</P>
