<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM PARTS WORKERS STRIKE; PRODUCTION COULD BE HALTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ In the town that launched General Motors as a
national icon, 3,400 workers at a GM metal stamping factory walked
off their jobs Friday waving American flags and hoisting green and
white cardboard picket signs, protesting what they called broken
promises about their job security.
</P>
<P>
   The work stoppage, called by the United Auto Workers, could halt
production at 17 of GM's 29 North American production factories
within a week. The metal factory builds fenders, hoods and steel
engine cradles, components critical to the assembly of many of GM's
bread-and-butter-light trucks and sport-utility vehicles, as well
as some cars.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides, which also faced such a tense labor showdown in
1997, when seven different strikes were staged at factories across
the country, were scheduled to head back to the bargaining table
Saturday morning. But even if a settlement were signed, GM and UAW
could be at odds again as early as Thursday, when 5,000 workers at
a nearby parts-making factory are scheduled to decide whether to
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The strike comes after weeks of negotiations over fears that GM
is scaling back a plan to equip the factory with $300 million in
new stamping machinery, leaders of UAW Local 659 said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation escalated over the Memorial Day weekend, when GM
quietly removed from the factory several large stamping dies that
press steel into various parts for its 1999 GMC Sierra, a full-size
pickup truck that industry experts expect to become one of GM most
profitable vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials said its investment plan for the factory, much of
which it contends is already under way, is contingent on the local
union honoring a series of promised work changes to help speed up
production rates. The company wants the flexibility to shift
workers without worrying about violating union job classifications
and to shed work that is not pivotal to vehicle production. A GM
spokesman said the equipment was removed to prevent the strike from
disrupting its upcoming truck launch.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers view the action as a direct threat to the factory's
future employment levels and say it underscores GM's refusal to
bargain in good faith.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They also say the company has already cut the factory's job
classifications to six from about 18. ``How are we supposed to
believe anything this company says when they sit at the bargain
table and tell us one thing, then at night sneak in and steal our
work right out from under us,'' said Lucy Matthew, a parts
inspector who has worked for GM for 15 years. ``It's been time for
the workers in Flint to send GM a message for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   GM employs 33,000 people at 18 different facilities in Flint,
more than in any other city in the country. In the late 1970s when
GM was still king of the auto industry, dominating more than 50
percent of the market, it employed 77,000 workers in Flint alone.
But as its market share declined, GM consolidated much of its
operations, eliminating more than 40,000 jobs here in the 1980s and
1990s. GM is slated to shut its Buick City large car assembly
factory in 1999. It employs 2,800.
</P>
<P>
   GM won't speculate on how quickly the strike will begin
affecting its other operations. But signs of the strike's other
toll were already beginning to surface all across this city of
140,761.
</P>
<P>
   The strike took center stage in conversations in Flint, which
was home to the automaker's founder and its first major assembly
operations but was cast as a victim of GM's corporate policies in
the documentary ``Roger and Me''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to downsize Flint right out of
business,'' said Aubrey Carter, a sales clerk. ``It used to be that
you could get fired from one plant in town and go get a job at
another in the same day. But over the last 10 years or so GM has
taken more jobs out of here than they bring in. A lot of good
people have left this town because of GM.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Anita Metevier believed GM would always be around to
be good to her family. Her father raised seven kids on a GM
paycheck. But in the 20 years that her husband has worked for GM,
she says the automaker's commitment to the city has declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM use to mean a stable future,'' said Mrs. Metevier, whose
husband works at the parts plant threatening to strike next week.
``But you can't count on that any more. No matter how loyal we are,
it's still doesn't seem enough to make them care about the families
they affect when they start talking about cutting jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Since talks of strikes started swirling around town three months
ago, Mrs. Metevier said she has been paying up credit bills and
stocking up on canned foods.'' With GM, you just never know what
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   GM says it remains committed to Flint and will invest $1.5
billion there through 2001, including a new $500 million engine
plant. ``We're not abandoning Flint, the UAW or the United states,
but we can't continue to be in businesses that are not
profitable,'' said a GM spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Pilipovich, owner of a used-car dealership and auto repair
shop, says his business slows virtually every time there is a rumor
of a strike. He estimates about two-thirds of his customers are GM
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM owns this town. People who don't even work for GM buy GM
just to be loyal,'' he said pumping gas into his 1993 GM Chevrolet
Lumina and straining to heard above throngs of honking horns in
support of nearby pickets. ``But it seems like they've turned their
back on us. The message their sending is real scary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
