u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-355&AMP;ADD-     06-05 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMAKERS SAY CRASH TESTS HAMPER DESIGNING SAFER VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ U.S., European and Japanese automakers said
at a conference here Friday that increasingly high-speed government
and insurance industry crash tests were preventing auto engineers
from designing sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and large cars
that would be less dangerous to other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry is under growing pressure to design sport
utility vehicles and other light trucks that would kill fewer
occupants of other vehicles. Light trucks _ a category that
includes pickup trucks and minivans as well as sport utility
vehicles _ are a third of the vehicles on the road but account for
half the traffic deaths, and their sales are growing rapidly. When
light trucks hit cars, 81 percent of the deaths are in the cars.
</P>
<P>
   Safety scientists from Detroit's Big Three automakers,
Daimler-Benz, Honda and a Japanese auto industry research
consortium all contended Friday that the recent trend toward crash
tests was forcing them to design vehicles with very stiff frames.
The latest government and insurance industry tests involve slamming
cars and light trucks into concrete barriers at speeds of up to 40
miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   At those speeds, the sheer weight of a big sport utility vehicle
or a very large car will tend to mash its passenger compartment
against the barrier _ unless the vehicle has a stiff frame to hold
everything in place, the auto industry representatives contended.
</P>
<P>
   But once a vehicle's frame has been stiffened to pass the crash
test, it poses more of a danger to other motorists, the auto
engineers said. Stiff vehicles tend to punch deeply into cars
during real-world collisions, increasing the risk of death or
injury for car occupants.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward high-speed crash tests requires automakers to
produce stiff designs for big vehicles that are less compatible in
crashes with smaller cars, said Falk Zeidler, a senior safety
engineer at Daimler-Benz. ``It is counterproductive for the
compatibility issue, especially for large cars'' and other big
family vehicles, he said at a conference here in this factory town
across the Detroit River from Detroit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The problem is particularly acute because sport utility vehicles
have become more luxurious over the last decade, as features like
leather seats and extra towing capacity have added half a ton to
the weight of the Chevrolet Suburban, for example. Federal
regulators say that some sport utility vehicles now have frames
that are five times as stiff as car frames.
</P>
<P>
   While federal regulators refused to discuss Friday the
automakers' complaints, people familiar with the regulators' plans
said in recent interviews that the federal government has been
considering ways to alter its tests.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is to slam a 3,000-pound barrier into each car,
instead of slamming cars into concrete barriers at 35 miles an
hour. A three-ton Suburban could stop a 3,000-pound barrier without
the stiff frame required by the current federal test.
</P>
<P>
   The moving barrier would also require Friday's small cars to be
built more sturdily. Sending a 2,000-pound subcompact into a
concrete barrier at 35 miles an hour is a fairly easy test because
there is not much weight in the subcompact to mash the passenger
compartment against the barrier. Requiring a subcompact to
withstand an impact by a 3,000-pound barrier would present more of
a challenge for engineers. But any actual change in federal test
procedures would likely require years of review.
</P>
<P>
   Any move to replace the current test could also leave drivers of
Suburbans feeling less confident about their survival prospects if
they ever did run into a bridge abutment or some other unyielding
surface. Insurance industry officials, who have begun issuing
safety ratings for family vehicles based on crash tests at 40 miles
per hour, insisted Friday that engineers should be able to design
even the heaviest vehicles to withstand high-speed impacts into
fixed barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian O'Neill, the president of the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety, a Washington-based group supported by insurers
seeking to reduce the cost of accident claims, said automakers
should be able to design vehicles with less rigid front ends that
crumple more in an accident, cushioning the force of the impact
while also reducing the damage to other vehicles. Only the
passenger compartment should be rigid, to reduce the likelihood
that the engine and other dangerous parts will intrude and hit
passengers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Lund, the institute's research director, said that the
hoods and front ends of big sport utility vehicles may need to be
longer, so that there is more metal available to be crumpled in a
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry research has also found that extremely stiff
vehicles can be less safe for their own occupants, particularly in
low-speed accidents. This is because more of the force of the
impact is transferred to the occupant instead of being absorbed by
the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. regulators originally labeled Friday's conference as the
Light Trucks and Vans Summit. But following complaints by the auto
industry that this suggested a showdown that might lead to new
regulations, the gathering ended up being named the International
Dialogue on Vehicle Compatibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2019EDT &QL; 
