<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6760 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STARR'S GUILT TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK RICH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that he's on a faster track, which we can only pray will
expedite the most extravagant investigation of a quickie sex act in
American history, you might think that Ken Starr has at last
regained his bearings. No more martyring of anybody's mother, no
more posing with garbage bags in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, alas, the independent counsel reverted to form by
making a speech so genuinely nutty it's hard to know which is more
amazing _ what he said, or the fact that his words escaped serious
scrutiny by a (you choose) bored or compliant press.
</P>
<P>
   The speech in question, delivered before lawyers in North
Carolina, was the one in which Starr implicitly likened himself to
Atticus Finch, the altruistic advocate for a wrongly accused black
man in Harper Lee's ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' and decried lawyers
who resemble Bruiser, the villain in John Grisham's ``The
Rainmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's literary parable was widely reported to be a sly attack
on President Clinton's lawyers, who, as the independent counsel put
it, ``try to concoct new privileges'' to thwart pursuit of the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   That charge is true enough. And yet a reading of the speech's
full text suggests that Starr, much like a criminal who
compulsively revisits the scene of a crime, was not so much out to
demonize the White House's legal stall artists as to indict himself
for his own legal whoring, for Big Tobacco. His thinly veiled
confession of sin might almost be construed as noble _ had it not
the bizarrely sadomasochistic quality of a self-flagellation.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Starr denounced legal ``hired guns,'' whom he
defined as ``greedy and unethical (lawyers) who hock their services
_ and indeed their morals _ to the highest bidder.'' Such lawyers,
he said, are ``indentured servants, rather than professionals'' _
because ``there are some things that a professional will not do for
money.'' He called on his peers to reclaim ``the moral high
ground'' by just saying no to clients who pay them fortunes to
``use their skills to impede the search for truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is Starr attacking most ferociously here? Whatever else is
to be said about Bill Clinton's lawyers, they're surely not
defending their now debt-ridden client for the money. Starr, by
contrast, has done exactly what he faults Grisham's villain for
doing, and did it while moonlighting on the government payroll: He
hocked his services to a high bidder whose main goal is to impede,
not further, the revelation of truth. In his case, that bidder was
Brown &AMP; Williamson _ a tobacco company much like the odious one in
another recent Grisham novel, ``The Runaway Jury,'' that he somehow
neglected to cite in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   What Big Tobacco got for the independent counsel's indentured
servitude was a Clintonesque attempt to use privilege to delay
justice. Starr was the lawyer who invoked attorney-client
privilege, however irrelevantly, before an appellate court in 1995
to further his client's efforts to intimidate and frustrate Henry
Waxman and Ron Wyden, who'd used a cache of Brown &AMP; Williamson
internal documents in their House investigation of the cigarette
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Starr lost the case. Had he won, he might have slowed or
derailed not just Congress' pursuit of that industry but state
tobacco litigation. The red-hot evidence Starr was trying to shield
with attorney-client privilege and other legal red herrings was not
of perjury about an alleged sex act but of a possibly criminal
conspiracy to destroy the health of millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown &AMP; Williamson documents suggested that the company had
known that nicotine was addictive since 1963 and had suppressed
research linking smoking to cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Starr really believes that if he finally does get to the
bottom of Monicagate, he'll be an American hero in the Gregory Peck
mold. But we don't have to wait another day to see that he already
fits the archetype of the Grisham heavy (Mickey Rourke in ``The
Rainmaker'') he deplores.
</P>
<P>
   What can't be explained, even by us armchair psychiatrists, is
what possessed the independent counsel to deliver a speech
trumpeting his guilt. Is he so blind to his own hypocrisy that he
didn't know what he was doing? Or is there an internal struggle
going on here that's more Robert Louis Stevenson than Harper Lee? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
