<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-SOLZHENITSYN-A     06-05 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SOLZHENITSYN-ART-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLZHENITSYN HAS FEW READERS IN THE NEW RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS toadd photo note)   (ART ADV.: a photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling 212
556-4204.) 
 (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ By the time the first copies of Alexander
Solzhenitsyn's latest book landed at a Moscow bookstore on
Thursday, its arrival had been heralded far and wide. Excerpts were
published in half a dozen newspapers, and there were announcements
on radio and television _ just the kind of fanfare that might be
expected for a work by the great Soviet dissident, Nobel Prize
winner and tireless defender of Russia's battered soul.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the advance publicity, the publication of ``Russia
in Collapse,'' a 204-page volume of apocalyptic musings about the
fate of the nation, begs a question that has dogged its 79-year-old
author since his return from exile four years ago: Who in Russia
today is prepared to read what Solzhenitsyn has to say?
</P>
<P>
   If the publisher's initial print run of 5,000 is any indication,
the answer is: not many, certainly far fewer than the millions of
readers who snapped up copies of Solzhenitsyn's classic, ``The
Gulag Archipelago,'' when it was finally printed here for the first
time in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is surprising is that such a famous, noted author would
put out a book in only 5,000 copies,'' said Roy Medvedev, another
Soviet-era dissident whose own book on Russian capitalism came out
last week, also in only 5,000 copies. ``What is striking is the
loss of interest in Solzhenitsyn on the part of Russian society.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet the phones were ringing all morning on Thursday at the
Russian Way bookstore _ a tidy, tiny haven of classical literature
on a street filled with features of the new Russia: beauty salons,
garish cafes, investment banks, currency-exchange booths.
Solzhenitsyn's loyal readers, many of whom share his alienation
from the culture around them, were calling in to ask when they
could come by and pick up their copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been waiting for days,'' said Nadezhda Ustelis, a
retired state bureaucrat, who walked out with a plastic bag stuffed
full of copies of the book ($1.40 in paperback, $2.20 in
hardcover). ``Friends and relatives from all over have asked me to
send copies, and I am sending the book to my grandsons, so they
will know our history.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday the publisher, Victor Moskvin, said, more than
2,000 copies had been sold and another printing of 5,000 is planned
next week. ``We are very happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Solzhenitsyn, who rarely gives interviews, has not personally
promoted the book, which is currently available only in Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Since his return in November 1994 after a 20-year exile, mainly
in Vermont, Solzhenitsyn has become one of the paradoxes of the new
Russia. Freed from the harsh Soviet censorship that made mere
possession of his books a criminal act, Solzhenitsyn _ more than
any other Russian writer or thinker _ has had ample opportunity to
address his public.
</P>
<P>
   He was host of a talk show on national television. He has
traveled the country, lecturing and listening to what people have
to say. His works have been published not only in select literary
journals but in Argumenti i Fakty, Russia's most popular newspaper,
with a readership of 3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our paper has always been interested in the opinions of
Alexander Isayevich,'' said Natalya Zhilnorova, assistant deputy
editor. ``We think they are very important and useful for Russia,
for our society. We consider him one of the geniuses of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet for all the reverence, Solzhenitsyn has been been unable
to connect with a broad audience, even though his gloomy assessment
of Russian society, government and culture is widely shared by
many. His talk show was canceled for lack of viewers, his trips go
largely unreported, and for all the prior notice, ``Russia in
Collapse'' has elicited little reaction of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks like a prophet, but who needs prophets when society
is changing every month, every day?'' Medvedev asked. ``The name
Solzhenitsyn allows him to be published in any newspaper, but that
does not mean he has readers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new book is a rambling collection of Solzhenitsyn's thoughts
and impressions about what he has seen and heard here over the last
four years. The picture he paints is relentlessly grim: a country
brought to its knees by the avarice and cowardice of its ruling
elite and by the West _ in particular the United States _ which has
wasted no time in taking advantage of Russia's weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Few leaders or institutions escape Solzhenitsyn's wrath. NATO
expansion, he writes, is a ``plot to exert pressure on Russia.''
Radio Liberty, the American-financed radio station that once
transmitted his works to Russian listeners, turned itself into
``something like a Chechen radio station'' during the two-year war
in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Even the International Monetary Fund _ a favorite bogeyman for
Russian nationalists _ is working against Russia's own interests,
Solzhenitsyn says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like slaves, we obey the program of the IMF _ either because
we are stupid or because we consciously put ourselves in somebody
else's hands,'' he writes. ``In 10 years we will sink to the level
of African countries, and already we are treated like one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians share Solzhenitsyn's bitterness, and according to
Medvedev, that may be one of the reasons so few are ready to hear
him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He criticizes the current regime, and for that reason neither
the authorities nor the West support him,'' Medvedev said. ``As for
ordinary people, the young and the disaffected, they see that his
criticisms are not as sharp as others'. His is general criticism,
without any new information. It is just a statement of fact: He is
against socialism, against capitalism, and he has no concept of
what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Vera Moseyeva, a retired clerk who remembers the first
book by Solzhenitsyn that she ever laid her hands on (it was almost
in tatters by the time it had been carefully and secretly passed to
her), it does not matter what he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he says is always interesting,'' she said, after
buying three copies of ``Russia in Collapse.'' ``He writes for the
people, and what he writes is very actual. Does he scold too much?
Given the way life is these days, how can one not be scolding?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
