<SLUG> BC-HOPE-ALIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HIS DEATH IS ANNOUNCED, BOB HOPE ENJOYS BREAKFAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Rep. Bob Stump, R-Ariz., announced the death
of Bob Hope Friday, he felt a sense of personal loss. Stump was a
homesick teen-ager in the Pacific Theater in World War II when the
comedian lifted his spirits with his stand-up comedy routine.
</P>
<P>
   So Stump was greatly relieved only minutes after his
announcement to learn that Hope, who turned 95 on May 29, was very
much alive.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press said it had caused the misunderstanding by
inadvertently displaying an advance obituary of Hope on its Web
site. Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the House Republican leader, saw
the obituary and handed it to Stump, asking him to announce the
death on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Stump was an obvious choice, since he had introduced the bill
that made Hope an honorary veteran. Many servicemen from World War
II to the Persian Gulf War recall Hope's morale-boosting
appearances. Stump closed his tribute, which was televised
nationally by C-Span, with the words, ``We're all going to miss
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But not yet. News organizations that reached Hope's California
home were told by his daughter Linda that Hope was enjoying his
breakfast. Armey apologized on the House floor for the
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Stump, who was a Navy medic, called Hope ``the best friend
anyone in uniform ever had.'' Stump spoke to Hope's daughter and
was relieved to find her ``not the least bit upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
