<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSOR NAMED TO LEAD CAMPAIGN FINANCE INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno announced Friday that
she has named a veteran federal prosecutor in New Hampshire to
succeed Charles Labella, a lawyer who is stepping down from the top
job in the Justice Department's campaign finance inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that David Vicinanzo, an assistant U.S. attorney,
would begin work this summer as Labella's deputy and will assume
control when Labella becomes interim U.S. attorney in San Diego in
August or September.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of who will head the inquiry has been a controversial
subject for Reno. Republican lawmakers have pressured her to seek
an independent prosecutor to investigate the matter, but she has
refused. She tried to reassure Congress by taking the case away
from prosecutors at the Justice Department's Public Integrity
Section and assigning it instead to Labella, a federal prosecutor
from outside Washington with an aggressive reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Under Labella, the inquiry gained momentum and in the last five
months, prosecutors have brought charges against Democratic
fund-raisers Johnny Chung, Charlie Trie and Maria Hsia. Recently,
prosecutors learned from Chung that an executive of a Chinese
aerospace firm with close ties to China's military contributed
funds to President Clinton's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers criticized Labella's departure, announced just
six months after he arrived. They suggested his resignation
represented a lack of commitment to investigate how the Democrats
financed the 1996 presidential re-election campaign. Reno's
announcement Friday suggested that Vicinanzo planned a longer
tenure and would move to Washington with his wife and seven sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
