u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-RIVALS-55     06-05 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-RIVALS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWELVE RIVALS FACE REAL QUIET AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are running, but they are not scared. Emboldened by doubts
regarding the ability of Real Quiet to sweep the Triple Crown,
rival trainers have entered 12 horses to face the hero of the
Kentucky Derby and the Preakness Stakes in Saturday's 130th Belmont
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers are more confident than the bettors, who are
expected to send Real Quiet off as a heavy favorite. He is the 6-5
favorite on Belmont Park's morning line, but a record number of
challengers are facing him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet follows 24 horses who previously captured both the
Kentucky Derby and the Preakness Stakes. Of those, 22 went on to
the Belmont Stakes. And none faced more challengers than Real
Quiet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fear him,'' the trainer James Bond, who sends out the
lightly raced Raffie's Majesty, said Friday morning at his barn at
Belmont Park. ``I think he's a nice horse, but I think he's
beatable. I'd be a fool not to think he's the horse to beat, but a
mile-and-one-half is uncharted water.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The challengers come from varied backgrounds, but they have the
same mission: to prevent Real Quiet from becoming the 12th Triple
Crown winner. Some of the challengers have faced Real Quiet in the
first two legs of the Triple Crown, and are hoping a change in
scenery will turn their fortunes. Others are hoping that the
Belmont's distance will trip Real Quiet, or that Real Quiet is
exhausted from his two previous victories, leaving him vulnerable
to a fresh newcomer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen how the Triple Crown takes a toll on a horse,'' said
Elliott Walden, the trainer of Victory Gallop, who has finished
second to Real Quiet in the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness.
``After the Preakness, Victory Gallop came out of his feed tub a
little and lost some weight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only Victory Gallop and the long-shot Basic Trainee have chased
Real Quiet in the first two legs of the Triple Crown. Chilito,
Hanuman Highway and Parade Ground ran in the Derby, skipped the
Preakness and have rejoined the party for the Belmont. Classic Cat
and Hot Wells bypassed the Derby, then ran in the Preakness and
continued on to the Belmont. Grand Slam, Limit Out, Raffie's
Majesty, Thomas Jo and Yarrow Brae ran in lesser races than the
Derby and the Preakness this spring and are making their Triple
Crown debuts in the Belmont. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Quiet is a game horse,'' Bond said. ``But the question
is, what has he run against? He ran better in the Preakness than
the Derby, but this is a whole different race now. The added
distance, a lot of horses back out of it that last half-mile. When
he gets to the top of the lane, he's got to run with my horse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be in this race if I didn't think he belonged,''
Bond said of Raffie's Majesty. ``I'm not running for second. Nobody
remembers who runs second. The only one they remember who ran
second is Alydar.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alydar finished second to Affirmed in all three legs of the
Triple Crown in 1978, the last time the Triple Crown was swept.
This year's Alydar is Victory Gallop, who lost the Derby by a
half-length, then was two-and-one-quarter lengths behind Real Quiet
in the Preakness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been close enough to Real Quiet that we think we can
beat him,'' Walden said. ``I feel like we're not that far off of
Real Quiet. We've got as good a shot to upset him as anyone
does.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet Victory Gallop will have to be fully recovered from an
infectious skin disease that has left unsightly patches on his
coat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a while to run its course,'' Walden said. ``On a scale
of 1 to 10, he had an 8. There aren't any patches in the area where
the saddle goes. It was all over his shoulder and his rump.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the Belmont figures to be demanding. Chilito, Basic
Trainee and two horses trained by D. Wayne Lukas _ Grand Slam and
Yarrow Brae _ all have sharp early speed. But at a mile-and-a-half,
the jockeys will need to remain patient, lest they waste their
chances by moving prematurely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to be really, really patient,'' said John
Velazquez, who rides Classic Cat. ``You don't know who will handle
the distance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of those challenging Real Quiet, Velazquez is among the most
respectful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't knock that horse,'' he said. ``I think he's the real
thing. He went around everybody in the Preakness. But I want to
beat him. I'm rooting for my horse. I don't care about history, the
Triple Crown. Real Quiet isn't putting food on my table.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
