<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOCCER TEAM SETS UP CAMP IN FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France _ The U.S. soccer team arrived in
the heart of the Beaujolais wine region Friday, setting up camp for
the World Cup in a 14th to 17th century chateau that has been
fitted with air-conditioning but still relies on roosters for alarm
clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by a 130-acre vineyard and a 75-acre oak forest, the
Chateau de Pizay, 25 miles north of Lyons, provides splendid if
tedious isolation from distraction as the Americans prepare for
their opener on June 15 against Germany in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   They are not the most famous Americans ever to stroll through
the magnificent gardens _ Hillary Clinton once visited the wine
cellars _ but they are one of 32 teams that will captivate the
planet over the next month in the world's most popular sporting
event.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks, geese, roosters and plainclothes police officers in
ill-fitting suits wandered about the estate, while gendarmes
strolled the perimeter, a reminder that even in this bucolic
setting, someone could choose to use the public stage of
international soccer to launch his own private terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd like to be closer to somewhere, but for our focus
this is an ideal place, a professional environment away from
everything, being awakened by roosters and cows,'' forward Roy
Wegerle said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the team will bivouac near the Arc de Triomphe in Paris,
and at an ocean resort on the Atlantic, but for now the players are
immersed in the culture of the verdant French countryside. At a
late-afternoon practice, local people set up a speaker in a window
and played the national anthem as the Americans prepared for a
light workout in the muggy heat. Tiny American flags were planted
near the stadium like beds of tulips, and young schoolchildren sat
and watched on the sidelines in what appeared to be rehearsed
jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   Guard dogs patrolled the outer fence of the stadium, and police
cars escorted the team bus, but the players who remembered their
stay at a military base in Italy for the 1990 World Cup said the
security here was sufficient without being overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Italy, every time we came to a corner, guys would start
waving their guns and pointing them,'' said Tab Ramos, who is
playing in his third World Cup. ``It was a lot more dramatic, as
you feel the Italians would be.''
</P>
<P>
   The next order of business for the team is a closed-door
scrimmage on Tuesday against Gueugnon, a team in the French
league's second division. Coach Steve Sampson still has two crucial
choices to make before the Germany game. He must find a starter on
the right wing in midfield and at striker in the 3-6-1 alignment
that features three defenders, six midfielders and one forward.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Hejduk, who has missed three exhibitions because of a
hamstring injury after an encouraging performance in a 3-0 victory
over Austria in April, will most likely see at least 45 minutes of
playing time in the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears that if he progresses sufficiently from
arthroscopic knee surgery two months ago, Eric Wynalda will be
favored ahead of Wegerle and Brian McBride at forward. Wynalda is
the career-leading scorer for the Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
