<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE'S SENATORS CITE COOPERATION IN FILLING JUDICIAL
VACANCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sens. Patty Murray and Slade Gorton have named a 12-member
bipartisan panel to screen would-be successors to U.S. District
Judge William Dwyer, who has delivered major decisions on Northwest
social, environmental and political issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slade and I will jointly interview the finalists they send us.
We will then jointly select, and jointly send a name to the White
House,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Selection of a successor to Dwyer, who wants to retire, will
complete a political dance in which Republican Gorton, Democrat
Murray and the White House have compromised and cooperated to fill
seven federal court vacancies in the Northwest and California.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said he expects to have all nominees to the bench, except
Dwyer's replacement, confirmed by the Senate before Congress'
scheduled adjournment at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are way ahead of other parts of the country in putting
together judicial appointments, despite the rancorous setting of
the U.S. Senate,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   The key has been a tradeoff in which Murray and the White House
gave Gorton a major voice in the selection of several judges, as
well as his own choice in filling one vacancy on a key federal
appellate court. Gorton had said he would block all judicial
confirmations in Washington state until he was able to help pick
judges.
</P>
<P>
   With a complicated agreement in place, a partisan logjam in
judicial confirmations by the Republican-run Senate has been
broken, at least in the Northwest. The breakdown of vacancies and
appointments includes:
</P>
<P>
   _Already confirmed: The Senate has approved Seattle trial lawyer
M. Margaret McKeown to the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, and
Pasco lawyer Ed Shea to the U.S. District Court bench in Yakima.
</P>
<P>
   McKeown and Shea were recommended by Murray. The 9th Circuit is
based in San Francisco, but five of its 28 judges sit in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   _Nominated and pending: With Gorton playing a significant role,
Clinton nominated Seattle attorney Ron Gould to the 9th Circuit,
and King County Superior Court Judge Robert Lasnik to the U.S.
District Court bench in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, the president has followed the
Constitution and asked for the Senate's advice as well as consent.
In my view, these nominees are entitled to consent by the Senate,''
Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gould and Lasnik are expected to be confirmed by the Senate
without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   _Pending and Controversial: In a complicated deal between Gorton
and White House counsel Charles Ruff, the Senate is expected to
vote soon on the long-delayed confirmation of University of
California law professor William Fletcher to the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher would take a San Francisco-based seat on the court. His
mother, Betty Fletcher, a 9th Circuit judge based in Seattle, would
retire.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would then nominate Washington State Supreme
Court Justice Barbara Durham, a candidate picked by Gorton, to
Betty Fletcher's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mixture of these appointments means the ideological
balance on the court will not be changed,'' Gorton said. The 9th
Circuit is closely divided between moderate and liberal judges
appointed by Presidents Clinton and Carter, and several outspoken
conservatives elevated to the bench by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   _The Dwyer vacancy: The committee to screen Dwyer's potential
successors will be co-chaired by Jenny Durkan, a Democrat prominent
Seattle trial lawyer, and former U.S. attorney Mike McKay, a
Republican active in George Bush's 1988 campaign. It is equally
divided between Murray and Gorton appointees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't put a definite timetable on the selection panel,
but they understand the need to get it done quickly because Dwyer
wants to get off the bench,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer has carried a full case load despite suffering from
Parkinson's Disease and back problems.
</P>
<P>
   After being screened, interviewed by the senators and
recommended to the White House, whoever is tapped as Dwyer's
successor must still undergo an extensive FBI background check.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmation of Dwyer's successor will probably come after the
next Congress convenes in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
