<HEADLINE>
BOY, 11, CONVICTED IN SEXUAL ASSAULT GETS 10 YEARS IN YOUTH
FACILITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ An 11-year-old boy who beat and sexually assaulted a
3-year-old girl was sentenced to 10 years in a Texas Youth
Commission facility Friday by a jury that apparently rejected the
notion that he should be treated as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence means that the boy, who could have received a
40-year sentence, will be released by the time he is 21.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Hal Gaither, a critic of trying pre-teen offenders as
adults, praised the jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demagogues in the Legislature want to try 10- and
11-year-olds as adults,'' he told the panel after he read its
verdict. ``You have sent a message that the adult system is not
where these young people belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Although defense attorney Garry Cantrell urged the jury to give
the child probation, the boy's father, who is on probation himself
for a drug conviction, apparently was satisfied with his son's
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' he said, smiling as he left the courtroom. ``I
never expected probation.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy was found guilty Thursday of two counts of aggravated
sexual assault and one count of injury to a child. Police said he
and two brothers, ages 7 and 8, beat the young girl with a brick
and molested her last April 9 after she followed them to a creek
bottom in West Dallas. By law, the brothers could not be charged
with a crime because they are under age 10.
</P>
<P>
   A string of prosecution witnesses, including psychologists for
the Dallas Juvenile Department and the Dallas Public Schools, had
testified that the older boy had acute behavioral problems and
would require lengthy sex offender treatment and counseling for his
anger and aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster has been a special education student since he
entered the first grade in 1995, and testimony indicated that he
has an I.Q. in the 64-74 range.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roderick Snead, a psychologist with the Dallas school
district, said the boy has ``borderline intellectual functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   There was testimony that he threatened teachers and yelled at
them, disrupted classes and fought with other children.
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell called several friends of the boy's family, who
testified that he was ``normal'' and did not display aggressive or
violent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, his mother concurred. On the witness stand,
she described her son as ``a good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, prosecutor Gina Savage did not request a
specific sentence, but urged the jury to assesses a punishment
``sufficient to protect Dallas County.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell was more impassioned in his plea. ``No matter how big a
monster you try to make (him) out to be, he is still a little
boy,'' he said. ``No matter what you say about TYC, it is a bad
thing. It is still a jail. Do not throw away the life of this
11-year-old boy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the sentence was read, Cantrell said, ``It was a good
outcome. It says that at some point he won't be treated as an adult
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
