<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   Faster Than a Speeding Mechanical Elephant on a Forklift
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England raised interest rates by a quarter-point to
slow the economy so the Labor government of Prime Minister Tony
Blair could finally hit its inflation target. The repo rate, the
lowest rate at which the central bank lends money to commercial
banks, was raised to 7.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   London stock prices plunged on the news, amid fears that higher
interest rates would raise the value of the pound, making British
exports even less competitive in global markets. The elephant, by
the way, was built in 1940, has a top speed of 6 miles an hour and
is for sale for $160,000. It was being delivered to an art and
antiques fair in London.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Advil Meets Nutra Sweet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the largest deal ever in the pharmaceutical industry, the
American Home Products Corp. said it would acquire the Monsanto Co.
for $34.4 billion in stock. The combined company would be the
nation's top seller of prescription drugs and a world leader in
insecticides and other agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   Its brands would include Advil painkiller, Centrum vitamins and
Nutra Sweet sugar substitute. The acquisition would allow American
Home Products to double research spending, and would also cover its
legal liabilities from two diet drugs that have been taken off the
market. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE COUNTY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gambling Without Casinos &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. agreed to pay $400 million to Orange County,
Calif., in a legal settlement that will largely close the book on
the largest municipal bankruptcy in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is by far the largest so far stemming from the
1994 Orange County bankruptcy, which created a morass of litigation
as the county sought to recover some of the more than $1.6 billion
it suffered in losses from risky investments.
</P>
<P>
   The county still has lawsuits pending against more than a dozen
Wall Street securities houses and a variety of other companies. But
Merrill Lynch was clearly the county's main target, since it was
much more heavily involved than other companies in selling risky
derivatives to the county-run investment pool.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Up, Up and, for Some, Away &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new single-family homes rose 5.2 percent in April to a
record, and the Conference Board, a private research group, said
its index of leading economic indicators rose 0.1 percent in April
_ the fourth consecutive monthly increase. The index has not
declined since April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, construction spending rose 0.8 percent in April, the
fifth consecutive monthly gain. Factory orders rose 1.2 percent,
the biggest increase in five months.
</P>
<P>
   On a less upbeat note, the productivity of workers continued to
grow, but more slowly. And on a downright sour note, Americans
filed nearly 342,000 personal bankruptcy petitions in the first
quarter, up 6 percent from the period a year earlier, according to
a lending industry group. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   VEHICLES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pedal to the Metal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nation's auto industry reported that May was the best month
for car and truck sales since September 1986, with sales totaling
1.51 million cars and trucks, a 12.1 percent increase from the
corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, fueled by hefty discounts, the seasonally adjusted
annual selling rate for light vehicles reached 16.3 million cars
and trucks last month, the highest since October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Lower gasoline prices have worked in Detroit's favor: The
average price for regular gasoline at the pump decreased slightly
last week, to $1.066 a gallon. It was about $1.22 a year ago. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARMS RACE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Nuclear Balance Sheet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within a week of Pakistan's detonation of a sixth nuclear
device, India increased its military budget by 14 percent, pushing
total arms outlays to 19 percent of all government spending.
</P>
<P>
   But even before India's action, The Nation magazine raised an
interesting possibility: Is India using the arms race as a means of
bankrupting its rival? A Princeton physicist and expert on the
Pakistani nuclear program, Zia Mian, says India is much less
dependent than Pakistan on the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's also warned recently that it might cut both
nations' credit ratings. That, The Nation contended, would hurt
Pakistan more than India. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flipper's Revenge &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd., the world's second-largest cruise
line, agreed to plead guilty to federal charges of dumping oil at
sea, lying to the Coast Guard about the discharges and tampering
with witnesses and evidence, and as a result would pay $9 million
in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The practice saved tens of thousands of dollars a year per ship,
the company said. In court, prosecutors said some officers had
received bonuses for cutting operating costs. The offenses covered
by the agreement occurred from 1990 to 1994, while Royal
Caribbean's stewards and deckhands wore buttons that said ``Save
the Waves'' and urged passengers not to bring on deck any paper
goods or other objects that might blow overboard. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEVERAGES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bubbling Over? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In what could become France's biggest wine scandal in decades,
one of Bordeaux's most prestigious wine properties, Chateau
Giscours, has been charged with fraudulent winemaking practices.
</P>
<P>
   According to the charges, cheap wine from another district was
added to the chateau's, wine from two vintages was blended
together, excess sugar was added to the wine to raise the alcohol
content (sacre bleu!), and wood chips were used to give some of the
chateau's wine the taste and smell of wine that had been aged in
oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Giscours, one of the largest estates in the Medoc, was one of
the 61 chateaus _ out of thousands in Bordeaux _ that were included
in the 1855 classification that remains the standard by which
prestige Bordeaux wines are known. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOBS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor Blues &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Inc. announced that it would eliminate 15,000 jobs, or
10 percent of its work force, and take a $1.95 billion charge
against second-quarter earnings, the strongest indicator yet of
tough times in the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   The company also warned Wall Street that it would report an
operating loss for the second quarter, its first plunge into the
red since the semiconductor industry slump of 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Other high-technology companies have also announced cutbacks:
National Semiconductor plans to lay off 1,400 people; Intel, the
world's biggest chip maker, expects to eliminate 3,000 jobs through
attrition, and Applied Materials, the biggest supplier of
chip-making equipment, is offering voluntary severance packages to
cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   For the economy as a whole, the unemployment rate was unchanged
in May, at 4.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
