<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOTHA-TRIAL-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUTU ASKS BOTHA TO GIVE AN APOLOGY, BUT IN VAIN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE, South Africa _ There were times during Archbishop
Desmond Tutu's two days of testimony that ended Friday when the
head of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission looked weary and
times when he seemed unable to hold back sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   When a lawyer for former President P.W. Botha suggested the
commission was biased because some members believed former
government officials engineered atrocities, the archbishop looked
incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you live?'' he asked. ``I live in South Africa. ``
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the questioning, lawyers for Botha tried to put the
commission on trial, though he is the one facing contempt charges
for refusing to appear before the panel. Over and over, the lawyers
disputed the open-mindedness of the commissioners and suggested
there was no need for Botha's appearance because he had answered
questions in writing. The only purpose in calling him, they said,
was to humiliate him.
</P>
<P>
   Under the relentless questioning, the archbishop insisted that
the commission was trying to be fair. It had been patient with
Botha, he said, by waiting nearly a year for his written responses
and had intervened to get the government to help with his legal
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Botha, 82, were serious, the archbishop
said, and the questions needed to be answered in a setting that
allowed follow-up questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were tortured.'' the archbishop said. ``People were
abducted. People disappeared. And that didn't happen in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   As the showdown came to an end, however, and the archbishop was
told he could step down, he hesitated. Ignoring court protocol, he
turned to Botha and asked him to apologize for the pain apartheid
had caused, even if he never intended it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to appeal to him,'' the archbishop said, ``to take this
chance provided by this court to say he may not have intended the
suffering to happen to people, he may not have given orders to
authorize anything. But if Botha was able to say that `I am sorry
that policies of my government caused you pain' _ just that, that
would be such a tremendous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When his plea was met by silence, the archbishop tried once
more. ``I appeal to him,'' he whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, who has shown little emotion since the trial resumed on
Monday and has usually left the courtroom quickly, appeared
agitated by the archbishop's remarks. At one point, he seemed ready
to speak to reporters, but his daughter intervened.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, though, when a reporter called out a
question to him, he came forward and in a characteristically
defiant tone, told the assembled journalists to go read a number of
books about him, including his biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing more to say,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, who led South Africa from 1978 to 1989 during some of the
most brutal years of white minority rule, has steadfastly refused
to apologize for apartheid, saying he will answer only to God. He
has called the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, set up to
investigate the nation's violent past, a ``circus.''
</P>
<P>
   He is on trial for ignoring three subpoenas to testify before
the commission, which has heard evidence from former members of his
Cabinet that Botha himself order the bombing of a church building
in 1988 as well as raids against apartheid activists outside the
country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Botha has had a stroke and recent hip replacement surgery, and
to persuade him to testify voluntarily, the panel has offered to
let him appear in a closed-door hearing here in this vacation
resort near where he lives in retirement. He refused.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Tutu's testimony Friday, the trial was adjourned
for 10 days, when closing arguments are expected. If convicted,
Botha faces up to two years in prison and a fine. If Botha hoped to
avoid the spectacle of an appearance before the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, he has hardly done any better in the
courts. The judge in the case, Victor Lugaju, has done little to
restrain the proceedings, giving both the prosecution and defense
wide latitude to make their cases.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution forced Botha to sit through accounts of the
bombing of the church building. It also called a bitter former
police colonel to the stand who called Botha a coward for not
acknowledging that the colonel and others were following orders
when they killed and tortured anti-apartheid activists.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing his testimony, Tutu said that even if there was
no conviction, the trial had served to make Botha accountable for
the past. ``The thing that we sought, we got in a different way,''
Tutu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
