<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-RATINGS-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMERTIME, AND THE DRIVING IS BREEZY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is around the corner, and the forecast, thanks to El
Nino, is for a dry, sunny season _ ideal conditions for open-air
motoring.
</P>
<P>
   Some three dozen open-top car models are currently available in
the United States, at prices of $20,000 to $350,000. And while
low-end models continue to fade away for lack of interest _ the
Honda Civic del Sol and Toyota Paseo are among this year's
casualties _ fancy droptops are being added. Among these are the
Volvo C70, which goes on sale next month, and the Mercedes-Benz CLK
Cabriolet, due this fall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a rundown of the topless cars on sale this summer,
excluding a number of sport utility vehicles _ like the Chevrolet
Tracker, Isuzu Amigo, Jeep Wrangler, Kia Sportage and Suzuki Vitara
_ that also have roofs that come down or come off. Prices are for
base models; luxury and gas-guzzler taxes are not included.
</P>
<P>
   ACURA NSX-T $88,782. Mid-engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NSX-T is lightning-quick, thanks to its very light aluminum
body, its wind-slicing profile and its V6 engines that use Formula
One racing technology. Indeed, since it is built to Honda's
exacting standards, the NSX has been criticized for being too
perfect _ a trouble-free appliance that thinks it's a Ferrari.
Still, it is a pleasant and reliable exotic car that can be driven
every day. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASTON MARTIN DB7 Volante, $141,600. Front engine, rear drive; 4
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The DB7's road manners cannot be faulted, and the supercharged
V8 is capable of pushing the two-ton grand touring car from zero to
60 in a mere 6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But what really separates this elite convertible from the pack
is aesthetics: the lithe swoop of the fenders, the mirror-like
paint job, the aromatic leather, the faultless walnut trim. Too bad
the DB7 costs twice as much as the rather similar Jaguar XK8. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUDI CABRIOLET $35,100. Premium, $38,800. Front engine, front
drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its superclean styling still looks fresh, but the Cabriolet is
the last of the previous-generation cars in Audi's lineup. Because
its V6 doesn't meet stricter pollution standards, the '98 is not
available in California, Connecticut, Massachusetts or New York. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BENTLEY AZURE $339,900. Front engine, rear drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All you really need to know about the Azure is its price. With
only 93 sold last year, you'll surely have the only one on the
block. It will get you a good table at Spago and will win you
respect from Hollywood's toughest critics: valet parking
attendants. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW 3-SERIES 323i, $34,700; 328i, $41,500; M3, $45,900. Front
engine, rear drive 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In all of its many body and drive-train configurations, the
3-Series was a benchmark when it was remade for 1992, and it
remains one of the world's most pleasurable cars for everyday
driving. Exceptionally rigid for a convertible, it handles
brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   New this year is the 6-cylinder 323i, which replaces the
4-cylinder 318i, and a convertible version of the legendary,
high-performance M3. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW Z3 1.9, $29,995; 2.8, $36,470. M Roadster, $42,770. Front
engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The M Roadster promises a high-octane fix for the Z3's
shortcomings. For while the voluptuous body grabs attention, the
car's performance hasn't matched its appearance _ especially the
wimpy, buzzy 4-cylinder 1.8. And the Z3, built in South Carolina,
lacks BMW's usual refinement. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CAVALIER Z24 $19,910. Front engine, front drive; 4
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A small package with reasonable accommodations for at least two
people and some luggage, the Cavalier has a family resemblance to
its big brother, the Camaro. The interior is attractive and
functional, although the hard, unsupportive seats make long trips
unpleasant. The 4-cylinder engine is adequate, and the handling is
good. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CAMARO V6, $22,650; Z28, $27,975. Front engine, rear
drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Camaro and its Pontiac counterpart, the Firebird,
may be living on borrowed time. The 30-year-old muscle car formula
_ raw power, reasonable price _ has lost its magic in an era of
high insurance rates and sport-utility mania. The Camaro still
performs, but it feels dated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CORVETTE $44,990. Front engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The classic nameplate was saved from General Motors' budget
cutters to be reborn as the best 'Vette ever. While some
aficionados dislike styling touches seemingly borrowed from Acura,
there is little grousing about the performance of the
345-horsepower V8 _ or about the newly accommodating interior and a
trunk that can hold golf bags. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER SEBRING JX, $21,235; JXi, $26,500. Front engine, front
drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's best-selling convertible is built in Mexico and has
little in common with the Mitsubishi-built coupe of the same name.
Spacious, stylish and comfortable, the Sebring offers good value.
It also has a rarity among convertibles: a back seat big enough for
two adults. But order the JXi V6; the 4-cylinder JX is
overwhelmed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DODGE VIPER RT/10 $64,700. Front engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only in America! No other country could produce such a bold,
aggressive, over-the-top car _ the whopping 8-liter V10 engine
produces an awesome 450 horsepower. But the performance is
American-brutal, not European-refined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FERRARI F355 SPIDER $138,115. Front engine, rear drive; 2
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari's V12's get the attention, but for enduring driving
pleasure it's hard to beat the smaller, lighter F355, with its V8
just in front of the rear wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Ferraris, this one requires getting used to. The manual
gearbox is balky; the cockpit is cramped for 6-footers. And judged
purely by the numbers, it performs no better than a Porsche or
Corvette. But for those hooked on the wheel's rock-solid feel and
the engine's sensual howl, there is no substitute. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORD MUSTANG $21,175; GT, $24,675; Cobra, $29,035. Front engine,
rear drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The original pony car will be revamped next year, and it may
eventually stand alone in this shrinking market. Still, the Mustang
has enjoyed a slight resurgence in sales, and it comes in versions
from plain (3.8-liter V6) to muscular (4.6-liter V8). Each offers a
lot of performance for the price. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAGUAR XK8 $70,480. Front engine, rear drive; 4 seats.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With its lean body, ground-hugging profile and long hood, the
XK8 is, quite simply, a ravishing beauty. Inside, the sumptuous
cabin sets standards. And the 4-liter, 290-horsepower V8 is smooth
and powerful. Except for the price, what's not to like? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAMBORGHINI DIABLO ROADSTER VT $284,000. Mid-engine, all-wheel
drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wedge silhouette, angular lines and side air intakes give
the Diablo the aggressive look of a Formula One race car, and with
a 492-horsepower V12 it nearly performs like one. Alas, with a
price so high, few will ever have the experience. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAZDA MX-5 MIATA $20,220. Front engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first Miata revived the moribund roadster market, and its
many fans held their breath when Mazda announced a redesign.
They're breathing easier now, because the qualities that made the
car shine _ its light weight, its agility, the growl of its eager
4-cylinder engine _ have been made better.
</P>
<P>
   The styling remains simple and timeless, and there is 140
horsepower, up from 133. So nimble it feels like an extension of
the driver, the Miata may offer more fun per dollar than anything
else on the road. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ SLK230 $40,295. Front engine, rear drive; 2 seats.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quiet and weatherproof, with a hard top that draws a crowd when
it retracts into the trunk, the SLK pleases baby boomers nostalgic
for the SL roadsters of the 50s. The interior is packed with retro
touches like white gauges trimmed in chrome. The supercharged
4-cylinder is economical and fairly peppy, but the overall effect
is more luxurious than sporty. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ SL SL500, $80,495; SL600, $125,595. Front engine,
rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along with the S-Class sedans, which will be replaced next year,
the SL roadsters are the last remnants of the ``old''
Mercedes-Benz: very expensive, very solid and just a bit uptight,
without the youthful feel of newer Mercedes models or the glamour
of, say, an XK8.
</P>
<P>
   Still, SLs are extremely refined, technologically advanced and
socially impressive. No wonder movie stars drive them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI ECLIPSE SPYDER GS, $21,850; GS-T, $27,080. Front
engine, front drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A car long on pizazz but short on practicality, the Spyder has a
futuristic look and, with the GS-T's turbo version of the in-line
4-cylinder, spirited performance. Indeed, with so much power
running through the front wheels, the driver must pay attention to
keep the car on track. The back seat is not just tight _ it is
virtually unusable. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH PROWLER $40,000. Front engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see and be seen, hardly anything gets more stares
than this nouveau street rod. The Prowler could scarcely be more
impractical _ there's no place to put anything _ and the
standard-issue V6 is nothing special. But the Prowler is built for
cruising, not commuting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC SUNFIRE SE, $19,995. Front engine, front drive; 4
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sunfire packs the flashy styling and gutsy performance of
Pontiac's larger cars into a small, reasonably priced package.
Although it is a near-twin of the Chevy Cavalier, the Sunfire's
look is inspired by the Firebird. The ride is characteristically
Pontiac: firm, but not stiff. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC FIREBIRD $24,830; Trans Am, $30,240. Front engine, rear
drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like their Camaro counterparts, Pontiac's pony cars offer power
and performance at an attractive price. But the Firebird goes
further, with bold, outrageous styling. Like the Camaro, the car
has a shrinking market, and its future is uncertain. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORSCHE BOXSTER $41,765. Mid-engine, rear drive; 2 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Boxster's proportions and bulging fenders mimic Porsches of
the past, but many of the touches _ like fan-shaped mirrors and
cat's-eye buttons _ are thoroughly modern. No speed demon, the
Boxster offers a nearly perfect balance of power and knife-sharp
handling. It is a joy to drive at any speed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORSCHE CARRERA CABRIOLET $81,745. Rear engine, rear drive; 2
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like the other all-new 911s, the Cabriolet is a rear-engine
rocket ship that coddles occupants with luxury appointments and
electronic gadgets. Space is well used, with rear jump seats that
fold for more storage.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAAB 9-3 $37,050; SE, $42,050. Front engine, front drive; 4
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the well-made, tight-fitting insulated top is up, it's easy
to forget you're in a convertible, and two adults can fit
reasonably well in the back. With Saab's traditional road-hugging
qualities, the 1999 9-3 is fun to drive, and the 185-horsepower
turbo-charged 4 has plenty of punch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VOLKSWAGEN CABRIO $18,475; GLS, $22,790. Front engine, front
drive; 4 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A perennial favorite of young women, the Cabrio remains a fun
and functional convertible _ and its back seat can actually
accommodate passengers. But they'd better travel light: A picnic
lunch is about all that will fit in the trunk. This is the last
season for the current Cabrio; it gets a makeover before next
summer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO C70 $44,000 (estimated). Front engine, front drive; 4
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volvo's first convertible since 1956 goes on sale next month,
and, no, it doesn't look like a box without a top. The styling is
sleek and the appointments are elegant, but the C70 shows Volvo's
usual attention to safety, including roll bars that pop up behind
the rear headrests. The turbo 5-cylinder is spirited, but the car's
handling is uninspired.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to this report were Michelle Krebs, James G. Cobb,
Peter Passell, Fred Brock and Keith Martin. &QL;
</P>
