<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN--FRENCH-HNS &LR;      06-05 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--FRENCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men's final features all-Spanish flavor
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ It will be Spaniard vs. Spaniard, good guy vs. good guy and
amigo vs. amigo in the French Open men's final Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The match between Carlos Moya and Alex Corretja will sorely lack
variety, not to mention drama-inducing antipathy, but it figures to
compensate with a furious outpouring of hugs, handshakes and
all-around warm fuzzies.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the late '60s, when the hail-fellow-well-met,
all-for-one-and-one-for-all Australians dominated Roland Garros,
has there been more mutual respect, closeness and affection between
the two combatants for tennis' most important clay-court prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful,'' Corretja said Friday after he made toast
of the toast of Paris, Frenchman Cedric Pioline, 6-3, 6-4, 6-2.
``Maybe we will have dinner together before. Carlos and I will be
friends if I win, or if he wins. We will find our game on the
court, but then we should make a big party together afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But not abnormal, either. Four years ago, Spaniards Sergi
Bruguera and Alberto Berasategui met for the French title,
announcing to the world that Spain would have to be reckoned with
in Paris, and maybe elsewhere, in years to come. There's no arguing
for now which nation rules the terre battue.
</P>
<P>
   And half of today's women's final is also Spanish. Twice
champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario plays thrice champion Monica
Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Moya, seeded 12th to Corretja's 14th, overcame countryman Felix
Mantilla's strong start to claim the first men's semi 5-7, 6-2,
6-4, 6-2. But if they held a playoff for third place, it's likely
Mantilla would make short work of Pioline, the 28-year-old from
nearby Neuilly-sur-Seine who, despite a largely underwhelming
career, has been a runner-up at Wimbledon and the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold this tournament here, in France,'' Pioline said, ``but
the Spanish are the best on clay. They are born and bred on it, and
you see the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Unseeded and outnumbered three to one in the semifinals by the
Iberian invasion, Pioline had battled through three five-set
matches en route to his encounter with the light-footed Corretja,
leaving him with dead legs and a weary brain. He wanted to defend
the national honor _ a standing-room-only crowd surrounded Court
Central to watch him try _ but he was unable to mount another
inspirational fight.
</P>
<P>
   He got ahead of Corretja in six of the Spaniard's service games
in a row and reached break point five times during one stretch yet
failed to convert any of them. Despite hitting just 43 percent of
his first serves, Corretja won 76 percent of his first-serve points
and never was broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't fast enough today to upset Alex,'' Pioline said. ``He
really played very, very well. I wanted very bad to go to the
final, but I didn't have enough left in me. When you're tired,
you're not as focused and you make bad decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've lost, you can always say `if, if, if.' I had my
chances. It's true, I suppose, that I could probably work on
improving my fitness.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15th-seeded Mantilla, who had dropped only two sets in five
previous rounds, had no reason to be fatigued, yet his focus and
shot selection also went into a steep decline as the match wore on
and he wore down.
</P>
<P>
   Mantilla had won five tournaments in 1997 to establish himself
as a player to be taken seriously, but he had slumped this year
before his timely run at Roland Garros. And until the middle of the
third set against Moya, you had to believe his chances of reaching
his first Grand Slam final remained at least 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, nothing. He lost his touch, his serve and
perhaps his nerve.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-1 lead evaporated in a few short minutes as Moya reeled off
seven games in a row, breaking twice at love, for a 2-1 set
advantage, and breaking again to start the fourth set. Another
break in the seventh game left Mantilla in the dirt, and Moya
secured the victory by rallying from a jitters-induced 15-40
deficit in the final game.
</P>
<P>
   Moya, 21, had been a surprise as a finalist in the Australian
Open against Pete Sampras in 1997. Here, he was far less of a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to lose in the final again,'' he said. ``I want
to be the winner, no matter who I play.''
</P>
<P>
   He easily defeated Corretja in the Monte Carlo quarterfinals in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I came here, I said I had good feelings, good
vibrations,'' Moya said. ``I don't say that if I don't feel it. I
don't fake.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked how he might react to facing Corretja again, with
far greater stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get on the court, you fight like crazy,'' Moya said.
``You run; you do everything; you try to step on him if necessary.
But it is always difficult to play against a friend. We know each
other so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Since neither player has won a major, the 39th different Slam
champion of the Open era will be crowned Sunday _ and the fifth
Spaniard. Bruguera had ended Spain's 21-year drought by winning
back-to-back at Roland Garros in 1993-94. France's only winner of a
major during the Open era, meanwhile, has been Yannick Noah here in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Noah was also the lone net-rushing player to have prevailed
since the golden age of the Aussies.
</P>
<P>
   Presumed to be a bygone age until now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
