A6825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      06-05 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   New WTA head &QL; 
relishes challenge
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ He had sought, and found, a slower track in rural Oregon,
near Bend. His wife would run the family horse farm. He would teach
a law class and play the role of gentleman rancher.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York City, fast-lane educated at Princeton and
Columbia and an 18-year veteran of the Washington, D.C., legal
whirl, Bartlett H. McGuire was ready, he thought, for a simple
regimen. He wanted to be where he could be just Bart, leading a
life of mainly leisure while pursuing his passions, squash and
tennis prominent among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they say,'' he noted, ``even if you win the rat race,
you're still a rat.''
</P>
<P>
   But guess who's back running with the rodents.
</P>
<P>
   In January, after an exhausting yearlong search for a CEO
resulted in the hiring of a guy who quit about 10 minutes after he
saw what he had gotten into, the Women's Tennis Association turned
its bloodshot eyes to McGuire, the WTA's legal consultant for the
previous decade. He decided it was his obligation to step into the
breach and help _ my words, not his _ save the organization from
itself. McGuire, who stands guilty of being noble or dumb, bid his
pastoral environs adieu and agreed to a two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, Bend. Hello, Stamford, Conn. Goodbye, horses. Hello,
rats.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire an able diplomat
</P>
<P>
   Tough job, this. The WTA has more warring factions than the
Balkans. Anne Person Worcester, the last boss, fought the good
fight for four years but left to have a baby, figuring childbirth
would be infinitely less painful.
</P>
<P>
   Why did it take a year to hook a replacement? Because a
unanimous vote by the board of directors was required, and roughly
half the board members wanted the post. Rick Carson of the PGA Tour
finally was chosen in a hard-won compromise, but once he got a look
at the morass, he quickly fled back to the safety of men's golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``An embarrassing situation,'' McGuire called it. ``I really
felt sorry for women's tennis because the product itself was
potentially so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its governing body being in near chaos, hamstrung by
conflicting interests, self-serving directors and no shortage of
petulant players screaming, ``Me! Me! Me!''
</P>
<P>
   But when McGuire took charge, he did so with his eyes open. He
accepted the posting on his terms, and he made everyone aware of
those terms. It would be his way or the highway _ for him. But to
date, things have gone swimmingly. He says the WTA, not
International Management Group or anybody else, is running women's
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   And he insists he's having ``a wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be a wonderful time to be in charge of the women's
game. In terms of depth of talent and marquee names, the Corel WTA
Tour never has been stronger. Monica Seles' comeback, certified as
official by her appearance in today's French Open final, plus the
promise of Steffi Graf's return for a last hurrah in combination
with the emergence of the marketable Williams sisters as rivals for
Martina Hingis makes for acres of high cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates Houston tour stop
</P>
<P>
   Assuming nobody screws it up.
</P>
<P>
   That's his primary role _ not to let that happen. Secondly, he
said, he must ``make sure the quality of the game is reflected in
the marketplace.'' In his spare time, he will try to grow the tour.
That doesn't necessarily mean adding tournaments, alas, given
Houston's unfortunate lack of same. Rather, he intends to enhance
the visibility, and thus profitability, of what the WTA has going.
</P>
<P>
   Toward this end, McGuire formed a partnership with Arnon
Milchan's Regency Enterprises, producer of such films as L.A.
Confidential, City of Angels and Pretty Woman.
</P>
<P>
   Regency's mission is to package the WTA's Tier I and Tier II
events for distribution and sale to as many TV networks and
stations as can be reeled in worldwide. Completed is a deal with
Eurosport, which has signed on to televise the tour's European
events.
</P>
<P>
   Because the product is, as McGuire brags, a primo one, Milchan's
task shouldn't be difficult. The men's game would kill to be as
well-positioned.
</P>
<P>
   But, uh, about Houston, Mr. CEO aren't we America's largest city
lacking a women's tennis presence? And isn't Houston where Gladys
Heldman founded what became the women's tour?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Houston,'' McGuire said. ``I've spent a lot of time
there (he was a Compaq consultant for years), and I recognize the
importance of the market economically and historically.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we tend to be more concerned about having too many
tournaments rather than too few, they do come up for sale on a
regular basis. I would hope that Houston interests would step
forward and make themselves known. I'd definitely like for us to
return to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, come on down, Bart. We have all the hustle and bustle a
man can stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
