<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STIFF BATTLE STANDS BETWEEN REAL QUIET AND RARE SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ For a second consecutive year, only the Belmont
Stakes stands between trainer Bob Baffert and Triple Crown history.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet goes into today's mile-and-a-half classic at Belmont
Park as a heavy favorite to become the first 3-year-old in two
decades to pull off the rare sweep. His stablemate, Silver Charm,
nearly accomplished the feat a year ago but couldn't hold off Touch
Gold's stretch rally in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 70,682 fans turned out for a chance to watch history
being made. A similar crowd is expected today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to disappoint the people this time,'' Baffert
promised.
</P>
<P>
   But Real Quiet isn't scaring away any competition. Twelve horses
are entered to face him, including his nemesis Victory Gallop, the
second-place finisher in both the Kentucky Derby and Preakness
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes is scheduled to be televised live on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet wins today, owner Mike Pegram will be rewarded
with much more than a trophy and a place in history. VISA, as
sponsor of the Triple Crown Challenge, will pay him $5 million for
a sweep, and the winner's share of the Belmont is another $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Victory Gallop, Real Quiet's primary rivals appear to
be Classic Cat, who finished third in the Preakness; and fresh
horses Raffie's Majesty and Limit Out, who are based in New York
and didn't compete in the Derby or the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   The stage is set for a rematch worthy of the hype. Real Quiet
and jockey Kent Desormeaux won the Derby by a diminishing
half-length over Victory Gallop. In the Preakness Stakes, Real
Quiet whipped Victory Gallop by 2 1/4-lengths.
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert isn't taking anything for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victory Gallop is a very, very good horse,'' he said. ``So
far, it's been like Affirmed and Alydar. Hopefully, it'll be the
same way (today). There's very little margin for error, though. If
we get in a tight jam, Victory Gallop can upset us.''
</P>
<P>
   Alydar, who chased Affirmed throughout the 1978 Triple Crown in
the sport's greatest rivalry, is the only horse to finish second in
all three races.
</P>
<P>
   The improbable Real Quiet, purchased as a yearling for only
$17,000 because of his crooked legs and angular frame, also will be
racing against history. Thirteen horses including Silver Charm have
won the first two legs of the Triple Crown only to lose the
Belmont, most of them falling victim to the fatigue of the
demanding five-week series.
</P>
<P>
   After his strong performance in the Preakness on a hot and humid
afternoon, Real Quiet was feeling the effects, too. In fact, the
colt was so knocked out Baffert elected to give him a week off, a
risky move for a trainer planning to run in the Belmont only three
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That came from my days as a quarter-horse trainer,'' Baffert
said. ``When you wanted to pick a horse's head up, you just walked
him around the barn for a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The vacation time seemed to do the trick. Real Quiet bounced
back to life and quickly regained the weight he lost in the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   And he seems to have lost none of his aggressiveness or
enthusiasm, Baffert said. One positive sign: Real Quiet was
fighting exercise rider Larry Demore to such an extent in a routine
gallop yesterday morning that Demore developed a cramp in his left
hand from pulling on the reins.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Baffert thought Silver Charm could win, but he knew
he was pushing the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had to work Silver Charm harder than he had ever trained
a horse to get him ready for the Santa Anita Derby and the Kentucky
Derby, because the colt was both lazy and behind schedule because
of an illness. On top of that, the Preakness was a ``blood and
guts'' race for Silver Charm, Baffert said, and took even more out
of him.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, Baffert looks at Real Quiet _ the colt he
once nicknamed ``The Fish'' because of his narrow body _ and sees a
horse who he believes is ready to forge a name in the Triple Crown
history books alongside Citation, Secretariat, Seattle Slew and
Affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes the Big Apple,'' Baffert said. ``He's got that ...
look. The energy level is there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
