<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-NAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FATHER GAVE TRIPLES NAMES THAT STILL CLICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mendez triplets from Woodside, Queens, are camera
shy. This is unfortunate, because their father loves photography.
It is also too bad, because their names have a certain quality that
courts exposure. In fact, although they just graduated from college
Friday, their names are already in lights and on billboards
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   And on a few million cameras, too.
</P>
<P>
   They are their own camera club: Konica, Leica and Minolta
Mendez.
</P>
<P>
   Before they were born 20 years ago in the Philippines, their
father, Manuel, so liked a fine German camera that he picked the
name Leica for a daughter. When triplets arrived, he added Konica
and Minolta to the mix. Nikon was a brief contender, but grandma
nixed it. You wonder what would have happened if he had liked, say,
the Three Stooges or three-card monte.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little easier for them to live in Queens, where their
German, Japanese and Spanish names are just a few more exotic
monikers in the melting pot. At least they're not saddled with the
expectations placed on two brothers who were named Winner and
Loser, according to a police officer who swore he worked with them
in upper Manhattan years ago. Imagine, forever knowing which one
mom liked best.
</P>
<P>
   The Mendez sisters suffer no such envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought we were special because we were triplets,'' Leica
said. ``It's like a double joy to have triplets, so he named us
after something he liked.''
</P>
<P>
   The triplets said they were living in Bahrain when they first
got an inkling their names were different. Their father had moved
the family there to take a job in graphic design. They were about
10 years old when they were given what was otherwise a routine
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``In school, we were asked what the meanings of our names
were,'' Leica said. ``We were named after products. That annoyed me
a bit because I couldn't go up in front of the class and talk about
what my name meant.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters got used to the reaction, which in some cases was
quizzical, but not for the expected reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was that everybody knew what Konica and Minolta
was, but not Leica,'' said Leica, she of the high end name. ``I
used to be bothered by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sisters nodded, then they broke into one another's sentences
like in a tag-team interview. ``In the Philippines,'' Minolta said,
``I had more renown as a photocopier.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a different reaction when they moved to Woodside a few
years ago and enrolled in Queensborough Community College. In a
consumer society, people know from brands. Konica and Leica, fine
arts majors, had to put up with incessant cracks from classmates
who wanted to know if they were into photography.
</P>
<P>
   Said Leica: ``I hate cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   Minolta became a business and marketing major, naturally, since
she had been pitching a product since birth. But brand recognition
often led some teachers to assume she was Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``My economics professor, the first time he heard my name, he
didn't stop talking about the Japanese economy,'' Minolta said.
``When we talked about the economy of Japan, they always talked
about products like Minolta cameras. It's funny, but my sales and
marketing teacher never mentioned anything to me about my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Among themselves, they call one another Koni and Mini, although
Leica is short enough to require no nickname. All in all, the
sisters said their names had given them the advantage of making an
unforgettable impression on whomever they met.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' Minolta said. ``People say if they have triplets
they would name them after products like Mercury, Ford and some
other car.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been those times when they longed for something
just a little plainer. Konica is partial to Marie or Claire.
Minolta was keen on Mary for a while. That just might be what they
call their children someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal names,'' Leica insisted. ``They're not going to go
through having some weird names.''
</P>
<P>
   When the sisters graduated Friday, many shutterbugs in the
audience toted their namesakes. Their father, however, did not,
since he replaced the Leica that inspired his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He uses a Contax now,'' said Leica, who wants to go into
advertising after finishing college. ``They say it's better than a
Leica.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, she displayed the kind of brand loyalty that will
serve her well when she starts her advertising career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give Leica a kick in the butt, for lagging behind,''
she said. ``What's up with that? Keep up your reputation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
