<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YORTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM YORTY, 88, CONTROVERSIAL EX-MAYOR OF LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Neb.)  (bl)  
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES, June 5 _ Samuel W. Yorty, the blunt-talking,
self-promoting mayor of Los Angeles who took credit for building up
the city yet deflected his office's responsibility for the Watts
riots in the 1960s, died Friday. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty had suffered a stroke May 24, and two days ago to be
released from a hospital. He died at his hilltop home in Studio
City.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Nebraska, Yorty also served two terms in Congress, but
became a national figure because of his highly public tenure in Los
Angeles from 1961 to 1973 and for his unabashed, contrary ways.
</P>
<P>
   The self-described ``maverick mayor'' began his career as a
liberal Democrat and ended it as a conservative Republican. He was
elected mayor despite alienating his party by supporting Richard M.
Nixon, not John F. Kennedy, for president in 1960. He was called
``Travelin' Sam'' for seemingly spending as much time away from Los
Angeles as within the city's expanding sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam did what was unexpected,'' said Joy Picus, a long-time
civic leader. ``Sam did what would get him attention.''
</P>
<P>
   He presided over a city that was moving from Midwestern outpost
to gateway to the Pacific Rim. In the 1960 census, the year before
Yorty first took office, Los Angeles was still the most Protestant,
the most white and the most native-born of America's biggest
cities. Indeed, Yorty might have been better suited to be the mayor
of Los Angeles in the 1940s or the early '50s, said Kevin Starr,
the state librarian of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. had become a new city,'' Starr said. ``In movie terms, he
began his career in `Chinatown,' came to political strength during
`L.A. Confidential' and he was mayor during ``Dragnet.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fitting description for a man who was one of the first local
politicians to recognize the power of the camera. He appeared on
television as often as he could, and at one point he was better
known for appearing on the ``Tonight Show'' while playing the banjo
with Johnny Carson, another Nebraska native, on drums.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, he hosted ``The Sam Yorty Show,'' and when it was
canceled he complained, ``They replaced my show with `Hee Haw!' ''
After he was defeated and left office in 1973, he had to settle for
being heard, not seen, and landed a job hosting a local radio
call-in show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Yorty's mayoralty,'' Mike Davis, a historian and author of
``City of Quartz'' (Verso, 1990), ``was the transition from a WASP
majority to the multicultural Los Angeles of Tom Bradley. Yorty's
death is symbolic of the passing of that whole period of L.A.
history when Midwesterns dominated the city and its culture.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1920s, so many Iowans settled in Los Angeles, that some
people called the city ``Iowa by the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel William Yorty had migrated from another Midwestern state,
Nebraska. He was born on Oct. 1, 1909, in Lincoln to Frank and
Johanna Yorty, who traced their roots and their hearts to Ireland.
Yorty grew up in Nebraska's capital, where his father, a former
farmer, ran a restaurant among other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Yorty's political heroes were William Jennings Bryan
and Woodrow Wilson. After graduating from high school, Yorty moved
to Los Angeles and began taking classes at Southwestern University
and the University of California, eventually earning a law degree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He entered politics in the 1930s and, according to the book
``Los Angeles A to Z'' by Leonard Pitt and Dale Pitt (University of
California Press, 1997) ``initially a left-winger, he moved
steadily to the right and became a staunch supporter of the House
Un-American Activities Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   All told he ran for office 20 times, including unsuccessful bids
for governor, the U.S. Senate and the White House. In addition to
his three four-year terms as mayor, he served in the state
legislature, the city council and two terms in Congress in the
early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the year before he was elected mayor, Yorty shocked his
fellow Democrats by not endorsing the party's shining star, John F.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a great mayor,'' said Harriet Weider, a former
aide to Yorty. ``But he was a contrarian and I think some of his
problems he brought on himself by his feisty independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yorty reduced city property taxes and backed the building of
freeways, the Los Angeles Zoo, the Music Center, the convention
center and other projects. Yet his mayoralty was badly scarred by
the 1965 Watts riots, which left 34 people dead and hundreds
injured. When the flames were finally put out, Federal officials
blamed Yorty for not cooperating with their efforts to avoid
trouble and uprisings in America's inner cities. Yorty was sharply
critical of the federal government's anti-poverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1969 elections, Yorty was alienated from the black
community that had helped elect him before and he used race and
charges of left-wing influences to beat back the challenge of a
black city councilman, Tom Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to view Sam Yorty as a metaphor, more than an
individual,'' said Gerald Horne, a historian and author of ``Fire
This Time,'' (University Press of Virginia, 1995) a book about the
Watts riots. ``You have to view as a metaphor because he was not
alone in his shift to the right. This was part of a massive shift
that was taking place in U.S. politics.'' After an unsuccessful
stab at the 1972 presidential campaign, Yorty was defeated the
following year by Bradley, who would become Los Angeles'
longest-serving mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Yorty's political fortunes dropped, he remained
infamously quotable. In the 1980s he startled a Chamber of Commerce
luncheon by saying that ``the black people are really racist. They
vote for black people because they are black.''
</P>
<P>
   His success or failure in shaping Los Angeles remains a debate
for city historians, but it is widely agreed that his two loves
were running for office and having an audience.
</P>
<P>
   As he told the journalist Ed Ainsworth, who wrote a biography of
Yorty, ``Maverick Mayor:'' ``I would rather gave a speech than
eat.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yorty is survived by his wife, Valerie King Yorty, and two
granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
