<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100. WASHINGTON, June 5
-- The following chart shows how senators and house representatives
voted on key bills and amendments this week. A ``Y'' means the
member voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted
against the measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a
``P'' means the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO SENATE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: DISABILITY
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 410-1, a measure that would allow
people receiving disability benefits to obtain Social Security
vouchers that could be used at job-placement, rehabilitation and
job-training centers. The measure also would extend coverage
available to disabled people returning to the work force from four
years to six. The measure was passed without debate. A ``yes'' vote
favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: PRAYER
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 224-203, a constitutional
amendment that would have permitted prayer and religious displays
in public buildings, including schools. The amendment, which gained
a simple majority of votes but fell short of the two-thirds
majority required to pass, marks the first time in 27 years the
House has voted on school prayer. Supporters said the amendment
would restore the right to express religion in public places.
Opponents said the amendment was unnecessary because the 1st
Amendment already protects religious freedom. A ``yes'' vote favors
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: AGRICULTRE
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 364-50, a bill to provide $1.9
billion for agricultural research, crop insurance and food stamps.
The bill includes $818 million in food stamp funding for certain
legal immigrants, which was challenged last month by the Republican
leadership. Supporters cited the importance of farmers' interests
and the restoration of benefits for legal immigrants. Opponents did
not want to reinstate food stamps to legal immigrants. A ``yes''
vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
