<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-STEINBRENNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BUSH-LEAGUE BRUSHBACK PITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 6:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner virtually
threatened to move his team out of New York City this week, but his
intemperate words must not be allowed to chill a robust public
debate about whether and where to build new baseball stadiums and
how to finance them. ``I do not want to move the Yankees from New
York, but I must warn: He is bringing us dangerously close,''
Steinbrenner said in a formal statement.
</P>
<P>
   The ``he'' Steinbrenner wrongly castigated is Peter Vallone, the
City Council speaker and Democratic gubernatorial aspirant, who has
proposed a referendum on whether to spend public money for a new
stadium in Manhattan. While we part company with Vallone on his
referendum, urging taxpayers to examine these issues is a vital
part of his job description. Steinbrenner has no business trying to
intimidate him into silence.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Vallone and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani have allowed their
differences on stadium issues to hobble negotiations on the city's
proposed $34 billion budget. The budget stalemate has its roots not
in the traditional give-and-take of city finances but in the
stubbornness of the mayor and the speaker. Most independent
analysts see the two sides as being closer than they sound. But on
Friday the mayor called the Vallone budget ``a joke,'' and Vallone
has complained that the mayor refused to negotiate because of the
Yankee Stadium fight.
</P>
<P>
   If Giuliani and Vallone could agree on a budget in the hard
times, it should be all the easier to shave a little here and add a
little there with a $2 billion surplus. There is more than enough
money in a $34 billion plan to pay down the debt and still make
room for longer library hours, expanded recycling, after-school
activities and other needed programs. But now that the Council has
adopted its own budget, the city is in unfamiliar territory where
the process and outcome are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Few ballparks in America are as steeped in history as Yankee
Stadium in the Bronx. We hope the Yankees continue to play in this
storied venue, in either a renovated or a new stadium. If that is
not the outcome of Steinbrenner's deliberations, there will be time
enough to weigh other sites in the Bronx and Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the referendum Vallone desires is unlikely to
enhance public discourse. Referendums are very blunt instruments.
More often than not _ witness California _ they turn nuanced issues
into bumper-sticker slogans. They relieve politicians of their
responsibility to lead. Referendum results often hamstring
government's ability to pursue effective policies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Vallone is right to raise the issue of public financing.
Almost monthly there are encouraging signs that stadiums can be
financed entirely or primarily by the private sector. The Green Bay
Packers recently turned to their football fans nationwide and
raised more than $24 million for capital improvements through the
sale of $200 shares that cannot be traded and bear no dividend.
This week the Cleveland Indians raised $60 million by offering
publicly traded stock. The universe of private financing options is
a lot wider than Steinbrenner and the other lords of baseball let
on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
