A6845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-527&AMP;ADD-N     06-05 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-527&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET RUNS FOR GREATNESS AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the racing world presents its
ultimate drama at Belmont Park: Real Quiet, an ugly duckling foaled
with crooked legs who was sold for only $17,000 as a yearling,
races 12 rivals Saturday in a bid to win the Belmont Stakes and
complete his Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   It is a goal captured by 11 horses and missed by 13 who tackled
the punishing logistics: at the tender age of 3, to win the
Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the Belmont within five weeks'
time at three tracks in three states.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario was set with theatrical effect last year before
70,682 spectators, the largest number to watch a horse race in New
York in 20 years and the third-largest ever at Belmont Park. They
watched in wonder as Silver Charm tried to last the mile and
one-half of the Belmont Stakes, and failed by three-quarters of a
length when he was caught in the final 100 yards by Touch Gold. He
also failed to win the bonus of $5 million posted by Visa Corp. for
a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, racing gets another chance. It gets one more
natural drama with a compelling story line: Another horse from
California stands on the edge of history with the same trainer, Bob
Baffert, king of the one-liners and the winner of four of the last
five races in the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the drama reached to Wall Street Friday morning
when Mike Pegram, the owner of Real Quiet, rang the opening bell at
the New York Stock Exchange, and said: ``When we got this horse, we
called him the Fish. I didn't know he'd be a fish they couldn't
catch. But then again, I never dreamed I could make $5 million in a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, who made a fortune in fast-food franchises, predicted
that his colt would deliver the dramatic ending that Silver Charm
did not deliver. And he intimated that Real Quiet might grow as a
racing hero who captures the public's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he suggested, referring to racing and its general
plight, ``we could put some more people in the stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Clear weather with temperatures in the 70s and a fast, dry track
were predicted for the race, prompting Belmont officials to hope
for another banner crowd at a track that drew only 6,784 fans
Friday. The day before, the New York Racing Association's Web site
registered 502,755 hits. And the press office reported that it had
issued more than 1,000 credentials to members of the news media
gathering to record the event.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 horses of the past who took the giant step and swept the
Triple Crown include three celebrated anniversary heroes: Citation
50 years ago, Secretariat 25 years ago and Affirmed 20 years ago.
The 13 who failed include some major stars, too: Carry Back in
1961, Northern Dancer in 1964, Spectacular Bid in 1979, Alysheba in
1987, Sunday Silence in 1989 and Silver Charm last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the race, Real Quiet galloped once around the
Belmont strip, which measures a mile and a half, and his trainer
reported one more time that he was ready to take on all comers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse likes the track,'' Baffert said. ``He's likes the
Big Apple. But sometimes you need more racing luck than anything
else. It's just a waiting game now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Baffert spent his evening of waiting at a baseball game at
Yankee Stadium, throwing out the first ball and watching the
Yankees play the Florida Marlins. His horse was the 6-5 betting
choice breaking out of the No. 8 post position, and all he had to
do now was win.
</P>
<P>
   But his 12 rivals included one old foe, Victory Gallop, who ran
second in both the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness and was listed
as the second choice at 7-2. Third in the early betting, at 6-1,
was Grand Slam, winner of the Peter Pan Stakes two weeks ago, a
colt trained by D. Wayne Lukas, who won six straight Triple Crown
races before Baffert started his recent roll. In fact, Lukas won
the Belmont three years in a row starting in 1994 with Tabasco Cat,
Thunder Gulch and Editor's Note.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas will try to derail Real Quiet by running two horses in the
Belmont: Grand Slam and Yarrow Brae, winner of the Illinois Derby.
Both horses galloped Friday morning, and Lukas observed that they
were in good shape but declined to stir any waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no ripples on the water here today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop also cruised once around the track Friday,
satisfying his trainer, Elliott Walden, who said: ``He went good.
It seems to me he's where we want him to be. Before the Derby, he
was very enthusiastic, very willing to train, and he's the same way
this week, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffie's Majesty, the least experienced horse in the Belmont,
has raced only four times in his career and won twice. His trainer,
James Bond, sent the colt out for one lap around the oval at 5:15
in the morning, and then said, ``All we can do is keep him in good
health for the next 36 hours, and pray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
