<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-FEL-PRO-$ADV07-A     06-05 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-FEL-PRO-$ADV07-ART-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBJECTS UNEASY AS A BENEVOLENT REIGN ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 7)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(jt) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOKIE, Ill. _ For 80 years, workers at Fel-Pro Inc., a
manufacturer of automotive parts based here, have enjoyed some of
the lushest benefits in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   The list is long and varied: as much as 12 weeks of vacation;
scholarships; summer camp for employees' children; a fitness
center; tutoring; the state's first licensed day-care center; use
of a 250-acre corporate retreat, and even a $1,000 savings bond for
the birth of an employee's child.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention solid health, pension and profit-sharing plans
and a pro-nepotism policy that has meant that two-thirds of the
1,900 employees at the company's headquarters plant have had
relatives on the payroll at one time or another. Or such gestures
as a ham at Easter, a turkey at Christmas and candy for Valentine's
Day. Even the employees' neighborhoods benefit: groups in which
workers volunteer receive grants.
</P>
<P>
   Pay averages $12.50 an hour, what the company calls ``very
competitive'' wages for the industry, and workers receive an extra
day's pay on their employment anniversary and birthday. And any
threat to job security has been largely eliminated by a sizable
temporary staff, which acts as a cushion to slack periods. Small
wonder, then, that in a review by Fortune magazine last year of the
nation's 100 best companies to work for, Fel-Pro ranked fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They coddled and spoiled us,'' acknowledged David Beller, a
tool-and-die maker who has worked at Fel-Pro for 20 years. ``They
were very generous to their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   But circumstances have changed, as Beller's use of the past
tense implies. Last December, the owners _ members of the Lehman,
Weinberg and Morris families, descendants of the company's founder,
Albert Mecklenburger _ said they intended to sell Fel-Pro. In
January, word came of a takeover by the Federal-Mogul Corp., a
gritty Michigan company four times Fel-Pro's size.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since, a large cloud has, not surprisingly, formed
over this workers' paradise as employees confront the inevitable
unease and search for reassurance about their prospects under a
traditional corporate regime and its emphasis on maximizing
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's nervous,'' said Lucy King, 34, a longtime employee
in the packaging operations. ``We really don't know what to expect.
It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The skittishness is widespread _ and magnified by the jarringly
quick dispatch of a few dozen marketing, accounting and other
support people to Federal-Mogul's headquarters in Southfield,
Mich., or to unemployment lines. Indeed, several people who
initially agreed to be photographed for this article subsequently
declined, saying they felt uncomfortable in the current corporate
environment.
</P>
<P>
   It is fair to say that such feelings are new to the factory
here. Fel-Pro began in 1918 as Felt Products, which made a horse
blanket that fit under saddles before felt was widely used as a
sealant in automotive parts like gaskets. Over time, corporate
policy that may have begun as benevolence grew to become a way of
business that the company's fans say was as resolutely focused on
the bottom line as any leaner-and-meaner approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefits paid for themselves, with additional cooperation,
higher productivity,'' said Robert O'Keefe, a retired vice
president for industrial relations. ``We used to say we couldn't
not do it because it was an enhancement to our profits.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Workers take some comfort in various provisions of the $720
million stock-and-cash deal that the Fel-Pro families negotiated
with Richard Snell, the chairman of Federal-Mogul. Under the
agreement, various benefits will be maintained for specified
periods while others will be replaced by those of the new parent.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Snell said recently that ``the first agenda item'' in
negotiations with the families was Fel-Pro's special corporate
culture of near womb-to-tomb beneficence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, interviews with employees here found considerable
skepticism about how they will fare. They know that even as
Federal-Mogul tries to accommodate Fel-Pro, it is also digesting a
much larger acquisition of a British automotive supplier, T&AMP;N PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, workers seemed resigned to losing most of the lesser
fringe benefits while hoping for the best on vital interests like
health insurance _ and keeping their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never say with a big company like Federal-Mogul,''
said Frank Donis, 26, who works in the paper unit and whose mother,
sister and an aunt all worked for Fel-Pro. ``If things go down, the
company's going to have to make adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   One source of unease is Snell's intention to build what he calls
an ``all-star'' team drawn from the top talent in the company; that
is, Federal-Mogul will identify its best workers and protect them
from layoffs. But job losses are coming: Federal-Mogul hopes to
shrink its worldwide payroll of 41,000 by about 10 percent, much of
it through attrition. The company has not, however, specified
Fel-Pro's share of the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Another unwelcome change: Kenneth Lehman, who served seven years
in various Peace Corps positions before joining the family business
and rising to co-chairman, will not join the Federal-Mogul board,
as intended when the deal was announced. The reason, Lehman said,
is that it might have presented a conflict: he is administrator of
family trusts, and being a board member could, for example, inhibit
sales by the trusts of Federal-Mogul shares because of his status
as a company insider.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a big challenge on their plates,'' Lehman said in
an interview the week after the deal closed in late February,
referring to Federal-Mogul management. ``They will be trying to
forge a new culture for a big new global company.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding not entirely confident, Lehman added that if
Federal-Mogul was convinced that treating employees well improved
the bottom line, ``then hopefully they'll use us as a model.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not at all certain, judging from what typically occurs
in such situations, said Jim Sillery, senior consultant at Watson
Wyatt Worldwide in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture of the acquirer tends to become dominant,'' he
said. ``Fel-Pro's benefits will begin to look a lot like Mogul's,''
he predicted, noting that agreements covering benefits were not
necessarily binding and were subject to interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Weatherly, a consultant at Towers Perrin in Chicago,
agreed. In the face of ``overriding'' pressure from auto makers on
suppliers to squeeze costs, Weatherly said, ``it really is hard to
see all the nice features of the Fel-Pro culture surviving.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Fel-Pro workers' profit-sharing plans can be
rolled over into Federal-Mogul's 401(k) plan; medical and dental
coverage converts to Federal-Mogul's similar, and in some respects
better, plan in 1999. The summer day camp and wellness center will
remain for at least two years, and vacations will be capped at four
weeks, except for employees already entitled to more time.
</P>
<P>
   The Fel-Pro families have set aside proceeds from the sale to
maintain the scholarship program for five years.
</P>
<P>
   One clear plus, however, is that Federal-Mogul hopes to extend
its year-old stock option plan to Fel-Pro employees. The
Federal-Mogul board is expected to approve the move within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Another, some employees say, is expanded opportunity as part of
a $5 billion company. ``Maybe all the benefits aren't there, but
you can maybe get a job somewhere else in the country,'' said Larry
Jenrich, 35, an inventory analyst in the distribution center for
whom Fel-Pro paid for two years of college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
