<SLUG> BC-HOPE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA REP. BOB STUMP ANNOUNCES BOB HOPE `DEATH' REPORT IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The testimonials to Bob Hope by grieving members of
Congress were so vivid that one could almost imagine the
95-year-old entertainer were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   He was.
</P>
<P>
   A thoroughly embarrassing string of events, even by
congressional standards, began Friday afternoon when House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Tex., introduced Rep. Bob Stump, R-Ariz., for
an ``announcement I think will be of great interest to this body.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump stepped to the microphone on the floor of the House and
said, ``Mr. Speaker, I have the sad responsibility to tell you this
afternoon that Bob Hope passed away.''
</P>
<P>
   At that very moment, Hope was in California ``eating a late
breakfast and preparing to go hit a couple of golf balls,'' said
his publicist, Ward Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Hope, who celebrated his 95th birthday a week ago, laughed when
he heard the report, and said, ``They were wrong, weren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional faux pas emanated from an Associated Press
article being prepared in the event of Hope's death. The article
was inadvertently displayed on the news service's Web site Friday
and relayed to Armey by congressional staff.
</P>
<P>
   Armey wanted Stump to make the announcement because the Arizonan
is close to Hope and his family. Stump, a World War II Navy veteran
who attended one of Hope's comedic performances at Pearl Harbor in
1943, helped push through legislation naming Hope an ``honorary
veteran'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said there had been rumors of Hope's demise before this
one, ``but not to this degree, not announced by Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by reports of his death before a performance eight
years ago, Hope replied, ``Does this mean I don't have to go on?''
</P>
<P>
   After Stump's announcement, House Minority Whip David Bonior,
D-Mich., said on the floor, ``I would add these comments to my
friend from Arizona that we are all saddened by his passing. He has
provided so much joy and happiness to this planet and to our
servicemen and women in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Tex., also paid homage to the
not-so-departed Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Phones began ringly madly at the United Service Organizations,
which Hope helped make famous with his entertainment programs for
armed forces personnel overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were from all over the place, people worried about him,
media people, board members, friends of Bob Hope,'' spokeswoman Pat
Messer said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Armey stepped back onto the floor to apologize for an
``announcement that was erroneous regarding a report that Bob Hope
had passed away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret the announcement, and I look forward to many more
happy memories from a wonderful entertainer and a distinguished
American,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee then returned to amend her earlier tribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that, I will gleefully acknowledge that I do not have to
offer sympathy to the family of Bob Hope, and I am joyful about
that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stump tried to telephone Hope and got the comedian's
daughter, Linda, instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said he was alive and well and wondered about the story,
and I told her exactly what had happened,'' Stump said. ``I said we
were sorry and that I hoped Mr. Hope got a kick out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Gersh, editor of AP Multimedia Services, said the
untimely &UR; obit was miscoded by human error so that instead of
showing up only on an internal display where an editor could work
on it, the preparedness was posted to the AP's Web site, The WIRE.
</P>
<P>
   The AP, like other news organizations, prepares obituaries on
celebrities so copy can be moved quickly when they die. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      06-05 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES OF REWRITING CAMPAIGN FINANCE LAWS CITE FIRST AMENDMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forces opposed to rewriting the nation's
campaign-finance laws are denouncing the effort as a siege on free
speech and are threatening the most widely supported overhaul plan
by questioning its constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning images of big government muzzling voices and building
barbed-wire fences to stem the spread of ideas, foes of changing
the way the nation finances elections are vowing to fight from the
halls of Congress to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment is not an idea that should be tossed aside
like a piece of garbage,'' said Representative Tom DeLay of Texas,
the House majority whip, expressing the sentiment of other GOP
leaders and a coalition of interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   With the House considering a dozen campaign-finance proposals,
nothing is likely to stir impassioned rhetoric and jeopardize major
changes in the law more than constitutional concerns.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how strictly the goverment can regulate political
spending, which exceeded $2 billion in the 1996 federal elections,
including the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular campaign-finance bill, sponsored by
Representatives Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican, and
Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat, has sparked opposition from a
range of special interests over a provision that would regulate
independent spending by groups other than political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Under a landmark Supreme Court ruling, organizations such as
labor unions, corporations, and nonprofit groups are not required
to report how much they spend or where they get the money to fund
``issue advocacy'' campaigns, which attack candidates without
directly calling for their election or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The high court decided in the 1976 case, Buckley v. Valeo, that
the government has the right to regulate ``express advocacy,''
which specifically calls for electing or defeating a candidate. The
justices said the regulations, which set contribution limits and
require candidates to disclose the source of their campaign money,
was justified to prevent corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But the court also said free-speech guarantees would be violated
by measures that restrict spending aimed at swaying public opinion
without directly influencing elections. ``So long as persons and
groups eschew expenditures that in express terms advocate the
election or defeat of a clearly identified candidate, they are free
to spend as much as they want to promote the candidate and his
views,'' the justices wrote.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $150 million was spent in 1996 on issue-advocacy
campaigns, many playing decisive roles in the elections. The
antiabortion National Right to Life Committee, which spent about $2
million in 1996 on issue advocacy, has vowed to challenge in court
any limits on independent spending, as have the American Civil
Liberties Union and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numerous provisions of the Shays-Meehan bill ignore the
Supreme Court rulings that provide broad protections for citizens
groups to comment on the positions and voting records of federal
politicians,'' said Douglas Johnson, legislative director for the
National Right to Life Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Even strong supporters of the Shays-Meehan bill worry about the
measure's constitutionality. ``I fear that it will be hard to sell
to the Supreme Court,'' said Representative Marcy Kaptur, an Ohio
Democrat who helped craft the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But other supporters of the bill assert that the high court
ruling left open the door for regulating issue advocacy and
establishing spending limits if the integrity of the election
system was threatened by a flood of undisclosed spending by
individuals and independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Supreme Court ruled that ``limiting corruption
provides a constitutionally sufficient justification for
contribution limits,'' the court could find that preventing
corruption also justifies expanding regulations on spending,
according to the Shays-Meehan backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment protects speech,'' said Representative
Scotty Baesler, a Kentucky Democrat who is running for the Senate.
``It does not protect corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based National Voting Rights Institute has filed
lawsuits in several states and municipalities aimed at asking the
Supreme Court to reconsider its Buckley decision that prohibits
regulating independent spending.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent House debate, Representative Asa Hutchinson, an
Arkansas Republican who is sponsoring a bipartisan freshmen bill
that would impose less-stringent regulations on campaign spending
than the Shays-Meehan bill, said changes are necessary to ensure
that big money does not control elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``By claiming to argue for free speech,'' Hutchinson said, ``the
opponents of reform are cynically attempting to make sure that big
money not only talks, but it screams.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said his bill, which is backed by President Clinton and a
coalition of groups such as the League of Women Voters and Common
Cause, has the support of a majority of House members, although no
vote has been scheduled. The measure also must survive a rare,
parliamentary process in which it could be killed if any of the 11
competing proposals receives more votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, a bill identical to Shays-Meehan passed last year
with 53 votes, but died when supporters could not muster the 60
votes needed to overcome procedural hurdles raised by Republican
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of the Shays-Meehan bill facing stiff opposition
is a ban on the unlimited and unregulated contributions known as
``soft money.'' The two major parties spent more than $260 million
in soft money in 1996, much of it on issue advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee has alerted its members
that the proposed ban would unconstitutionally nullify ``the right
of political parties to engage in unrationed issue advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan said such a ban is constitutional and in the public
interest. He said his bill would allow politicians ``to take a step
away from the well-heeled special interests and take a step toward
restoring the one-voice, one-vote principle upon which the country
was founded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
