<HEADLINE>
TRACKING THE FLOW OF CASH ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic comparing cash flow and total return for emerging
market funds will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calling this year's overseas markets volatile is a bit like
saying India and Pakistan are having a neighborhood cook-off.
</P>
<P>
   How have fund investors reacted to the spinning markets? By
piling into hot European funds, bailing out of plummeting Latin
American stock funds and _ surprisingly _ plowing enormous amounts
of cash into the debt of emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings come from data on estimated regional fund cash
flows for the first four months of 1998 from Lipper Analytical
Services, the research firm in Summit, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   For those who think that going against the grain can lead to
outsized profits, such cash-flow figures can be useful in deciding
when to buy or sell.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had directed a net total of $2.6 billion into European
funds in 1998, through April 30. Moreover, flows into European
funds were consistently positive each month.
</P>
<P>
   That bespeaks enormous positive sentiment, according to Michael
A. Lipper, president of Lipper Analytical _ perhaps too much. ``At
some point,'' Lipper said, ``the enthusiasm for Europe may be
overplayed.''
</P>
<P>
   European funds, as tracked by Lipper Analytical, posted gains in
all four months. In February alone, they returned 8 percent. ``If
you have not invested in Europe as a sector bet, it's probably too
late,'' Lipper said, but he added, ``if you own Europe, I don't
think you have to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, that loud whoosh you hear is the sound of investors
pulling money out of Latin American stock funds. Such funds have
had net outflows every month since June 1997. During the first four
months of 1998, investors pulled out $609.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this: Latin American stock funds have experienced
negative returns in just one of the first four months of 1998: a
10.5 percent loss in January. Since then monthly returns returns
have been positive. That helps lead Lipper to believe that such
funds are oversold.
</P>
<P>
   More curious is the bullishness on emerging-markets debt funds.
Investors have put a net of $559.4 million into such funds in the
first four months of the year. Only in January did they withdraw
money. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an absolute constitutional right to earn 7 percent on
high-quality paper,'' Lipper joked. ``If the U.S. government isn't
going to deliver that, and corporates aren't going to, Brady bonds
do,'' he added, referring to the bonds developed in 1989 by
then-Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady to reduce Latin America's
foreign bank debt.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are likely to be lulled by two facts: First, Brady
bonds, which are heavily bought by emerging-markets bond funds, are
denominated in dollars and hence are seen as immune to currency
meltdowns. Second, the United States Treasury guarantees repayment
of the principal _ though not the interest.
</P>
<P>
   But owning individual bonds is different from owning a bond
fund, which is still subject to the price fluctuation of its
fixed-income portfolio. In October 1997 alone, for example, such
funds lost 9.7 percent on average, according to Lipper Analytical.
</P>
<P>
   Cash flows for emerging-markets stock funds have been erratic.
Investors yanked out $246.6 million in January, only to invest a
net of $457.4 million in February. Then they pulled out $162.6
million in March and sank $146.3 million into the funds in April.
</P>
<P>
   All told, there was a net cash inflow of $194.5 million. Which,
of course, has likely set up investors for the most recent
downdraft. Many investors were probably looking for a classic
rebound from last year's emerging-markets selloff, Lipper said, and
are instead experiencing a double-dip selloff. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the push for plain-English prospectuses. The State
Street Research and Management Co., which manages $16.3 billion in
mutual fund assets, has gone another step: to plain Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already translated the prospectus for its Alpha
fund, as well as an educational brochure, and Chinese translations
are in the works for four other funds, too.
</P>
<P>
   The translations follow from State Street's simplification of
its English prospectuses a year ago, said Joan Miller, senior vice
president for retail marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We translated from lawyer's English to plain English and then
into other languages because there's no way to translate some of
the legal terms used in ordinary prospectuses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Why Chinese? As a group, Chinese-Americans are better educated,
save more and earn more than the average United States household,
Ms. Miller said. She added that the response to the Chinese
prospectus was ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   State Street is also pushing ahead with plans to translate
prospectuses for six funds into Spanish. No plans have been made
for other languages _ yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
