<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S WRONG WITH NOT KEEPING SCORE?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Okay, so the solution may be too simplistic. But grant the
Massachusetts Youth Soccer Association this much: At least the men
and women who rule our Saturday mornings are trying to save us from
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's no easy mission.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to eliminate keeping score in soccer tournaments
for kids under age 10 has brought the Wrath of the Righteous down
upon the heads of those who govern children's soccer in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   They're Marxists, killing competition.
</P>
<P>
   They're welfare-state Liberals, destroying incentive.
</P>
<P>
   They're do-gooders, promoting self-esteem above
self-improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they're just parents, as horrified as the rest of us by
what they see from the sidelines. The coach who browbeats a boy who
can't practice for two hours on a school night because his mother
subscribes to the quaint notion that he should eat his supper and
do his homework. The coach who dispatches his wife to the practice
fields of neighboring towns to scout the opposition. The coaches
who meet in pre-draft caucuses to compare detailed game notes on
9-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   If only the problem stopped with the coaches. But what about the
soccer mom who demands that the coach send in her boy whenever a
teammate misses a goal? Or the soccer dad who runs along the
sideline swearing at his own son? Or the parents who hurl
invectives at the teenage referees?
</P>
<P>
   It's ugly out there on the soccer field. And the Little League
diamond. And the CYO basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, eliminating keeping score will not end the excesses
of adults any more than it will stop children from counting the
number of goals scored. There is not a ``non-results oriented
competition,'' from sports to board games, that does not end with a
healthy child asking, ``Who won?''
</P>
<P>
   What the rule change by the Massachusetts Youth Soccer
Association might accomplish, however, is to force us to focus on
the larger issues. &UR;  &LR; Why, for instance, do we insist on ranking
children before they've had the time to learn the game? How are
children under age 10 to develop the skills necessary to excel if
they are classified as ``B'' players by overzealous coaches their
first or second season on the field?
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery why the coach of kindergartners who wears a
rubber pig nose and feathered chicken legs to practice wins the
affection and the attention of his team of 5-year-olds, while the
bellicose father on the other side of the field can't get his team
to listen. Why, then, is the coach of middle-schoolers who welcomes
a slow-moving but plucky kid back into the lineup after a broken
leg the exception rather than the rule?
</P>
<P>
   What is undermining childhood in America is not our refusal to
hold our children to high standards; it's deceiving them and
ourselves into believing that a score alone _ whether on the soccer
field, on the SATs or the Boston Latin School admissions exam _ is
what separates winners from losers.
</P>
<P>
   That's the lesson Julia McLaughlin's father taught her when he
insisted that her test score alone entitled her to a seat at Boston
Latin. That's the lesson we teach a computationally challenged
child when we force him into an upper-level math class, lest his
course load fail to impress Harvard. That's the lesson we teach our
tone-deaf daughter when we insist she continue violin classes.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that, by adolescence, most children have
abandoned team sports and music lessons? They're burned out.
</P>
<P>
   To compound matters, this faith in the inviolability of winning
scores is awfully selective. In Xenia, Ohio, this spring a student
with a 3.8 grade point average was barred from joining her high
school's National Honor Society. Amanada Lemon, 18, had been
invited to join her school's chapter until a five-member faculty
council learned she had a 9-month-old daughter. She had the
required score, the teachers said, but she lacked the requisite
character. So much for the sanctity of objective standards.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to mock the decision to eliminate score-keeping in the
early years of youth soccer; it's tempting to ridicule the blanket
award of trophies to 6-year-old T-ball players. Is it so much
harder to acknowledge that all skills, in the classroom and on the
playing field, take time to develop and to teach our children that
we are willing to give them the time it takes?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
