<HEADLINE>
HUNTING FOR HEADHUNTERS THROUGH SALES OF STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 7) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on executive search firms that go public is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When most companies go public, the aim is to recruit
shareholders. Now, recruiters may be going public partly to help
recruit recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts point to six executive search firms that are
either planning or considering initial public offerings, including
the two leaders, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles and Korn/Ferry International.
Capital needs such as new computer systems for sophisticated
searches or a war chest for acquisitions are mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than the cash the offerings raise, the most important
payoff may be the ability to use lucrative stock option plans to
lure top talent in an industry where compensation does not vary
widely from one firm to another.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that adds up to an attractive proposition for investors
is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the executive search business is booming,
because of a strong economy and the great emphasis many
corporations place on recruiting the most suitable executives for
top posts rather than automatically promoting from within. Revenues
of the top 10 firms in the field grew 23 percent last year, and
half of them have seen revenue more than double over the past five
years, according to Hunt-Scanlon Advisors, which publishes a
newsletter called Executive Search Review.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in similar businesses where the assets all go home at
night _ like consulting, advertising and money management _ have
gone public with some success. And the one major executive search
company to follow their lead in recent years, LAI Ward Howell, has
done well so far, rising from its offering price of $12 last July
to $19.50 on Friday. (LAI filed plans in May for a secondary
offering with the Securities and Exchange Commission.)
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of reasons for investors to look twice at
executive search company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Korn/Ferry went public once before, in 1972, and
did not enjoy it. The company was small and the stock thinly traded
and volatile; the founders, Lester Korn and Richard Ferry, found
the bobbing of the stock price a maddening distraction. They
repurchased all the stock in 1974 and went private again; their
experience made others in the industry shy of public offerings for
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Korn/Ferry is considering going public again now, said president
and chief executive Michael Boxberger, because the company wants to
expand its business to the Internet and finance growing technology
needs. But Korn/Ferry also wants to use its stock to attract and
retain staff.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that objective can be a concern for investors, too.
Executive search firms have high turnover rates, providing the
potential to seriously burn investors if a firm is hit by a wave of
defections.
</P>
<P>
   And earnings can be difficult to forecast. ``This is a very
relationship-oriented business, and it often takes years to develop
relationships with clients,'' said Susan Chadick, a partner at
Gould, McCoy &AMP; Chadick, a small executive search firm in Manhattan.
``Our product doesn't unfold on a predictable basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Jacob, an analyst at IPO Value Monitor, said: ``Going
public is a good move for the companies, but it has a certain
degree of risk for investors. In most cases, these companies have
fairly uneven operating results _ that's just the nature of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   That is probably because most firms in the industry are small,
and as Korn/Ferry's 1970s sojourn illustrates, size is an important
concern. Boxberger said his company is now big and global enough to
make its earnings fairly predictable.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, however, the executive search business remains
a cottage industry, and one beset by worrisome trends under the
surface. According to Scott Scanlon, editor in chief of Executive
Search Review, many firms not only lack the financial and marketing
capacity to be publicly-traded entities, but they also have poor
training programs for new hires. ``This is an industry that hasn't
made an effort to attract young talent, but that could sorely use
it,'' Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, it now takes the average recruiter longer
to fill an assignment, and the number of successfully completed
assignments is dropping.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, executives at some of the largest search firms
continue to resist the idea of going public. The recruiting concern
Spencer Stuart recently lost two top executives to Heidrick &AMP;
Struggles. But Joseph Griesedieck, chief executive of Spencer
Stuart, said the company's 115 partners voted unanimously last
month to remain private, partly because of concerns over the
potential loss of client confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that publicly traded search firms may
have an edge on the recruitment front.
</P>
<P>
   At Strategic Legal Resources, a Manhattan search company that
places high-level executives as well as lawyers, Jay Horowitz, one
of its founders, said stock options had definitely helped lure new
employees since Strategic Legal was acquired earlier this year by
Staffmark Inc., a publicly traded staffing company.
</P>
<P>
   ``These options have huge appeal. I can pay people one-half to
two-thirds of the salaries they wanted,'' Horowitz said. ``And
that's because people feel like they're part of something in a
publicly traded company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
