<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCEONE-VANISH-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADAR DATA VANISHES TWICE ON AIR FORCE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some radar data from Air Force One carrying
President Clinton disappeared mysteriously from air traffic
controllers' screens twice Friday morning as the plane flew over
New Jersey, the second time this year that the presidential jet has
trailed off the same radar system.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration insisted that ``in neither
incident was safety compromised'' on Friday, noting that a
controller initiated voice contact with Air Force One to keep track
of its flight. The agency promised to investigate, saying that
similar radar glitches have occurred on other flights around the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The lapses occurred Friday while Air Force One was en route from
Andrews Air Force Base to Bedford, Mass., where the president was
to give a commencement speech at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. First, a text block of data vanished from the screen
for 24 seconds; then a while later, the same data disappeared for
36 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was being tracked with data from an FAA long-distance
radar in Gibbsboro, N.J., about 15 miles southeast of Philadelphia,
and the controller handling the jet was stationed in Ronkonkoma,
N.Y., which handles high-altitude traffic in the region. The radar
lapses involving Air Force One were not related to a software
problem at another FAA office earlier in the day that delayed
hundreds of passenger flights.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the anomaly remained in dispute, but FAA officials
confirmed that the Gibbsboro, N.J., radar is the same one that lost
track of Air Force One on March 10 when the plane also partly
vanished from controllers' screens.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers say they believe there is a problem with
the Gibbsboro radar, which was brought online in September. The
Federal Aviation Administration, however, believes that the problem
is a generic flaw of the radar system used nationwide, because it
becomes confused if it sees two airplanes over the same spot of
land, at different altitudes. The agency says it has no way to
correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This phenomenon is not particular to the New York area or to
this radar,'' said Eliot Brenner, the chief spokesman for the
agency. ``It is seen at other locations around the country, and
controllers are well aware of it and trained to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, ``when it's the president's aircraft, you want everything
to work properly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it doesn't, the incident is quickly publicized. On
January 28, also departing Andrews, Air Force One came within 2.36
miles of a US Airways flight bound for National Airport. That was
not because of a radar failure, though.
</P>
<P>
   The radar involved Friday morning works mainly by sending out an
electronic question to planes in flight, and receiving responses
from an on-board radio device called a transponder. The transponder
sends a radio message back, giving the plane's name, model,
destination and altitude.
</P>
<P>
   The radar system records which way the antenna was facing when
it received the answer, and thus knows the direction of the plane;
it also keeps track of the time the response was received. Since
radio waves travel at a known speed through air, knowing the time
means knowing the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Then the system displays on the screen a text block, giving all
that information, and a symbol depicting the plane's estimated
location.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that if two airplanes are over the same spot,
while they may be miles apart in altitude, the radar does not know
that. It sees in only two dimensions, bearing (compass direction to
the plane) and range (distance to the plane). When it gets two
signals back simultaneously, it often garbles or loses one of them,
according to FAA radar experts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Friday morning, parts of Air Force One's text block were
absent on two radar sweeps at about 8:11 a.m. A sweep takes 12.5
seconds, so that gap was 25 seconds. The plane was about 23 miles
northeast of the Gibbsboro radar at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 8:17 a.m., some data was lost for three consecutive
sweeps, or 37.5 seconds. By then the plane was about 65 miles
northeast of the radar.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said it did not know yet how much of the data was lost.
In each instance, the agency said, the controller handling the
plane made certain by voice contact that the president's plane was
still flying.
</P>
<P>
   In case of brief radar failure, separation of aircraft is still
likely because the planes are operating at a fixed speed over a
fixed route, and like a line of cars traveling down the highway,
their position relative to each other changes much more slowly than
their position relative to a fixed object. Also, in clear weather
they can see each other, and all passenger planes carry
anti-collision radar.
</P>
<P>
   Radar experts say events like the two that happened to Air Force
One on Friday morning are very common, especially in places where
air space is congested, and thus where two planes are likely to be
over the same spot. At the Professional Airways Systems
Specialists, the union that represents the electronics technicians
who keep radars running, Henry Brown, who is based on Long Island,
N.Y., said, ``If you were to ask the FAA for all the sweeps they
miss in a month, you wouldn't have room for the data.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason they make a big deal out of it is it's Air
Force One,'' he said. ``We're talking about technology here,'' he
said. ``Stuff goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But controllers say that a data block disappearing from radar is
a shock. ``Your heart goes from your chest up to your throat,''
said Dean Iacopelli, an official of the controllers union, the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association, at the office in New
York that handles lower-altitude flights. ``You say, `American 001,
are you still with me?' And they say, `We're still here,'''
Iacopelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it's American 001, nobody seems to care,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
