u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-575&AMP;ADD-N     06-05 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. READY TO RESUME SANCTIONS OVER KOSOVO STRIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has reversed course and
is ready to impose new sanctions on Yugoslavia to punish President
Slobodan Milosevic for his attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo,
senior American officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, British officials said they would move ahead
with European sanctions, would press NATO to plan possible military
action and would push the U.N. Security Council for a resolution to
justify such a use of force.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they are moving to impose sanctions but
that the decision will not formally be made before a White House
meeting of senior officials on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The violence in Kosovo, the southernmost province of Serbia,
threatens to reignite the ethnic and religious conflicts in the
Balkans that NATO introduced troops to stop in Bosnia. There are
fears that Albania and Macedonia could be drawn into a larger war
or even break up if Milosevic is not prevented from an ethnic
cleansing of the Albanian majority in Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians from Germany and Switzerland are joining the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The move to impose sanctions is a reversal of an American
initiative taken last month by the special envoy Robert Gelbard and
Richard Holbrooke, the architect of the Dayton accords that ended
the war in Bosnia, who had been asked to help break the logjam over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had pushed European allies to suspend sanctions on
Milosevic, who agreed to meet with Albanian separatists but then
unleashed the largest assault since the Bosnian war ended in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, in particular the British and the Germans, felt
that Milosevic had manipulated the Americans, promising to open a
dialogue but not promising it would lead to any results.
</P>
<P>
   Friday a senior American official did not dispute that judgment,
saying: ``There is a perception that Milosevic is using the talks
as a device to continue his campaign and not using them as a means
to find a peaceful solution to the problem. So the trend away from
sanctions has now been reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   British officials said that London had already concluded that a
stronger policy is needed to try to deter further violence by
Milosevic against the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, they said, the British government will push the
European Union's foreign ministers to introduce tough economic
sanctions, in particular a ban on new foreign investment that the
Clinton administration suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ban would be the most important measure because it
affects the economy most directly. It will prevent foreign
companies from taking part in sales of national companies that
Milosevic uses to finance his government. It is the European ban
that matters the most, because there has been very little American
investment in the rump Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Senior American officials said a formal imposition of the
investment ban might have to wait until Wednesday, when the
Americans meet the British and other members of the Contact Group
on Yugoslavia _ Germany, Italy, France and Russia. The foreign
ministers of those countries plus Russia, Canada and Japan will
meet in London on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that Washington favored a rapid NATO
study of all military options, but stressed that no decisions had
been made, expressing concern that Congress would be unlikely to
support any further American deployments in the Balkans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday members of the Senate Armed Services Committee
pressed Gelbard to set a date for withdrawing American troops from
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Holbrooke persuaded Milosevic to engage in talks with
ethnic Albanian leaders from Kosovo who favor independence through
peaceful means. In exchange, Washington convinced the Europeans to
suspend the implementation of an investment freeze on Yugoslavia,
angering many of its European allies who had reluctantly agreed to
go along with sanctions and who thought they were being suspended
too easily.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hooper of the Balkan Institute said Friday: ``I think
Holbrooke played into Milosevic's hands by bringing him carrots and
giving the stick to the Kosovo Albanians. Milosevic took those
concessions as a green light to proceed, and cracked down harder on
the Kosovars and in Serbia itself, withdrawing autonomy from
universities and moving against independent media.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivo Daalder, a National Security Council official in the first
Clinton term who is now at the University of Maryland, said that
Holbrooke had erred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Richard Holbrooke has a special rapport with Milosevic
and used it to great effect in Dayton and at other times,'' he
said. ``But in this case I think he misread Milosevic, who had no
interest in real dialogue. The suspension of the sanctions in
return for a procedural victory was ineffective, as the escalation
of the past week has shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who works in the private sector, was not immediately
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A huge crackdown by Milosevic's forces on the mainly ethnic
Albanian population of Kosovo has killed dozens of people, caused
thousands of refugees to flee into Albania and has displaced as
many as 40,000 people, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown caused ethnic Albanian leaders of Kosovo, led by
Ibrahim Rugova and received last week by President Clinton at the
White House, to cancel a session of talks with Yugoslav officials
scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were concerned that talking to Serb officials
while the fighting continued would undermine their own credibility
and the search for a peaceful solution, while further consolidating
the popular appeal of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which Milosevic
is trying to wipe out.
</P>
<P>
   After having pressed the Albanian Kosovo leaders to continue the
talks despite the crackdown, American officials said Friday that
they ``understood'' the cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense is that the Kosovar Albanians have some
justification in not wanting to talk right now,'' an American
official said carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke and Gelbard, working with the full approval of the
Clinton administration, had pressed to start the Rugova-Milosevic
dialogue, the first time Milosevic has talked to a Kosovo leader in
nearly a decade. Without dialogue, they argued, there could be no
peace, and efforts by European leaders to start such a dialogue had
failed.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic did not deliver, they and other American officials
said, the investment ban could easily be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belgrade is on notice we will not accept a sham dialogue,''
Gelbard said to the senators on Thursday, warning Milosevic that
suspended sanctions ``can be quickly reinstated and that we will
work with the allies to develop additional measures if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   That moment has now come, American officials said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
