u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH CANDIDATES WILL ALWAYS BE WITH US
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Herb Kohl is a low-key, soft-spoken member of
the US Senate's millionaire caucus. The son of immigrants, he
parlayed a Milwaukee grocery fortune into political success in
1988, winning the Wisconsin seat he has held ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But he almost lost his first race when his wealth and
inexperience became issues. ``We wanted him to respond to the
attacks, but he said no,'' recalls his campaign consultant, David
Doak. ``Herb thought that wealthy newcomers had to behave
differently in politics. And even though that election was very
close, he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Doak belongs to another millionaire caucus, the Gephardt-Kennedy
consortium of political consultants. Three hired guns, whose
political training took place under the aegis of the Missouri
congressman and the Massachusetts senator, were at triangular odds
in the June 2 California gubernatorial primary. Doak backed the
winner, Lieutenant Governor Gray Davis. His former partner, Bob
Shrum, produced the thousands of ads purchased by former airline
tycoon Al Checchi, and Bill Carrick was media guru for
Representative Jane Harman.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spent about $12 million, raised from other people. Harman
coughed up about $15 million, mostly from her husband's checkbook.
Checchi laid out $40 million from his own fortune, built on
corporate makeovers of Marriott, Disney, and Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive primary in American history tested a New
Testament truism, from the Book of St. Matthew, 19:24: ``It is
easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a
rich man to enter into the kingdom of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Future political consultants will rewrite their pitch: ``You're
a much better candidate than Checci or Harman, Mr. or Ms. Potential
Client. I suggest a closer look at that camel's favorability
ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it cost Checchi $60 per vote, last week's defeat may
have been a bargain. Most nominees for governor of California
contract Potomac Fever and consider running for president, a task
that requires serious money.
</P>
<P>
   California has spawned 15 such candidacies in the past 50 years.
Earl Warren, a two-time governor, was a national candidate in 1948.
Richard Nixon, who ran for governor in 1962, ran nationwide five
times. Ronald Reagan ran four times, Pat Brown gave it a
favorite-son feint in 1960. Pat's son, Jerry, ran for president
three times. Pete Wilson, the incumbent, ran in 1996, actually in
1995, since he never made it to the New Hampshire presidential
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Brown is now mayor-elect of the city of Oakland, many
acres of which Harman and Checchi could have purchased for a
reasonable price with the amount they spent on political ads.
</P>
<P>
   The next rich candidate will probably demand better commercials.
When Checchi campaigned in the streets of San Francisco, several
voters said to him, ``You're so much better than your
commercials.'' This observation contradicts the essence of American
advertising: The ad is supposed to be better than the product.
</P>
<P>
   No one can make millions without some charm or originality, but
Checchi's first ads lacked either. Cliche-ridden strolls on the
beach talked of thoroughly poll-tested bromides that few real
voters talked about. He wanted ``a 10 percent cut in state
bureaucracy'' as a way to finance school aid, even though
California has one of the lowest per-capita state payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   When Checchi turned negative, attacking Harman, the few real
voters he encountered saw no resemblance to the villain in the
30-second melodramas they had seen. His ads made Checchi seem like
Bela Lugosi and Boris Karloff put together.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson Doak learned from Senator Kohl will be tested in
future campaigns by rich candidates. A humbler, or at least less
arrogant, camel can saunter through the eye of that needle. Others
will look at last week's voting, assuring themselves that they will
be smarter than Harman or Checchi. Steve Forbes, who ran for
president in 1996, will not be discouraged and plans to renew his
membership in the Mensa Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
