A6885 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-DIRECTORS-ART     06-05 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-DIRECTORS-ART-$ADV07-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUND DIRECTORS: EMPTY SUITS IN THE BOARD ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 7)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic comparing compensation for mutual fund and
corporate directors is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's a mutual fund director to do? Lately, when independent
directors have stood up to fund managers, they've gotten their ears
boxed. And when, to some eyes, the directors have let fund managers
go their own way, they've gotten their ears boxed again.
</P>
<P>
   Consider events of the last two years, a period in which the
fund industry has experienced some of its most rapid growth ever:
</P>
<P>
   _ When the independent directors of two fund families, the
Navellier and Fundamental funds, asserted their legal authority to
remove portfolio managers at some of those funds, they swiftly
found themselves the targets of nasty proxy battles waged by the
fund managers _ and, in the case of the Navellier directors, a
shareholder lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   _ When the Securities and Exchange Commission brought charges
against the managers of the Parnassus fund and the Rockies fund,
contending violations of securities laws, it also charged the
funds' independent directors with failing to properly value
securities owned by the funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago,
questioned the independence of directors after finding that among
the 82 largest fund families, the more that directors were paid,
the more that shareholders shelled out in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a lawsuit brought by a shareholder of the Brazil fund, a
closed-end fund managed by Scudder Kemper Investments, a federal
judge in Manhattan agreed with the plaintiff that outside directors
who received compensation for sitting on the board of more than one
fund in the same family might not be independent at all.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, if ever, since the current system of mutual fund
oversight was laid out in the Investment Company Act of 1940 have
fund directors been under fire on so many fronts at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, you've got innumerable parties, including the
SEC, emphasizing the importance of the independence of directors,''
said Robert J. Zutz, a partner in the Washington office of the
Kirkpatrick &AMP; Lockhart law firm and a specialist in mutual fund
law. ``But on the other hand, where to the greatest degree
imaginable, directors have exercised their independence, they get
caught up in these unfortunate situations. Ultimately, it could
cause a director to pause and take the consequences into account
before deciding to act.''
</P>
<P>
   To almost any degree that directors hesitate, individual
investors stand to lose. Shareholders in most publicly traded
corporations can expect various parties _ institutional investors,
independent watchdog groups and securities analysts, to name a few
_ to help a company's board keep an eye on what insiders are doing.
But the fund industry leaves the job almost solely to independent
directors _ a disparate bunch. At even the biggest fund families,
they can range in background from experienced corporate managers
and directors to the friends or college buddies of the top
executives of the fund management company.
</P>
<P>
   Their authority, moreover, is unique in American business,
because of the peculiar legal fictions that define mutual funds. In
theory, a fund is owned by its shareholders, who hire independent
directors to run it. The directors select companies to manage the
fund, to underwrite the sale of shares and to provide services to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, of course, the entire operation is run by one fund
company _ Fidelity or Merrill Lynch, Navallier or Fundamental _
which not only provides all those services, but is the brand name
that brings shareholders to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent years, as even some of the most mediocre fund
companies have generated spectacular returns, the balance of power
has kept shifting farther from fund directors and toward the
companies that conceive, market and manage mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in and around the fund industry say that is just
fine. After all, they note, funds have piled up $5 trillion in
assets _ doubling in size in just the last three years _ with
barely a whiff of the scandals seen in the banking, savings and
loan, brokerage and insurance industries. But around the fringes of
the fund business, the strain is starting to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many mutual fund companies are so new that the industry has
just not had enough time and experience to sort out the rules and
responsibilities,'' said John A. Hill, chairman of First Reserve
Corp., an energy investment firm. He also serves as an independent
director of the Putnam funds and has sat on the boards of several
publicly traded companies. ``Some mutual fund boards are aware of
the issues,'' he said, ``but many others are not very aware at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, for its part, has acknowledged that some aspects of
mutual fund governance need examination. But the commission appears
to be edging quite gingerly into the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proper role of a fund's board has become a bit
controversial lately,'' allowed SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt Jr. in
an address in May to fund industry executives. This fall, he said,
the SEC will be the host for a round table intended ``to air the
issues and to work toward a consensus on whether changes are needed
in the current system.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the SEC has been flooded with requests from fund
companies, corporate governance experts and academics to
participate in the round table, SEC officials said. But until that
discussion takes place, many directors may be wondering if taking
decisive action is more likely to harm than help investors.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that is the question raised by events surrounding
Navellier Aggressive Small Cap Equity, once a $250 million fund
that saw its assets shrink by three-quarters last year as the
fund's manager battled with its independent directors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
