<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PORSCHE 911 DIFFERS IN STYLING, COMFORT AND CONVENIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Porsche has done it again; if you thought the last 911 was good,
if you thought (as I did) that the Boxster was about as perfect a
car as you'd want, prepare to change your mind. A brief tour of the
new 911 _ Type 996 _ would indicate that ``best'' title has a new
car under it.
</P>
<P>
   The new 911, a 1999 model, comes as Carrera Coupe or Cabriolet
with a 296-horsepower (258 ft/lb torque), 3.4-liter, six-cylinder,
water-cooled, boxer engine. It is the first water-cooled engine in
a 911 and employs two radiators with electrically powered fans. The
new Carrera with six-speed manual gearbox is $65,030, with
five-speed Tiptronic, $68,450. The convertible is $74,460 with
manual, $77,880 with Tiptronic. Tiptronic is Porsche's dual-mode
automatic that either works as full automatic or is shifted
manually with fingertip controls on the steering wheel. As usual
with Porsche, the option list is long, offering the possibility of
ordering something unique _ and exceedingly expensive. The basic
equipment ought to satisfy most drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Coupe comes with an electrically operated sunroof; the
Cabriolet's ragtop folds out of sight automatically in 20 seconds
at the touch of a button.
</P>
<P>
   The car differs substantially from its predecessor model in
styling, comfort, and handling. Acceleration is still
neck-snapping; cornering ability is phenomenal. A day's tour in a
new 911 leaves one panting for more time behind the wheel. The
911's rude habit of educating drivers through sudden oversteer was
corrected several incarnations ago; the newest model introduces a
level of forgiveness unheard of in a Porsche with the latest in
traction control and antiskid electronics.
</P>
<P>
   And this year Porsche offers a wheeled accessory _ a mountain
bike. Actually two mountain bikes, the S for $2,250 and the FS for
$4,500 _ if you forget to refuel in your exuberance behind the
wheel, now you can pedal in style for a can of gas. I do not know
if Porsche offers a matching gas can with the Porsche crest, but
maybe they should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-DIRECTORS-ART     06-05 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-DIRECTORS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: independent directors.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louis G. Navellier, a money manager based in Incline Village,
Nev., founded the fund in 1993. Three years later, Louis Navellier
proposed merging the fund into a separate fund group that had a
different set of independent directors _ steps that he said would
reduce operating expenses through economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   But the directors of Aggressive Small Cap Equity opposed the
move, and the difference of opinion quickly grew ugly.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which said Louis Navellier refused to provide
information about his management company, dismissed him in March
1997 and hired Massachusetts Financial Services, proprietor of the
MFS family of mutual funds, to manage the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Navellier, who said he provided the board with all the
information to which it was entitled, fought back. Under the
Investment Company Act, the directors were required within 120 days
to get shareholder approval for the manager change. With a campaign
of mailings and phone calls, Louis Navellier rallied enough
investor support to block the move. The directors rehired him _ and
subsequently resigned.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult, though, to declare anyone a winner. During the
battle, most shareholders simply moved their money out of the fund,
whose assets have dwindled to $60 million. And now, Louis Navellier
has joined with several of his loyal shareholders in a class action
suit against the former independent directors, their lawyer and
MFS, seeking to recover up to $14 million in capital gains taxes
that shareholders incurred last year.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants and others in the fund industry have asked why
the SEC did not support what the independent directors believed was
an attempt to protect shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the Navellier directors did precisely what they
were supposed to do: They raised the issues and went to
shareholders to vote on them,'' said C. Meyrick Payne, a senior
partner at Management Practice, a New York consulting firm that
works with independent directors. ``But there was a moment when you
wondered whether the SEC should have been a little more
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Barbash, director of the commission's division of
investment management, which regulates mutual funds, declined to
comment on the Navellier case. But in general, he said, the agency
seeks to avoid taking any action that could influence how
shareholders vote in a proxy contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SEC tries to play referee and make sure everybody plays
fair,'' Barbash said. ``We'll throw a flag if someone is clearly
violating the rules. But a proxy contest is not a situation where
the SEC should come in and say something that will change the
outcome of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If Navellier were an isolated case, it might be dismissed as an
anomaly in a rapidly growing, diverse industry. But another
confrontation is occurring at the Fundamental funds, a New
York-based family of six funds with total assets of about $170
million. And in this case, shareholders may be faced with an even
less appealing set of choices.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamental's history has not been full of investing success;
its volatile funds tend to careen between the top and bottom
performance quartiles. Fundamental's New York Muni, its largest
fund, is the only municipal bond fund of any type to lose money in
the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that investors in the funds had suffered enough, their
directors voted last year to seek a replacement for the company
that has long managed the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Vincent Malanga, president of Fundamental Portfolio
Advisors, the fund manager, supported the move; in fact, he found a
potential replacement, Tocqueville Asset Management, which oversees
a family of funds operating under the Tocqueville name. The board
concurred, and, as an interim measure, a manager from Tocqueville
began managing the Fundamental funds last year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the fund's filings with the SEC, the board soon
discovered that the manager had been routing portfolio trades
through a Tocqueville-related brokerage firm, a potential violation
of securities regulations. Tocqueville dismissed him, but the four
independent Fundamental directors split on whether to go ahead with
the plan to hire Tocqueville permanently. The two directors who
opposed the hiring resigned.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Malanga and his firm were charged by the SEC
with failing to disclose the risks involved in special securities
owned by one of the Fundamental funds in 1993-94; the firm, without
admitting or denying the allegations, recently settled a
false-advertising complaint by the National Association of
Securities Dealers over the same issue.
</P>
<P>
   Now Malanga has turned against Tocqueville; he wants
shareholders to replace all the board members with a new group
that, presumably, would again name him the funds' manager. The
directors responded by throwing out Malanga and his firm June 1 and
hiring Toqueville to take over the funds _ a move that requires
shareholder confirmation within 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   Given the situation, even the most educated shareholders might
have trouble deciding what is in their best interest. As with the
Navellier funds, many have decided to flee rather than to choose
sides; assets have dropped by nearly one-third over the last year.
And while a consequence of that decision for investors is to lock
in losses, some in the industry say it is the best way to
discipline fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that if a fund company is not looking out for
shareholders, we get to vote with our feet,'' said Gregory
Sullivan, a principal at Sullivan Bruyette Speros &AMP; Blayney, a
McLean, Va., investment adviser. ``There are a lot of alternative
funds for us to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   The system, of course, is set up to provide checks and balances
other than pitched battles and mass redemptions of shares. But if
shareholders can get hurt when a fund's directors and its managers
are at loggerheads, they can also suffer if everyone gets too cozy.
</P>
<P>
   That is the assertion in a lawsuit that threw the fund industry
into a tizzy last year. The lawsuit, brought by a shareholder of
the Brazil fund, contends that directors of the fund were likely to
put the interests of Scudder, its manager, ahead of those of
shareholders, because the directors received tens of thousands of
dollars for overseeing scores of other Scudder funds as well.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert Sweet of U.S. District Court in Manhattan, in
refusing to dismiss the complaint, said that ``the close and
financially rewarding relationship with Scudder is sufficient to
call into question the independence and disinterest of these
directors.'' The case is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   The industry mainstream was shocked by the judge's ruling. ``I
think he was off his rocker,'' said Thomas R. Smith Jr., a partner
at the New York law firm of Brown &AMP; Wood, and co-chairman of an
American Bar Association task force that wrote a legal guidebook
for fund directors. ``The whole structure of the '40 Act provides
that serving on more than one board will not make you'' an insider,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC took no formal position in the case. ``Our view is that
the amount of money a director is making does not make him
independent or not independent,'' said Barbash. ``But shareholders
should be told how much the directors are being paid.'' That
information is included in a fund's SEC filings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6891 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-DIRECTORS-ART     06-05 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-DIRECTORS-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: SEC filings.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fund companies have less direct control over fund directors than
one might assume. Independent directors themselves usually select
nominees to fill vacancies, and nominees must be voted on by
shareholders. Independent directors also set their own salaries and
hire their own outside lawyers. And while the law requires only
that 40 percent of a fund's board be independent, in practice they
constitute a majority on nearly all fund boards.
</P>
<P>
   Fund directors also say they regularly stand up to a fund's
managers. ``I'd say that every year we have some issue,
particularly involving the contracts to manage the funds, where we
have some disagreement with the manager,'' said Hill, the Putnam
director.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that directors are always pushing for lower
fees. ``We have to make sure that the fees the funds are paying are
competitive enough to keep the players in the game,'' said Stephen
West, a lawyer at the New York firm of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell who
serves as an independent director of the Pioneer and Winthrop Focus
funds. ``The competition for managerial talent is enormous, which
has caused the cost of running the business to explode.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fund industry has boomed in size, fund companies have
seen their profitability soar. In part, the growth comes from
having more assets to manage. But an oft-cited Morningstar study
found that newer funds charge higher management fees than older
funds. And in another study, Morningstar found that directors were
paid more by fund families with higher expenses, raising ``serious
questions about the role independent trustees play in protecting
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Signals from the SEC have been mixed on this front. Regulators
have warned that they will be quick to question the directors of
fund companies that consistently get higher-than-average management
fees but produce below-par performance. Yet Levitt told fund
executives in May that ``directors don't have to guarantee that a
fund pays the lowest rates, but they do have to make sure that fees
fall within a reasonable band.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has been more consistent in challenging directors whom
it judges have failed to oversee fund managers' conduct. It has
recently brought enforcement cases against the Parnassus fund, a
mutual fund, and the Rockies fund, a closed-end fund, charging
independent directors with failing to adequately police how the
fund's managers valued certain stocks. The charges are being fought
by the directors and the fund companies involved.
</P>
<P>
   While a different form of corporate governance might be able to
better assure the independence and competence of directors,
shareholders don't seem to be banging down the doors for change.
Still, some new ideas might come up at the SEC round table this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the rest of the world, and in unit trusts in the
United States, fund directors are not responsible for setting a
fund's management fee. Free from questions about the economics of a
fund's management contracts, directors could spend their time
monitoring a manager's business practices _ how brokerage
commissions are allocated, whether investment guidelines are being
followed and the like.
</P>
<P>
   And shareholders are now being given more leeway to directly
influence the governance of their funds. In May, the SEC reversed a
longstanding precedent, ruling that directors of closed-end funds
must adhere to results of votes on shareholder proposals to replace
the manager of a fund. (A closed-end fund operates much like a
mutual fund, except that its finite number of shares are traded on
a stock exchange.)
</P>
<P>
   The industry may also take a fresh look at some existing,
alternative governance plans. The boards of the American Express
IDS funds, for example, employ full-time officers separate from the
officers of the management company. That structure emerged after a
struggle for control of the funds' managers in the late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the board is confronted with issues that raise questions
about whether a fund's assets are being properly used and managed,
that structure adds an additional safeguard,'' said Leslie Ogg,
president of Board Services Corp., the independent company that
oversees the operations of the American Express IDS funds.
</P>
<P>
   Even that structure does not guarantee that directors will stand
up to management on all issues. For that, Ogg said, responsibility
ultimately lies with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does take a strong SEC to make independent directors
effective,'' Ogg said. ``In the end, as a director you've got very
little economic leverage. You've only got your prestige. That's the
point where a director has got to be able to say that he has the
support of regulators in acting independently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
