<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHREWD AND CYNICAL COMEDY DEBUTS ONB HBO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEX AND THE CITY &QC; 
Starring: Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis,
Cynthia Nixon &QC; 
On: HBO &QC; 
Time: The two-episode premiere is Saturday at 9:45. The regular
timeslot for the series will be Sundays at 9 p.m. &QC; 
Rated: TVMA  &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cupid has deserted the New York of ``Sex and the City,'' a
nighttime landscape of clubs and galleries where men and women vie
for what George Costanza on ``Seinfeld'' called ``hand.'' Slippery
bachelors and ``modelizers'' narrowly avoid depth and commitment,
while beautiful, successful women wake up to discover they are 41
and lonely. He takes her home to see his Ross Bleckner painting,
she angles for breakfast at Tiffany's.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes on ``Sex and the City,'' a shrewd and very
cynical comedy that premieres tonight at 9:45 on HBO. Created by
Darren Star, the man behind ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Melrose
Place,'' it's an original series that is quite different from
Star's sudsier ventures, particularly with its de-emphasis on
ongoing story line. The concept, based on Candace Bushnell's
columns for the New York Observer, has Sarah Jessica Parker's
Carrie Bradshaw writing about the Manhattan dating scene by using
her own experiences and those of her three close friends. She's a
self-labeled ``sexual anthropologist,'' and she goes on nightly
field trips to note the mating habits of the wealthy and maybe
bring home something resembling romance for herself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.3l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With all the late-night clubbing and yuppie attitude, the New
York of ``Sex in the City'' looks more like the 1980s versions
portrayed in books and movies like ``Bright Lights, Big City'' and
``Slaves of New York.'' Parker and her 30-something friends are
fairly obsessed with the rules of chic culture, gathering regularly
to engage in racy and ironic talk about whether the man or the
woman has the power in a given situation, and what role money plays
in the game. Along with Parker's Carrie, the women are Kristin
Davis's naive Charlotte, Cynthia Nixon's intellectual Miranda, and
Kim Cattrall's predatory Samantha. In tonight's episode, the
weakest of the three sent for review, Carrie experiments with the
typically male approach to sex, trying to have no feelings
afterward. In the second episode, the women deal with modelizers
(men who date only models), and in the third, called ``Valley of
the Twentysomething Guys,'' they mix it up with a few slackers.
</P>
<P>
   Parker deploys Carrie's thoughts in a witty voice-over, and
occasionally she breaks the fourth wall to comment on the action.
``Are men in their 20s the new designer drug?'' she wonders. While
Carrie's big ideas are explored in each episode, ``Sex and the
City'' is also savvy enough to smile wryly on its heroine's
journalistic tendency to invent trends: ``Were women in New York
really giving up on love and throttling up on power?'' Carrie asks,
preparing for her next column. ``What a tempting thought.'' Parker
is perfect as a woman who is attractive enough to run with the
beautiful people, but self-conscious and cautious enough to be
gathering observations for a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' is sure to offend some, with its retro and
not very politically correct approach to the battle of the sexes.
It takes a grim view of single living, generally putting the women
at a disadvantage _ unless they are contriving revenge of some
sort. Almost none of the characters is particularly likable _
unless he or she is angling for something. What's refreshing about
``Sex and the City'' is that it pushes to a darkly comic extreme
the situations that already fuel the many urban-singles sitcoms on
network TV, particularly those with female leads like ``Suddenly
Susan'' and ``Caroline in the City.'' More social satire than
sitcom, it looks openly at relationships steeped in ambivalence,
fear, and the games people play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
