<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FLIGHT-DELAYS-350&AMP;     06-05 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FLIGHT-DELAYS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF FLIGHTS DELAYED BY FAA COMPUTER CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of flights were delayed early Friday
morning, some for more than an hour, as a computer system used by
controllers at an air-traffic control center on New York's Long
Island crashed during a software upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The problems arose as computer specialists from the Federal
Aviation Administration, working on the midnight shift, were
testing new software intended to fix a glitch in the computer
system that handles traffic around Newark (N.J.) International
Airport. But the technicians could not install the software
properly, and when they switched back to the old software, air
controllers' screens froze, said FAA spokesperson Arlene Salac.
</P>
<P>
   Some screens lost the data identifying planes by name, type,
destination and altitude. That forced the controllers to reduce
sharply the number of planes in the air to a number they could
track in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that from about 5:30 to 7:30 a.m., well into the
morning rush, controllers at the Terminal Radar Approach Control,
in Westbury, N.Y., had very limited data on their screens.
</P>
<P>
   Some screens froze, some showed only what the controllers call a
``splat,'' a set of digits that alternates between showing air
speed and altitude, but not identity, airplane type or destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the volume isn't too high, you can work airplanes
like that,'' said Dean Iacopelli, an official of the controllers'
union at the control center. ``Assuming good weather, which was
today, you could probably do two to four, but four would be about
the most you'd want to be fooling around with,'' said Iacopelli, of
the National Air Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure occurred at a time of day when a flood of planes
belonging to Federal Express, United Parcel Service and DHL arrives
at airports in the New York region, as well as red-eye passenger
flights from the West Coast, Iacopelli said. As a result, some
flights had to be told to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the worst nightmare, but it's a nightmare,'' said
Iacopelli. ``We've lost a pretty big tool of ours.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to preliminary data from the FAA, 153 departing planes
were delayed at Newark, for an average of 41 minutes and a maximum
of 86 minutes; 64 departing planes were delayed at New York's La
Guardia Airport for an average of 24 minutes and a maximum of 37,
and 5 planes were delayed at Teterboro Airport in New Jersey, for
an average of 36 minutes and a maximum of 77. No delays were
reported at New York's Kennedy International Airport, which is also
handled by the Westbury control center.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 24 planes arriving at La Guardia were delayed for
an average of 15 minutes. The FAA figures did not count airplanes
that were held on the ground in distant locations until the problem
was fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many other problems they've had,'' Ms. Salac said, ``they
don't know exactly what caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   But an official of the union that represents electronics
technicians at the control center where the problem occurred said
the cause had been identified. The official, Jimmy Anderson, of the
Professional Airways System Specialists, said that the software
engineers were trying to install a software patch on about 50
different workstations over a network, and that some of the
workstations accepted the new software while others were
``write-protected,'' like a floppy disk that has been set up not to
accept new data. Then they tried to run the system with two
different versions of the software, said Anderson, who worked the
midnight shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting all these printouts, `incorrect program
version, incorrect program version,''' Anderson said. In the end,
he said, managers decided to fix the problem terminal by terminal,
rather than shutting the whole system down for two or three minutes
and fixing them over the network.
</P>
<P>
   Software at the control center has been upgraded dozens of times
without problems. But around the country, the FAA has often created
major failures in its complicated, tightly linked systems when
trying to upgrade them.
</P>
<P>
   The patch in this case was for a new system called the
Convergence Runway Display Aid, which is supposed to make it easier
for controllers to let planes land and take off using two crossing
runways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
