<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMAN-TRAIN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-TRAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS MOURN VICTIMS, NOTION OF TECHNOLOGICAL EXCELLENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Harmut Fricke never used to think twice about hopping
on a high-speed Inter City Express train for business trips. But in
the wake of Germany's largest postwar train crash, Fricke was
wondering Friday whether to get on any train at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, I never had a strange feeling about getting on a
train,'' said Fricke, a 50-year-old tax consultant, watching a
gleaming, snub-nosed ICE train slide into Berlin's main train
station, Bahnhof Zoo. ``But my confidence is a little bit shaken.
So-called `German technological perfection' might not be so
perfect, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   As investigators pored over the twisted remains of the ICE 884
that crashed Wednesday, killing at least 96, Germany was plunged
into grief. Across the country, flags hung at half staff. Train
workers wore black armbands. Mourners laid flowers near the crash
site in the town of Eschede.
</P>
<P>
   But the country also is lamenting another loss: the once
unshakeable belief that Germany could create fast _ and safe _
trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ICE is more than just a train. It is a symbol, almost a
myth,'' noted the Stuttgarter Zeitung, a daily newspaper in
southern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   From washing machines to vacuum cleaners, German industry has
prided itself on products that reflect the new Germany itself:
efficient, safe, and reliable. But when it came to automobiles and
trains, Germany added speed to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Germany and its industrial competitor, France, have
sought to create fast trains that could speed up travel on Europe's
far-ranging rail system. The German ICE can travel at 173 miles per
hour; France's TGV hits 186 miles per hour, railway officials say.
</P>
<P>
   This week's train crash has thrown these values into question.
The French and the Japanese, who also have high-speed trains, are
watching the investigation closely, wondering what the results will
mean for their rail service.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the crash was that a rear wheel broke off 3
or 4 miles before the train derailed and slammed into a road
overpass. Tons of concrete crashed into the train's middle section.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know if it was a failure of the train, the
tracks, or whatever,'' said Christian Hopper, a spokesman for
DeutscheBahn, or German Rail.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, German Rail idled 60 of its 104 ICE trains,
delaying hundreds of passengers. On the arrival board in Berlin,
nearly every arriving train had been marked either ``cancelled'' or
``delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   But few passengers complained. Instead, they stared at the
massive TV screen in the waiting room that bore a sobering message
of regret from German Rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grieve for the dead of Eschede, and we'd like to offer our
sympathies for people who got hurt and the families of the
victims,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, 133 million passengers have ridden on Germany's ICE
trains. While not used as extensively as cars or planes, trains are
used far more in Europe than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And train travel in Europe remains far more safe than driving.
In 1995, there were 44,000 road fatalities in the European Union
and 936 rail deaths, according to Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
   But that is little comfort to Silvia Kienitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't get on an ICE,'' sniffed the Berliner, who came to
the train station here to see a friend off. ``German technology
isn't as great as everybody thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash came as Germany was already deep into national
self-reflection, in an election year that is seeing the economy
steadily worsen. And the accident was the worst since June 1945,
when a train wreck claimed 102 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the tangled train wreckage and the broken bodies were
everywhere, on the television and in the newspapers. Germans, as
they waited for trains, or waited in cafes, couldn't help but
reflect on the tragedy and the questions it raised.
</P>
<P>
   Some wondered why Germany needed to be so obsessed with speed.
``Why do things have to be faster and faster all the time?'' asked
Ursula Gensicke, 72, as she waited for her local, slow train
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurter Rundschau agreed. ``What to do?'' editorialized
the left-wing newspaper. ``Travel less. Go slower. Change the means
of transportation. Stay at home. All thinkable, some of it
feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed promises to become a political issue this summer, when the
Bundestag, or parliament, will discuss a proposed new
Berlin-Hamburg train. The Green Party hopes to halt the project,
arguing faster trains simply aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But many Germans said that while they've lost their illusions
about safety on fast-speed train, they haven't lost their faith in
train travel, overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite this horrible accident, the train is the most secure
means of transport,'' said Gila Altman, the transport spokesman for
the Green Party. ``We can't be 100 percent sure of it, but that
doesn't mean we should look for another technology.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, the nervous Harmut Fricke decided to board his
train, an ICE to Hannover, not far from the scene of the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
