<HEADLINE>
CHIP MAKER DIODES FORECASTS `SIGNIFICANT' EARNINGS DIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. _ Blaming an industrywide slump in
semiconductor prices and the Asian currency crisis, Diodes Inc.
said Friday it expects to post ``significantly lower''
second-quarter earnings than it did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to say precisely how far this quarter's results
will fall, said spokesman Philip Bourdillon. ``We chose to say
`significantly' _ that's as precise as we can go at this point with
three weeks left in the quarter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to release the second-quarter results during
the week of July 27.
</P>
<P>
   Those results will reflect a downward trend the company also saw
in its first quarter, when per-share earnings fell by 3 cents from
fourth-quarter 1997 results to 22 cents ($1.2 million).
</P>
<P>
   Second quarter 1997 net income had been $1.2 million, or 23
cents per diluted share, on sales of $15.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because these adverse market conditions are still with us and
have in fact been more severe in the first two months of the second
quarter, we expect second-quarter earnings to be significantly
lower than earnings in the first quarter,'' company President
Michael Rosenberg said in a statement from Westlake Village
northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock closed Friday at 7 3/4 (one-eighth, down 3/4
(three-quarters).
</P>
</TEXT>
