<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-HNS &LR;      06-05 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ELMONT, N.Y. _ Horse racing is ``the sport of kings,'' but Mike
Pegram, the multimillionaire who owns Triple Crown aspirant Real
Quiet, seems anything but aristocratic.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He typically wears jeans, cowboy boots and a golf shirt, almost
never wears ties. He drinks Budweiser often and French champagne
only when ``there's a woman involved.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a college dropout who's so unsophisticated that some New
York racing writers have called him ``a character out of Hee Haw.''
The blue-eyed Pegram contributes to the image by describing
himself, in a country drawl, as ``a little guy racing the back
roads.''
</P>
<P>
   It hardly seems possible those roads have led to New York and a
$5 million bonus from Visa if Real Quiet captures the Triple Crown.
The 3-year-old colt can do it by winning the 1{-mile Belmont Stakes
today at 4:27 p.m. CDT (Ch. 13).
</P>
<P>
   Pegram has invited some 200 friends and relatives to accompany
him at the Triple Crown coronation. He's providing hotel rooms and
catered meals.
</P>
<P>
   He knows what it's like to be a hanger-on. He was here last year
as Bob Baffert's friend, cheering on Silver Charm, the winner of
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram is very much a man of the people. While the other owners
were up in their booths at Churchill Downs, he watched the Derby
from the ground floor, huddling with the masses in front of a
television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having trouble getting in position to see it,'' he said.
``I had to yell, `Hey, I got a horse in this race.'''
</P>
<P>
   He would not allow the post-Derby picture-taking ceremony to
begin until his entourage had assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worth holding up the winner's circle to get my friends
in it,'' he said. ``When you've got the fastest horse and you have
your friends with you, you're on top of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't forgotten those on the bottom. Upon arriving in
Long Island on Wednesday, he headed for the Ronald McDonald House
to promote care for ill and needy children. Last week, he announced
he would donate all royalties from Real Quiet's merchandising
rights to Ronald McDonald House Charities.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, 46 and a divorced father of two grown children, grew up
in Princeton, Ind., and has been a sports fan since his boyhood
days, when he ``skipped school to go to Churchill Downs.''
</P>
<P>
   He also played basketball and baseball and was scouted by
major-league teams before a severe hamstring injury ended his
athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, he moved with his father, Jim, to California and
opened a couple of McDonald's franchises. He began racing horses in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram relocated to the state of Washington, where he put
together a string of 22 McDonald's while continuing his racing
business. When he entered a quarter-horse deal in 1987, Baffert was
the trainer, and the two men became friends.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram soon persuaded Baffert to switch to thoroughbreds, and
they began assembling a moderately priced stable that has expanded
to 60 horses.
</P>
<P>
   Until Real Quiet began making noise, Pegram's most notable horse
was Isitingood, who broke Dr. Fager's revered record of 1:32 for a
mile. By the way, Pegram has a penchant for giving his horses
provocative names, such as Straight to Bed and Zippersup.
</P>
<P>
   As for Real Quiet, he was bred in Florida and cost Pegram only
$17,000. Real Quiet's sire, Quiet American, was no Triple Crown
threat; his biggest win was the NYRA Mile at Aqueduct. Real Quiet's
dam, Believe It, earned only $31,000 in her racing career.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the colt's pedigree unexciting, he was scrawny,
with crooked legs. Said his breeder, Colombian-born Eduardo
Gaviria: ``It was the cheapest price I ever got for a horse, but I
was happy. I was almost sure he was going to break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Most horsemen are happy to see Pegram succeed with a horse
everyone thought would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would feel about Real Quiet completing his triple
play, David Cross, who trains Belmont entry Classic Cat, said, ``I
would love to see the owner win it.'' Then he added, for emphasis,
``the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a jab at Baffert, the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Cross and other horsemen resent the fact that Baffert shows up
later at the barn than most trainers and is quick to claim credit
for his horses' success. His wisecracking ways and showmanship also
annoy the sport's traditionalists, such as the 62-year-old Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in some of his antics,'' Cross told the New
York Daily News. ``I think it makes a mockery of things. Some of
his statements are pretty stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody has harsh words for Pegram, who charms people with
his self-deprecating humor.
</P>
<P>
   He loves to mention his fondness for cold beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't drink coffee,'' he said. ``I start the morning with
Diet Coke and work my way on up.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't enjoy his recent flight from Phoenix (where he owns a
home), because the flight attendant cut him off after two beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said my face was red,'' Pegram said. ``I said, `Your face
is supposed to be red when you're leaving Arizona.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram's partying ways occasionally activate a case of gout. But
of course, that doesn't stop him. He's having too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   As he put it: ``Every morning, I wake up and look in the mirror
and I say, `I'm the luckiest (guy) God put on this earth. Who could
be having more fun than me?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2121EDT &QL; 
