A6910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STUDENT-JUDGE-NYT     06-05 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STUDENT-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED JUDGE, 89, RETURNS TO COLLEGE
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph DiFede hunched over a desk in his spartan
chambers at State Supreme Court in the Bronx and began mulling over
why, at this stage of his life, he decided to become a candidate
for a master's degree in history at the University of Rochester. He
is 89.
</P>
<P>
   A former judge of the New York State Supreme Court who has been
a hearing officer since retiring in 1985, he may have been inspired
by another former judge, Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr. When Holmes was
in his 90s, so the story goes, he learned ancient Greek so he could
read Plato in the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that was what drove me, or maybe it was that I don't
like to leave things unfinished,'' he said. ``I did all the course
work for the degree in the 1930s, but I never followed through and
wrote a thesis. Maybe it's that I have more free time now, or maybe
it's that as you grow older you look back and think of what you'd
like to do that you didn't get around to doing earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   So Friday, DiFede stood before a panel of two unsmiling
historians and a political scientist on the third floor of the Rush
Rhees Library on the Rochester campus. It took him about 20 minutes
to explain his paper on the ambiguities and contradictions of the
Labor-Management Relations Act of 1947, better known as the
Taft-Hartley law. Then he was grilled for about 40 minutes, coolly
explaining such esoterica as Provision 883 and its political
nuances.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph DiFede, who was born in Sicily and moved with his family
to Rochester in 1924, had graduated from the University of
Rochester with a degree in mathematics in 1933 and planned to do
graduate work in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 1933 was the year that Roosevelt took office,'' he said.
``That was a very exciting time, and math seemed just too
confining. I've always been interested in history and current
events, so I dropped math and from 1933 to 1935 I did the course
work for an M.A. degree in history.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, DiFede was elected to the state Assembly in Rochester,
but as a Democrat in a Republican district he was defeated the next
year. He earned a law degree and a doctorate at St. John's
University, specializing in labor and administrative law. He was
chief labor officer for the military government in Italy during
World War II. In 1955 Gov. Averell Harriman named him chairman of
the New York State Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   From that time on, DiFede was wrapped up in politics (he ran
unsuccessfully for New York City controller in 1961) and was
appointed a judge in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   After retirement, he began thinking about that unfinished M.A.,
and this year wrote to Thomas Jackson, the president of the
University of Rochester, asking whether he could use a law review
article he had written some years ago as a thesis.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, came the reply, but he would have to present the article
to the history faculty and defend it.
</P>
<P>
   After the defense, he was asked to step into the hallway while
the professors deliberated _ for a minute. ``It never takes long
when it goes well,'' said Robert Westbrook, chairman of the
department of history.
</P>
<P>
   The three professors marched into the hallway and congratulated
the graduate. ``Now,'' said Westbrook, ``we'd like to have you
enter our Ph.D. program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
