<HEADER>
A6912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-MINOR-LEAGUES-ART-     06-05 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MINOR-LEAGUES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN.: CONN., N.Y.) 
 MINOR LEAGUES CAPITALIZE ON NOSTALGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By IVER PETERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR, N.J. _ They filled the brand new Yogi Berra Stadium
Friday to watch a team that did not exist until this year and that
plays in a league few have even heard of.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The game was baseball, and for the fans who turned
out to see the fledgling New Jersey Jackals take on the
Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs, that was enough to fill every seat.
</P>
<P>
   Minor league baseball, a game that used to evoke languid summer
afternoons on pine board bleachers in some smiley rural corner, has
moved in force into the teeming suburbs of metropolitan New York.
It is nourished by nostalgia for a simpler version of a game
dominated by major league millionaires, and is financed by wealthy
businessmen with time and money to play out a childhood dream.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, 15 professional minor league teams, of widely
varying quality and affiliation, have been formed or have moved
into the populous region loosely bounded by Albany, Hartford and
Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   At their home opener Friday night, the Jackals had Berra
himself, the baseball sage and their stadium's namesake, to throw
out the first ball. But he was about the only link to the more
famous franchise in the Bronx, and that seemed to suit the fans
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 15 minutes from home, I bought a season ticket for $8 a
game and I'm practically sitting on the field,'' said George Rauth,
who brought his 8-year-old grandson. ``It would cost me $8 just to
park at Yankee Stadium.'' (It's $6, to be precise.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, major league owners helped create the minor-league boom
by forcing their farm teams to acquire newer, safer stadiums or
move. Municipalities, eager for new tax revenue or just hoping to
put a few more people on downtown streets after dark, have courted
the new teams with money and tax breaks. Nine new stadiums have
been built in the region since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Berra Stadium was built by Floyd Hall, the chairman of
Kmart Corp. and a resident of Montclair, who spent $15 million on
the ballpark and an attached complex of two ice rinks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the 172 minor league baseball clubs affiliated with
Major League Baseball sold 34.7 million tickets last year, compared
with 30 million in 1950, when there were 400 teams.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the region's 15 new teams are affiliated with the
major leagues, which has trademarked the term ``Minor League
Baseball.'' The others belong either to the 3-year-old Northeast
League, or this year's rookie, the Atlantic League, whose five
teams have only three stadiums among them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden interest? Team owners and club managers point to
a robust economy, the bargain basement admission prices and easy
access. Above all, they credit the mood of baby boomers as their
nests fill up.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound too philosophical, but for years our
society had gotten away from the family doing things together, and
people want to get back to that,'' said Peter Kirk, a partner in
three minor league teams in Maryland who is recognized as an expert
in marketing minor league baseball. ``It's nostalgia for the old
ball game, and minor league baseball is just tapping in to that.
It's something the family can do together.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What the casual fans get for the $2 parking and $8 box seats is
an intimate ball park with seating for 4,000 fans that is so close
to the game that the manager's hollering reaches the stands, along
with an atmosphere designed to have almost as much circus as
baseball to it. Children race the clumsy mascot around the bases
between innings (the mascot always loses), comedy acts like Myron
Noodleman, professional nerd, or Brackney's Mad Cap Mutts entertain
during the seventh-inning stretch, and commercial promotions erupt
at all times under the guise of crowd participation games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They come here and they see a dog catching Frisbees between
innings'' _ that would be Brackney and his dogs _ ``and you give
all the kids a baseball bat and that kind of makes it for them,''
said Tony Torre, general manager of the New Jersey Cardinals, a
farm team of the National League's St. Louis Cardinals, which moved
to New Jersey from Hamilton, Ontario, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans at Friday night's game in Montclair also brought
bitter memories of the 1994 baseball strike and its canceled World
Series. Winfield and Tracy Parsons, sitting in the $6 bench seats,
came in part to show their sons Scott and Daniel a game played by
hungry young dreamers earning an average of $900 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely had it with the majors, a bunch of overpaid
crybabies,'' said Parsons, who teaches at Montclair State College.
``I want my kids to start getting their baseball experience in a
place like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parsons favored the practical. ``Where else can I take my
family out for an evening of good, clean fun for $26? The movies
cost more than this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
