<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCup-HNS &LR;      06-05 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World </SLUG>
 Cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dutch may be only way to go
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Going Dutch seems to have taken on a whole new meaning lately.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it has been the abundantly talented Netherlands team
that somehow finds a way to fall short of expectations at the World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Going Dutch, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, fans of this traditional power bemoan the
apparently unstoppable 1974 Dutch team that sailed into the World
Cup final only to turn in a nervous, sloppy performance and lose to
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the Dutch again looked unbeatable, but once
into the Cup final again collapsed in a 3-1 loss to Argentina.
Similar disappointments occurred in 1982 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
   And ever since, going Dutch in the World Cup has meant going
belly up when the pressure was on.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the Netherlands enters the World Cup on a
tremendous roll, with a new coach, a veteran team, a superstar
scorer in Denis Bergkamp and an overall confidence that should help
it finally live up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   One opposing coach even has said of this Dutch team that it now
has an, ``over-my-dead-body'' approach to the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, then once-proud Mexico seems to have taken
on the role of the team that needs life support.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it is the Mexicans who have gone Dutch. They are
spiraling out of control downward, with no apparent hope for a
turnaround in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a contender for the Cup and ranked as high as
No. 4 in the world, Mexico has struggled so badly of late that
earlier this week it even lost to VfL Wolfsburg, a mediocre German
Bundesliga team that had finished 14th in the First Division this
year. The score was 4-1. A humiliating rout.
</P>
<P>
   In previous World Cup tune-up matches, Mexico was embarrassed
5-2 by Norway and lost to a pair of under-23 teams, one from
Argentina and the other from Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how this sudden and spectacular free fall has occurred
for Mexico is anyone's guess. It never should have happened.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that looked as talented as ever only a few months
ago, with such proven stars as goalie Jorge Campos and goal-scorer
Carlos Hermosillo. Only last year it was a team that was creative
and successful in every way en route to taking control of the
CONCACAF World Cup qualifying group.
</P>
<P>
   But even before coach Bora Milutinovic was replaced by Manuel
Lapuente earlier this year, things began to unravel. Defense turned
weak and few opportunities were converted into goals.
</P>
<P>
   One Mexican national newspaper already has called for the team
to pull out of the World Cup altogether and come home now to avoid
further humiliation. Another Mexican newspaper had only a one-word
headline following the loss to VfL Wolfsburg: ``Pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are looking grim for the proud Mexican team.
</P>
<P>
   But what Mexico's apparent collapse means for the remaining
teams in Group E is that the Dutch should only gain confidence
during the first stage, while Belgium likely will distinguish
itself as the second-best team in the group and South Korea might
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans, in fact, considers themselves as contenders
to win the group, but realistically they should set lower
standards. Like winning their first-ever World Cup game.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally a tough if overmatched team, South Korea has but
two draws to show for what will be its fourth World Cup appearance.
Since it is co-hosting the next Cup in 2002 with Japan, the Koreans
will be inspired to prove they belong.
</P>
<P>
   However, the team most likely to step into Mexico's position as
a second-place contender in the group behind the favored Dutch is
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that always seems to be underrated, but has
reached at least the second round of the World Cup four consecutive
times. In 1986, Belgium was but one spectacular Maradona goal away
from upsetting Argentina and making it to the final.
</P>
<P>
   Now, coach Georges Leekens has picked up the offensive pace and
emphasized more daring passing. The biggest reason Leekens changed
strategies for this defensive-minded team was because the Belgians
were drawn into the Dutch group and the Dutch have dominated
Belgium the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dutch favored, the South Koreans still a bit
overmatched and Mexico on the slide, the opportunity for another
appearance in the second round certainly is there for Belgium if it
can get the offense rolling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
