<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOMO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 MEDIA TYPES MOB NOMO AT FENWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hideo Nomo's first official duty as a Met took place
atop the third-base dugout at Fenway Park Friday night, where the
Japanese pitcher sat with his legs dangling while more than 100
reporters, photographers and camera operators crowded around the
steps. It was a strange scene, made stranger by the Red Sox fans
who barely uttered a word, but it was also a glimpse at what
Nomomania can mean for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added another marquee name from the Los Angeles Dodgers
when they acquired Nomo and reliever Brad Clontz for the struggling
starter Dave Mlicki and setup man Greg McMichael late Thursday and
then unveiled him before their first interleague contest of the
season. It was an odd place for a news conference, but the Mets,
who have seriously boosted their image since getting Mike Piazza,
Nomo's catcher with the Dodgers, last month, trumpeted their new
player in an unusual manner because there was no other place to
accommodate such a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be here,'' Nomo said through an interpreter. ``I
needed a change of scenery. I'm being reunited with people who
understand me. This is a contending team and we have a chance to do
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Nomo be critical to the Mets' pursuit of a postseason
berth? Is he better than the pitcher who was 2-7 with a 5.05 earned
run average so far this season? The Mets feel that Nomo can
resurrect a career that included the Rookie of the Year Award in
1995, which is why they were eager to trade for the 29-year-old
right-hander, even though they have routinely praised Mlicki's
repertory and will miss McMichael in the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me we had Mike Piazza and Hideo Nomo, I would
have called you crazy,'' general manager Steve Phillips said. ``I
wouldn't have believed you.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine, who has scheduled Nomo to start against
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on Tuesday at Shea Stadium, added,
``There's probably 20 days he's going to go out there for us. We've
had 10 of those days taken up and we've won one game. I'm very
confident he is going to win more games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are confident because they believe Dave Wallace, a
senior adviser who used to be Nomo's pitching coach in Los Angeles,
can help him, they believe the presence of the first-year Met
Masato Yoshii, a Japanese pitcher who is Nomo's best friend, will
be a positive influence, and, besides, they do not think that
Nomo's season has been a total fiasco. A close analysis of the
statistics reveals that Nomo has not performed as terribly in 1998
as the numbers seemingly indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo allowed seven earned runs in two-thirds of an inning
against the Cubs. Eliminate that performance and his ERA with the
Dodgers would have been 4.16. He also had three starts in which he
gave up only six earned runs in 23 innings, yet was 0-2 with a
no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time for him to get back,'' Piazza
said. ``He's not going to go out there and throw a no-hitter the
next time out. You got to walk before you can run. We just need him
to be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nomo was asked why he has slumped this season, he said,
``Simply put, I'm getting hit.'' When he was asked if he knew why
he has had a subpar season so far, he answered, ``If I knew the
answer, I would be shutting people out.'' Nomo would not address
why his relationship with the Dodgers soured so dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   After watching videotapes of Nomo, Wallace said, ``Your sense is
that not much has changed. He's a true professional. Maybe it's
psychological.''
</P>
<P>
   One general manager said that Nomo has lost velocity on his
fastball and scouts indicated that he has struggled with the
command of his forkball, but the same general manager added, ``It's
taking somewhat of a chance, but most people would be willing to
take that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo had calcium deposits removed from his right elbow last Oct.
7, but Phillips said the Dodgers provided a full physical report on
him and the Mets do not consider the injury an issue. The Mets were
somewhat fortunate to get Nomo, who is wearing the No. 16 last worn
by Dwight Gooden, because the Orioles and Indians were both
negotiating heavily with the Dodgers before dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad I'm in a situation where we have the chance to
win,'' Nomo said. ``The ultimate goal is to get to the World
Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
