<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE HERO NEEDS HELP THIS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Michael Jordan seemed unusually testy yesterday
morning. Perhaps it was the pressure of trailing the Utah Jazz in
the NBA finals after losing the opening game of the series. But it
could very well have been the questions about whether his skills
were eroding.
</P>
<P>
   When one reporter asked whether Jordan was confident, given the
fact that the Chicago Bulls had been extended to a seventh game by
Indiana and beaten Wednesday by the Jazz, Jordan rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the question is more relevant than Jordan may want to
admit. He can no longer take over games at will and with each
successive performance appears more and more vulnerable. Jordan
needs help. He may have difficulty accepting it.
</P>
<P>
   Like the typical hero, Jordan responds to impending doom by
assuming an even greater responsibility. There's a thin line
between heroism and selfishness. But who can criticize Michael
Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has saved the day, carried the load, so many times. He
helped bring five National Basketball Association championships to
a city that a decade ago felt it might never win one. Now, driven
by his mission, Jordan may be the last to grasp his barely
discernible slide from deity to mortal.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls coach Phil Jackson tried to get Jordan out of the game at
a crucial juncture Wednesday night, but Jordan talked his way back
in. When Jordan was promptly beaten by Jeff Hornacek, Utah's
injured guard, Jackson snatched him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling incident occurred after Scottie Pippen
culminated a great rally by nailing a 3-pointer that tied the score
with 2 minutes 34 seconds left in regulation. Jordan had scored on
the Bulls' two previous possessions.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back to the bench, Jordan could be seen yelling at
Pippen for failing to recognize that Jordan had a mismatch in the
post on Hornacek. In previous championship runs, such combustion
has served as octane for the Bulls. This time, the Bulls lost in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an inner strength and confidence,'' Jordan said. ``One
game does not deteriorate that.'' He added: ``One game does not
dictate how this series is going to end. If you want to write us
off, go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely because of Jordan, everyone is reluctant to write off
the Bulls. Now the issue is not one game but an accumulation of
games and years of improbable expectations met and exceeded.
Meanwhile, the Bulls' bench sits and seethes and listens. Utah's
bench is heralded; Chicago's bench, outscored by Utah's, 22-8, is
cited as the reason the Bulls' empire may be about to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would their bench be coming off their bench if they had
Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman?'' said Scott
Burrell, a backup Bulls forward. ``We have three of the greatest
players ever; you can't look for a lot of minutes on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Chicago is to win a sixth championship, Jackson knows he
must find minutes somewhere. Even if they come out of Jordan's
stash.
</P>
<P>
   Stamina, a great ally throughout Jordan's career, is giving way
to fatigue. He is shooting 37 percent in the fourth quarters of his
last six playoff games. He made three fourth-quarter turnovers in
Game 4 against Indiana; a 24-second violation in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   As great as Oscar Robertson was, one lingering scene from the
end of his career was Jo Jo White and Don Chaney running him into
the ground in the NBA finals. There are similar memories of other
athletes: Muhammad Ali being punished by Larry Holmes, Willie Mays
falling down in the field as a Met.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is seasons away from that sort of dramatic decline,
though in an ideal world he would retire after this season and
leave memories of triumphant heroism.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls management would love for Jordan to return; so would the
NBA. But for Jordan, the work environment would very likely be
dramatically altered: no Pippen, no Rodman, no Jackson. Jordan
might be reduced to a novelty act with no hope of winning a
championship. Just playing to be playing. Gunslinging.
</P>
<P>
   Allow Jordan the chance to fall and burn, then hope he rises
from the ashes like the phoenix to bring forth a final
championship.
</P>
<P>
   This quest represents the last great challenge of Jordan's
career. The nature of it is unlike anything Jordan has faced.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it so daunting is that the force Jordan must overcome
is Jordan. The pride, the ego, the vanity of the hero giving way
ever so slightly to a supporting cast that may well be a life raft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
