<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-CANCELED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING'S `D-DAY' SHOT DOWN BY VIRUSES, PREGNANCY AND CHILD
SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The night of fights at Madison Square Garden, once
one of boxing's glamorous stages, had been advertised as ``D-Day''
_ a mix of bouts that included Evander Holyfield, the heavyweight
champion, Roberto Duran, an aging legend, and Christy Martin, the
world's top-rated female boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite weeks of promotion, the fights had failed to generate
much excitement, and Friday the event unraveled completely after a
series of strange developments: two fighters tested positive for
hepatitis, a female boxer turned out to be pregnant and promoters
were ordered by a Florida court to withhold any payment to Duran
because he owed thousands of dollars in unpaid child support.
</P>
<P>
   And so barely 24 hours before D-Day was to start, boxing and
Garden officials stepped in to cancel Saturday's event and postpone
the fights indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The concluding episode to the troubled event proved yet again
the sport's ability to provide the unexpected and to provoke
questions about basic safety.
</P>
<P>
   Don King, one of the fight's promoters, said he fully expected
some people would believe the problems were staged so he and others
might limit the financial damage of a loser of a fight card.
</P>
<P>
   For the Garden, which had a riot break out in the ring during a
major night of fights two years ago, this was the latest setback to
its bid to make boxing a profitable enterprise in the city.
Instead, Garden officials were left to announce refunds, while
Showtime, the cable television network, was canceling orders for
tens of thousands of pay-per-view orders.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, one of the more unusual tales of the
tape read this way: Henry Akinwande, the World Boxing Association's
top heavyweight contender and the man set to take on Holyfield, had
been diagnosed with hepatitis B, which can cause serious liver
damage and which can be transmitted through blood; Ray Mercer,
another heavyweight, had been diagnosed with hepatitis A, a milder
form of the disease that his manager said he contracted by eating a
salad; Maria Nieves Garcia, the fighter slated to box Christy
Martin, was found to be 21 weeks pregnant; and Duran, the
46-year-old Panamanian, was set to see a state court judge in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring the best boxing to New York City,'' said Paul
Munick, the Garden's director of athletics. Munick cited several
recent successful events, but conceded ``it's got its ups and
downs.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest financial losers for the moment are the fighters.
Holyfield will not receive his $10 million purse, and Akinwande
won't get his $2.5 million. The Garden, as well as Don King
Productions, the promoters, will not collect the gate receipts and
concession revenues they were going to share. And all money spent
by the promoters and Showtime, the television company that was
offering the fight on pay-per-view for $39.95, will only have value
if the fights are staged again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this is just a small hiccup, Akinwande will be able
to fight, and all this will create more interest for the fight,''
said Mark Greenberg, an executive vice president of Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   The only other heavyweight fight canceled so close to fight time
was the February 1996 bout between Tommy Morrison and Arthur
Weathers, which was canceled hours before the match when Morrison's
blood test revealed that he had tested positive for the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, whose share of weird boxing moments includes having
part of his ear bit off by Mike Tyson and having a paraglider drop
into the ring in the seventh round of his fight against Riddick
Bowe in 1993, said he was headed back to Atlanta to see his two
children compete in a track meet, while Akinwande, who could be out
of boxing for as long as six months, returned to his training camp
in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's disappointing,'' Holyfield said. ``I've been
training hard for 13 weeks. This kind of thing is worst when it
happens the day before the fight. I can't control what happens. You
just have to roll with the punches. That's part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Athletic Commission, the state's regulatory
agency, administered a blood test to Akinwande on Tuesday
afternoon, checking him for HIV, as well as hepatitis B and C,
according to Tony Russo, the commission's executive director.
California, Texas and Maryland are the only other states that test
boxers for hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Donald Kaminsky of the Albert Einstein Medical
Center, who studied Akinwande's blood sample for the commission,
the disease was at the infectious stage, and could be transmitted
through body fluids or blood. Hepatitis B, which is contracted by
roughly 300,000 people in the United States annually, is typically
passed along through sex or dirty hypodermic needles, but can also
be transmitted by something as innocent as a shared toothbrush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
