<HEADER>
A6934 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNCOVERED-AZR &LR;      06-05 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNCOVERED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S EX-WELFARE FAMILIES WALKING AWAY FROM FREE HEALTH
BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Thousands of Arizona's former welfare families are
walking away from free state health-care benefits, and no one is
sure why.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; While bureaucrats debate what to do, these former welfare
families are increasingly dependent on costly emergency room care
at taxpayers' expense _ even though most remain eligible for state
insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's welfare reform began a year earlier than most states,
but researchers already are tracking this unexpected effect
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   They blame it on lack of education and parents who assume that
when they lost welfare benefits, medical benefits went with them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, some critics say, state officials aren't eager to stop
a trend that saves money in the short run _ about $30 million just
from July 1997 through April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also suggest that former welfare parents are sick of
red tape and too overwhelmed with new job responsibilities to make
health insurance a priority.
</P>
<P>
   More than 48,000 former welfare recipients, mostly children, are
missing from the state's health-care rolls, said Diane Ross,
assistant director of the Arizona Health Care Cost Containment
System.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a strong job market, Ross is skeptical that all these
former welfare parents _ the majority of whom quietly disappear
from the system with no follow-up _ found jobs that provide health
insurance or pay at least $10 an hour, which would make an average
family ineligible for free health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have asked more questions, given more information,''
Ross said about welfare reform. ``We should have sent information
that said, `If you found a job you still may be eligible for
Medicaid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That never happened. Not in Ross' agency and only sometimes in
the Department of Economic Security's offices responsible for
welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Former welfare mother Sonya Wilkins spent seven months without
insurance before she found a job as an accounting clerk at a health
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a sickly person,'' Wilkins said. ``I thought, `I felt
well, I don't need it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, her children continued to get food stamps, which
meant they automatically remained covered by state health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so automatic when you apply for AFDC (Aid to Families
with Dependent Children),'' said Wilkins, 34, who lives in Pinal
County. But now it requires busy parents to set aside time, find
transportation to the agency, and fill out a new application.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've never done it before, it's a step people don't get
around to doing, unless you have sick kids,'' Wilkins said. ``Some
parents may not realize their kids can still qualify for AHCCCS.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross doesn't believe the state is slow to move because it is
saving money in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was an intentional plot, but we all could
have done more to make sure people clearly understood,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   But the former director of Pinal County Public Health
Department, a county especially hard hit by uninsured former
welfare families, thinks short-term savings are a big reason for
the slow reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude is if we don't enroll people, we won't spend the
money,'' said Chuck Teegarden, who now heads Pinal County Cities in
Schools, a non-profit family resource center.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, county taxpayers not only fund state health
programs that provide preventive and non-emergency care and mental
health counseling, but they also foot the bill when uninsured and
untreated poor people end up in emergency rooms for far costlier
care, Teegarden said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Arizona Physicians IPA, AHCCCS's largest health
care plan, say the cost of treating an ear infection in an
emergency room can be five to 10 times more expensive than
treatment in a physician's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``County taxpayers should never pay twice,'' Teegarden said.
``This is insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents walking away from these benefits also might be eager to
distance themselves from the bureaucracy that once ruled their
lives, Teegarden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She must face the same people who kicked her off welfare and
ask to re-enroll her child (in Medicaid),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Public health researcher Leighton Ku said parents might be so
worried about maintaining a job, food and shelter that health care
doesn't matter until there's an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have chaotic and difficult lives, and this is not a
priority,'' said Ku, a senior researcher with the Urban Institute
in Washington, D.C., who studys the problem.
</P>
<P>
   People with jobs can no longer afford to sit around for hours at
state agencies, which are usually only open during working hours,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Everyone expected state welfare reform to spur a decrease in
the number of Arizonans getting public assistance _ and it has, by
28 percent in just the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials never expected thousands of these families
to drop out of the state's free health care program at the same
time, said Vince Wood, an assistant director for DES.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he can't explain why it didn't trigger a quick
response from his agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer to that,'' Wood said. ``We're trying to
study the impact of welfare reform, but it's new, and it's going to
take time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if parents decide not to sign up for free health benefits,
it's their decision and the state should respect it, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   He also added: ``We have a responsibility to educate them (about
health care benefits), and maybe we're not doing a good enough job
educating.''
</P>
<P>
   But as more families drop out, state bureaucrats still seem to
be waiting for each other to come up with a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Sketchy plans for an outreach program are just being formulated
between AHCCCS and DES officials.
</P>
<P>
   Plans could include home visits and phone calls to former
welfare parents, training for front-line social workers or
additional staff in DES offices to help families maintain health
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of better-written letters to replace the
computer-generated letters DES now uses to communicate with welfare
families.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has happened yet.
</P>
<P>
   In Pinal County, health and human service agencies burdened by
uninsured families are no longer waiting for state agencies to act,
Teegarden said, and ``recently decided to take the bull by the
horns.''
</P>
<P>
   They've recruited Arizona Public Service Co. to fund posters and
brochures to reach uninsured families and alert welfare families of
their eligibility before they drop off the rolls. They are
recruiting people to help parents fill out applications.
</P>
<P>
   Ku's national research shows that states are responding in
different ways at different speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, (1997), South Carolina's governor sent home a letter
with every school child asking parents to make sure they sign up
for Medicaid if they are eligible, he said. The letter included a
simplified application that could be mailed in. But Wisconsin,
which led the nation in welfare reform, isn't much further along
than Arizona, Ku said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Wisconsin, only in the past few months have people become
alarmed,'' Ku said.
</P>
<P>
   And it's common to find battles among state agencies over
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mix in missions,'' Ku said. Welfare reform workers
are eager for rolls to drop and families to become independent;
health workers are eager to ensure that people's health problems
are prevented or cured before they become emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Sen. Cindy Resnick, who works for the University of
Arizona Rural Health Office, is tired of the state's slow response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there's a bunch of kids clearly eligible
for medical programs who are falling off the rolls,'' she said,
``and all we're doing is finger-pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation needs strong leadership,'' Resnick said.
``Someone to say, `I don't care who you are, let's sit down and end
this.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
