</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTATE-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLSTATE SUES FOR FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Allstate Insurance Co., the focus of a federal
investigation into its handling of damage settlements from the
Northridge Earthquake, has filed a $1 million lawsuit against a Los
Angeles-based firm for allegedly having homeowners file false
claims after the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Northbrook, Ill.-based Allstate's suit maintains that the scheme
by Building Permit Consultants involved large numbers of
Northridge-area homeowners and cost it and other insurers millions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The suit identifies John, Juliana and James Kaldawi as the
operators of Building Permit Consultants. None of them returned
numerous messages left for them Friday at the company's office and
at John Kaldawi's home in suburban Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   John Kaldawi, a former engineer with the city of Los Angeles'
Building and Safety Department, was convicted in 1995 of soliciting
a $10,000 bribe from someone who wanted to build an auto body
repair shop.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to three years probation and fined $5,000,
according to court filings.
</P>
<P>
   The civil fraud suit filed May 27 in U.S. District Court in Los
Angeles claims he subsequently started Building Permit Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate alleges that after the January 1994 disaster, Building
Permit Consultants called and mailed notices to homeowners telling
them they could get insurance money for damage even if their homes
came through untouched. Those that agreed to the plan had to sign a
contract stipulating they would share the proceeds with Building
Permit Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   So far, homeowners who participated appear to be off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe that all this could have happened without
the homeowners not having any clue,'' said Peter H. Klee,
Allstate's attorney. ``The fact of the matter is Allstate is
reluctant to sue its own customers unless there is a substantial
amount of evidence. And from a customer-relations standpoint it is
reluctant to (sue).''
</P>
<P>
   The suit comes after it was revealed last month that federal
investigators were looking into charges that Allstate altered
documents to save money on homeowner claims after the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've strongly and consistently denied those allegations,''
said company spokesman Peter Debreceny.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Allstate is cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 46,043 claims filed after the temblor, all but 120 have
been settled and nearly $1.7 billion paid out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Debreceny said Allstate uncovered the Building Permit
Consultants scheme during its own investigation into fraud stemming
from the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is committed to fighting fraud on a number of
fronts. We want to make sure that fraud is (excised) from the
insurance system,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
