Bravo, dropped by and was surprised at how easy it was to meet
people. ``I haven't done the singles scene in a while and this was
unintimidating,'' she says. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
SHORTPANTS-FASHION, 6-05 -- The author, Abbott Combes, is ``a
50-something guy you may have seen in summertime Manhattan going
about his business clad in coat and tie, dressy loafers (no socks)
and what used to be called Bermuda shorts. Like crocuses or
allergies, my legs became harbingers of summer,'' he writes. (Fred
R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
JOHNSONS-FASHION, 6-05 -- Betsey Johnson, front, and her daughter,
Lulu, in their SoHo store. If Betsey Johnson, 55, isn't exactly
growing up Q she ended her latest Bryant Park fashion show with a
trademark cartwheel Q Lulu, 23, who is in charge of the designer's
Ultra line, has definitely brought a new level of sophistication to
her mother's fashion carnival. ``If anything, Betsey's vision is
even younger than mine,'' says Lulu. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
BREAKDANCING, 6-05 -- Breakdancers are once again performing head
spins and other gyrations in music videos, clubs and arenas, often
to the beat of ``old school'' rap by the likes of Erik B and Rakim,
and cheered on by audiences in retro styles like track suits. The
return seems an inner-city counterpart to the 1980s nostalgia on
view in recent hit films like ``The Wedding Singer.'' (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
DIOR-FUR, 6-05 -- John Galliano's first fur collection exploded the
old notion of the matronly mink stole. His provocative designs
ranged in style from Oriental to flapper and beyond. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
