<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENT LOTT LEADS SENATE TO TUNE OF CORPORATE AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I keep waiting for Senator Trent Lott to step up and do
something for which I can admire him. And I'm still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the syrupy Mississippian keeps tanking on me. His
latest cave in the direction of Big Money is his
triple-gainer-back-flip-with-full-twist on behalf of the tobacco
lobby. No better example exists of the perfidy of campaign
contributions' influence on the political process than the rescue
effort captained by Lott in the face of reform as championed by
Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   To Big Tobacco, the Senate majority leader's real name is
Thanks-a-Lott. When it comes to grabbing campaign dough with both
hands, Lott has no equal. And Corporate America knows it. And loves
it. Where else can you purchase such bang for your buck as in the
majority leader's office?
</P>
<P>
   Even the stout-hearted McCain seems weary of the chore of
summoning his 99 colleagues to a higher cause than servicing the
tobacco lobby, whose swath, through this and previous Senates, has
been wide, and deep, and effective.
</P>
<P>
   The most hilarious line of the week came from Trent-as-in-bent
Lott hisself: ``The well has been poisoned tremendously by what has
been going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the guy, caught red-handed tossing cyanide into the water
supply, and he's griping about the contamination of ye olde welle?
Follow the money from the tobacco lobby, and you see that the
lion's share ends up in Trent's greasy mitts, his and his fellow
bag-jobbers. They live off Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, alas, seems not to realize that his place in history will
depend on what he does to improve life for the majority of
Americans, not by gutting some improvement that would reduce
cancer, or bring tobacco company desperadoes to book. Why doesn't
he get it?
</P>
<P>
   Lott is elected by the majority party's members in caucus. But
his role is to serve the American people in leading the upper
branch of the national legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Trent, what do you want on your tombstone?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Here lies Trent Lott,
</P>
<P>
   Of campaign loot, he raised a lot?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is that all there is? That you were the last big fixer of your
era? That you had a chance to halt the process by which tobacco
executives hooked 3,000 teenagers a day? And that you blew it?
Because you wanted a few hundred thousand more bucks in your
political action committee's coffers? Is that all there is? Your
lousy PAC?
</P>
<P>
   Brokering compromises, cutting deals, packaging this-and-that
for the benefit of passage, those are the kinds of sausage-making
compromises that are the meat and drink of legislative leadership.
</P>
<P>
   We're not looking for courage above-and-beyond the call of duty
here. We all understand that the demands of party usually pull
politicians down from the ranks of the archangels. But does Trent
have to go into the tank every time some lobbyist flips open a
checkbook? Is there nothing this guy will stand for?
</P>
<P>
   There must be someone in Lott's office who opens his mail, or
who talks to the good people of Mississippi who phone in, or who is
charged with making nice, and furnishing coffee to the many
distinguished delegations that file into his important office.
</P>
<P>
   Don't they hear what's on people's minds? Don't they blanch when
they realize their boss is doing another deal at the behest of the
latest wicked interest with cash on the barrelhead? Doesn't it
bother them?
</P>
<P>
   I hope one of Lott's munchkins clips for him the following
letter I received Friday as a result of a Wednesday column
describing McCain's uphill struggle to wean his fellow senators,
many Democrats as well as most Republicans, from the teat of
tobacco largesse. The letter comes from a woman whose last name I
will withhold, but her sincerity shines through:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir:
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive the paper, but at 6:30 in the morning I'm not about to
chance waking my husband looking for my stationery. I'd like to
thank you for the column on John McCain and his adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 73 years old, stopped a very minor smoking habit (one pack
a week) about 35 years ago, but still have serious lung problems.
Other members of my family have not been so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently my sister Marge succumbed to lung disease. My brother
Joe, a Korean veteran, also stopped too late. In a third cemetery
is my sister, Betty. Buried with her is her daughter, Lynn. Four
victims of cigarettes. All died needlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the ads for a new `coffin nail,' I think it stands
for guaranteed pulmonary cancer. How fitting a name.''
</P>
<P>
   That's from Dorothy in Watertown. And it begs for someone in
authority to make a change in the way people get hooked.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of us loved nicotine. Thrilled to the way it scrambled our
brainpan, titillated our intestines, stung our lungs. Yes, it was
great. But very dangerous. Carried a huge price tag, down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But we all know a lot more now. It's time we took advantage of
all the new science, and the new politics, to make a change in the
assembly-line delivery of new cancer victims to the tobacco lobby.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we look to Washington for. And we're happy to follow
a Sun Belt conservative named McCain, who has the public interest
at heart. We do not like to see a Senate majority leader going in
the tank for Big Tobacco, and trying to con us with mealy-mouthed
excuses.
</P>
<P>
   He's the chief cook and bottle washer in the Senate. And all
he's done on this issue is cave in to the businessmen who write him
the big checks.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't that be some epitaph?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Here lies Trent.
</P>
<P>
   He was bent.
</P>
<P>
   He was always for rent.
</P>
<P>
   To the highest bidder he went.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
