   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/05/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MONTCLAIR, N.J. -- June 5, 1998 -- NJ-MINOR-LEAGUES-2,
6-05 -- Austin Purvis, 9, watches the New Jersey Jackals take
batting practice at the newly opened Yogi Berra Stadium. Nourished
by nostalgia for a simpler version of a game dominated by major
league millionaires, minor league baseball has moved in force into
the teeming suburbs of metropolitan New York. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MONTCLAIR, N.J. -- June 5, 1998 -- NJ-MINOR-LEAGUES-1,
6-05 -- Yogi Berra celebrates with his wife, left, and sons at the
the Yogi Berra Museum, situated alongside the newly opened minor
league stadium in Montclair that also bears his name. Nourished by
nostalgia for a simpler version of a game dominated by major league
millionaires, minor league baseball has moved in force into the
teeming suburbs of metropolitan New York. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MOSCOW -- June 5, 1998 -- RUSSIA-SOLZHENITSYN, 6-05 --
At a Moscow book store, the new book by Alexander Solzhenitsyn,
``Russia in Collapse,'' is prominently displayed at the register
but the cashier is not rushed. The book offers a gloomy view of the
``new'' nation. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 5, 1998 --
NEW-GRATEFUL-DEAD-REVIEW, 6-05 -- Bruce Hornsby, left, joins former
Grateful Dead members Bob Weir, center, and Phil Lesh in San
Francisco on Thursday. Three years after the death of Jerry Garcia,
his fellow members of the Dead are back together as the core of a
new band, the Other Ones, that sets out to resurrect and extend the
Dead's legacy. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- June 5, 1998 -- HOUSE-BUDGET, 6-7 -- After
the House narrowly approved a plan today to cut taxes and spending,
Rep. John Boehner confers with House Budget Committee chairman John
Kasich, right, as Speaker Newt Gingrich briefs the press. The plan,
which calls for about $100 billion in tax cuts over the next five
years, passed with a 216-204 vote. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SKOKIE, Ill. -- June 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
EARN-FEL-PRO, 6-04 -- Richard Snell, chairman of Federal-Mogul, the
new owner of Fel-Pro, talks with a Fel-Pro worker after a January
speech. Behind them are Kenneth Lehman and David Weinberg, former
Fel-Pro co-chairmen. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-ADS-2, 6-05 -- Direct-to-consumer ads may be
good marketing, but are they good medicine? Dr. Nancy Dickey,
president-elect of the American Medical Association, says the ads
may interfere with the doctor-patient relationship. ``We have come
to understand that some of these ads can be educational. And that's
fine,'' she says. ``But we don't want them to go the way of floor
wax and compare one drug to the next.'' (Barbara Alper/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-ADS-1, 6-05 -- Direct-to-consumer ads may be
good marketing, but are they good medicine? Mark Schwatka and Ulla
Kling-Atkinson of Grey Advertising were responsible for the ad
campaign for Zomig, a treatment for migraines. ``In some instances,
the doctors may not know everything about the drug,'' says
Schwatka. ``Some doctors could learn something from these ads they
can't stand.'' (Steven O. Boljonis/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
HATS-DRESS, 6-05 -- A snap-brim leather hat at Agnes B., left;
black oiled cotton fishing hat at Paul Stuart. Given the natural
impulse to dress down for summer in a lightweight jacket, polo
shirt and khakis, a good hat adds a crucial bit of personality and
polish to an otherwise lackluster outfit. (Carrie Boretz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
HOT-ITEMS-2, 6-05 -- Frou by Paige Novick expanded to women's wear
last November. It started as a hair-accessory business four years
ago and grew to include handbags two years ago. ``I really design
around my handbags,'' Ms. Novick says. ``I look at the skirts as
accessories and the handbags as the focal point.'' (David Corio/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
HOT-ITEMS-1, 6-05 -- On the Roof Garden at the Metropolitan Museum
of Art recently, a spot where youthful culture seekers go to meet
and mingle. Laura Marino, a 37-year-old broadcast producer for
Bravo, dropped by and was surprised at how easy it was to meet
people. ``I haven't done the singles scene in a while and this was
unintimidating,'' she says. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
SHORTPANTS-FASHION, 6-05 -- The author, Abbott Combes, is ``a
50-something guy you may have seen in summertime Manhattan going
about his business clad in coat and tie, dressy loafers (no socks)
and what used to be called Bermuda shorts. Like crocuses or
allergies, my legs became harbingers of summer,'' he writes. (Fred
R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
JOHNSONS-FASHION, 6-05 -- Betsey Johnson, front, and her daughter,
Lulu, in their SoHo store. If Betsey Johnson, 55, isn't exactly
growing up Q she ended her latest Bryant Park fashion show with a
trademark cartwheel Q Lulu, 23, who is in charge of the designer's
Ultra line, has definitely brought a new level of sophistication to
her mother's fashion carnival. ``If anything, Betsey's vision is
even younger than mine,'' says Lulu. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
BREAKDANCING, 6-05 -- Breakdancers are once again performing head
spins and other gyrations in music videos, clubs and arenas, often
to the beat of ``old school'' rap by the likes of Erik B and Rakim,
and cheered on by audiences in retro styles like track suits. The
return seems an inner-city counterpart to the 1980s nostalgia on
view in recent hit films like ``The Wedding Singer.'' (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
DIOR-FUR, 6-05 -- John Galliano's first fur collection exploded the
old notion of the matronly mink stole. His provocative designs
ranged in style from Oriental to flapper and beyond. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
