<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEYOTE-AZR &LR;      06-05 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEYOTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS MAN'S CLAIM THAT HE USES PEYOTE AS SAC RAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDI VILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Leo Mercado claims that his use of the hallucinogenic
drug peyote is part of his religion, a ``sacrament'' that helps him
to spiritually purge his soul and cleanse his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little to enjoy about peyote,'' said Mercado, 37,
of Kearny. ``It's a very hard road. If I was looking for personal
enjoyment, I'd drink beer, which I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Pinal County Superior Court judge saw it differently,
ruling this week that Mercado was essentially hiding behind the
cloak of religious immunity to veil illegal activities and that he
should forfeit a quantity of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Mercado claims that he is a member of the Native American Church
and that, as such, he has a right to possess peyote, a cactus pod
containing mescaline. Church members believe the drug allows them
to commune with God.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling that revolved around whether a single peyote button
should be returned to Mercado, Judge William O'Neil wrote that
Mercado failed to prove that he embraced the peyote religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, he presents himself far more as some carny offering
cotton candy for any and all to use,'' O'Neil wrote in Tuesday's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Mercado called the judge's statements ``spiritual bigotry'' and
``blasphemy'' and said he plans to appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like ruling that the sun's not shining here, that the
Gila River doesn't flow by our property and that I don't believe in
this medicine _ because I do,'' Mercado said. ``It's a little
strange to be told that you don't believe in something. It kind of
upsets me to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This peyote is good medicine for those who believe in it, and
God created it, and I trust in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The peyote button in question was found inside Mercado's
``medicine bag'' and seized by police during a traffic stop on Jan.
8, 1997. No criminal charges ever were filed against Mercado in
connection with the seizure, and he subsequently petitioned the
state for its return.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, the state returned to Mercado the same peyote
button and about 1,000 hallucinogenic cactuses that had been seized
in a 1995 raid at his remote ranch.
</P>
<P>
   What followed this time was a year-long court battle, during
which Mercado set out to prove that he really did believe in and
practice the peyote religion, while the state sought to discredit
that.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona law allows the use of peyote in connection with the bona
fide practice of a religious belief, as an integral part of a
religious exercise and in a manner not dangerous to public health.
</P>
<P>
   The Native American Church generally is recognized as the only
organization that has a bona fide claim that peyote is a sacrament
in its rituals.
</P>
<P>
   But a church leader testified in court that Mercado was not
among its 250,000 members and that his actions in growing peyote _
because he believes it is becoming extinct _ are contrary to church
tenets. Church members believe peyote is a supernatural plant that
either manifests itself or grows where God chooses and is not to be
cultivated or planted by humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mercado testified his belief that it could become extinct;
that the supernatural power that it possesses could somehow be
lost; in short, that the very supernatural power he claims to
worship is subject to natural laws,'' O'Neil wrote. ``This is
hardly the stuff of which religion is made.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil also wrote that Mercado's own writings indicate that he
widely advocates peyote use and that ``he promotes its use, not its
worship or worship through its use.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no testimony encouraging others to follow a system
of beliefs, but rather to try peyote,'' O'Neil wrote. ``If the
claimant has a religion, it is a convenient wrapping of one talking
the talk but not walking the walk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mercado, who has used peyote for half his life in spite of
the nausea it causes, says that's simply not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for very few people overall,'' Mercado said. ``But for
those that it is important, it's essential. That's why it's
religious. We rely on it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
