<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-05 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS SHOULD ROOT FOR REAL QUIET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Bet on Real Quiet? Not for the promise of a $4.40
payoff. Not unless you're looking for a souvenir ticket on the
first Triple Crown winner in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Root for Real Quiet? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   If you're watching the Belmont Stakes on TV at home today, your
money safe in your pocket, cross your fingers for Real Quiet and
jockey Kent Desormeaux, who will need a little luck to find a clear
and straight path in a 13-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   Don't cheer for them just because, as the horse-racing marketing
men will say, the sport needs a reminder of the glorious '70s and
Triple Crown winners Secretariat, Seattle Slew and Affirmed. The
sport has had plenty of stars _ has Cigar been forgotten already? _
and racetracks continue to fail. Besides, wouldn't it be refreshing
if marketing isn't the focus for once, if this is the rare sports
accomplishment that isn't turned into a Nike commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Cheer for them because when Real Quiet and Desormeaux win,
they'll annoy the sourpusses on the Belmont Park backstretch, where
the tree-lined roads are named for Triple Crown winners, where
they're ready to cry, ``There goes the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nonsense, this stuffy notion that Real Quiet _
crooked-legged and late blooming, not even the most promising
2-year-old in his Santa Anita Park barn _ is somehow unworthy of
the title Triple Crown winner.
</P>
<P>
   John Veitch, trainer of Alydar _ the horse who ran second three
times to Affirmed, the last horse to sweep the Triple Crown _ said
last week Real Quiet would need an asterisk next to his name if he
made that august list.
</P>
<P>
   The allusion was to Roger Maris, whose audacity in beating Babe
Ruth's home-runs record prompted baseball to type an asterisk into
the history books, noting that Maris' season was eight games longer
than Ruth's. What the Maris-bashers didn't grasp was that he wasn't
claiming to be the greatest baseball player of all time, he was
only proposing to break one of his records.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Real Quiet rider, trainer and owner aren't claiming
he's the equal of Count Fleet, Citation or Secretariat. They're
only proposing to match one of those great horses' achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the Triple Crown winners were immortals. The first,
Sir Barton, lost six races in 1918 before his first victory, just
as Real Quiet lost six in a row last year. Try to find Omaha and
Whirlaway on anybody's list of all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   But now (begin ital)we're(end ital) being sourpusses.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet isn't getting enough credit for what he's done so
far.
</P>
<P>
   The bashers say he's only 4 for 14. But he simply isn't a
sprinter, and if you subtract his races of a mile or less last
summer and fall, he's 4 for 8 with losses excusable for traffic
trouble, a horribly muddy track, a layoff and a front-runners'
track bias. He's 3 for 4 in Grade I races.
</P>
<P>
   The bashers say he beat injury-weakened fields in the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness. But he beat the Santa Anita Derby winner, the
Blue Grass winner, the Florida Derby winner, the Arkansas Derby
winner and the reigning Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Lil's Lad missed the race? He was beaten by Halory
Hunter in the Blue Grass; and Real Quiet beat Halory Hunter. So
what if Coronado's Quest missed the race? He wasn't entered because
he's a mental basket case; since when is that an excuse? When you
boil it down, the only good 3-year-old that Real Quiet didn't beat
_ or beat somebody who beat them _ is Event of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Derby prospects get hurt every year. Usually they get
hurt in January, February, March and April. The difference this
season is that the Lil's Lads and Event of the Years stayed healthy
longer, so when they went to the sidelines, they were more sorely
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Slew beat nobody important on the way to his 1977 Triple
Crown. And, surely, there have been years with as many injuries as
this when nobody was good enough to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, why isn't Real Quiet applauded for racing as often as a
stakes horse can and still winning the war of attrition? With more
sturdy horses like him, it would be a healthier sport.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to think Real Quiet is a victim of prejudice. His
owner, Mike Pegram, is beer-bellied and ribald. His trainer, Bob
Baffert, comes from quarter horses, the wrong side of the tracks,
and his immediate thoroughbred success makes some people
suspicious. The colt himself made his mark in California, far from
the power centers of the racing press. When he ran second to
stablemate Indian Charlie on an unfavorable surface in the Santa
Anita Derby, few of the reputation-makers were on the scene to
appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   As Los Angeles-based writer Jay Privman points out, if the
Triple Crown hopeful were Rick Pitino-owned Halory Hunter, the
third-best 3-year-old on the (begin ital)East(end ital) Coast this
winter, the attitude would be much different.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, California product Silver Charm suffered no such
disrespect here in 1997, but he was a striking gray colt with a
pun-friendly name and the first horse in eight years to threaten
the Triple Crown. Real Quiet, without the charisma, suffers in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all for the racing establishment, the physically flawed
Real Quiet was purchased for a mere $17,000 by a man with little
interest in becoming a breeder. He's hardly an advertisement for
the national industry of Kentucky. The bluebloods (begin
ital)shouldn't(end ital) root for him.
</P>
<P>
   Should you? You bet your asterisk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
