<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOBS-WAGES-BOS &LR;      06-05 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-WAGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBLESS RATE STAYS AT 4.3 PERCENT AS WAGES GROW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reporting figures that both workers and investors
can love, the Labor Department Friday said the nation's
unemployment rate remained at 4.3 percent in May, the 28-year low
it hit in April, while wages continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The news surprised many economists, who had said the economy
could not sustain such a low jobless rate. In surveys, economists
had predicted an increase of about 225,000 jobs in May, but
businesses created nearly 300,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, strong job growth prompts investors to sell stocks and
bonds on fears that the economy is growing too quickly and that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates. But instead, the Dow
Jones industrial average rose 167 points Friday, or 1.88 percent,
to close just under 9038. Bond prices rose as well.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark US Treasury bond rose 13/32 of a point, or $4.06
on a $1,000 bond. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction
of price, declined to 5.79 percent from 5.81 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond market is celebrating forcefully,'' said Gary
Ciminero of Independent Economic Advisory, a Providence consulting
firm. ``The bond market is very, very happy, and that is probably
what is driving the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   However, David Kelly of Primark Decision Economics in Boston
found signs of inflation in Friday's report. The government said
wages rose 0.3 percent in May, a modest gain from April. But
compared to a year ago, wages were up by more than 4 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should make people a little nervous,'' Kelly said. ``It
raises deeper questions for the Federal Reserve about how long the
economy can continue to grow so fast without some inflation
penalty.'' He said wages are growing at their fastest pace since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Fed chairman Alan Greenspan testifies before Congress next
Wednesday and may indicate how he reads the job numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk job growth is usually a sign for investors to sell bonds.
They fear that businesses will have to pay more for labor, forcing
them to raise the prices of their goods. Inflation, in turn, cuts
the value of the stream of interest payments they have purchased by
buying bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation may also prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest
rates, which slows the economy and potentially hurts the value of
investments.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts cited several factors that might have prompted
investors to ignore this logic Friday.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, not all sectors of the economy fared well. Job
growth was strong in service and retail businesses, but
manufacturers actually cut 26,000 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Asian financial crisis was probably to blame
for the manufacturing cutback. Currency and stock market downturns
in Southeast Asia mean that the entire region has less money to
spend on US products, and that it is able to sell its own products
in the United States at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   That trend will probably keep the US economy from growing too
fast in future months, analysts said, and could persuade the Fed
that an interest rate increase is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reasonable to suspect that at least some of the recent
declines in manufacturing employment and (working) hours are
related to Asia's economic problems,'' said Katharine G. Abraham,
commissioner of the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the Asian situation written all over it,'' Ciminero
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, fears about wage growth are being offset by recent
news on productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Rising productivity means businesses are doing more work with
the same amount of labor and materials, and it suggests that wages
can also rise without sparking inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Thursday that productivity grew at an
annual rate of 1.1 percent in the first three months of the year.
That is considerably lower than the 1.8 percent rate of 1996 and
1997, but it is better than the 0.2 percent estimate for the first
quarter of 1998 the government had initially reported.
</P>
<P>
   Stock and bond prices may also be rising because a large amount
of money is &UR;  &LR; chasing a fixed number of investment opportunities,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Ciminero said the Dow may be benefiting as investors flee Asia
for safer US securities.
</P>
<P>
   And Kelly noted the US government is running a surplus, meaning
it needs to borrow less, and some corporations are buying back the
debt they have issued. ``There is a lot of investment money out
there and not a lot of debt'' to buy, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
