<HEADLINE>
GIANT KILLER JUMPS INTO FRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Even for the trainer nicknamed The Giant Killer,
this would be quite a feat.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Jerkens will challenge Triple Crown hopeful Real Quiet
with lightly raced Limit Out today. He said, ``I'm trying to fight
a battleship with a canoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Limit Out's 1:20 2/5 victory in the 7-furlong Bay Shore at
Aqueduct earned the highest speed figures for any horse in the
Belmont Stakes field, but he has never gone farther than a mile or
run in a Grade I race.
</P>
<P>
   Jerkens, 69, a Hall of Famer based here, is best known for
springing upsets: Onion and Prove Out over Secretariat, Beau Purple
over Kelso three times, Handsome Boy over Buckpasser. But he said
the chance to spoil a Triple Crown bid isn't important.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just trying to get the money (for) your horse,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerkens, a student of racing history, believes the Belmont
distance is the best reason to think the result will be different
than in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness. Before the Derby, there
were questions about Real Quiet's breeding for 1\ miles, and the
Belmont is 1{ miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Training great) Sunny Jim Fitzsimmons said a mile and a
quarter is about as far as a horse could go just on his class,''
Jerkens said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Jerkens said he's watched Real Quiet since
that colt's arrival at Belmont on Wednesday and said, ``He looks
good. He doesn't look like he's tailing off (physically).''
</P>
<P>
   On the town: Real Quiet owner Mike Pegram _ there's a
contradiction in terms _ went to the New York Stock Exchange Friday
morning and rang the opening bell. No, he didn't wear a tie.
</P>
<P>
   That was the latest appearance by the Real Quiet team at various
New York events. Bob Baffert and family were scheduled to throw out
the first ball at the Yankees-Florida Marlins game Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to enjoy the good times,'' Pegram said.
</P>
<P>
   Track records: The only jockeys making their Belmont Stakes
debuts in today's race are Jean-Luc Samyn (Limit Out) and Calvin
Borel (Hot Wells). Chris McCarron (Thomas Jo) rode Belmont winners
Danzig Connection (1986) and Touch Gold ('97). Pat Day (Parade
Ground) rode Belmont winners Easy Goer ('89) and Tabasco Cat ('94).
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas (Grand Slam, Yarrow Brae) is the only trainer in
today's race who has won the Belmont _ and he won it three years in
a row with Tabasco Cat, Thunder Gulch ('95) and Editor's Note
('96).
</P>
<P>
   Give 'em L: Parade Ground, one of the Belmont long shots, will
race on the anti-bleeding medication lasix for the first time
today.
</P>
<P>
   A trace of respiratory bleeding was found in the Tampa Bay Derby
winner after he finished third to Grand Slam in the Peter Pan last
time out.
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT STAKES &QL; 
AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   What: 130th running of the 1{-mile third leg of the Triple Crown
for 3-year-old thoroughbreds, racing this year for shares of a $1
million purse. &QL; 
Where: Belmont Park, on Long Island, N.Y. &QL; 
Weather forecast: Clear skies with a high of 72 degrees. &QL; 
When: 2:27 p.m. PDT. &QL; 
TV/radio: Coverage starts at 1:30 p.m. on Channel 7 and 2:20 on
KNX-AM (1070). &QL; 
Where to bet: Wagers on the Belmont will be taken at Hollywood
Park, Santa Anita and 15 other Southern California locations,
including the Ventura County and Antelope Valley fairgrounds. First
post at Hollywood Park is 1:20 p.m. &QL; 
Favorite: Real Quiet can earn a $5 million bonus for owner Mike
Pegram by becoming the 12th horse _ the first since Affirmed 20
years ago _ to sweep the Triple Crown. &QL; 
Western flavor: Real Quiet, runner-up in the Santa Anita Derby, is
one of seven horses in the Belmont who have raced in Southern
California or have jockeys, trainers or owners based here.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE CROWN HISTORY-MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux, who will ride Real Quiet today in the Belmont
Stakes, can join the 10 jockeys who have swept the Triple Crown: &QL; 
John Loftus (Sir Barton, 1919) got the job when Earle Sande chose
the Derby runner-up. &QL; 
Earle Sande (Gallant Fox, '30) ended a two-year retirement at age
34 _ just in time to ride this horse. &QL; 
William ``Smokey'' Saunders (Omaha, '35) is one of four to capture
a Triple Crown but never a national riding title. &QL; 
Charlie Kurtsinger (War Admiral, '37) was riding in his last Triple
Crown races. &QL; 
Eddie Arcaro (Whirlaway, '41, and Citation, '48) is the only
two-time Triple Crown rider. &QL; 
John Longden (Count Fleet, '43) was a guest star on ``I Love
Lucy.'' &QL; 
Warren Mehrtens (Assault, '46) won the only Derby he rode. &QL; 
Ron Turcotte (Secretariat, '73) has been in a wheelchair since a
1978 riding accident. &QL; 
Jean Cruguet (Seattle Slew, '77) had been a soldier and riding
champion in France. &QL; 
Steve Cauthen (Affirmed, '78) was an 18-year-old boy wonder. &QL; 
_Kevin Modesti
</P>
</TEXT>
