<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOB GAINS SURGED IN MAY; UNEMPLOYMENT STAYED LOW
</P>
<P>
   The government said employers added nearly 300,000 jobs to the
economy last month, unemployment held steady at a 28-year low of
4.3 percent and pay continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   The data provided powerful evidence that the American economy's
seven-year-old expansion remains vibrant despite Asian tremors,
market jitters and fears that the country is running out of
workers.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER BORROWING SURGES
</P>
<P>
   The pace of borrowing by U.S. consumers more than doubled in
April to $5.5 billion, compared with a month earlier, to total
$1.25 trillion, the Federal Reserve reported. Credit card borrowing
alone rose $2.3 billion, quadruple the rate in March.
</P>
<P>
   GM WORKERS STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   A strike over job security by 3,400 General Motors workers
halted work at a components factory in Flint, Mich. The strike
could cripple production at 17 of GM's 29 North American production
factories within a week. The two sides, which faced a similarly
tense labor showdown in 1997, when seven different strikes were
staged at factories across the country, were scheduled to negotiate
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   SHIFT IN INTERNET CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it would turn over the
management of the Internet's address system to an international
nonprofit group. The decision would remove the last vestige of
control by the U.S. government over the structure of the global
computer network. Management of Internet addresses has become the
focus of heated debates and litigation.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE PASSES DEEPER TAX CUT PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The House narrowly approved a plan to cut taxes and spending far
more deeply than last year's bipartisan balanced budget deal. The
House plan calls for about $100 billion in tax cuts in the next
five years, offset by spending cuts of the same amount. The primary
tax cut would be a reduction in the so-called marriage penalty, the
provision in the tax code that requires many two-income couples to
pay more than they would if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   VW BACKED FOR ROLLS PURCHASE
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of Vickers voted overwhelmingly to sell Rolls-Royce
Motor Cars to Volkswagen for $703 million, rejecting bids from BMW
and a group of Rolls enthusiasts, who had hoped to keep the famed
luxury car brand in British hands. The deal still needs the
approval of Rolls-Royce PLC, the aircraft engine company, over use
of the Rolls name.
</P>
<P>
   NO FURTHER CUTS, MOTOROLA SAYS
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Motorola, Charles Galvin, said it did not
expect any additional job cuts beyond its announced plans to
eliminate 15,000 positions, or 10 percent of its work force, in the
next year. Galvin also said the company, a leading maker of
cellular phones and pagers, expects the semiconductor market to
shrink by 2 percent this year, a sharp contrast to forecasts of a
17 percent growth rate at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIAN BANK BIDDING BRAWL
</P>
<P>
   Fortis Group raised its bid for Generale de Banque to about
$13.4 billion, topping a $12.6 billion offer from ABN Amro Holding
NV. The move elevated the intensity of an unusual bidding battle to
form one of Europe's biggest financial services companies in
advance of European monetary union next year.
</P>
<P>
   VIVENDI SELLS ELECTRAFINA STAKE
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi, the French municipal services, media and
telecommunications conglomerate formerly known as Compagnie
Generale des Eaux, sold its 24.6 percent interest in Electrafina,
an energy and communications company, to Groupe Bruxelles Lambert
for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS CRITICIZE CRASH TESTS
</P>
<P>
   American, European and Japanese automakers told a safety
conference that increasingly high-speed government and insurance
industry crash tests were preventing auto engineers from designing
sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and large cars that would be
less dangerous to other motorists.
</P>
</TEXT>
