<HEADLINE>
AFTER DAYLONG SIEGE, SUSPECT LINKED TO CHESIMARD SURRENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a 23-hour siege punctuated by police bursts of
tear gas and water from high-pressure hoses, a robbery suspect once
active in a black militant group surrendered Friday and ended a
standoff that shattered the calm of a New Jersey coastal town, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Donald Bunting, an ex-convict identified as a
friend of fugitive Joanne Chesimard, emerged from his barricaded
apartment in Bradley Beach at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman used the standoff, which had turned a
blue-collar neighborhood of converted bungalows into a paramilitary
camp, to criticize the Clinton administration for not pressing
Cuban President Fidel Castro to surrender Ms. Chesimard to the New
Jersey authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this has not been at the top of a president's
agenda,'' Whitman said in a letter to the White House released
after Bunting was taken into custody. ``But, while it may be clear
that Castro and Chesimard may be perfect together, the United
States should have no part in supporting his corrupt regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chesimard, whom police once called the ``soul'' of the Black
Liberation Army, took refuge in Cuba in 1984, five years after
escaping from a New Jersey prison while serving a term for the 1973
murder of a New Jersey State trooper, Werner Foerster.
</P>
<P>
   Foerster was slain execution-style with his own weapon after a
gunfight with Ms. Chesimard and two companions on the New Jersey
Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   The state police described Bunting as a member of the Black
Liberation Army in the late 1960s and early '70s and said he had
corresponded with Ms. Chesimard in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Bunting, 48, was charged with armed robbery and attempted armed
robbery in an Asbury Park case and weapons violations for two
handguns recovered in Bradley Beach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
