<HEADLINE>
STIFF SUSPENSIONS ISSUED IN ANGELS-ROYALS BRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Measured by the suspensions that Gene Budig, the American League
president, issued to members of the Anaheim Angels and the Kansas
City Royals Friday, last month's brawl between the Yankees and the
Baltimore Orioles was only a preliminary. Budig suspended managers
Terry Collins of the Angels and Tony Muser of the Royals for eight
games each and nine players for one to four games for their roles
in a game filled with beanballs and fights on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Budig, continuing to crack down on such incidents, fined the
managers and players and also fined three coaches: Joe Maddon of
the Angels and Rich Dauer and Jamie Quirk of the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials of the American and National leagues, the
number of player suspensions resulting from the game _ 22 _ was the
most in at least 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Five players were suspended after the Orioles' Armando Benitez
hit the Yankees' Tino Martinez with a pitch on May 19, triggering a
brawl at Yankee Stadium. Benitez had the longest suspension, eight
days.
</P>
<P>
   The latest disciplinary action stemmed from two brawls during
the game in Kansas City, which featured five hit batters. Chris
Haney and Jim Pittsley of the Royals hit Phil Nevin in the fifth
and seventh innings, respectively; Rich DeLucia of the Angels hit
Dean Palmer in the eighth; Scott Service of Kansas City hit Darrin
Erstad in the ninth, and Mike Holtz of Anaheim hit Jose Offerman in
the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Benches emptied and brawls erupted after Nevin was hit in the
seventh and Offerman in the ninth. Twelve players were ejected from
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents had their origin in a home-plate collision last
year between Nevin, when he played for Detroit, and Mike Sweeney, a
Kansas City catcher. According to a lawyer with firsthand knowledge
of the circumstances, Nevin and Sweeney resolved their differences
the next day but did so unknown to some of the Royals pitchers.
Haney presumably was one of those who did not know and hit Nevin.
Pittsley, another one, also did not know that Haney had already hit
Nevin, so he plunked him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Budig noted the responsibility of the managers in Tuesday's
incidents, which resulted in the ejection of 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American League has a right to expect much from its field
managers,'' he said. ``They are, after all, the ones who chart the
strategy of the game for their players and the ones who determine,
in large measure, player attitudes and actions. Managers are
expected to be strong leaders and epitomize the highest degree of
accountability on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Budig, who coincidentally attended the game, said he was
distressed to see what he called ``utter disregard for player
safety,'' adding, ``There was a clear breakdown in leadership, and
the managers must assume much of the responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight-game suspensions for the managers match the penalty
incurred by Benitez, who ignited the brawl at Yankee Stadium. Four
other players received suspensions of three or two games for that
incident.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest action, Budig suspended Kansas City's Felix
Martinez, who was sent to the minor leagues after the brawl, for
five games, and Jack McDowell of Anaheim for four games. Other
Angels players suspended were Nevin for three games, DeLucia and
Holtz for two each and Frank Bolick and Damon Mashore for one each.
Two other Royals players, Pittsley and Service, each incurred a
two-game suspension. The players were fined $1,000 or $500 for a
total of $7,500.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is not the first time that both managers were suspended for
their part in the same on-field fight. In fact, the most recent
incident also involved Collins, when he was managing the Houston
Astros. Collins and Davey Johnson of the Cincinnati Reds were
suspended along with four players for a fight on Sept. 5, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The last time both managers were suspended following an American
League game was also in 1995. The managers were Terry Bevington of
Chicago and Phil Garner of Milwaukee, who had been suspended with
Tony LaRussa of Oakland after a 1993 brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of nine players surpasses the seven players who
were suspended in 1993 following a fight between the Orioles and
the Seattle Mariners. In a 1984 incident, managers Joe Torre of
Atlanta (three games) and Dick Williams of San Diego (10 games)
were suspended and 17 players were disciplined, though only five
were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   None of the suspensions will begin until next Friday, and they
will be served consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   The league had two reasons for the delay. It wanted to wait
until after the seven-day appeal period had elapsed and avoid the
interrupted three-game suspension that the Yankees' Darryl
Strawberry concocted so that he could play against Boston two weeks
ago. The league also didn't want to interfere with the interleague
schedule that began Friday night and runs through next Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
