<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC REACHES CWS FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. - USC ended LSU's recent dominance of what was once
its own private tournament and at the same time wiped aside any
lingering questions about West Coast college baseball by knocking
the Tigers out of the College World Series Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you hope to survive?'' was one of the questions put to
USC coach Mike Gillespie last weekend after LSU bombed homer after
homer, a record eight in all, in beating the Trojans in a
first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   Safe to say the Trojans are surviving just fine after marching
through the loser's bracket with three successive wins, the last
two over two-time defending champion LSU, including what Gillespie
called a ``near perfect'' 7-3 victory on Friday at Rosenblatt
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With it, the Trojans reached the championship game for a record
14th time and today will face Pac-10 rival Arizona State for the
CWS crown.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second successive year two teams from the same
conference have met in the title game - last year LSU and Alabama
of the Southeastern Conference battled in the championship game -
but it's hard to imagine two more bitter foes going after the same
ring. In recent years there have been two on-the-field brawls
between USC and ASU, and earlier this season Arizona State coach
Pat Murphy complained bitterly about the Trojans stealing his
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been allegations that we know their signs,''
Gillespie said Friday. ``We don't. I'm just hoping our guys know
our signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie has flashed all the right ones since that 12-10
opening-round loss to LSU, and he made all the right moves again on
Saturday, enough for LSU coach Skip Bertman to note, ``SC is at the
top of its game. They're hitting on all cylinders. Murphy better
watch out. His team has been sitting for two days (since knocking
out Long Beach State, 14-4, on Wednesday night) and (USC's)
momentum really helped them today.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior right-hander Mike Penney shut out LSU on four hits over
seven innings and benefited from three home runs, two by Jason
Lane, who also pitched the final 1 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never seemed to make any mistakes,'' LSU's All-American
first baseman Eddy Furniss said of Lane. ``It was masterful
pitching. We put the ball in play against him, but not with much
authority. We haven't run into dominating pitching all season, but
he shut us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Seth Etherton did on Thursday in a 5-4 victory that got
the Trojans to Friday's elimination game.
</P>
<P>
   Penney was tagged for a three-run homer in the eighth by
designated hitter Jeff Leaumont -- ``One of the few mistakes he
made all day,'' Leaumont said - but by then the Trojans had opened
a seven-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who leads the CWS in hits with 12, slugged a two-run homer
in the fifth to highlight a three-run inning against LSU's Doug
Thompson, Morgan Ensberg homered with no one aboard in the sixth
and Lane hit his second to lead off the seventh - his first
two-homer game as a Trojan - and knock out Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd had my number the whole series,'' Lane said of Thompson,
who hurled three scoreless innings in the first-round meeting. ``I
just tried to stay back, and he hung a curve. I was able to get the
good part of the bat on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Penney, who had pitched in relief in two earlier games, reeled
through the first four innings, allowing only two baserunners,
which was a key, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nerves were a factor early on,'' Penney said, ``and I'm
normally a slow starter. After the first inning I thought, `Hey, I
survived it,' and then I just tried to keep my team in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If Penney was nervous at all, Bertman didn't notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been playing with a lot of excitement, a lot of
enthusiasm,'' the LSU coach said, ``and Mike Penney took that away.
USC is clearly better than we are right now . . . over the last 48
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's All-Pac-10 showdown, freshman Rik Currier, who struck
out 12 and pitched four-hit ball in a 7-1 victory over Mississippi
State last Tuesday, will start for USC; Ryan Mills, well-rested
after beating Miami, 9-2, last Sunday, will start for Arizona
State.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans and Sun Devils split their six regular-season games.
Mills was 1-1 against the Trojans, getting rocked for five runs on
six hits in three innings in a 6-3 loss March 15, then three weeks
later striking out 15 and allowing only three hits in an 18-3 romp.
Currier was the losing pitcher in another ASU runaway, 24-4, on
April 11.
</P>
<P>
   But, as ASU's Murphy pointed out, ``They didn't have (Eric)
Munson then, and to me he's the best hitter in college baseball.
They've got the momentum, they've won three in a row, we've got our
work cut out.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
