<HEADLINE>
MAN AVOIDS DEATH PENALTY TRIAL WITH PLEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Avoiding what would have been the first federal death
penalty trial in Manhattan in more than four decades, a Connecticut
man made a plea bargain in federal district court Friday, admitting
he burned his fiancee to death while she was locked in the trunk of
his car, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Deric Frank, 23, of Norwalk, Conn., pleaded
guilty to one count of interstate kidnapping, conspiracy and three
charges related to domestic violence and violating an order of
protection. If a jury had convicted him of the kidnapping charges,
Frank could have faced execution.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank agreed to a brokered arrangement of life in prison
without the possibility of parole, said Shirah Neiman, deputy
United States attorney for the southern district of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Frank admitted that he abducted his fiancee, Shaneika Price, 24,
on March 11 in Stamford, Conn. Frank had often beaten and menaced
Ms. Price, prosecutors said, and on the day before her murder, she
had obtained an order of protection against Frank.
</P>
<P>
   He locked her into the trunk of his car and drove to New York,
to an access road to the Cross Bronx Expressway. He then lighted
the car on fire, burning his girlfriend alive.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they believed that the last federal capital
case in Manhattan was in 1954, ending in the execution of Gerhard
A. Puff, who killed an FBI agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
