r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-AZR &LR;      06-05 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH-STATE SEPARATION THIN AT CHARTER SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The line between church and state shrinks to a
pinstripe at a Higley charter school. While the school runs on
taxpayer dollars, its big red-white-and-blue sign proudly
proclaims: ``In God We Trust.'' At a Phoenix charter school, a
picture of the Virgin Mary hung for a time in the school office.
And in Mesa, a charter school placed an advertisement encouraging
students to attend Mormon seminary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; When it comes to separating religion and government, there are
charter schools that walk that fine line and others that have
clearly crossed it.
</P>
<P>
   National and local critics say that such violations cannot be
tolerated in schools that are run privately but are funded
publicly. Charter-school supporters say mistakes are bound to
occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think horrible things are happening in charter schools,''
said Eleanor Eisenberg, executive director of the Arizona Civil
Liberties Union. ``Religion is one of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   If religion is cropping up on signs and in advertising, what's
to say it isn't seeping into Arizona classroom, she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, believe that isn't happening. They contend the
religious overtones that have percolated to the surface in Arizona
-_ many of which were corrected as soon as they were discovered _-
are part of the growing pains charter schools must go through as
they find their place in today's educational marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to live and learn,'' said Mary Gifford, a charter
school advocate who works for the conservative think tank, the
Goldwater Institute. ``We're going to have to roll with the punches
and let the market correct itself.''
</P>
<P>
   As a graduate of Mountain View High School, she remembers an
incident more than a decade ago where she was asked to fill out a
religion-type card. Her mother complained and the practice was
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But no one called for the public district school to be closed.
It's a different story when charter schools make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask that the charter be revoked,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   She realizes that the incidents damage charter schools in some
people's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this type of (religious) thing scare some people away? Of
course,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But every time a problem arises at one school, it makes all
charter schools take a magnifying glass to themselves, Gifford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Take Life School College Preparatory in Mesa. In May, an
advertisement the school took out in the ``Beehive,'' a Church of
Latter-Day Saints publication, was passed along to various media
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The ad listed 10 reasons LDS parents should choose Life School.
</P>
<P>
   ``1. Select an LDS Mentor. Your child will be with this master
teacher every day for several years if you wish,'' the
advertisement states.
</P>
<P>
   The ad worried even those who embrace charter schools, including
Lisa Graham Keegan, Arizona's superintendent of public instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Alverson, Life School's executive director, sent her an
apologetic letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have instructed the paper to pull our ad immediately,'' he
wrote in the letter dated May 18. ``If our advertising misleads the
general public to think we are, somehow, offering religious
instruction, then we are in the wrong and need to change the way we
advertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Alverson said this week he may have approached the line, even
looked at it but he skirted it when he placed the ad in the
``Beehive'' more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a public school,'' he said. ``Advertisements and what
happens in the classroom are two different animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Alverson wanted to show off his schools and what they have to
offer. So he took out ads in a Mormon publication, a Catholic
newspaper and a Jewish one as well as nonsecular publications,
similar to what his competition, Mesa Public Schools, has done.
</P>
<P>
   Never did he envision his actions would make news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet every charter school looked at the way it markets itself
after the Life School ad,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the country, the problems have been more
blatant.
</P>
<P>
   In California, a lawsuit recently was filed against a
New-Age-type charter school claiming it was promoting religious
perspectives in the classroom. Teachers apparently were asked to
undergo specialized training that smacked of religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to see national problems when it comes to
charter schools violating the separation of church and state,''
said Joe Conn, a spokesman for the Washington D.C.-based Americans
United for Separation of Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some schools are going as far as they can with this. That
raises very serious legal issues,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Conn said that laws governing charter schools should be
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John Huppenthal, R-Chandler, doesn't see it that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think generally people should be cautious about these
things,'' said the charter-school proponent. ``But the remedies are
more likely to be at the administrative level than the statutory
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Larsen, executive director of the State Board for
Charter Schools also cautions against over-reaction. Many of the
problems are caused by naivety, she said.
</P>
<P>
   There's the story of a charter school that wanted to advertise
by placing fliers on cars parked at churches. They were advised not
to by the charter board. &UR; Instead, market broadly, they advised.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was NFL-YET Academy in south Phoenix. During a visit
last spring, Gifford, who used to be the state charter board's
executive director, noticed a prayer and a Virgin Mary picture in
the school office. She told school officials it might be
misconstrued and workers removed the item.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people who get into the charter school business
really want to help children and parents,'' Larsen said. ``People
``People don't do it (promote religion) intentionally but it's part
of what they believe in and they don't think it's harmful. When
it's charter schools, you have to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, it's complaints from parents that make officials aware of
the possibility of religion making it's way into charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   One of them alerted the State Board of Charter Schools about the
sign in front of Eagle's Aerie School in Higley. ``In God We
Trust'' it says, underneath the school name and a picture of an
eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Unsure if such words were appropriate, the charter board sought
advice from the Attorney General's Office. It's OK, experts
decided. Basically, it's similar to the ``Pledge of Allegiance''
that includes the line: ``One nation under God,'' Larsen explained.
</P>
<P>
   However, there have been other complaints against the same
school. Parents who volunteer on the playground apparently referred
to each other as ``sister,'' a common practice in the Mormon faith.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldwater Institute's Gifford called school director Tim
Peak at the time and asked him to put a stop to it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peak, who admits many Arizona charter schools are predominantly
filled with LDS children, said in no way is religion part of the
school day at Eagle's Aerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's against the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The school, like it's name and sign suggest, is strong on
Americanism.
</P>
<P>
   But several parents still have concerns about the school. None
of Patty Wilson's children will be back at Eagle's Aerie in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   They got tired of being asked if they are Mormon, which they are
not, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening is they're trying to take public money and
open a private school,'' Wilson said. ``It isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Pearce can be reached at 444-7981 or at
kelly.pearce(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
