<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6995 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TRUEVALUE-TEX     06-05 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUEVALUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART HOPES TO ESTABLISH A SLOW RACE; BOAT HAS FASTER
EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ With his straightest poker face, pole sitter
Tony Stewart says he is plotting a comfortable race pace for the
True Value 500K.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 qualifier Billy Boat says he is anticipating a flat-out
sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Who's zooming whom?
</P>
<P>
   Front-row starters Stewart and Boat _ and a handful of drivers
who routinely have been breaking the 220-mph barrier _ will have
312 laps to decide if the True Value 500K becomes a shootout at 8
tonight on the revamped 1.5-mile Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Boat emerged as odds-on favorites in the Pep Boys
Indy Racing League Series event after two hot laps of qualifying
yesterday afternoon. Originally scheduled for Thursday night,
qualifying was washed out by a rainstorm and rebooked yesterday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by an ambient temperature of only 66 degrees after a
muggy, mid-90-degree day Thursday, Stewart bagged the No. 1
qualifying spot with a top lap of 224.448 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get around here,'' said Stewart, 27, who exited
the Indy 500 last month with a blown motor while in the lead. ``I
was thinking what I wanted to eat for lunch after I got done
qualifying. It's a tribute to the job they've done on this
racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was referring to the massive revamping done to TMS since
April 22, when the 24-degree banked turns were torn up and
reconfigured, and the entire track repaved.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's run, which took only 24.059 seconds, was a record
breaker on several fronts. It erased the TMS qualifying mark of
216.494 mph Stewart set last June, when the format also included a
pit stop and tire change.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's lap also is the fastest pole-speed run by a ``new
formula'' IRL car, a package featuring specification chassis and
normally aspirated V-8 engines introduced in January 1996. The
prior IRL pole record was Boat's four-lap average of 223.503 mph
set at the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway last month.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who held the pole before Stewart bumped him off here,
settled for the outside spot of the two-car front row at 223.547
mph.
</P>
<P>
   But more than two hours after the conclusion of qualifying,
Stewart fired another shot. The reigning series champion ripped off
a lap of 225.696 mph during the day's final practice _ a speed that
is the fastest by a ``new formula'' IRL car but not a record
because it was not posted during qualifying or the race. The
previous record was Boat's 224.573 mph on the first lap of his
four-lap qualifying run at IMS.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, Stewart insisted he was not going to run his race
car into the blacktop once the green flag falls at 8 p.m. Stewart
posted the fastest circuit of last year's race, at 218.094 mph, on
lap 97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really concerned at the start about setting the
pace,'' said Stewart, driver of the No. 1 Glidden/Menards Special
Dallara/Aurora. ``I'll run what I think is comfortable, and I'm not
going to look at a stopwatch to do it. I'll just run what I feel
the car is happy with. If that's fast enough to lead the race,
we'll lead. If someone wants to go a little quicker at the
beginning, we'll let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be Boat's cue to scoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I foresee this being a sprint race,'' said Boat, 32, driver of
the No. 11 Conseco Dallara/Aurora owned by four-time Indy 500
champion A.J. Foyt. ``I think you're going to be running as hard as
you can every lap, because as long as your race car doesn't go
away, the racetrack lets you run hard. You're going to have to be
flat out as much as you can if you're going to run up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who exited the Indy 500 with a drive line problem, said
running flat-out figures to take its mechanical toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably won't see 224 mph laps in the race, but I think
you'll see 220s,'' Boat said. ``There's no doubt we'll be running
faster here than we did at Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen drivers in the 28-car field _ four short of the full IRL
complement of 32 _ broke Stewart's old qualifying record of 216.494
mph. Robbie Buhl, Stewart's teammate, will start on the inside of
Row 2 after a lap at 223.104 mph in the No. 3 Johns Manville
Dallara/Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   Arie Luyendyk, who was awarded the victory in this race last
year after an all-night scoring review, will start fourth in the
No. 5 Sprint PCS/Radio Shack G Force/Aurora after a lap at 221.166
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a good starting position,'' said Luyendyk, the two-time
Indy 500 champion who won here at the expense of Boat. ``They're
(Stewart's team) still 3 mph quicker than we are. But the race is
going to be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who was denied his first IRL victory by the revamped
scoring, insisted that TMS does not owe him a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we definitely have a lot of incentive going into this
race,'' Boat said, ``to try to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
