<SLUG> BC-BABBIT-TROUT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT PUTS BULL TROUT ON THE THREATENED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, MONT. _ The Endangered Species Act reached higher into
mountains of the Columbia Basin Friday when the bull trout was
listed as threatened by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service listed the brawny fish as
threatened in parts of Montana, Idaho, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbit, who made the announcement, said
the agency is considering extending the listing to include bull
trout in Puget Sound and Olympic Peninsula, as well as along parts
of Montana and the Idaho-Nevada border. In addition, Babbit said
the government is planning to study whether the westslope cutthroat
trout are also in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting bull trout, which require especially cold, clean
water for spawning and rearing, would entail leaving more trees
near timberland streams, screening of irrigation pumps, leaving
more water in rivers in late summer and providing passage around
dams.
</P>
<P>
   Babbit announced the listings from the bank of the Big Blackfoot
River, the legendary trout stream from Norman Maclean's novella,
``A River Runs Through It,'' then pulled on waders to go fly
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dammed our rivers,'' Babbit said, as he explained the
causes of the bull trout's decline. ``We diverted them, split them
with roads and culverts, pumped them dry. We mined their headwaters
and left acid waste to bleed into them for decades after exhausting
the mine. We logged them from mouth to source, removing shade,
shelter, nutrients and insect habitat, letting the barren banks
erode and silt up spawning gravel beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove vast cattle herds into and up their waters. We
dumpled chemicals and sewage and slaughterhouse waste into them.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, the secretary said, we must repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will resist, Babbitt said. But he added, ``I think
we're getting past that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Farm Bureau is worried irrigators could face
government demands to leave water in streams. And some timber
industry officials grumbled that they were already doing things for
the fish.
</P>
<P>
   But the flood of regulatory action surrounding the bull trout
sparked nothing like the anger that greeted the listing of the
northern spotted owl eight years ago, nor the anxiety that met
salmon listings in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The states of Montana and Idaho, along with the Plum Creek
Timber Co. and an assortment of agencies and landowners in the bull
trout's range, are already working on habitat protection and
planning, Babbitt noted.
</P>
<P>
   Pacts with state agencies assure that the listings will not
prevent bull trout fishing, Babbitt noted, as he waved his Montana
fishing license. Most fishing rules across the region call for live
release of the bright orange or red speckled fish.
</P>
<P>
   The new federal actions extend fish-protections to the upper
streams and lakes of the Columbia and Klamath basins, beyond lower
reaches to which dwindling salmon and steelhead already are
bringing the influence of the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   In Blackfoot, a partnership of ranchers, local industries and
fish and wildlife agencies has spent $1.5 million improving stream
habitat during the last seven years. The remedies have shown some
improvement. Bull trout numbers are up 57 percent; cutthroat trout
have exploded to more than seven times their former abundance. And
fly fishermen are spending an estimated $7 million annually to fish
the Blackfoot alone.
</P>
<P>
   The job is far from finished, but, ``we've got the river turned
around,'' said Paul Roos, who runs Pro Outfitters, which provides
guiding and gear for fishers here and in other rivers in Montana,
the fly fishers' nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Far from accelerating the listing, the Interior Department
stalled it for most of the last six years, sometimes by saying
listing was warranted by bull trout declines but precluded by other
agency priorities. The agency was pushed to action by repeated
proposals and lawsuits from several environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to litigate every step of the way,'' said Mike
Bader, executive director of the Alliance for the Wild Rockies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
