<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-MOTOROLA-FOLO     06-05 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-MOTOROLA-FOLO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola Investors, analyst skeptical about Motorola
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Tx. Analysts and the investors were skeptical Friday
about Motorola Inc.'s restructuring plan, which includes slashing
its work force by 10 percent _ 15,000 workers _ in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   After rising in early trading Friday, shares of the company fell
56 1/4 cents to $50.93 3/4 to close near the company's 52-week low
of $50.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts warn that a restructuring begun last year in the
company's Semiconductor Products Sector, based in Austin, has yet
to show benefits. They wonder if the one announced late Thursday
will be more effective.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, based in Schaumburg, Ill., said it was downsizing in
an effort to save $750 million over the next year. It also will
consolidate its semiconductor manufacturing and cut low-performing
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola blamed the cutbacks on weak pricing and lower demand in
Asia. The company got 26 percent of its 1997 revenue of $29.8
billion from Asia, Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNBC news on Friday morning, chief
executive officer Chris Galvin said the company had expected a 17
percent growth rate for the chip industry instead of the 2 percent
drop now forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said Motorola will trim ``pockets of the company'' around
the world. ``We very much regret the impact that this will have on
selected employees at Motorola,'' he said on CNBC. ``We'll handle
the people situation with the traditional Motorola sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Austin operations, where it has about 10,000
workers, are expected to be hard hit. Motorola's Semiconductor
Products Sector is based in Austin and the company has five chip
plants here. Two of them are more than 20 years old and another is
16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday how many workers in the area would be
fired and what parts of the semiconductor sector would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the company said temporary workers might be let
go first and that senior employees would be offered severance
packages. Announcements on cuts are expected to come as early as
Monday as managers at the company met Friday to discuss the
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the company's actions will help its prospects, but
some said Motorola's retooling, including the semiconductor
restructuring begun last year, have been sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Modoff, an analyst at Alex Brown, said investors are
taking a ``wait-and-see'' approach to the stock. His company
recommends holding. ``People have heard this before. Obviously,
people aren't buying into this as they have in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A report from the Merrill Lynch brokerage firm said signs are
positive for the corporate restructuring, ``however, a
semiconductor sector renewal plan was implemented about a year ago,
and we have yet to see tangible benefits from that plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The semiconductor plan was aimed at making the company more
responsive to customers and bringing products to market faster.
</P>
<P>
   In semiconductors, Motorola is the fourth biggest supplier in
the world. It leads in one category, microcontrollers. Those are
chips that are embedded in autos, for example, to control braking
and accleration. In its Thursday announcement, Motorola said it
would continue to concentrate on microcontrollers.
</P>
<P>
   In other chip categories, however, it ranks third or fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Motorola and Lucent Technologies said they
would team up on a new generation of digital signal processors,
chips that translate sound and vision into a digital format. It is
expected to be a high growth market.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been working on a broad corporate plan that
would give it a more customer-focused approach. It has yet to
reveal details of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola also faces intense competition in its cellular and
wireless phone businesses. Ericsson and Nokia have eaten away much
of Motorola's market share in cellular. Motorola has been slow to
bring wireless products to market.
</P>
<P>
   Will Strauss, president of Forward Concepts Market Research,
said the company's management faces a tough Asian market as well as
its own sprawling size in turning its fortunes around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to turn an aircraft carrier,'' Strauss said.
``It's a very slow thing and the Asian economic situation really
rubs salt into the wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss and other analysts predicted Motorola would close some
of its older chip production factories and spin off some of its
slow-performing businesses while concentrating on its satellite,
digital signal processor and digital wireless products.
</P>
<P>
   Investment firms including Merrill Lynch revised their estimates
for the current quarter after warnings from the company that it
would not meet the expected 20 cents a share earnings for the
second quarter. In a report issued Friday, Merrill Lynch said the
company's problems ``were worse than we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola engineers and chip designers looking for jobs may find
their best prospects at smaller firms, said Kim Butler, president
of Greywolf Consulting in Austin. ``In Austin, a lot of the
opportunities are with smaller design centers and start-up
companies rather than the larger firms,'' he said. ``There are also
a lot of opportunities on either coast, especially in California
and Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   At larger companies, Samsung, with has about 1,000 Austin
employees, isn't hiring, said Bill Cryer, a spokesman. ``Right now
we're at a plateau,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AMD Inc., on the other hand, is hiring product test and
development engineers, semiconductor design engineers and process
engineers, said spokesman Robert Durand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
