<HEADER>
A7000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-COX     06-05 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catholic Church examines its response to Priests' misconduct
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- For 2,000 years, symbolic devices have
been essential to the Catholic Church and its rituals for the
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The ring of the bells, the smell of the incense, the light
radiating through stained-glass windows and the priest's bright
vestments touched the senses, transforming ceremony into spiritual
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Today one of the church's most sacred symbols wears the stain of
scandal. The priest's white collar that once was a sign of trust
and virtue has become an emblem of a breach of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no more pedestals left for priests,'' said Bishop
Robert Lynch. ``Priests must behave differently now _ even the good
priests. Times have changed, and people look at us differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Lynch took control of the Diocese of Palm Beach when
its bishop, J. Keith Symons, resigned after admitting he sexually
molested five boys decades ago. Three of them have reportedly come
forward and acknowledged their abuse to the church.
</P>
<P>
   The highest U.S. Catholic to be forced from office for molesting
minors, Symons adds another disgrace to a troubled ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American bishops have made some progressive steps toward
dealing with this crisis,'' said Jason Berry, author of Lead Us Not
Into Temptation, a 1992 book on clergy sexual abuse. ``I don't
think they understand the depths of the decay. I think the bishops
view this as a public relations problem that will pass in time as
many problems have for the church through the centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The fall of Symons is a reminder that the clergy are vulnerable
to the same evils that infect the rest of humanity. Lynch said the
church has turned again to symbolism to demonstrate that the
priesthood is not deity and not far removed from the faithful
masses.
</P>
<P>
   Confessionals are now being built with clear glass windows
instead of heavy curtains, he said. Communion rails no longer
separate priests and their altar from parishioners. And more and
more, priests are taking off their collars when going to public
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do things the same way we did 30 years ago,'' Lynch
said. ``We have to earn the respect of the people through honest
ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   The continuing onslaught of sexual misconduct cases has
complicated the already difficult task of recruiting young men to a
life of celibacy in the clergy, then keeping them in it.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 men worldwide have left the priesthood since
the 1960s, according to Georgetown University's Center for Applied
Research in the Apostolate. In the United States, the number of
priests has fallen to just under 50,000, a 17 percent decline since
the mid-1960s. Some breakaway Catholic reform groups predict that
by the year 2000, the number of married former priests will exceed
that of active ones.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the bishops have moved to used tougher screening
procedures for seminary candidates. Catholic students attend two or
three psycho-sexual workshops each year as part of the five- to
seven-year process of training for the priesthood. Psychological
examinations are required for admission to the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working harder to develop a high sense of
professionalism,'' Lynch said. ``Maybe Ronald Reagan said it best:
Trust but verify.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishops also have developed a plan of action for handling
scandal. The National Conference of Catholic Bishops in 1992 wrote
these guidelines for use in cases of sexual abuse:
</P>
<P>
   _ Respond promptly to all allegations of abuse where there is
reasonable belief that abuse has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   _ If such an allegation is supported by sufficient evidence,
relieve the alleged offender promptly of his ministerial duties and
refer him for appropriate medical evaluation and intervention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comply with the obligations of civil law as it regards to
reporting of the incident and cooperating with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reach out to the victims and their families and communicate
sincere commitment to their spiritual and emotional well-being.
</P>
<P>
   _ Within the confines of respect for privacy of those involved,
deal as openly as possible with members of the community.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge, however, that the guidelines are more symbolism
_ that they're more public relations than solutions to real
problems in the real world outside the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Peters, of Palm Beach Gardens, has been doing battle with
the church over the sexual abuse inflicted by her uncle, a Jesuit
priest, close to 50 years ago. She said he molested her more than
100 times and also molested her four sisters as they grew up in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after suffering quietly for more than five decades, the
women informed the Maryland Provincial of the Society of Jesus in
Baltimore of their abuse. The Jesuits acknowledged the priest's
problems and sent him to the St. Luke's psychiatric center in
Suitland, Md., for therapy.
</P>
<P>
   After four months, he was released and given a job on the
Georgetown University campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't believe that after so much abuse, this was how the
church dealt with this,'' Peters said. ``It's incredible that he's
on a college campus in the company of women.''
</P>
<P>
   A Jesuits attorney did not return phone calls Friday, but Rev.
James R. Stormes, the Jesuits' provincial, defended the handling of
the case in a letter to Peters and her sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sympathize with the pain they are feeling,'' he wrote. ``He
is forbidden to exercise any public pastoral ministry. (He) has
complied generously and sincerely with the program of treatment and
supervision . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Denis L. Ventriglia, a Wilmington, N.C., attorney who represents
the women, said a monetary settlement is not why the women came
forth with their charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting to see whether or not the Jesuits will put in
writing that his collar will be removed permanently,'' Ventriglia
said. ``The reason being the collar engenders so much trust by
children and adults. It is a symbol that carries great power.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry believes the bishops have not yet confronted the root
issues that create the continuing turmoil within the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this mentality of institutional defenses that seems
to view the messengers of bad news as culprits rather than trying
to understand why the news is bad,'' he said. ``The priesthood is
not the institution it was a generation ago. Symons is another
episode in a continuing scandal of epic proportions. There is a
deep systematic problem in Catholic culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
