</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANDER-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another bizarre twist for Holyfield
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- What is farce to the rest of the world is normal to
Evander Holyfield. He lives in a place where fools wearing fans
pounce from the sky and where ears are hors d'oeuvres. Around each
corner, abomination awaits.
</P>
<P>
   What's a little virus when you've survived being called a
walking heart attack?
</P>
<P>
   So, even as his Saturday night fight with Henry Akinwande was
collapsing, Holyfield kept to routine. It's all that maintains a
sane man in an insane position.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say he didn't have a violent reaction during a
quick huddle with his advisors late Friday morning beside the
Madison Square Garden training ring. The news of Akinwande's
hepatitis caused Holyfield to arch not one, but both, eyebrows. For
him, that was an emotional earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Holyfield climbed directly into the ring and began the
regimen of stretching and sweating just as if nothing were said.
</P>
<P>
   He shut out the buzzing of the conspiracy theorists around the
ring. Was it really a virus that had suddenly gripped the
challenger, they wondered, or had Akinwande actually tested
positive for poor ticket sales? Boxing always brings out the worst
kind of thoughts, no matter the blood evidence.
</P>
<P>
   All around this doomed fight card, medical science intervened.
Heavyweight Ray Mercer, on the undercard, also was diagnosed with
hepatitis. Maria Nieves-Garcia, the opponent for women's champion
Christy Martin, was found to be 21 weeks pregnant. Suddenly,
Madison Square Garden was turned into the world's largest free
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield pushed down the inevitable disappointment of Friday's
events. This was to be the $11 million payday at the end of 13
weeks of training, as well as some much-needed activity while
Lennox Lewis was out of reach. Still, outwardly, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the guy things happen to,'' he said after the workout
without a cause. ``Personally, I didn't do anything. As long as
it's not my fault, it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   He even joked about the lost wages. ``I would have won anyway,''
Holyfield said. ``I feel I should get the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, y'all will take up a donation for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty is not in understanding such a strange twist, but
in where to rank Friday among all the other bizarre Holyfield
happenings.
</P>
<P>
   This one, of course, would have to go below the night Mike Tyson
used Holyfield's ear for a chew toy. Below Fan Man flying into the
ring during the second fight against Riddick Bowe. Below the
diagnosis after his loss to Michael Moorer that briefly caused
Holyfield to retire with a supposedly defective heart.
</P>
<P>
   But probably above the scramble and cancellations that put him
in an Atlanta ring against Bert Cooper, who then knocked the
hometown champion on his rear. Above his only appearance at the
Garden, an ugly thing halted when Bobby Czyz claimed he was blinded
by some substance on Holyfield's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute nature of the Akinwande test and findings is
baffling, ready fodder for suspicious minds.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone else, the absurdity of Friday would strike like a
shovel between the eyes. For Evander Holyfield, it was just another
day at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
