<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVANDER-MAIN-COX     06-05 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANDER-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hepatitis KOs Akinwande
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After wilting physically against Riddick Bowe and
looking harmless against Bobby Czyz, the munchkin of the
heavyweight division, Evander Holyfield, appeared headed for
retirement. What followed was a rebirth: consecutive dominating
wins over Mike Tyson, a five-knockdown avenging of a loss to
Michael Moorer and $62 million in purses won.
</P>
<P>
   It follows that when Holyfield's soap-opera career continued
Friday with the postponement of tonight's WBA and IBF title fight
against hepatitis-stricken contender Henry Akinwande, Holyfield's
disappoinment soon was replaced by thoughts that this might not be
a horrendous development.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Jim Thomas, said, ``Don't laugh. I've been hanging
around with spiritual people a lot and maybe because of that I
believe something good may come out of this. Things happen in a
strange way. What I'm hoping is that this event unclogs the logjam
and leads us to the fight we all want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Holyfield against Lennox Lewis to unify the
heavyweight championship. Negotiations for that bout fell apart
last winter because the HBO cable network, which held pay-per-view
rights, would not satisfy the purse demands of the two fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas planned to meet with promoter Don King late Friday night
about Holyfield's future.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the WBC champion, tentatively plans a mandatory defense
Sept. 26 against Zeljko Mavrovic.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield would like to meet Lewis in November or December,
which would necessitate Lewis-Mavrovic taking place earlier _ or
not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will be decided until the results of Akinwande's second
blood test are known early next week. He submitted a blood sample
Tuesday that came back positive for hepatitis B on Friday. The New
York Athletic Commission, one of seven state bodies that mandate a
screening for hepatitis, called off the bout because of the risk of
Akinwande spilling infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   If the results are negative, the fight could be rescheduled for
as early as next month. The camps of the two fighters will join
King and Showtime cable executive Jay Larkin next week to determine
whether to set a new date or cancel it. J.C. Courreges, Akinwande's
manager, said, ''If Henry is not going to be well for six months,
obviously we are not going to sue (Holyfield) if he wants to fight
somebody else. We are not his enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield also has a defense, mandated by the IBF, pending
against Vaughn Bean. But Larkin said, ''Nobody wants to see that
fight. Everybody wants Holyfield-Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   The WBA, which mandated the Akinwande fight, also could dictate
a defense against another contender.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield wasn't told of Akinwande's condition until about 11
a.m., after finishing his pre-workout prayer circle with camp
members.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been training for 13 weeks,'' he said. ''For this to
happen the day before the fight is disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he gave his blood sample 10 weeks ago. ``They
want to check me very early,'' he said. ``I'm the guy with the bad
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The joking reference was to Holyfield's misdiagnosed heart
ailment following a loss to Moorer in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is no stranger to hepatitis. A blood sample taken
during training for the third Bowe fight showed he also had
contracted the virus, but had recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things happen to me,'' he said. ''You have to roll with the
punches.''
</P>
<P>
   All parties denied suspicions of doctored blood tests in light
of minimal interest in the fight. Madison Square Garden had
distributed over 8,000 tickets but sold only 4,000 after paying a
$3 million site fee. Some Showtime insiders say the network was
headed for a $5 million pay-per-view loss.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a concern to Holyfield. After concluding his wasted
workout Friday, he was asked about his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''My kids are running track (today),'' he said. ''So I guess I'm
going to a track meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
