</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Testing blowing in Charlotte
 &HT;    Bt Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may be a wind tunnel in Hendrick Motorsports future.
</P>
<P>
   That's the word from team president John Hendrick, who adds that
if it does happen, it will be available for use by all Winston Cup
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made a decision yet, but we are looking at the
expense and so forth,'' said Hendrick, brother of Rick Hendrick.
``We feel that it could work with all the teams that are here
(Charlotte), but we're not sure if we have the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup and Busch Grand National teams currently use the
Lockheed tunnel in Marietta or go to a similar site in Langley,
Va., to test the aerodynamics of their cars. The General Motors
tunnel near Detroit is available to GM teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the teams here, there is definitely a need,''
Hendrick said. ``As many times as we go in (during) the year, and
with all the teams here, it certainly will be more convenient than
others we've used.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 48 Winston Cup teams, 44 are in North Carolina. Of those,
34 are near Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie race
</P>
<P>
   With high profile rookies Kenny Irwin and Steve Park, most
people thought Jerry Nadeau and Kevin Lepage would be also-rans for
Rookie of the Year. Not any longer. Park has been out of action
since breaking his leg in Atlanta, and Irwin has struggled. Lepage
trails Irwin by six points, 128-122. Nadeau, despite missing three
events, is 30 behind Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Last dance
</P>
<P>
   Randy LaJoie makes his final Winston Cup start tonight in place
of Ricky Craven. Then he will pick up his Busch schedule, which
features stops at Fountain, Colo., Watkins Glen, N.Y., West Allis,
Wis., and Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Busch
</P>
<P>
   Baseball-racing
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has invaded NASCAR. St. Louis slugger Mark
McGwire recently purchased a piece of Bobby Hillin's Busch teams
and induced five others to get involved. Joining McGwire are
teammate Gary Gaetti, Danny Shaffer, Andy Benes, Hal Morris and
Pete Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   The missing ingredient is a primary sponsor. Gaetti believes
McGwire's presence will take care of that. ``It's all about opening
doors,'' Gaetti said.
</P>
<P>
   New team
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader and Andy Petree Racing make their debut here
tonight, followed by seven events at Indianapolis Raceway Park,
Michigan Speedway, Bristol Speedway, Dover Downs, Charlotte Motor
Speedway, Gateway International and North Carolina Speedway.
Oakwood Homes is the primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The Earnhardt look
</P>
<P>
   Legendary NASCAR car owner Cotton Owens paid tribute to Dale
Earnhardt Jr. during a recent question-and-answer session. ``He's
got everything it takes. I like the look in his eyes. It's the same
look his dad has. He's going to be something special.'' . . .
Earnhardt is taking the same car, same motor and same setup that
took Park to victory in his final Busch season last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Craftsman trucks
</P>
<P>
   Kirk in jeopardy
</P>
<P>
   It's been a tough year for Dalton's Tammy Jo Kirk. The reason is
lack of sponsorship. As a result, she's made only three races, and
she's unsure about the future if things don't go well this weekend
at Texas and maybe Bristol June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes money to run these things, and we just don't have the
money to do it,'' Kirk said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk ran 17 races a year ago for Geoff Bodine, but he folded the
team to support his son, Barry. ``The biggest thing that is killing
us right now is we don't have the guys here full-time to get the
trucks ready to go and these trucks right,'' she said. ``To run the
rest of the season, we need $30,000 a race, and it would still be a
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy
</P>
<P>
   Jack Sprague took an 18-point lead over Ron Hornaday into
Friday's Pronto Auto Parts 400 at Texas Motor Speedway. Sprague had
a string of 19-consecutive top-10 finishes over two seasons. That's
one short of Hornaday's all-time record.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
