</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-POLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford on the defense
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ One-third of the way into its first year of
Winston Cup racing, Ford's Taurus is winning, while becoming a
popular source of debate in the NASCAR garage area.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the top five drivers and six of the top 10 are driving
the Taurus. Ford drivers also were leading in the standings and
manufacturers' title chase until Jeff Gordon spoiled their party by
driving his Monte Carlo to victory in the Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been tough to find anyone to predict this type of
success one year ago, when Ford began discussing the change from
Thunderbird to Taurus. But the Taurus has five victories _ three by
Mark Martin, two by Dale Jarrett _ in the first 12 races of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even surprised ourselves,'' said Travis Carter, who owns
the Fords driven by Jimmy Spencer. Spencer, 10th in the points
standings, never has finished better than 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet teams contend that the Taurus teams have taken full
advantage of concessions NASCAR gave to the teams when they
switched from Thunderbirds. The Chevy and Pontiac teams also
complained that the racing Taurus bears little resemblance to the
street version.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Evernham, Gordon's crew chief, has been one of the leading
critics of the new Taurus. He argues that the car has been given so
many rules concessions that it could prevent a Chevrolet driver
from winning the Winston Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I said that, and I'm not taking it back,'' Evernham said.
``It's still my opinion and my opinion only, but I believe Ford
still has an aerodynamic advantage with the race car over a
Chevrolet. But that's nobody's fault. They built a good car.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hmiel, manager and crew chief for Johnny Benson's Taurus
team, said it would have been unreasonable to expect a race car to
look identical to the street version.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's normally give and take'' Hmiel said. ``The
manufacturer shows up with something real wild, and NASCAR says,
'Well, we need to look at something a little bit less insane than
that.' We were prepared for that. We knew that we would eventually
get what we thought was a good race car out of it, because NASCAR
wants everything to be so competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the complaining GM teams fail to consider one
important factor: There are more good Ford teams than GM teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong _ every team out there is good,'' Carter
said. ``But as far as on-the-edge-type race teams, I think Ford has
more of those teams right now, and, consequently, they're going to
win more races.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon doesn't appear to be getting much help in holding up the
Chevrolet banner. He won 10 races each in 1996 and 1997, and this
year has three of the five victories by Monte Carlos. Dale
Earnhardt and Bobby Hamilton have the other two, but they're now
13th and 15th in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has got a gift for driving a race car that nobody else
in this garage possesses,'' rival Chevrolet team owner Felix
Sabates said about Gordon. ``I know some of these drivers will get
mad at me for saying that, but it's the fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kid can drive a race car,'' Sabates said, ``and they've
got a great race team. The rest of the Chevrolets aren't going
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many Tauruses in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
