<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL AT WAR WITH MAYOR OVER NEW YORK CITY'S BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Combining a righteous resolve with the nervous
bravado that comes from venturing into the unexplored, the City
Council adopted its own $34 billion budget Friday, triggering what
is likely to be a protracted confrontation between the usually
compliant Council and the city's combative mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The war of words and dollars was well under way before the day's
end. Even as Council members were casting their votes on the second
floor of City Hall, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was holding forth on the
first floor, letting loose a string of adjectives _ ``damaging,''
``illusory,'' ``make-believe,'' _ to describe the Council's version
of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most irresponsible budget I have seen as the mayor
of New York City,'' he said of the first budget ever passed
independently by the City Council. He said that he would do
everything he could, including freezing city financing, to stop the
Council plan from bloating the city's deficit several years from
now.
</P>
<P>
   But Council Speaker Peter Vallone, who is juggling his
governmental duties with his campaign to become governor, dismissed
Giuliani's criticisms as the rantings of a mayor offended by the
bicameral relationship between the executive and the legislative
branches. And he issued an assessment that directly contradicted
the mayor's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most fiscally responsible approved budget that we
have ever seen,'' said Vallone, his words echoing throughout the
City Hall rotunda. It includes what the speaker calls the largest
tax cut in city history, but also provides more money for
libraries, museums and various programs affecting housing and child
care than the mayor's proposed budget does.
</P>
<P>
   Where the truth, or the future, lies in a budget process that
should have been a lot simpler _ the city has a $2 billion surplus,
not a deficit _ remained unclear Friday night. The Council would
actually spend $49 million less in the coming fiscal year than the
mayor proposed, but because the Council would eliminate the
income-tax surcharge, the city would lose substantial revenue in
future years, Giuliani argued. He would extend the surcharge but,
modestly _ compared with the Vallone plan _ cut the personal income
tax over three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mayor and the speaker both indicated Friday that they would
use the powers granted to them by the City Charter to derail each
other's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was expected to make the first move by issuing a new
estimate of city revenues, designed to disrupt the calculations the
Council used to develop its budget. He can also subsequently veto
the budget in whole or in part. But the Democratic-controlled
Council, which approved its budget by a vote of 43-7, can easily
override his veto. Then the mayor could impound the budget, meaning
he could refuse to spend money as the Council dictated.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have the option of taking the matter to court, but
there are time constraints: by law, the budget must be adopted by
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   As the Republican mayor and the Democratic speaker volleyed in
press conferences throughout the day, the unlikely shadow of George
Steinbrenner, the principal owner of the New York Yankees, loomed
over the remnants of their fractured relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone and his aides have maintained that budget negotiations
broke down with the Giuliani administration because of its
insistence that no deal would be made unless the speaker dropped
his plans to test one of the Mayor's pet plans through a referendum
question on November's ballot: whether city taxes should finance a
new ballpark for the Yankees on Manhattan's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has argued that the referendum would hurt his efforts
to prevent Steinbrenner from moving his team out of the Bronx, and
out of the city entirely. Steinbrenner, while indicating his great
interest in moving the Yankees to Manhattan, announced several
weeks ago that he would stay out of the debate until after the
fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, Steinbrenner changed his mind, and suddenly
a resident of Tampa, Fla., had injected himself into the budgetary
process of New York City. He accused Vallone of using the stadium
issue as a ``political baseball'' in his quest to defeat Gov.
George Pataki in November.
</P>
<P>
   Decrying what he called the speaker's ``barrage of hostile
threats,'' Steinbrenner issued a threat similar to ones he has
issued so many times over the last decade: ``I do not want to move
the Yankees from New York, but I must warn: he is bringing us
dangerously close.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the mayor and Howard Rubenstein, Steinbrenner's spokesman,
denied Friday that they had prevailed upon the team owner to issue
the statement. And a person close to Steinbrenner said that his
advisers urged him to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he made a mistake, but he thought he had to defend
Rudy, who's hanging out there,'' said the person, who requested
anonymity. ``I was against it. I thought everyone should shut up
until after the election.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vallone responded by announcing that he was more determined than
ever to push for the referendum _ which might also prompt a higher
voter turnout that could help his political aspirations. He
reiterated that the Council passed its own budget ``because we
would not be held hostage on the single issue of Yankee Stadium _
an issue that has nothing to do with this year's budget priorities
but everything to do with the mayor's personal agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner's comments briefly overshadowed the Council's
unprecedented action, and forced Giuliani to contend with
persistent questions about whether a referendum-related ultimatum
from his administration had caused budget talks to collapse. He
declined to answer those questions directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of versions of what this person said to that
person, people yelling at each other, jumping up and down and
negotiating,'' the mayor said. ``The reality is that irrespective
of any issue with the stadium, this budget is way out of the realm
of reason.''
</P>
<P>
   That concept _ of a budget beyond reason _ became the
administration's official reason for why budget talks had broken
down. And the mayor attributed its irresponsible nature to
Vallone's gubernatorial aspirations. ``This is the kind of thing
that happens,'' he said, ``when people do election-year budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani then delivered a withering critique of the Council's
budget. He said that Council leaders had used extraordinarily
optimistic projections regarding Wall Street's health to calculate
tax revenues for the next several years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
