<SLUG> BC-PIXEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   New Software Finds Crack in Microsoft Armor  
   
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Hoping to loosen Microsoft's ironclad grip on the personal computer
desktop, a tiny Seattle company will unveil an onscreen menu bar
Monday that bypasses Windows with direct links to programs and the
Internet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Pixel Co.'s product, called MySpace, does not replace
Windows. Instead, it sits directly below the Windows taskbar, in
the border around Windows that usually is black. MySpace launches
itself when the PC is started up, before Windows is loaded, and it
remains on the screen at all times.
</P>
<P>
   The innovation also will give PC-makers the ability to display
their brand names continuously onscreen, something that Microsoft
has prevented through its strict licensing agreements that govern
the use of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, say industry experts, it could even serve as a
gateway to an operating system other than Windows, such as one
based on Sun Microsystem's Java software.
</P>
<P>
   PC-makers can program buttons on the MySpace bar to launch
applications or take users directly online. For instance, a
PC-maker could program buttons linked to its own troubleshooting
features inside the computer or to the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   MySpace also can be used to run hardware components such as the
PC's CD player or telephone answering machine. It takes several
steps to run those components through Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Because MySpace uses an area of the screen not used by Windows,
Pixel officials say Microsoft cannot legally oppose it. Nor can the
software giant rig Windows to prevent MySpace from starting or
disable it because the program works directly with the PC's video
software.
</P>
<P>
   Pixel will sell the product to PC-makers, but it also plans to
make a free version available this fall over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``That's important because all my investors had to be
convinced that this couldn't be turned off by some funny code in
Windows,'' said Tom O'Rourke, chief executive of Pixel.
</P>
<P>
   The first big PC-maker to embrace MySpace will be Packard Bell _
which owned Pixel (then called Ark Interface II) for four years
before spinning it off last month to a group of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell will incorporate the control bar into all of its
systems in a phased rollout starting this month. Pixel officials
hope to line up other PC-makers during the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think other companies will use it because it's a way
to have an interactive relationship with your customers,'' said Mal
Ransom, who heads up marketing for Sacramento-based Packard Bell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Industry experts say Microsoft is not likely to oppose Pixel's
new technology in light of the antitrust suit that looms over the
software giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Microsoft didn't like anything that changed the
desktop, but they can point to this as a way they provide
opportunities to innovate,'' said analyst Rob Enderle of Giga
Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   In another example of a PC-maker attempting to customize the
desktop, Gateway announced last week that it would offer some
customers direct links to Gateway's Internet service and the
opportunity to choose Netscape's browser over Microsoft when they
start their computer for the first time. If MySpace succeeds, it
will be sweet revenge for O'Rourke, who founded Ark Interface nine
years ago and has been bloodied by Microsoft. In the mid-'90s, he
devised a graphical interface for Packard Bell that lay on top of
Windows, letting users go directly to multimedia programs and
service features that came with their PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, including market leader Compaq, had similar
Windows ``shells,'' which helped them differentiate their systems
and create brand identity. But Microsoft saw the trend as a threat
and rewrote its contracts to bar the interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke got the idea for MySpace from ESPN, which routinely
shrinks the size of a game to make room for announcements at the
bottom of the TV screen. O'Rourke asked his chief technology
officer, David Nason, to see if there was a way that the empty
space below Windows could be used in a similar way.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Not only was it technically feasible, but it also looked
legally possible. ``Bill (Gates) had spent all of his time
defending his territory with 10-foot high, 10-foot thick walls, but
the area outside Windows was open,'' O'Rourke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
