<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Wells May End Free Checking  
   
 By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
About 150,000 Wells Fargo customers received letters earlier this
week informing them that they may have to start paying fees next
month on what many had believed were lifetime free checking
accounts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The move has angered many customers, especially senior citizens
who thought they were promised such accounts when they banked with
First Interstate Bancorp and were assured that their agreements
would stay in effect after Wells Fargo took over First Interstate
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992 when I reached 55, First Interstate told me I could
get lifetime free checking,'' said Bruce Freeman, a retired
political science and economics teacher who lives in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   When Wells acquired its Los Angeles rival in 1996, Freeman said
he went to his new Wells branch and was told, ``Quote unquote _
`Don't worry. We'll honor First Interstate's obligations.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman was surprised when he recently received a ``Dear Valued
Customer'' letter from Wells Fargo with this note: ``We've recently
reviewed our fee-waiver policies and decided to discontinue the
arrangement that provided you with a fee waiver.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of next month, he and about 3 percent of the
bank's 5 million retail customers were told that their accounts
would be subject to $7 to $9 in monthly fees unless they met
certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   These included a daily minimum balance of at least $1,000 in a
checking account or $3,000 in linked checking and savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Those on Social Security (about a tenth of those who received
the form letter) also can escape monthly fees if they simply have
their recurring government payments deposited directly in their
checking accounts. In many cases, such payments are far less than
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this waiver information was not included in the
bank's recent letter to Freeman and an estimated 15,000 to 20,000
other seniors. Wells called it an oversight and said it is
informing those customers about the waiver when they phone in to
inquire about the upcoming changes to their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Most banks are raising fees and adding new ones to make sure
that all customers pay for the services they use. In Wells Fargo's
case, the wide array of services includes access to more than 4,400
automated teller machines, 1,800 branches, 24-hour telephone
service and online banking.
</P>
<P>
   Some customers and consumer groups were quick to criticize Wells
Fargo for allegedly reneging on previous promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like the banking-industry version of bait and
switch,'' said Jon Golnger, a director of California Public
Interest Research Group. ``We would warn those who think they have
special deals to look at the fine print; the terms and conditions
may change at any moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see promotions about free checking for life, be aware
that your life might be longer than your bank's,'' added Gail
Hillebrand, senior attorney for Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo spokeswoman Kim Kellogg insists that neither First
Interstate nor Wells Fargo ``ever made written promises that
accounts would be free for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wells Executive Vice President Jim Ketcham said,
``If customers have proof or can explain a situation where Wells or
its predecessor made a promise, then we will honor it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg said she told Freeman yesterday that even if he does not
have his $550 monthly Social Security check deposited directly, he
can continue to receive free checking.
</P>
<P>
   But Freeman said this was not what he was told when he received
the notice and called the bank last Tuesday. ``I was put on hold
for 35 minutes before talking to an agent and another half hour to
talk to a supervisor,'' he said. ``Both told me their hands were
tied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
