<HEADER>
A7014 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCITE-SFCHRON &LR;      06-05 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Disney Inks Deal to Provide Web Content to Excite's Site  
   
 By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Excite Inc. said yesterday that it will carry a variety of content
from Walt Disney Co. Web sites, confirming that the Magic Kingdom's
online plans are anything but Mickey Mouse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the end of June, Excite's site _ known mostly for its search
engine and free e-mail _ also will have news, sports and
entertainment from Disney.com, ESPN SportsZone and ABCNews.com,
which all are owned by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   The nonexclusive agreement with Redwood City-based Excite is
expected to be the first of many that Disney will ink with Internet
service companies in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is making good on Chairman Michael Eisner's comment in
late &UR;  &LR; April that ``we will be aggressive competitors on the
Internet, as you enter the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Disney plunked down $250 million to buy
Starwave, the Bellevue, Wash.-based Web development company that
created SportsZone and ABCNews.com. Its technical innovations range
from developing electronic-commerce sites to creating intricate
Java programs &UR;  &LR; that let ESPN users replay game footage.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's comments and Disney's acquisition initially were
interpreted as proof that it would follow Microsoft, AOL, Netscape
and others in creating a major ``portal'' site on the Internet,
where consumers log on to shop, manage their money, play games,
exchange e-mail and peruse news.
</P>
<P>
   A Disney spokeswoman declined to comment on the company's Web
portal plans, but analysts assert that it does not need to build an
all-in-one ``supersite'' to distribute its content widely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their content is so strong ... they can depend on other sites
(to carry it). They don't need to become a full-service provider,''
said analyst David Simons, of Digital Video Investments in New
York. ``Besides, Disney can effectively promote its online services
on its TV shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Excite and Disney did not disclose terms of their deal.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, published reports speculated that Disney
was on the verge of buying a 40 percent stake in Excite for about
$400 million, but officials from both companies denied that such a
deal was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Zapata _ a Texas
oil-company-turned-fish-processor founded 45 years ago by former
President George Bush _ unsuccessfully offered $1.7 billion in
stock to buy Excite.
</P>
<P>
   Excite shares rose $2.28, to $58.25, in trading yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
