<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7015 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-SFCHRON &LR;      06-05 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Antitrust Suit Againt Intel Imminent   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Federal Trade Commission is expected to launch an antitrust
action on Monday against Santa Clara-based Intel Corp., the world's
largest maker of computer chips.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like their colleagues at the Department of Justice, who last
month filed an antitrust suit against software behemoth Microsoft
Corp., the trade commissioners have set their sights on a mammoth
high-tech target. Intel, a $25 billion company, commands more than
90 percent of the market for microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Intel used that dominance to stifle
competition by cutting off rivals' access to crucial information
about its microchips _ the brains that run a computer system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Intel argues that it is not a monopoly, and it has no
obligation to share its intellectual property with its legal foes.
Intel officials met last week with FTC commissioners and staff in
an eleventh-hour attempt to forestall the suit. ``We made our best
argument, and we'll just have to see,'' Intel chief counsel Tom
Dunlap said Friday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The commissioners are expected to vote about Intel in a closed
meeting at noon Monday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Since the FTC launched a probe against Intel in September, the
chipmaker has provided the commission with more than 4 million
documents chronicling its business dealings. FTC investigators have
questioned executives at Intel, and at the chip firms that compete
with it and the computer makers that buy its chips.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts and antitrust lawyers don't expect the FTC
case to hurt either Intel's way of doing business or its bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow suit on patent rights ``is nonthreatening to Intel,''
said Joe Moore, a securities analyst with Goldman Sachs and Co. in
New York. &UR;  &LR; ``It's not pricing, or contracts, or keeping competitors
out of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC and the Department of Justice share the enforcement of
the nation's antitrust laws, and decide between themselves which
cases each will pursue.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Justice Department, along with 20 states'
attorneys general, is giving Microsoft a broad challenge to whether
it can fold new features, such as a Web browser, into its core
operating system, the FTC is more likely in the short term to look
only at the relatively obscure issue of whether Intel manipulates
markets by deciding who can use its chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect Intel will say, `Oh gosh, if you redefine the laws,
we'll go ahead and share the information.' It's not critical to
Intel's long-term success like the browser is to Microsoft,'' said
Nathan Brookwood, semiconductor analyst for Dataquest, a San Jose
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is already fighting the issue in a federal court in
Alabama, where workstation maker Intergraph has sued it. Intel had
supplied Intergraph with advance information about its chips, which
Intergraph used to make its new corporate computers. But after
Intergraph sued Intel in a patent dispute, Intel withheld
information about its upcoming chips _ an action that Intergraph
says threatened its core business.
</P>
<P>
   Intergraph chief executive James Meadlock said Intel engaged in
unethical behavior and ``strong-arm tactics to force us into
submission.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel counters that it had the right to withhold information
from Intergraph, which had altered the once-friendly relationship
by filing the patent lawsuit. ``It's our fundamental belief that it
is not a prudent act to continue to ship your intellectual property
_ your secrets _ to a company that has made you a defendant in
intellectual property litigation,'' said Intel spokesman Chuck
Mulloy.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, U.S. District Court Judge Edwin L. Nelson ruled in
April that Intel probably did abuse its power, and he ordered the
company to give Intergraph the information. Intel is complying with
the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the preliminary injunction was issued by the court in
Alabama ... the likelihood of FTC action shot up to 100 percent,''
said Rich Gray, an antitrust and intellectual property lawyer at
the San Jose firm of Bergeson, Eliopoulos, Grady and Gray.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Intergraph case, the FTC is likely to examine
similar disputes Intel has had with Digital Equipment Corp., Compaq
Computer and the Acer Group.
</P>
<P>
   A legal battle between Intel and Houston-based computer maker
Compaq was settled several years ago, and Intel settled its suit
with Digital earlier this year. Intel's dispute with Acer, a
Taiwanese computer company, never reached the courts.
</P>
<P>
   While the FTC's initial suit is expected to be narrow, the
agency is continuing to investigate Intel's business practices.
Industry watchers identified several other areas in which the FTC
may move against Intel farther down the road:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Intel Inside: &LR;  In the most successful marketing campaign ever
undertaken by a chip maker, Intel pays a share of the advertising
budget for computer makers using its chips. Competitors say Intel
may have withheld those advertising dollars _ a key to a computer's
profitability _ if the PC maker chose a rival chip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Design clampdown: &LR;  Competitors say Intel abruptly switched the
design of its Pentium chip so other chipmakers couldn't clone it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Cornering a market: &LR;  Opponents claim Intel used its clout in
the microprocessor market to crowd out smaller firms that make
chipsets, which work with the main chip to process information.
Intel vaulted from holding 25 percent of that market in 1995 to 90
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Moving into new markets: &LR;  Although the FTC approved Intel's
acquisition of the graphics chipmaker Chips and Technologies in
January, the agency also said it would continue to monitor Intel's
push into the graphics market.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest threat to Intel may be the ruthless nature of the
marketplace rather than the FTC. Over the past year, Intel was
caught flat-footed while rivals developed cheaper chips, leading to
the rise of sub-$1,000 PCs, and analysts say other firms are doing
a better job of making chips for consumer electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, slowing PC sales and the Asia currency crisis have
dragged Intel's once-soaring profitability back to earth. The
company has reported flat earnings for the past year, and expects
the trend to continue in its next quarterly report, slated for the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's stock has fallen along with its earnings. It closed
Friday up $1.63 at $69.81, still a far cry from its 52-week high of
$100.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
