<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC--HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      06-05 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC--HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   Odds are, Real Quiet will make history
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ELMONT, N.Y. _ One reason there is often a quiet time in horse
racing is because of the division of speaking parts. The trainers
do 90 percent of the talking, the jockeys take 10 and the horses
none.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet is a heavy favorite today to claim his page in racing
lore, along with 600 grand for winning the Belmont Stakes and the
Visa bonus of $5 million for sweeping the Triple Crown. The
pressure is where the money is, the confusion factor is ripe in a
field of 13, and the excitement is rising.
</P>
<P>
   All that appears to be missing is good old-fashioned melodrama.
There is no high-voltage rivalry on the menu, even though Victory
Gallop finished second to Real Quiet in the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness. Up to now, this latest Bob Baffert colt has not captured
our hearts or wallets, has not Silver Charmed us.
</P>
<P>
   If one could indeed get a tip straight from the horse's mouth,
it probably would be this: If you wish to double your money, fold
it and put it back in your pocket. Real Quiet is 6-5 on the betting
line, and who wants to risk a five to win a buck? This is not the
American way as most of us like to practice it.
</P>
<P>
   And yet this 130th running of the Belmont doesn't lack the
trimmings of a grand race. At the Garden City Hotel, the marketing
director had put 50 cases of champagne on ice and boasted, ``I'll
sell more cigars this weekend than I (usually) sell in three
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the guests at the Floral Park Motor Lodge on the
Jericho Turnpike were checking in with a clerk who sat behind
bulletproof glass.
</P>
<P>
   What you see here is a microcosm of Real Quiet's journey, the
leap from commoner to high roller, or even royalty. If money was
all that mattered, the heavy wagering would be on Victory Gallop,
the Houston-owned horse, at 7-2; or Grand Slam, one of the two D.
Wayne Lukas entries, at 6-1; or Raffie's Majest, a 20-1 long shot
trained by James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   You assume Mr. Bond prefers to shake the field, not merely stir
it.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice play at 10-1 is Limit Out, the son of Northern
Flagship, trained by Allen Jerkens, who has a history of producing
upsets and colts that can travel a distance.
</P>
<P>
   This Belmont includes a father-and-son act, among the trainers,
not the horses. James Jerkens, Allen's son, has an even longer shot
in Thomas Jo, at 30-1. The colt was ordinary as a 2-year-old but
has won six of his past seven starts and has Chris McCarron, a Hall
of Fame jockey, on his back.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the above information is offered with the usual
disclaimer: It is possible to bet on these and other quadrupeds and
actually lose.
</P>
<P>
   The backers of Real Quiet are confident that a good many
disbelievers will be converted today. Kent Desormeaux has seen the
Kentucky-bred colt deliver two flawless races. He was even
impressed with Real Quiet's poise during a short but bumpy flight
from Louisville to John F. Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He balanced himself with his head against the roof,''
Desormeaux said, ``and his feet on the floor. He has nerves of
steel.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lungs and legs will have a higher value today. This
is why Gary Stevens, riding Victory Gallop for only the second
time, will lay off the pace, saving his mount for a late surge.
This is where a jockey trusts his instincts. Real Quiet wasn't bred
for a mile and a half, but if he gets to the front he has the heart
to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet would emerge as the 12th Triple Crown winner today,
or the seventh colt to fail after winning the first two legs. So
the hay is in the barn, as football coaches are fond of saying, and
the handicappers are reviewing their notes. Where is the early
speed? Who will set the pace?
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a race anyone is likely to steal, partly because it
is in broad daylight in front of 70,000 or so fans, and partly
because it is a long road home. But the turns are soft, and this
should help the favorite and the second choice.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens replaced Alex Solis after Solis was faulted for taking
Victory Gallop too wide, twice, in the Kentucky Derby. Having won
at Belmont on Thunder Gulch in 1995, Stevens finished second on
Silver Charm a year ago, as Touch Gold blew past them at the wire.
No need to ask him about the agony and the ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is bright with a nice gift for a phrase. When he rode
the favored Indian Charlie in this year's Derby, he says he knew
when he paraded to the post his horse wouldn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very, very quiet,'' he said. ``Usually, he's full of
himself. When they sing My Old Kentucky Home, you know there's
going to be an eruption from the crowd at the end. So I grabbed
some mane, but there was no reaction from him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the three-eighths pole, he knew he was running for second
money. He had to settle for third.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tired horse,'' Stevens said, ``feels like a car engine
that's running out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't go to Solis for advice because there is a code among
jockeys _ you don't seek help from someone who lost his ride for
reasons other than an injury. At the Preakness, Stevens knew the
race would be lively. Victory Gallop's ears were up and moving and
he responded to the slightest tug on the reins. Sitting on the colt
for the first time, Stevens felt comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt like my old Porsche,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the only descriptions of Real Quiet, the horse who
would be king, are not flattering. He wasn't a pretty baby, and was
bought at auction for $17,000, racing's version of a five-and-dime
store.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins today, he will look mighty handsome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
