<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7024 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-AD     06-05 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-ADS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM LAB TO PATIENT, BY WAY OF YOUR DEN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.Y., Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic showing most heavily advertised companies; most heavily
advertised drugs will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The advertisement seemed innocuous enough. A few minutes into
the March 17 episode of ``Home Improvement,'' the ABC sitcom, the
TV screen flashed scenes of men and women rubbing their eyes as a
female voice sang the praises of a new brand of prescription eye
drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like you have tried just about everything,'' the
voice cooed, ``but now there is Patanol.'' Not only did Patanol,
developed by Alcon Laboratories, soothe ``itchy allergy eyes for
eight hours,'' the ad assured viewers, but only a few people
``experience side effects, like a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   For the millions of Americans who suffer from allergies,
Patanol's promise of relief might have been, literally, too good to
be true. The Food and Drug Administration took one look at the
commercial and asked Alcon to take it off the air, saying that some
of its claims of effectiveness were exaggerated and that the side
effects were played down.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly made Patanol exceptional. Of the 22 products
that have been advertised on TV since last August, the FDA has
found problems with 11 commercials _ including those for Pharmacia
&AMP; Upjohn's Depo-Provera contraceptive and Galderma Laboratories'
Metrogel lotion.
</P>
<P>
   All of that only underscores what federal regulators and the
pharmaceutical industry have wrought in the last year: a bold
experiment in directly marketing prescription drugs on TV to
American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ads like the one for Patanol are something of a yawner in the
make-believe world created by Madison Avenue, where lizards scheme
to kill Budweiser frogs and half-naked superstars sell Nike shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But they are just the initial forays in what marketing experts
believe will be a steady march toward the kind of aggressive,
image-filled and patently manipulative advertising that so
successfully sells Americans everything from cars to cosmetics to
computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the FDA relaxed its barriers to television ads,
letting pharmaceutical companies identify their products by name
and describe their purposes. Since then, drug makers have rolled
out a record number of campaigns, both in print and on television.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to shell out some $350 million for television
spots this year _ almost three times what they spent just two years
ago, according to IMS Health, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The best ads have worked their magic, making blockbusters of
drugs like Schering-Plough's Claritin brand of antihistamines,
which has grabbed 54 percent of its market.
</P>
<P>
   And the industry, eager to cash in on life-style drugs aimed at
aging baby boomers _ products like Merck's Propecia for fighting
baldness and Glaxo Wellcome's Zyban for kicking the tobacco habit _
is certain to press the FDA to loosen its guidelines when the
agency completes a review of its policies this summer.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the FDA, for all its storied fastidiousness about
protecting consumers from dangerous medications, has taken a
surprisingly wait-and-see attitude on advertising drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, pharmaceutical companies are reveling in
their new-found freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising directly to consumers is one of the most
successful movements ever in the pharmaceuticals industry,'' said
Neil Sweig, a pharmaceuticals analyst with Southeast Research
Partners, a brokerage firm in Boca Raton, Fla. ``It is the product
of advertising executives all over America who went to sleep each
night trying to figure out how to sell prescription drugs to the
public without upsetting the apple cart at the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy. The ads unleashed the last several months have
prompted an outcry from doctors and consumer advocates, who fear
that the commercials could confuse or mislead the public.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the frequency of dubious claims, the critics contend that
sales pitches for prescription drugs often offer false hope and
encourage people to march into their doctors' offices to demand
prescriptions for drugs they know almost nothing about. Some
physicians view the ads as a personal affront _ proof, they say,
that pharmaceutical executives see them as nothing more than highly
paid prescription writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big problem with some consumer prescription drug ads is that
they are so simplistic,'' said Dr. Gillian Shepherd, an allergist
and clinical associate professor at New York Hospital Cornell
Medical Center. ``The ads make like these drugs work on all people
and in every case. It simply doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical and many advertising executives tell a different
story. Consumer drug ads, they say, not only educate patients about
diseases and available treatments, they also persuade people to see
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some instances, the doctors may not know everything about
the drug,'' said Mark Schwatka, executive vice president of Grey
Advertising Inc., the creator of consumer drug campaigns for Glaxo
Wellcome and SmithKline Beecham. ``Some doctors could learn
something from these ads they can't stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of the FDA's decision last summer to relax its
restrictions, ads for antihistamines became as common as spots for
home-exercise machines.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1997, spending on consumer advertising for
prescription drugs rose by 125 percent from the previous year, to
$107 million, at Bristol-Myers Squibb; by 76 percent, to $122
million, at Merck, and by 57 percent, to $156.6 million, at Glaxo
Wellcome, the industry's biggest consumer advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schering-Plough paid $55.8 million to promote Claritin
antihistamine, and reaped a 38 percent jump in U.S. sales, to $907
million.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the growth in ad spending for pharmaceuticals as an
industry has not been nearly as robust. Last year, the industry
spent $3.2 billion in the United States promoting all its
medications, up only 6 percent from 1996, according to Competitive
Media Reporting, a unit of VNU NV, a Dutch publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never spent much money on television to advertise
prescription drugs before last year,'' said Richard J. Lane,
president of the United States pharmaceuticals division at
Bristol-Myers Squibb. ``Before the FDA changed its rules, it was
difficult to get the message across.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a typical commercial, we want the consumer to remember what
we told them,'' he noted. ``But with a drug commercial, the
consumer must be persuaded to take action, see his doctor, make
that appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the airwaves have been particularly busy with
commercials for prescription drugs, perhaps because the industry
senses that its freedom may not last. The FDA, as part of its
review, could reverse course and enact new restrictions, though it
is unlikely to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA first issued regulations in the late 1960s governing
consumer advertising of prescription drugs, but it wasn't until
1981 that the first ad appeared in the mass media _ for Merck's
Pneumovax, a pneumonia vaccine, in Reader's Digest. Little more
appeared before Arthur Hull Hayes, then the FDA commissioner,
declared a moratorium in 1983 on consumer prescription-drug
advertising to allow the the agency to re-evaluate the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical companies waited for two years, but nothing
happened. Pressured by Congress, the FDA lifted its moratorium in
1985, with the initial guidelines still in place.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, the CBS television network, eager to capture
new ad revenue, released a set of rules all its own. CBS announced
that it would feel free to broadcast responsible prescription-drug
commercials, but would avoid those that tended to frighten or were
overly emotional. Four years passed before it broadcast its first
commercial for a prescription drug.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies proceeded to experiment gingerly with how far
they could push the envelope on commercials. The FDA was insisting
that television spots trumpeting a particular drug should also
include detailed information about side effects and risk.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid cramming so many words on the screen, drug companies
avoided the issue by mentioning only the brand and not its purpose,
or by running a commercial about the illness in general without
naming the drug.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Upjohn &AMP; Co., now Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, ran
television ads for Rogaine, its hair replacement drug, in the late
1980s without mentioning the name of the product. The spots used
beach scenes with the line, ``I always thought hair loss was as
inevitable as the tides.'' The ad then urged people to see their
doctors if they were concerned about thinning hair.
</P>
<P>
   By May 1997, several television ads had begun to use obvious
imagery to convey their products' purposes. Without mentioning
allergies, Hoechst Marion Roussel's commercial for Allegra, an
antihistamine, showed people surfing through wheat fields. After
seeing that ad and meeting with Hoechst executives to discuss it,
the FDA decided to loosen its guidelines for a trial period.
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth, companies would be allowed to identify their
products and describe their use, as long as they included several
elements: major risk information, an ``800'' number and an address
for consumers to obtain further information; a reference to a print
ad or Web site, and an appeal for consumers to discuss any medical
problems with their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it wanted to see whether companies would refrain
from making exaggerated claims or playing down risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid that the pharmaceutical companies would stress
far too much the drugs' advantages and not enough of the risks,''
said Nancy Ostrove, chief of the marketing practices and
communications division at the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   That was the agency's objection to an ad for Propecia that Merck
recently ran in Time magazine, without a syllable about the drug's
possible side effects. The FDA said the omission was a violation of
its guidelines. It could also be fodder for liabilities lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Merck said the company believed the ad was not
required to contain risk information because its primary purpose
was to prod consumers to seek help. The FDA disagreed, Ms. Ostrove
said, and Merck made immediate changes.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, she said the agency had found much that was useful in
print ads for prescription drugs, but that it would be continuously
evaluating its policy on TV ads. ``If we find that the prescription
ads have negatively affected the patient-physician relationship,
then we will rethink our whole position,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the public, though it has embraced the most heavily
advertised drugs, has shown little interest in the debate. Yet
consumer rights groups have been among the most vocal critics, with
some urging a ban on TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a record number of new drugs introduced
recently on the market,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe, executive director
of the Public Citizen Health Research Group, a consumer advocacy
group founded by Ralph Nader. The FDA, he said, had fallen behind
in reviewing ads, so a lot of mistakes can get through. ``The
combination of a misled doctor and a misled patient,'' he said,
``leads to the wrong prescription.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies are not required to submit their consumer ads to
the FDA for prior approval. And when violations of FDA ground rules
are caught, the penalties are almost nonexistent. Companies pay no
fines and rarely have to issue corrective ads
</P>
<P>
   Even so, advertisers operate under much stricter rules for
prescription drugs than those enforced by the Federal Trade
Commission for over-the-counter medication. Unlike the FDA, for
example, the FTC encourages comparative ads.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with consumer ads for prescription drugs have not
sat well with many doctors. Of 5,000 polled by IMS Health on the
Internet in December, 61 percent favored reducing the number of
such ads or discontinuing them altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association has had problems with the ads,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these ads don't encourage patients to get back to
their doctors,'' said Dr. Nancy Dickey, president-elect of the AMA.
``Now we have come to understand that some of these ads can be
educational. And that's fine. But we don't want them to go the way
of floor wax and compare one drug to the next. The ads also have a
way of interfering with the doctor-patient relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, advertisers have refrained from making unfavorable
comparisons to rivals' products, but the prospect of such TV
slugfests clearly worries the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If companies try comparative ads, we would really scrutinize
those very heavily,'' Ms. Ostrove said. ``We would demand to see
the data from a controlled trial. We want the doctors to make
decisions between one drug and another. It's when the
pharmaceutical companies start pushing the envelope that everyone
could get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Even naysayers acknowledge that prescription-drug ads have the
potential to benefit consumers, if, for example, they persuade them
to go to the doctor's office. And that often happens.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bristol-Myers Squibb's advertising campaign last
year for Pravachol, its drug for cholesterol reduction and stroke
prevention, urged consumers to see their physicians. And indeed,
some 8.8 million people sought treatment last year for
cholesterol-related therapies, up from 7.2 million in 1996,
according to IMS Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer prescription-drug campaigns are both a blessing and a
curse,'' said Shepherd of New York Hospital Cornell Medical Center.
``They are a blessing in that they increase awareness of a
specialty, as with the antihistamines for allergies, for example.
And the campaigns can bring patients into a doctor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The curse? Patients often ask for drugs they don't need.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors may not like patients to request a prescription drug
they have seen on television, but, on the other hand, they're
willing to discuss the pros and cons with them.
</P>
<P>
   Of 3,000 doctors polled in the first quarter of this year by
Scott-Levin, a pharmaceutical market-research firm in Newtown, Pa.,
89 percent said they would discuss an advertised drug with a
patient even if they thought the ad for it had been misleading.
Such numbers make marketing executives salivate.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, many pharmaceutical executives want to
stretch the FDA's rules a little more. One sore spot is the
agency's requirement that the highly technical language about risks
and side effects that appear on a product's label also appear in
some print ad copy.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that such wording _ including Merck's warning that
its Propecia could interfere with the PSA test for screening
prostate cancer _ often befuddles people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still evolving with how we do these commercials,'' said
Lane of Bristol-Myers Squibb. ``But the language with the warnings
about the drugs needs to be more consumer-friendly. There's too
much technojargon. That doesn't foster the kind of dialogue we
want.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all the companies' current restraint, some advertising
experts believe Americans may eventually see commercials mocking
rival drugs, in marketing tussles similar to the famous battles
between Pepsi and Coke or between Peter Pan and Jif peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that we are not selling Lay's potato chips,''
said Schwatka of Grey Advertising. ``Drugs are powerful stuff. But
consumers are definitely going to be seeing more ads for
prescription drugs. And they're going to be getting more
information about those drugs. Information does not go backward. It
only moves forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
