<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-BOSOX-475&AMP;AD     06-05 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BOSOX-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT RED SOX AFTER PIAZZA BRUISES HAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The most distressing development of Friday evening for
the Mets occurred before the game was five minutes old. Pedro
Martinez drilled Mike Piazza in the left hand with a fastball,
quickly causing Piazza to grimace and the Mets to feel a little
queasy. Hideo Nomo arrives and Piazza gets injured: the Mets had to
wonder if this was some type of practical joke.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets said that Piazza's hand was bruised and that X-rays
taken at Children's Hospital showed no broken bones. By game's end,
they had turned a distressing night into a delightful one by
battering Martinez for four homers and cruising to a 9-2 victory
over the Red Sox in their first interleague game of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, the best pitcher in the National League last season
while with Montreal, was done after four innings because Albert
Castillo, Piazza's replacement, John Olerud, Luis Lopez and Bernard
Gilkey stunned him by going deep at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez even heard boos from many of the disappointed 32,214
fans who were watching this interleague matchup with heightened
interest since it was the first time the Mets opposed the Red Sox
in Boston since the memorable 1986 World Series. The ``Darryl,
Darryl'' chants were born here for the former Met Darryl Strawberry
12 years ago, but there were no ``Pedro, Pedro'' chants Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Another impressive turn by Al Leiter was overshadowed by
Piazza's injury, which will almost certainly cause the catcher to
miss Saturday's game and perhaps a few more, and the power outburst
from a team that is still last in the major leagues with 39 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter (6-3) stifled the Red Sox on one run and four hits in six
innings and limited them to one hit in 10 at-bats with runners on
base, ruining possible rallies before they ever started and ending
New York's three-game losing streak. He lowered his National
League-leading earned-run average to 1.72.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (6-2), who was belted for six earned runs and eight
hits, has dropped three of his last five starts. That includes a
13-7 victory over the Yankees last Sunday in which he was sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mets claimed Piazza's status will be evaluated
on Saturday, they would be fortunate if the catcher does not have
to be put on the disabled list because he was almost hit in a more
precarious spot. Martinez's fastball tailed in on Piazza and got
him on the meaty side of the hand between the pinky finger and the
wrist. If Piazza had been plunked directly on the wrist, a more
fragile part of the hand, the damage could have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez entered the game with a 10-2 career record and a 1.65
ERA against the Mets, his best statistics versus any NL team. But
the Mets had beaten Martinez twice last season, by 2-1 on June 3
and by 7-0 on May 28, though not exactly clobbering him: Martinez
gave up four earned runs in 13 innings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Friday night, after Gilkey lined a one-out double to right in
the first, Martinez came in tight and hit Piazza with a 2-2
fastball. It was immediately obvious that Piazza was in trouble. He
dropped the bat, trudged toward first and stopped halfway to the
base so trainer Fred Hina could examine him. It looked as if Piazza
was in pain, but he stayed in and even ran to second when Olerud
ripped a run-scoring single. But Piazza did not put on his shin
guards in the bottom of the first as Castillo replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the third and a taut pitcher's duel emerging
between Leiter and Martinez, Castillo, of all players, stroked a
2-2 pitch over the Green Monster and over the screen in left.
Martinez is one of the most dominant pitchers in baseball and
Castillo has one of the ugliest swings in the game, but the home
run gave the Mets a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Olerud, who entered the game 0-for-9 with
five strikeouts against Martinez, deposited a homer in the right
field seats. Carlos Baerga lined the next pitch past the pitcher's
mound for a single. Four pitches had produced two homers, a single,
a 3-0 lead for New York and a conspicuous murmur throughout the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   It got even bleaker for Martinez in the fourth. Lopez, the No. 9
batter, poked a two-run homer into the Red Sox bullpen, his first
of the year and the fifth of his career. Two batters later, Gilkey
bashed a 1-0 pitch 429 feet into the screen in left-center, giving
the Mets a 6-0 bulge.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn countered with a prodigious homer off Leiter in the
fourth, and he hit another homer off John Hudek in the ninth. But
by then, Martinez had endured his shortest outing for Boston and
the Mets were simply waiting to learn about Piazza's X-ray results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
