<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-ZO     06-05 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-ZOMIG-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING HEADACHES TO LIFE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About a year ago, Ulla Kling-Atkinson was named to
the creative team developing an ad campaign for Zomig, a
prescription drug made by Zeneca Pharmaceuticals for migraine
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   It was a match made in the Madison Avenue version of heaven
because Mrs. Kling-Atkinson has chronic migraines herself. And it
was with the insight of a longtime sufferer, combined with her
experience in marketing over-the-counter drugs, that she developed
the image now being used to sell Zomig in print and television ads
_ that of an onrushing 18-wheel tractor-trailer with engine
roaring, horn braying and high-beam headlights glaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first idea was this is something that comes on, that you
can't stop, and you are totally helpless,'' she said. ``We tried
elephants, rhinoceroses, trains _ anything that came at you that
you couldn't control.''
</P>
<P>
   Focus groups told the team that animals were not as frightening
as runaway machinery. And trains failed to produce a real sense of
panic because people do not often think of themselves walking along
a railroad track into a train's path.
</P>
<P>
   But the truck was terrifying, and the flashing headlights were
an important subliminal trigger for people with migraines because
extreme sensitivity to light at the onset of an attack is common.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something called aura that comes on before you get a
migraine, and it can be either a sensation of flashing lights or a
sensitivity to light,'' said Mark Schwatka, executive vice
president of Grey Advertising, who oversaw the Zomig campaign.
``With the truck, there's a sense of: It's coming at me, the light
is shining, it's hurting my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising has always been about pushing the right button to
motivate buying. But as marketers and ad agencies apply what they
know about consumer products to help sales of prescription drugs,
they are finding a medically informed vocabulary for invoking
consumers' urges _ in this case, to go to the doctor and ask about
the new drug they saw on TV.
</P>
<P>
   In developing the brand image for Zomig, Schwatka said he
realized the need for what he called ``a relevant consumer
insight.'' He also needed to make Zomig stand out in a din of TV
advertising, including ads for its direct competitor, Imitrex,
which is made by Glaxo Wellcome. Imitrex has already made a mark by
pointing out that it does not cause drowsiness, something feared by
migraine sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were second in,'' Schwatka said. ``This feeling of
helplessness became the insight we led with _ the feeling that
something big and ominous and so much more powerful than you was
bearing down on you.''
</P>
<P>
   At every stage, focus groups of migraine patients were shown the
ads under development. By the time the final version was shown,
``they were cheering,'' said Mrs. Kling-Atkinson, who has developed
campaigns for Maalox and Desenex as well as other prescription
drugs and refers to herself laughingly as ``the drug queen.''
</P>
<P>
   One person's comment, she said: ``Whoever did this must have
migraines.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when it came time to cast an actress to play a migraine
sufferer _ a nonspeaking role _ she tried for authenticity, casting
a woman who gets migraines. The headaches affect ``your whole
well-being,'' Mrs. Kling-Atkinson explained, and she wanted the
actress to accurately portray someone bowed in pain.
</P>
<P>
   More than in commercials for nonprescription painkillers or
cough preparations, though, the ad makers had to temper the power
of their creation to stay within Food and Drug Administration
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the graphics are very strong, the language is
moderate,'' Schwatka said. For example, over serene images of the
headache sufferer on her sailboat, an announcer intones a stream of
warnings about not using Zomig if you have high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over-the-counter advertising is much more rough and tumble,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Mrs. Kling-Atkinson, like most other people
involved in the Zomig campaign, got their stripes. Earlier, she
created fashion ads, then switched to campaigns for steel and beer
before returning to fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I mostly do drugs,'' she said, sitting in a Manhattan
office stacked high with story boards. ``Over-the -counter,
under-the-counter, whatever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
