<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIREMAN-BRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS' BRAWL MORE BRUTAL THAN FIRST REPORTED
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A drunken brawl by New York City firefighters at a
Bryant Park cafe Wednesday night was more extensive and brutal than
first reported, senior law-enforcement officials said Friday. But
they acknowledged that it was unlikely that any of the participants
would face criminal charges unless the brawlers filed complaints
against one another.
</P>
<P>
   As three city investigations went forward, investigators said 50
to 100 firefighters, scores more than originally reported, had
battled one another for hours in scenes of chaos that left faces
bloody, teeth knocked out, bodies cut and bruised and uniforms
shredded.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the extent of the brawl became known, outraged city
officials had called it the worst breach of conduct by the
uniformed services in years, a night of debauchery in which
firefighters turned into a mob, urinating publicly, exposing
themselves and terrorizing the cafe's patrons and staff.
</P>
<P>
   Despite official expressions of revulsion and significant
progress Friday in identifying those present at the rampage,
however, law-enforcement officials said it appeared unlikely that
any of the brawlers would face criminal charges, though some might
face Fire Department sanctions ranging from fines to dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of any criminal action coming about are remote,''
a law-enforcement official said. I'd be surprised if any of these
guys came forward and said, `He punched me.'''
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, explained
that the brawlers could be prosecuted for assault only if someone
who was struck filed a criminal complaint. Moreover, he said, the
firefighters could not be prosecuted for lewd behavior or even
disorderly conduct unless witnesses could be found to identify
specific suspects and testify as to their actions.
</P>
<P>
   But as investigators for the Police and Fire departments and the
Manhattan district attorney's office pressed their inquiries, new
accounts from as many as 18 civilian witnesses and some
firefighters shamed by the conduct of their colleagues gave a
clearer picture of events in and around the Bryant Park Grill's
outdoor cafe on Wednesday night following a late-morning ceremony
at City Hall in which Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, other officials and
hundreds of firefighters and their families gathered to honor
scores of firefighters for acts of heroism last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investigators said the drunkenness and violence had
begun about 5 p.m. and lasted almost six hours. They said at least
half of the 50 to 100 firefighters present engaged in fights, many
of them apparently stemming from longstanding rivalries among fire
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Amid heavy drinking and smashed glasses and flowerpots, dozens
of fights broke out all evening as fraternity-like rowdiness
degenerated into ugly battles that sent combatants flying over
furniture and planters.
</P>
<P>
   Harassed patrons fled, but the 14-member cafe staff stayed on,
although they were too frightened to call the police for hours,
according to Donna Simms, the cafe manager.
</P>
<P>
   None of the firefighters was taken into custody. Most were
drifting away when the police arrived, and the officers were
unaware then that numerous fights had taken place, so they halted
no one.
</P>
<P>
   While the police appeared to be making little headway Friday,
fire investigators said they had interviewed 18 civilian witnesses
and had even received several anonymous calls from firefighters who
gave the names and fire companies of department members who had
been present at the brawling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will come forward,'' one investigator said. ``People are
talking. This is not going to be done by Sunday, and maybe not even
by Monday. But we are confident that we will find those
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen said he told his department's
internal investigators to conduct an ``aggressive, comprehensive''
inquiry ``to ensure that those who are responsible are punished
quickly and severely.'' He said the department would deal harshly
with members who withheld information, and said that ``special
consideration will be granted to any member who comes forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
