<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS IN DEATH PENALTY CASE ARGUE VIOLENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two jurors nearly came to blows Friday as a Brooklyn
jury was unable for a third day to decide whether a former jail
guard should be sentenced to death for killing three people, a
court officer told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The report of the heated emotions in the jury room in state
Supreme Court came in the first death penalty trial under New York
state's 3-year-old capital-punishment law.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Darrel Harris, who was honored as a hero for
saving another jail guard during an inmate riot a decade ago, was
convicted by the same jury on May 19 of first-degree murder for
shooting two people in the head and fatally stabbing the third
while robbing a Bedford-Stuyvesant social club in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now the jurors are deciding whether to sentence Harris, 40, to
death by lethal injection or to life in prison without the
possibility of parole. The panel's deliberations will resume
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The only communication from the jurors Friday came in the
morning, when they asked the judge, Acting Justice Anne Feldman, to
repeat the legal instructions she gave them on Wednesday, just
before they began their deliberations on the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in midafternoon, Feldman announced that something was to
be ``put on the record.'' One of the court officers, Gary Thompson,
then gave an account of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was outside the jury room and I heard a heated argument
going on,'' he said, adding that this had occurred about 12:45 p.m.
``I heard some chairs moving around.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he entered the room. ``One juror was standing up
and being held back by a couple of male jurors,'' he continued,
recalling that the man being restrained was ``yelling and cursing''
and that the man he appeared to be cursing at was cursing back.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he had told them to ``relax,'' and assured them he
understood that they had been under stress but ``you've been
getting along for two and a half, three weeks'' and ``you really
got to try.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They relaxed, calmed down and apologized to each other,'' he
said, suggesting that the deliberations had then resumed. He did
not identify the angry jurors or what they had said to each other.
</P>
<P>
   One of Harris' lawyers, Russell Neufeld, then argued that the
confrontation indicated that there ``must be significant
differences within the jury,'' despite what he called the
``extensive'' deliberations that had taken place, and he asked the
judge to dismiss the jury and sentence Harris herself.
</P>
<P>
   The capital-punishment law says that if a jury is unable to
agree unanimously on a death sentence or on life in prison without
possibility of parole, the judge is to decide the sentence, with
the maximum allowed being 25 years to life in prison for each
murder. In Harris' case, that would mean parole would not be
possible for at least 75 years if the terms are ordered to run
consecutively, which lawyers say would be most likely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
