<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YORTY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM YORTY, 88, CONTROVERSIAL EX-MAYOR OF LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite throughout; changes background of Frank
Yorty from Irish to Dutch in 12th graf; adds some additional
biographical reporting)  (bl)  
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Samuel William Yorty, the blunt-talking,
self-promoting Mayor of Los Angeles who took credit for building up
the city yet denied any responsibility for the Watts riots in 1965,
died Friday. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty had suffered a stroke on May 24, and two days ago asked to
be released from a hospital. He died at his hilltop home in the
Studio City section of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty also served two terms in Congress, but became a national
figure because of his tenure in Los Angeles, from 1961 to 1973, and
for his unabashed, contrary ways.
</P>
<P>
   The self-described ``Maverick Mayor'' began his career as a
liberal Democrat and ended it as a conservative Republican. He was
elected mayor despite alienating his party by supporting Richard
Nixon, not John Kennedy, for president in 1960. He was called
``Travelin' Sam'' for seemingly spending as much time away from Los
Angeles as within the city's expanding sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam did what was unexpected,'' said Joy Picus, a long-time
civic leader. ``Sam did what would get him attention.''
</P>
<P>
   He presided over a city that was moving from Midwestern outpost
to gateway to the Pacific Rim. In the 1960 census, the year before
Yorty first took office, Los Angeles still had the most residents
who were Protestant, white and native-born of America's biggest
cities. Indeed, Yorty might have been better suited to be the mayor
of Los Angeles in the '40s or the early '50s, said Kevin Starr, the
state librarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. had become a new city,'' Starr said. ``In movie terms, he
began his career in `Chinatown,' came to political strength during
`L.A. Confidential' and he was mayor during `Dragnet.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fitting description for a man who was one of the first local
politicians to recognize the power of the camera. He appeared on
television often, and at one point, was well known for playing
banjo on the ``Tonight Show'' while the host, Johnny Carson, played
drums.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, he was host of a local television program, ``The Sam
Yorty Show,'' and when it was canceled he complained, ``They
replaced my show with `Hee Haw'!'' After being defeated and leaving
office in 1973, he had to settle for being heard, not seen, and
landed a job as a host for a radio call-in show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Yorty's mayoralty,'' Mike Davis, a historian and author of
``City of Quartz'' (Verso, 1990), ``was the transition from a WASP
majority to the multicultural Los Angeles of Tom Bradley. Yorty's
death is symbolic of the passing of that whole period of L.A.
history when Midwesterners dominated the city and its culture.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1920s, so many Iowans had settled in Los Angeles that
some people called it ``Iowa by the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Yorty had also come from the Midwest. He was born on Oct. 1,
1909, in Lincoln, Neb., to Johanna, an Irish immigrant, and Frank
Yorty, who was of Dutch descent. Yorty grew up poor in Nebraska's
capital, where his father, a former farmer, ran a restaurant, among
other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty's political heroes as a boy were William Jennings Bryan
and Woodrow Wilson. After graduating from high school, Yorty moved
to Los Angeles and attended Southwestern University and the
University of California, eventually receiving a law degree.
</P>
<P>
   At age 27, he entered politics, running successfully for the
state Assembly in 1936. In World War II, he served in the Army Air
Corps and became a captain in the intelligence unit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After losing a Los Angeles mayoral election at the end of the
war, he was elected again to the Assembly in 1948, and then won a
seat in Congress, in 1950. Through the years, his politics became
more conservative.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book ``Los Angeles A to Z'' by Leonard Pitt and
Dale Pitt (University of California Press, 1997) ``initially a
left-winger, he moved steadily to the right and became a staunch
supporter of the House Un-American Activities Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the year before he was elected mayor, Yorty shocked his
fellow Democrats by not endorsing the party's shining star, John
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a great mayor,'' said Harriet Weider, a former
aide. ``But he was a contrarian and I think some of his problems he
brought on himself by his feisty independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yorty reduced city property taxes and backed the building of
freeways, the Los Angeles Zoo, the convention center and other
projects. Yet his mayoralty was badly scarred by the 1965 Watts
riots, which left 34 people dead and hundreds injured. When the
flames were finally put out, federal officials said Yorty's
attitude toward the inner city and his failure to heed the warning
signs contributed to the riots. In turn, Yorty criticized the
federal government's anti-poverty programs for promoting false
hopes for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1969 elections, Yorty was alienated from the black
population that had helped elect him and he used race and
accusations of left-wing influences to beat back the challenge of a
black city councilman, Tom Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   What made Yorty's campaigns against Bradley especially
disappointing to many was the memory that when Yorty first ran in
1961 he had widespread black support and had opened his
administration to more racial minorities than any other mayor up to
that point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yorty ran unsuccessfully for the 1972 Democratic nomination for
president, and was defeated for mayor the next year by Bradley.
This time, Yorty ran as a Republican. All told, Yorty ran for
office 20 times, including unsuccessful bids for governor and the
U.S. Senate, and yet another bid for mayor, in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to view Sam Yorty as a metaphor, more than an
individual,'' said Gerald Horne, a historian and author of ``Fire
This Time'' (University Press of Virginia, 1995), a book about the
Watts riots. ``You have to view him as a metaphor because he was
not alone in his shift to the right. This was part of a massive
shift that was taking place in U.S. politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yorty was called ``Saigon Sam'' for his support of U.S.
involvement in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Yorty's political fortunes dropped, he remained
infamously quotable. In the 1980s he startled a Chamber of Commerce
luncheon by saying that ``the black people are really racist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They vote for black people because they are black,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yorty's political nadir was the `69 campaign against
Bradley,'' said Mike Davis, the historian. ``In a city that has had
some pretty dirty campaigns, that was the low point.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His success or failure in shaping Los Angeles remains a debate
for historians, but it is widely agreed that his two loves were
running for office and having an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather give a speech than eat,'' Yorty is quoted as
saying in ``Maverick Mayor'' (Doubleday and Company, 1966), a
biography by Ed Ainsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty is survived by his wife, Valerie King Yorty, and two
granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
