<DOCNO> NYT19980605.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STADIUM-ASSESS-NYT     06-05 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STADIUM-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: MAYOR THINKS VOTERS MIGHT DEFEAT NEW STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If a referendum is held in November on whether city
money should be used for a new ball park for the Yankees, it
wouldn't be hard to imagine the motifs opponents would use in their
campaign commercials attacking the project: a tormentingly long
traffic jam, backed by a soundtrack of car horns and coughs. A
procession of public schools disfigured by age and neglect. Or
perhaps an unflattering photo of George Steinbrenner, with dollar
signs cavorting around him.
</P>
<P>
   Such provocative images are hard to fight, and that may help
explain why Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is crusading against the
referendum. Giuliani strongly believes that the city should
consider building a stadium on the West Side, but he understands
that in such a referendum, the naysayers here, as in similar votes
elsewhere, would tend to have the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor maintains that a stadium would yield considerable
benefits to the city over the long term, increasing tax revenues
and revitalizing a moribund part of Manhattan without causing
traffic problems. Those arguments, though, might be felled by more
visceral appeals to a populace wary of more congestion and
concerned about whether the city should be spending more on schools
and the rest of its infrastructure. (Not to mention the views of
baseball aficionados who loathe Steinbrenner and say the Yankees
should never leave their historic homeland of the Bronx.)
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the referendum grew more heated on Thursday when
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, all but threatened to
move the team out of New York unless the City Council speaker,
Peter Vallone, abandons his proposal for the referendum.
Steinbrenner appears to feel that the referendum might cripple
plans for a Manhattan stadium. The mayor does too, and in recent
days he has refused to negotiate with the City Council over the
next budget unless Vallone gave up on the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday the mayor acknowledged that he would
lose a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that people would vote against it,'' Giuliani said,
referring to the stadium. He later added: ``I wasn't elected mayor
of New York City to follow the popular will in every poll every
time. I was elected the mayor of New York City to exercise my
judgment, my reason, my wisdom, and I have a different view of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani invoked, as he often does, the westward flights of the
Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Giants, suggesting that Vallone's
brand of leadership was responsible for those earlier defections.
And the mayor recounted how in other places, residents had voted
against stadiums that then proved to be wildly successful when they
were eventually built.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that you are probably going to laugh at me when I say
this,'' he said. ``But I believe that 10 years from now I'll be
very popular for doing this. But 10 years from now. Maybe for a few
years I won't be so popular.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what would happen to the mayor's plans for a
stadium should the voters oppose using city money for the project.
Giuliani might go to court to get the results nullified, or he
could turn to another method of financing, such as setting up an
authority that is quasi-independent from the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a Republican who has been striving mightily to mend
fences with party leaders in recent years, also no doubt realizes
that a referendum might galvanize voters in the November election.
The increased turnout in a city that is overwhelmingly Democratic
could hurt Gov. George Pataki and the rest of the Republican slate.
</P>
<P>
   Such an outcome was one reason that the referendum was proposed
by Vallone, who is seeking the Democratic gubernatorial nomination.
Vallone says that the public has a right to vote on whether the
city should allocate hundreds of millions of dollars for a new ball
park, and his aides acknowledge that if he is the Democratic
nominee, he could benefit from a referendum drawing voters to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor himself benefited from a referendum when he was first
elected in 1993. In that year residents of Staten Island voted to
secede from the city in balloting that drove up the turnout in the
borough, the city's only Republican stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good government groups have been wrestling for years with how
to increase participation in elections,'' said Kevin McCabe,
Vallone's campaign manager. ``It's interesting that now, people are
concerned that more people may actually be participating in an
election. I don't see how that is a bad thing in a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCabe added that the primary purpose of the referendum would be
to ``let the people have their say.''
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor and his advisers have conceded that winning a
referendum would be tough, if not impossible, they have also sought
to shift the focus to the idea that the city elects a chief
executive to make major decisions, not punt them to the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   But that assertion may fall flat among voters at a time when
referendums have become an increasingly popular method of deciding
issues around the country. Borough President Fernando Ferrer of the
Bronx, who opposes a Manhattan stadium, said the best way to muster
support for holding a referendum would be to tell voters that it
would publicize the project's costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a debate in front of the public that airs out all
these financial issues,'' Ferrer said. ``You can't do this deal in
the back room or the luxury suite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
