<HEADLINE>
INDY WINNER IN TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
and LEN HAYWARD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Two in a row looks even more like a long
shot for Eddie Cheever Jr. after yesterday's qualifying run for the
True Value 500K.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever and his No. 51 Team Cheever//Rachel's car managed
215.595 mph in the first practice session Thursday, 24th-fastest in
the 31-team field. A qualifying speed of 214.985 yesterday places
Cheever Jr. in the 10th row for tonight's race. Pole winner Tony
Stewart was 10 mph faster.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, the Indianapolis 500 winner said his team hasn't
even come close to figuring out how to get the car to go any faster
at Texas Motor Speedway. With time running out for tonight's race,
Cheever said his team is in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's a pretty enormous problem right now,'' Cheever
said. ``It seems like everybody else is running fast and we can't
get it down. I could tell as soon as I got on the track that it was
going to happen.'' &QL; 
BOAT'S FRIENDLY RIVALRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat, who drives for the A.J. Foyt Racing Team, said it
seems like every time he takes to the asphalt, one challenge he
faces is running faster than a car from Team Menard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a friendly little rivalry going,'' Boat said. ``It's
fun. We didn't beat them to the pole, which is what we really
wanted, but we'll go out tomorrow and do our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat qualified in the front row beside Team Menard driver and
pole-winner Tony Stewart. Team Menard driver Robbie Buhl is in the
second row. Kenny Brack, the second A.J. Foyt entry, will start in
the sixth row.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is gripping so well and all the cars are running so
fast that I think we're in for a sprint to the finish,'' Boat said.
``From the start, it's going to be all out.'' &QL; 
SAM THE SALESMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his qualifying session yesterday, IRL driver Sam Schmidt
wheeled out a glass case full of sunglasses near his spot in the
garage, and turned from race-car driver to salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who sells the glasses as a favor for one of his new
sponsors, said he sells 25 to 30 pairs at each race. The price
ranges from $45 to $125.
</P>
<P>
   A good sales day would take some sting out of a tough week for
Schmidt and his team on the track. After a crash at Indianapolis,
the team did not get another car until Thursday, the first day of
practice. Schmidt will be in the 12th row for today's race after
qualifying 24th. &QL; 
ONE FAST ROOKIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Beechler came to the series from the dirt tracks of the
Midwest, racing sprint cars and midgets. He started 24th in the
Indianapolis 500, but because of engine trouble, finished 32nd.
</P>
<P>
   He was the fastest qualifying rookie for tonight's race, and
will start 17th after qualifying with a speed of 216.485 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like running in a coffee cup here,'' Beechler said of
TMS. ``I have yet to run on anything this banked; about the only
thing I can compare it to is Eldora (Speedway in Ohio). It is very
smooth, and it really puts you down in your seat. These speeds are
not far off what we qualified at Indy.'' &QL; 
GEAR GAMBLE COSTS RAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greg Ray consistently turned in some of the fastest practice
laps Thursday, then dropped to the seventh row when qualifying for
True Value was over yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said his team ran pretty fast in sixth gear the first day,
then made a ``radical switch'' before qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rolled the dice,'' Ray said. ``It's not like we hit snake
eyes, but we didn't exactly miss the table, either. We'd like to be
closer to the front, but we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final IRL practice session yesterday evening, Ray was
back near the front with the seventh-fastest speed. &QL; 
