<HEADER>
A7162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REDWINGS-STARS-NY     06-05 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS BEAT STARS FOR STANLEY CUP BERTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Texas)   (ja) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ With Chris Osgood atoning in a big way for his lapses
in goal two nights earlier, the Detroit Red Wings beat the Dallas
Stars, 2-0, Friday night in Joe Louis Arena and won the Western
Conference finals by four games to two.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the Wings returned to the championship round, which
they won in a four-game sweep against Philadelphia last season.
They also set up a Stanley Cup finals against the Washington
Capitals that will feature starkly contrasting franchises and a
human-interest subplot that is both sincere and sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a lead with a goal in each of the first two
periods, the Red Wings held off the visitors in the third period
with a ferocious checking effort that brought the capacity crowd to
its feet repeatedly with long, loud bursts of chanting and
cheering.
</P>
<P>
   The checking helped Osgood earn his second shutout of this
series in a postseason that has been erratic for him. One final
hurdle remains for Osgood and the Wings: Washington, starting next
Tuesday night here.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the Red Wings and the Capitals and their
hockey cultures is clear. The Red Wings, the defending champions,
will be playing for the third time in four years for the title. The
Capitals, in their 24th season, are making their first appearance
in the finals, having eliminated Buffalo in six games on Thursday
to clinch the East.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, which has been in the National Hockey League since the
1920s, is an industrial city on the Canadian border where fans
routinely buy all the tickets and crowd the standing-room tiers.
The Capitals, who moved to a new arena this season, work in a
government-driven city that has no baseball and favors football, a
city only casually familiar with hockey. The Caps played many times
this season before large gaps of empty seats, even in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On an individual and personal level, the most interesting man in
the final series might be Ron Wilson, the first-year coach of the
Capitals. He was born in Windsor, Ontario, a Canadian city less
than a mile from the drab gray walls of Joe Louis Arena. Wilson's
father, Larry Wilson, played and coached the Wings before his
death. So did Johnny Wilson, Larry's brother and Ron's uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson carries in his suit coat a hockey card with a picture of
his father in a Detroit uniform. He has said that one of his career
goals is to coach the Wings. After his team beat Buffalo on
Thursday night, Wilson was asked which team he would rather face,
Detroit or Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, Detroit,'' Wilson said. Noting that his team will
be a clear underdog to the Wings, he added, ``Probably everybody
thinks we'll go down four straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit did nothing Friday night to dispel that notion. Scoring
first, while short-handed, was Larry Murphy, the veteran
defenseman. When the Wings' captain, Steve Yzerman, banked the puck
off the boards to Darren McCarty in the neutral zone, Murphy jumped
off his bench to turn a one-on-one rush into a two-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   After Murphy beat goalie Ed Belfour with a backhander at 6
minutes 20 seconds of the first period, the Stars argued that
Detroit had too many men on the ice. Although one of the Detroit
skaters went to the bench after Murphy came on, it was not soon
enough, in the view of the Stars. Referee Bill McCreary ignored
their protests and the goal stood.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings made it 2-0 at 1:48 of the second period on a goal by
Sergei Fedorov. It was his first of the series but his ninth of the
playoffs, most in the league. After taking a pass from Murphy,
Fedorov fired a long shot between the circles that Belfour only
partly stopped before the puck trickled over the line.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, Detroit goalie Chris Osgood stopped 18 shots
in the first 40 minutes. Several of them were difficult and he was
cheered by the fans, clad mostly in red and white. In the previous
game, a 3-2 Stars victory, the winning goal was scored in the first
minute of overtime on a shot by Jamie Langenbrunner from center
ice.
</P>
<P>
   That was the third goal of the soft sort that Osgood had given
up in this tournament. Although he seems to have the support of the
Wings players, fans and news media, Osgood is widely perceived
outside Detroit as one of the Wings' vulnerabilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
