A7164 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRL-SCORING-TEX     06-05 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-SCORING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL TURNS TO COUNTER MEASURES TO PREVENT ANOTHER SCORING SNAFU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In order to prevent post-race protestations,
Victory Circle roundhouses and morning-after headaches, the Indy
Racing League wants you to know that it can count to 208.
</P>
<P>
   That magic number is 208 _ the number of laps it will take to
complete the True Value 500K tonight, and the IRL can count them in
four _ count 'em, ``four'' _ different ways.
</P>
<P>
   They use their computerized Data 1 system with its 11 on-track
antennas that track the position of the transmitter in each of the
28 cars on the track.
</P>
<P>
   They use NASCAR's computerized AMB system with its in-track
cables that track the position of ``another'' transmitter in each
of the 28 cars on the track.
</P>
<P>
   They use the four _ count 'em, ``four'' _ eyeballs of Randy
Kenyon and Sandy Griffith, who write down the numbers of each of
the 28 cars on the track as they pass the start/finish line _ the
way races have been doing it since the beginning of time.
</P>
<P>
   And they use their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   They can count to 208 with their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, people would write down the time on scorecards
and our auditors would collect and collate the data,'' IRL official
Steve Mansfield explained from the scoring center in a suite
overlooking the Texas Motor Speedway. ``Now, we've taken that one
step further. Each team has a scorer who sits with an Apple Newton.
You tap the screen when your car passes and it registers. All the
Newtons are wired together, and this data is passed onto the
computer and we can see it immediately. I take the data from all
our serial scorers and all the electronic systems and make sure
they are in synch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let what happened last year happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened last year depends on who's counting.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to have taken Arie Luyendyk 208 laps to win the
inaugural race last year. But a scoring glitch counted Luyendyk a
lap behind when Billy Boat finished his 208th lap ahead of the rest
of the field, and U.S. Auto Club
</P>
<P>
   escorted Boat to victory circle.
</P>
<P>
   Mayhem ensued: Luyendyk, stormed the circle claiming he was a
lap ahead of Boat and had actually run 210 laps. Boat's car owner
A.J. Foyt shoved Luyendyk. USAC reviewed the scoring, revised its
decision, awarded Luyendyk the victory the next day and was
promptly relieved of its duties by the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Britton, who ran data systems for Luyendyk that day, said
the headaches started at about lap 50 when he and his teammates
noticed that USAC had Luyendyk eight laps down when he was on the
lead lap. The Treadway Racing team told Luyendyk to stay on the
track until the checkered flag fell, even though their records
showed he'd won it two laps before.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt still disputes who won the race, but one thing he and
Luyendyk can agree on is that USAC couldn't be counted on to count
straight last year.
</P>
<P>
   USAC ``put the pace car on us and we thought Luyendyk was two
laps behind us so we waved him by,'' Foyt said. ``You're not going
to wave somebody by if you want to win a race. My computer on my
car said we won that race, and I think my computer knew more than
some of those idiots that were upstairs scoring!''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, A.J., IRL executive director Leo Mehl has taken
great pains to make sure there are no ``idiots'' upstairs anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Among Mansfield's fleet of Newton scorers is Betsy Starne, whose
husband has known Foyt for some 32 years. Her finger hits the
Newton pad every time Boat crosses the start/finish line. She then
has about 25 seconds to copy the elapsed time onto a lap-by-lap
race sheet and a 10-lap card until Boat crosses the line again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be completely focussed and concentrate on your one
car,'' said Carol Blackwell, the Team Cheever office manager who
started counting for Eddie Cheever Jr. when the IRL implemented the
Newton system last year after the Texas race. ``You just always
have to be watching that one car while the race fan in you wants to
watch the race.''
</P>
<P>
   But when a car goes around and around and around and around 208
times?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always in the back of your mind that you might mess up
and it's pretty stressful,'' Starne said. ``You know that if you
have a problem you can hold up your hand and they'll come check for
you, but that's why they have four systems.''
</P>
<P>
   And since the IRL can count to four, they hope it will be easier
to count to 208.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
