<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL APPROVES BUDGET WITHOUT MAYOR'S AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Except for huge personal income tax cuts, the $34.08
billion budget that the City Council passed Friday _ the first in
the city's history that was approved without the agreement of the
mayor _ included relatively modest changes from a plan Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani proposed only weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic-controlled council made the tax cut the highlight
of the budget _ which passed 43-7 _ slashing $201 million next
fiscal year and more than $500 million in the years after that.
</P>
<P>
   Budget experts said that the greatest impact of the council's
plan will be on the city's long-term fiscal condition, because the
tax cuts would permanently eliminate a significant source of
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the council's plan would hurt the city's health
into the new millennium because it would widen the gap between
revenues and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But Speaker Peter Vallone trumpeted many of the changes that the
council at his urging, implemented for the new fiscal year, which
begins on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up a battered wooden seat from a public school, Vallone
said he thought it was more important to replace students' chairs
``than worrying about where and what kind of seats we're going to
have and what kind of luxury boxes we're going to have in Yankee
Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The council's plan added $4 million to buy furniture for public
schools. The council also increased appropriations for a host of
other agencies, including $22 million for libraries, $28 million
for the Administration for Children's Services, $18 million for
cultural affairs, $7.6 million for parks and about $5.5 million
each for city hospitals and for the Department of Housing
Preservation and Development.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate budget for capital projects, the city would borrow
$100 million to buy gas furnaces for public schools with coal
furnaces. To finance that project, the council killed several of
the mayor's capital projects, including a $65 million contribution
to the privately owned Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   However, the budget could change over the next few weeks. While
the mayor can veto part or all of the spending plan the Council
approved, Vallone demonstrated Friday that he clearly had the
support to override a veto, an action that would require a
two-thirds vote of the council's 51 members.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani has also said he is prepared to impound city funds,
if necessary, to block the council budget, a move that would likely
end up pitting the two sides against one another in court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Friday night, just hours after council members gathered to cheer
their new budget in the City Hall rotunda, Giuliani showed how his
mayoral powers can throw the council's plan in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Under the City Charter, the mayor reveals what the city can
expect in non-property tax revenues only after the council adopts a
budget. Essentially, that means that the mayor can determine how
much money the city will have to spend next year. In its budget,
the council was forced to use tax revenue estimates that the mayor
included in a plan he proposed a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the mayor announced that he expected the city to
receive less in taxes than he had anticipated a month ago, a move
that could force the council to agree to spending cuts or to raise
the property tax, the one tax it controls.
</P>
<P>
   Council officials accused the mayor of acting purely out of
political vindictiveness, adding that all government fiscal
monitors reported that they expected higher tax revenues than the
mayor predicted last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the mayor reduces revenues _ contrary to what the city
comptroller and the state comptroller and the other monitors say _
he's putting the city at fiscal risk,'' said Bruce Bender,
Vallone's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has trained his criticism at the plan's long-term
impact. City spending is growing faster than revenues, and Giuliani
said the council's budget means widening deficits by more than $2.2
billion in the years 2000 to 2002. He added that the council had
tried to cover those future gaps through an unrealistically rosy
prediction of the tax revenues the city will collect through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This assumes that Wall Street continues to function precisely
the way it is and grows over the next three to four years,'' the
mayor said, ``that there is no drop, that for the first time in the
history of Wall Street or America, there will be no downturn in our
economy at all, at any time in the next three to four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This newest thing that they've done, where they just start
pulling revenues out of the air on the assumption that the economy
is going to continue to grow at record levels, is a highly
irresponsible thing to do,'' Giuliani added in a news conference,
clutching at the air with his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hevesi, the city comptroller, said the council's plan would
increase the deficits, but by about $767 million.
</P>
<P>
   Council officials said future deficits would actually shrink
under their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Criscitello, director of the city's Independent Budget
Office, said that, except for the personal income tax cuts, the
council's plan hewed to Giuliani's proposal from a month earlier.
The council's budget calls for about $49 million less in spending
than the mayor's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge departure from what the mayor proposed,''
Criscitello said. ``It's close to what a negotiated budget would
look like if negotiations had occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   The council's budget drew praise from many lobbyists and
advocates who have been milling inside City Hall this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council should be commended for their first budget, which
clearly puts children first and encourages working families to work
and raise their children in New York City,'' said Rose Anello,
associate executive director of the Citizens' Committee for
Children. ``It enhances programs that support family life, like
after-school programs that will enable working parents to work and
not worry about their children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
