<SLUG> BC-NY-VOTERS-RESIDENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS CHALLENGED TO PROVE RESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN BEACH, N.Y. _ This Fire Island summer colony is often
called the ``Land of No'' for its many rules and regulations,
including some banning beach Frisbees, shirtless men and drinking
on walkways.
</P>
<P>
   But when voters went to the polls Friday, they confronted a rule
of an entirely different sort.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, Paul Pugliese, had people placed in the polling place
to ask voters to swear that they met all residency requirements
before they entered the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   Pugliese has asserted that owners of village businesses, intent
on denying him a second four-year term, schemed to register
waitresses, busboys, shop workers, landscapers and other seasonal
employees as voters. He said many of the employees used bogus
addresses to satisfy the 30-day residency requirement called for
under state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fraud,'' said Pugliese, who was standing Friday outside
the boathouse that serves as the polling place. ``These people
don't live here, they don't sleep here, and some of them have
probably never even been here.''
</P>
<P>
   By midday Friday, no voters who were challenged had refused to
take the oath. But leaders of an opposing village party, the Unity
Party, accused Pugliese of trying to intimidate voters, an
assertion he denied.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents said they were especially angered because Pugliese
had been warning voters that the penalty for lying on registration
forms or in oaths was a fine of up to $5,000 or four years in jail,
or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Land of No' has become the `Land of No Voting,''' said
Andrew Miller, a village trustee who is a member of the Unity
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Pugliese, 56, a retired Time magazine cartographer who is a
village homeowner but also has a home in another Long Island
community, Dix Hills, angered opponents last week when the leader
of his New Community Party, Jon Marin, filed suit challenging the
registration of more than 100 voters.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Jack Cannavo of state Supreme Court in Central Islip on
Wednesday removed from the case all but 14 of the voters named
because Pugliese and his supporters had not served them with
summonses. A hearing in the case is scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the New York state Board of Elections, Lee
Daghlian, said election law did not strictly define residency. He
said that Pugliese was right in saying state law provided for
penalties against people who falsely swore they were residents, but
added that he had never heard of anyone being fined or jailed for
lying on a registration form or in an oath.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hirsch, a lawyer and owner of the Island Mermaid
restaurant, said the seasonal employees and business owners
challenged by Pugliese had the same right to vote as Pugliese and
others who had homes in Ocean Beach but didn't live there year
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nobody on their list who isn't qualified to vote,''
Hirsch said. He said many of the voters Pugliese was challenging
were registered in the village four years ago, when many business
owners supported his bid to become mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Beach, a half-square-mile of Atlantic oceanfront, shops,
restaurants and tightly clustered bungalows, has fewer than 150
year-round residents but about 750 registered voters. That is still
a small fraction of the more than 10,000 summer residents.
</P>
<P>
   In challenging the voters, Pugliese said he was trying to
protect Ocean Beach from the ``rowdiness'' brought in by the day
trippers whose patronage is sought by many of the business owners
who oppose him.
</P>
<P>
   But his detractors, who favor a village trustee, Natalie Katz
Rogers, for mayor, called him a weak administrator with a penchant
for enforcing picayune rules, particularly against village
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's part of an old guard that is so inflexible and thinks if
it didn't invent something it doesn't exist,'' said Brenda Ruello,
the owner of an Ocean Beach landscaping business, Pistils and Peat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ruello, who spends her summers in Ocean Beach but also has a
home in New York City, is one of the remaining defendants in the
voting suit. She voted Friday after a formal challenge from members
of Pugliese's party.
</P>
</TEXT>
